<h2 align="center"><img src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle"
width="32" height="32">The Complete Guide to Garden Stuff<img
src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle" width="32" height="32"></h2>

<p align="center">Brought to you by <a href="http://www.btw.com/"><b>Books
That Work</b></a>, Visionary Home and Garden Software.<br>
<a href="../products/products.htm">Click here for a complete list
of Books That Work's products.</a></p>

<hr size="4">

<h2><a name="RTFToC1">WALL ANCHOR </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Vine hanger, vine support, vine nail, wall
nail, garden wall tie</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Extra-sturdy 1-1/4 inch nail (a masonry nail)
with a soft lead arm, or clip, about an inch or two long. Another
version is a small fiber disk with a 2 inch long wire tongue,
supplied with a tube of weatherproof adhesive. The simplest
version is a long steel wedge with a hole in the wide end, called
a <i>vine eye. </i>Another type of holding pin for vines and
climbing plants is the <i>pole pin</i>, a sturdy, long U-shaped
pin which is designed to be pushed into soft wood.</p>

<p>USE: Holding up vines or other climbing plants on masonry or
wooden walls.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Bend holding arm before attaching to wall. Make sure
you follow adhesive directions, leaving a thick pad of it between
the wall and the anchor.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC2">ANCHOR </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Short stakes made of wood, metal or plastic,
designed to be driven into the ground with a mallet or hammer.</p>

<p>USE: Holding down plastic sheeting, whether for landscape
fabric used as <b>mulch (Chapter 2)</b> or <b>row covers (below),</b>
as well as <b>protective netting (Chapter 4).</b></p>

<p>USE TIPS: Drive in deeply for extra holding strength and
shield exposed end with rocks or potted plants to limit the
chance of someone tripping on the stake. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC3">PLANT SUPPORTS </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Cage, hoops, perrenial supports, flower
supports, flower support rings, border supports </p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Rust-resistant or plastic-coated wire hoops,
loops, or grids with vertical wire legs, or stakes, of various
designs: <i>Peony supports</i> are single or double wire hoops
attached to heavy vertical wires 24 or 35 inches long, making a
cylinder. Others have a large, round grid, or frame, over the top
which the stems go through as they grow--they are often called <i>grow-through
flower supports.</i> Another version has just a single stake with
a small loop at the top, called <i>Blossom </i>or<i> Bulb
supports, or Loop-stakes.</i>. And some, <i>link</i> - or<i>linking
stakes</i>, are just straight wire pieces available in three
lengths from about 1 to 3 feet, that are linked together as the
gardener wishes, custom-designed for each plant or garden. <i>Tuteurs</i>
(French for &quot;tutors&quot;) are 6 foot high supports for
vines amd climbing plants. All are usually dark green and
available in a small range of sizes.</p>

<p>USE: Holding up top-heavy plants that have a tendency to flop
over, whether due to their own weight or heavy winds and rain. <i>Blossom</i>
or <i>bulb supports</i> are obviously for single, top-heavy
flowers. The <i>round plant support</i>, or grid, is more
suitable to taller perrenials. </p>

<p>USE TIP: Place the supports over the plants just as they start
to grow. Push the vertical wire in the ground around the plant so
that it is centered in the hoop or hoops. Note that it is darn
hard to push a full grown plant with large blooms through a small
opening, so put supports out when the plant is beginning to grow,
not afterward.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Peony supports are not very expensive at under $2
for a single hoop and under $3 for a double hoop, although a
homemade version using chicken wire is a good alternative, and it
doesn't show that much. The chicken wire (about 1 foot square) is
placed over the plant just as it starts to grow and is raised
with the plant. Linking stakes are the most versatile. Look for
strong wire and smooth coatings. Though more expensive than tying
plants, this is a lot easier. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC4">TOMATO CAGE </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Tomato stake cage</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Rust-resistant metal or plastic frame, 48 or 54
inches high, shaped like a cone, with the larger end of the cone
on the top, or as a straight cylinder or rectangle. Four or five
concentric wire rings are held together by four vertical metal
wires. Some makes are pieces of large wire mesh which form 18
inch cylinders.</p>

<p>USE: Supports tomato and other fruiting plants, eliminating
the task of staking and tying.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Cages should be placed over the plants shortly after
they have been transplanted into the garden, before they become
to big to be easily caged.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Unless you grow hundreds of tomatoes, cages are
not an expensive purchase. They can be used for many years and
are much easier to use than stakes and ties.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC5">ALUMINUM SPIRAL TOMATO STAKE </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Thick wire spiral with straight pointed end, 5
1/2 feet tall and 1/2 inch in diameter, which can be stuck in the
ground near a tomato plant.</p>

<p>USE: Holding tomater plants upright without tying: they grow
through the tunnel that is created by the spiral. </p>

<p>USE TIP: Keep sucker growth (buds and stems that appear
between the main stem and a branch) pruned. Sucker growth not
only saps the strength of the plant, but can create a bushier
plant than this type of stake is designed to accommodate.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: These are more expensive than other types of
stakes. Try one out before deciding whether you want to use it
for all your tomato plants.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC6">PLANT TIES </a></h2>

<p>POPULAR BRAND NAME: Twist-ems</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Thin wire sandwiched inside a 1/4 inch wide
paper, usually green. sold in reels ranging from a few feet to
250 feet long as well as in packages of pre-cut pieces about 6 or
8 inches long. Alternatives include soft, natural <i>jute twine </i>(green
or natural beige color)<i>, vinyl ribbon, nylon loops, </i>and<i>
foam-coated, cushioned wire, </i>some of which stretch as the
plant grows. Most can be found in the color green.</p>

<p>USE: Temporary and gentle holding of plants against supports
and stakes.</p>

<p>USE TIPS:</p>

<p>BUYING TIPS:</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC7">TRELLIS NETS </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Plastic netting designed to be strung beteen
poles or posts. </p>

<p>USE: Temporary trellis for climbing vegetable crops such as
cucumbers, beans, and peas. Reduces the amount of space needed in
the garden. They also make harvesting from vines easier.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Place poles and posts that are used to support nets
close enough together to support the weight of the crops.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Gardeners in the past made their own net vegetable
trellises by stringing twine between upright poles. Plastic net
trellises simplify this task, and they can be used for many years
more than twine. Make sure the net you are buying can support the
weight of the crop that you wish to grow on it. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC8">RIGID PLANT TRELLISES </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Sold in a variety of shapes including the old
fashioned <i>fan trellis</i>, a wider-bottomed <i>flair trellis</i>,
a rectangular <i>ladder</i> design, and the diamond grid trellis,
also called <i>lattice</i>. Made of aluminum, plastic, fiberglass
or wood. An <i>arbor</i> (or <i>trellised arch</i>) is sort of a
three-dimensional trellis that spans a walk like a free-standing
doorway or arch, and a <i>tunnel</i> is a longer version, each
size made longer by adding a hoop for as much as 20 feet . <i>Bean
and pea towers </i>are merely 6 feet long stakes bunched together
at the top like a skinless teepee. An <i>A-frame</i> trellis is
two 5 x 8 foot metal frames with a large mesh nylon net, and a
similar rigid trellis is made of large panels that unfold like a
Japanese screen.</p>

<p>USE: Supporting climbing or vining plants that cannot adhere
to a wall. In some cases you may not want vines on the wall (thus
avoiding harm) or in other cases the trellis may create a natural
wall. Allows you to harvest vegetables without bending over.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Be sure that the trellis is well secured,
particularly when using woody or heavy vines. Excellent for those
who have trouble reaching ground level, such as wheelchair-bound
or elderly gardeners.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP:</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC9">border fencinG </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Trim fence, bed guard, folding fence, flower
border</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Small, decorative fence made of welded, platic
coated or enameled wire, or of wooden pickets. Vinyl coated in
green or white. Commonly sold in 8, 10, and 12 foot lengths
folded by sections, or in 20 foot and 25 foot rolls, 8 to 32
inches high, and in a variety of styles, such as round tops,
angular tops, or gothic tops. Picket patterns usually have model
names like &quot;Colonial&quot; or &quot;Cape Cod.&quot; Wooden
lattice panels also available. Also available 36 or 48 inches
high version, called a lawn guard.</p>

<p>Larger welded wire fences are available with large mesh and
fence posts in 36 and 48 inch high models, sold in 50 foot rolls.
<i>Hex netting</i>, or <i>poultry netting</i> or <i>chicken wire</i>,
is available in 50 and 150 foot rolls 24, 36, and 48 inches wide
of light gauge galvanized, woven wire. <i>Diamond mesh</i> is
available galvanized or vinyl coated, usually with a 2-1/2 inch
woven mesh made of14 gauge wire, in 50 foot rolls 36 or 48 inches
high--it looks like the much stronger <i>chain link fences. </i>Welded
mesh is has square openings in various sizes including 1/2 x 1
inch, 1 x1 inch, 2 x 1 inch, and 4 x 2 inches and is available in
36 and 48 inch heights sold in rolls 50 foot and 100 feet long. </p>

<p>USE: Marking off flower beds and protecting them from people,
pets, and lawn mowers.</p>

<p>USE TIP: If placed near a popular short cut, try to notice if
people are tripping on the fence rather than going around it. If
so, replace with a higher fence.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Avoid untreated pine fencing, as it will rot after
just one year in the soil. Welded fencing is stronger than woven
fencing, and wire fence material that is galvanized after welding
is better protected against the elements.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC10">edging</a></h2>

<p>POPULAR BRAND NAMES: Easy-Edge, Sure edge</p>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Plastic border, landscape border, grass stop,
grass edging, lawn edging, border edging, bed divider, lawn
border</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Several different types. Semi-rigid polyethylene
or aluminum sheet, 4 to 6 inches high, with a tubular edge on the
plastic version, driven into the ground vertically, with the
tubular edge of the plastic version left just at the surface (a
small &quot;L&quot; on the bottom edge keeps the plastic from
coming back up). Plastic available in black, white, green, or
redwood color, sold in rolls of 20 and 100 feet Also available in
6 inch and 12 inch high scalloped cedar slabs in 10 and 20 foot
sections or 3 inch diameter <i>pegs</i> or <i>logs</i> 4-1/2 to
10 inches high, joined by wire or rubber sheet in 3 foot
sections. Still other types are made of pressure-treated pine
(with a green/gray color) with decorative picket tops, or fake
plastic &quot;pegs&quot;. Better brands have a &quot;T&quot; or
flared bottom to keep it from coming out.</p>

<p>USE: Making borders of flower beds and lawns. A particularly
good way to keep creeping grass out of perennial beds and off of
walks.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Push metal or plastic in slowly so it does not
buckle. Edging should be in the soil deep enough to block roots
and for a lawn mower to pass over it.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Black plastic edging with the tubular top replaces
green metal (and other forms of plastic edging) and is
considerably more durable. Some brands are guaranteed for 20
years. Avoid promotionally priced lightweight metal edging, as it
is likely to bend when it is being installed.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC11">SHADE Fencing </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Snow fencing, shading fence</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Small, 3/8 inch thick wooden boards, called <i>lath</i>,
3 to 6 feet long by about 1inch wide bound together with several
rows of wire, twisted on both side of each lath. Often painted
red or maroon. Sold in rolls of 50 feet. A similar type of
protective fencing is woven from thin, chemically treated
freshwater reeds, called <i>reed fencing. </i>It comes in 6 foot
rolls 15 and 25 feet long.</p>

<p>USE: Breaks wind a bit to control drifting of snow and sand.
Also a simple wind break for small shrubs and trees--an
application particularly useful in areas where the winter winds
can be damaging. Can also be used to shade newly planted
seedlings or hardwood cuttings.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP:</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC12">PROTECTIVE MATERIALS AND SEASON EXTENDERS </a></h2>

<h2><a name="RTFToC13">Burlap</a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Wind shield, windbreak, plant protector</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Loosely woven, light brown cloth traditionally
made from natural jute fiber. Sold in square sheets from 20 x 20
inches to 120 x 120 inches or in rolls up to 125 yards long and
in widths of 36, 40, 48, or 60 inches, called <i>continuous
burlap</i>. May be treated (to prevent rot) or untreated.
Packages of squares may be called <i>totes</i>. Plastic version
is also available, though only in squares and short rolls. <i>Erosion
cloth</i> is a term sometimes used to refer to a wide (or
&quot;open&quot;) mesh, lightweight version. Available also in 8
to 12 foot squares with grommets in each corner and reinforced
edges for use as a leaf carrier.</p>

<p>USE: Rolled burlap is used to construct wind shields to
protect sensitive plants from cold, damaging, winter winds and
snow. Sheets are used to wrap root and soil balls when
transplanting or moving woody shrubs and trees. Smaller sheets,
about 8 by 8 feet , can be used for carrying large loads of raked
leaves or other garden debris. Erosion cloth is used for erosion
control in newly seeded lawns, especially on gentle slopes and
embankments. </p>

<p>USE TIP: When wrapping root balls, wet the soil around the
plant well to keep the soil in a compact ball. Be sure to use
natural twine to bind a natural burlapped root ball, so that it
decomposes after planting. Most burlaps products, especially the
lightweight version, disintegrate naturally after one
season--considered an advantage by most users. Do not use as a
duster: the dust will go all over, not as directed, and is likely
to pose a hazard to you.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Natural burlap is easier to use as it is more
pliable than plastic, which does not allow plant roots to breathe
and does not decompose in the ground. </p>

