<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><img src="../headgifs/headbar.gif" alt="Books That Work"
width="545" height="24"> </p>

<h2 align="center"><img src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle"
width="32" height="32">The Complete Guide to Garden Stuff<img
src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle" width="32" height="32"></h2>

<p align="center">Brought to you by <a href="http://www.btw.com/"><b>Books
That Work</b></a>, Visionary Home and Garden Software.<br>
<a href="../products/products.htm">Click here for a complete list
of Books That Work's products.</a></p>

<hr size="4">

<h2><a name="RTFToC1">CLOCHE</a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Season extender, plant protector, teepee, plant
cover</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Plastic, glass, or fabric cone which is placed
over a single plant, several plants or an entire row of plants in
a garden. Similar in theory to a<b> cold frame (below)</b>, but
portable, like a miniature cold frame or greenhouse. Light passes
through the material so that the green leaves can still
photosynthesize. Many ingenious designs are available, from
galvanized wire mesh covered with plastic to paper on wire hoops,
as well as the familiar molded or formed plastic. A newer kind is
a set of interconnected clear plastic tubes which are filled with
about 3 gallons of water, forming a ribbed cone (brand name:
Wall-O-Water). The water retains heat from the day and releases
it at night, acting as a temperature moderator and insulator.</p>

<p>USE: Protects young and tender crops during the early (and
late) season when you might get caught by a late (or early)
frost, and from cold winds. It is also used to extend the season
into the cooler weather in the fall. Crops such as tomatoes,
peppers, and other transplants can get a head start when a cloche
is placed over them.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Be sure to remove the cloche when the day
temperatures are particularly warm (75<sup>o</sup> F +), as the
plants may heat up too much. Replace the cloche when the
temperatures begin to drop.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: If you plan on using cloaches for several years,
buy a higher- priced fabric or solid plastic one which will last,
and store carefully between seasons. It will be worth the
investment.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC2">ROSEBUSH PROTECTOR </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Winterizer, plant protector, season extender,
rose collar</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Two basic types: one solid and one open. The
solid one is a styrofoam plastic cone about 1-1/2 feet high that
resembles a large wastebasket with a flange. Stakes (supplied)
are driven through holes in the flange to hold the cone down. The
open one is fiberglass screening or corrugated plastic which
forms a cylinder a foot high and from 1 to 1-1/2 feet in
diameter. It is filled with a light, insulating mulch, such as
peat moss, peanut shells, or the like. </p>

<p>USE: Protecting rose bushes from winter weather extremes, or
extending the growing season for vegetables that are planted
early in the spring.</p>

<p>USE TIPS: Prune carefully first. Clean and store properly to
get long life out of your protectors.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC3">COLD FRAME </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Essentially a miniature greenhouse consisting of
an open pit dug in the ground up to 2 feet deep by about 3 or 4
feet long and wide, with a wooden (rot-resistant redwood most
often), plastic (polycarbonate), or aluminum frame around the
sides and a hinged glass or clear plastic top. Some models come
with themostatically controled tops that automatically open when
the temperature reaches a certain point, or other automatic
venting systems, or it can a simple homemade job.</p>

<p>USE: Allows you to winter over tender plants as well as to
start and protect seedlings in the spring. Can double during the
summer as a small compost bin when it is not being used for
plants.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Cold frames should be opened when the day
temperatures begin to climb, otherwise you risk a premature
cooking of the plants within. Watch out that you don't drop the
top and break the glass; plastic glazing is advantageous in this
respect.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Cold frames are so easy to make that most people
(even those who are not handy) can put one together in an
afternoon using scrap lumber and old windows. However, the
polycarbonate ones sold commercially are excellent--they even
insulate a bit--and won't break if you drop the tops or
accidently step on them when chasing an errant shuttlecock or
baseball. Look for ones with wind-protected vents.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC4">ROW COVER </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Fabric row cover, floating row cover</p>

<p>POPULAR BRAND NAME: Reemay</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Essentially a sort of<b> coldframe (above)</b>
brought to the plants instead of the other way around.
Lightweight, transluscent, spun-bonded polyester material between
5 and 6 feet wide and 250 to 2550 feet long. Sunlight and water
penetrate easily (75% of sunlight). Some are slitted.</p>

<p>USE: Protects seedlings from animals, flying pests, and season
extremes (early spring and late fall) to a certain extent, while
still allowing light and water to enter. Also helps retain
moisture and heat in a seed bed.</p>

<p>USE TIPS: Support with some kind of light framework or stakes.
Though the manufacturer claims that it is so light it can be
placed loosely over new plants or seedbed, letting the plants
push this material up as they grow, tender seedlings might not be
strong enough to do this and could get damaged. Remove the fabric
once the seedlings are established to avoid heating up the bed
too much.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC5">Shade Fabric </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Loosely woven black polypropylene fibers sold in
6 foot rolls in lengths up to 300 feet . It is graded according
to density, ranging from 30 to 92% (commonly 53%,63% and 73%),
which indicates the amount of shade it provides. Price varies
accordingly, with the densest costing roughly twice as much per
square foot as the most open. Rot-proof, mildew-proof, UV ray-
resistant, chemical-resistant. <i>Shading compound</i> is a
concentrated paint that is used on glass greenhouses to temper
the sunlight. A different kind of compound is used on plastic. <i>Greenhouse
film</i> is UV resistant plastic sheeting, 14 to 40 feet wide,
sold in 100 foot rolls, used for the same purpose; it is secured
with staples and <i>greenhouse tape, </i>an adhesive tape
specially formulated for this purpose.</p>

<p>USE: Primarily for shading tender new seedlings and
transplants but also for covering a planting bed where cuttings
are rooting.</p>

<p>USE TIP: It is easier to install above a planting bed if it is
attached to a wooden frame.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: As with many products sold by the roll, larger
ones are cheaper per foot to buy. Look for shade fabric which is
U.V. tested, as this indicates that it does not break down under
sunlight. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC6">STEEL MESH TREE PROTECTOR </a></h2>

<p>Popular Brand Names: Tree Tender </p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Stainless steel mesh, soft and flexible, which is
sold in small pieces 2-3/8 inches by 7-1/2 feet. Secured with
clips supplied by the manufacturer. Can be cut to fit. Another
version is made of sturdy foam rubber.</p>

<p>USE: One layer protects against rodent damage; multi-layered
wrap protects bark from string trimmer and mower damage. The open
weave permits natural ventilation but discourages insect larvae
development. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC7">Tree Wrap </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Tree paper</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Waterproof paper, plastic fiber, vinyl, foam
rubber, or burlap in widths from 3 to 6 inches, sold in rolls of
100 or l50 feet in the case of woven goods. Plastic items may be
spirals in 2 and 3 foot lengths. Paper type is dark brown kraft
paper sandwiching a layer of weatherproof asphalt and given a
&quot;crepe&quot; finish.</p>

<p>USE: Wound in a spiral around the bottom six feet or so of
small trees' trunks. Protects trees, especially young, newly
planted trees, from damage by insects, pets, deer, rabbits, and
weather (sun scald or early frost), as well as from loss of
moisture.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Paper and natural fiber burlap is easier to use than
synthetic material, which when used as a tight fabric wrap does
not expand as the tree grows, and if not removed, will constrict
the tree. Tie with jute twine, which will rot off over time and
not harm the tree as it grows. Solid plastic spirals should be
avoided as they neither breathe nor decompose. Trees with
lenticles (breathing pores) located on the trunk and branches can
suffer from plastic tree wrap.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC8">TREE TUBE </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Tree guard</p>

<p>POPULAR BRAND NAMES: Ross Tree Gard, Clark's Weed Whacker
Guards </p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Plastic tube slit along the side, sold in 36 inch
lengths.</p>

<p>USE: Snaps onto trunks of young trees to protect them from
insect and animal damage as well as from excessive sun, like tree
wrap, above, but plastic, because it is stiff, also protects
street trees from minor bike or dog abuse, and is particularly
good winter protection. A new specialty model only 6 inches high
has been developed for protecting against nylon string <b>trimmers
(Chapter 7)</b>.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Remember to remove tubing as the tree grows too big
for it, although one advantage to slit tube or spirals is that
they expand easily with the growth of the tree.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP:</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC9">TREE SUPPORT KIT </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Collection of 3 18 inch hardwood stakes, 3 12
inch rubber sleeves (probably sections of old hose), and 30 feet
of heavy galvanized wire. Others may include 6 foot cedar stakes
instead, usually in urban areas.</p>

<p>USE: Holding newly-planted tree upright without damaging it. </p>

<p>USE TIPS: Wrap wire around stakes securely so that it really
holds the tree if tension is placed on it. Use the hose to
protect the tree from damage. Flag stakes to prevent people from
tripping over them. Remove after one year.</p>

<h3 align="center"><a href="10_misc1.html">Click Here for Next
Page</a> </h3>
