width="545" height="24"> </p>

<h2 align="center"><img src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle"
width="32" height="32">The Complete Guide to Garden Stuff<img
src="../art/gleaf.gif" align="absmiddle" width="32" height="32"></h2>

<p align="center">Brought to you by <a href="http://www.btw.com/"><b>Books
That Work</b></a>, Visionary Home and Garden Software.<br>
<a href="../products/products.htm">Click here for a complete list
of Books That Work's products.</a></p>

<hr size="4">

<h2><a name="RTFToC1">BIRD FEEDERS </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: A tremendous array of designs exist, from
whimsical and rustic to extremely high-tech, but all bird feeders
consist of some type of chamber to hold bird seed and some place
for birds to perch while feeding. Bird feeders can be round
cylinders, rectangular boxes or covered top shelters in which the
seed is placed in a feeding tray. They are made of plastic, wood,
glass, metal and combinations of these materials. Some are even
designed to be mounted on a window. Most have some device for
preventing squirrels from feeding, or to exclude heavier
&quot;nuisance&quot; birds, such as blackbirds or pigeons.</p>

<p>USE: Bird feeders are most often used to attract birds to the
garden during off-seasons such as winter, when other food is
scarce. Some feeders, however, are designed to attract a
particular type of bird during seasons when they migrate through
your area. Other feeders are used to attract particular types of
birds in the spring in the hope that they will nest in or near
your garden. Always keep your feeder full during the season.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Squirrels are the enemies of bird feeders, as they
enter and devour all the seed if at all possible. Place bird
feeders in locations that make it difficult for squirrels (and
cats, of course) to get to them, such as on metal poles and away
from branches and climbable parts of buildings. Or add an
accesory called a <i>squirrel baffle</i>, a large plastic disk
which fits on the support pole or hangs above a wire-held feeder.
A <i>seed catcher</i>, a large saucer that attaches to the pole
under the feeder, catches any stray seeds that might fall.
(Sunflower seeds act as herbicide and kill your grass.)</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Other than buying a sturdy, well-made feeder,
particular consideration should be paid to whether the feeder is
squirrel- or cat-proof.</p>

<p>Look for models hung from wires or poles with circular
squirrel guards. Bird feeders that have wide platform areas give
squirrels a place to perch while raiding a feeder, and should be
avoided. Window-mounted models may work better with one-way
mirrors so you don't scare the birds away. The feeder should be
able to adequately dispense the size of bird seed you wish to put
in it. For example, finches, wrens and many small birds feed on
thistle seed and small grains. If the dispensing part of a feeder
is too large, these smaller seeds will not be held well.
Sunflower seed cannot be dispensed if the openings are too small.
Buy feeders that will attract the specific birds you want. This
information should be included in the packaging but can also be
found in reference books.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC2">BIRD SEED </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Grains and seeds, usually mixed, including
sunflower, safflower, peanut hearts, millet, sunflower chips,
thistle, and cracked corn. Mixtures of different types of grain
and seed are blended to match the diets of certain types of
birds. Some garden centers sell the seed unmixed so that you can
buy and mix your own, depending on the type of birds you have or
want to attract. </p>

<p>USE: Placed in bird feeders primarily to supplement birds'
diets during times when other food is scarce, such as winter.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Select the type of seed to attract the birds you want
most. Avoid unshelled sunflower seeds if you have a squirrel
problem, as this is their favorite. Mixes that contain unshelled
sunflower seed are for larger birds. The shells of sunflower
seeds contain a natural herbicide and kill vegetation if they
collect on the ground under a feeder, so you would not want them
to accumulate on lawns or flower beds. </p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Bird seed is not expensive, so experiment to find
those mixes that attract the birds you want. With a little
research, you can easily learn what types of seed certain birds
prefer.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC3">SUET BALLS AND CONES </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS:</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Suet balls are made of animal fats or lard
compressed into a small ball and imbedded with bird seed. The
ball has a string or a wire attached so that it can be hung from
a tree. Suet cones are large pine cones that have been dipped in
animal fats and sprinkled with bird seed.</p>

<p>USE: Supplement to birds' winter diet, when food is scarce.
The suet itself is supposed to be helpful to the birds during
cold weather.</p>

<p>USE TIP: Note that suet balls and cones are primarily for
winter feeding— they become a dripping mess in warm weather. A
metal collar is necessary to act as a squirrel guard.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Suet balls are an inexpensive and easy way to feed
birds in winter. As inexpensive as they are, some people find
them a nice home project to make themselves.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC4">HUMMINGBIRD FEEDER </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: There are several types of hummingbird feeders on
the market but all have several things in common. Each has a
reservoir for holding a liquid sugar mixture (often sold as <i>hummingbird
nectar</i>). All or part of the feeders are red, as this color
attracts hummingbirds. Feeding tubes that resemble the trumpet
shape flower that hummingbirds naturally take nectar from are
attached to the sides. Feeders may have a single or several
feeding tubes or fountains (small holes that the hummingbird
sticks its beak into). </p>

<p>USE: Attracting this fascinating bird to the garden.</p>

<p>USE TIP: If the liquid reservoir on your feeder is clear, a
little red food coloring can be added to the nectar to help
attract hummingbirds. Learning something about the hummingbirds
in your area will help you attract them to your garden. For
example, hummingbirds migrate through the northeastern United
States in late summer, so this is the best time for putting out
feeders. Remember that hummingbirds feed from flowers, so the
feeder should not be placed higher than where the birds will
naturally look for it. </p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Hummingbird feeders are not expensive. Most will
attract hummingbirds if they are in the area at all, but ones
designed to be bee-proof are better. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC5">BONSAI AND FLOWER ARRANGING TOOLS &amp;
EQUIPMENT </a><br>
<a name="RTFToC6">ABOUT BONSAI </a></h2>

<p>The enduring Japanese art of growing miniature trees, Bonsai,
is very popular in all parts of this country. The trees leaves,
branches, and roots are clipped regularly, forcing the plant to
mature without getting large. Specialized tools have been
developed which make this work easier.</p>

<p>Bonsai plants need gentle care. If you are not a serious
bonsai hobbiest and receive a plant as a gift, take a course at a
nearby botanic garden or search out some good books on the
subject, of which there are many.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC7">BONSAI SNIPS </a></h2>

<p>TYPES:</p>

<p><i>Scissors</i></p>

<p><i>Shears</i></p>

<p><i>Branch Nippers</i></p>

<p><i>Wire Cutters</i></p>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS:</p>

<p><i>Scissors: </i>Beginner's shears, Bud shears (with small
finger loops)</p>

<p><i>Shears: </i>Trimming shears</p>

<p><i>Branch Nippers: </i>Concave cutter</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Specially adapted snips for more control and
precision in the detail work required by Bonsai gardening.</p>

<p><i>Scissors: </i>Black wrought iron or carbon steel scissors
with short blades (about 1&quot;-- <i>Koryu</i> style) and long
handles, either with small finger holes on the end or with large
butterfly loops for the entire hand. Overall length about
6&quot;. </p>

<p><i>Shears: </i>Like scissors, but with slightly longer blades
(about 2&quot;) and butterfly handles--called <i>ashinaga</i>, or
more correctly, <i>naga ashi</i> <i>bonsai hasami</i> --<i>hasami</i>
means shears in Japanese.</p>

<p><i>Branch Nippers: </i>Black wrought iron pincers, with
beveled, wide, curved jaws about 1&quot; long and 3/4&quot; wide.
Resemble wide pliers. Long handles; tool is about 8&quot; long
overall.</p>

<p><i>Wire Cutters: </i>Resembles above-mentioned scissors, but
1&quot; short blades are thicker. Handles have finger loops at
end.</p>

<p>USE: Maintaining bonsai plants with precision. <i>Scissors</i>
are for leaf trimming; <i>Shears</i> for cutting small branches
and leaves; <i>Branch Nippers</i> are for making concave cuts
when removing branches; <i>Wire Cutters</i> cut wire close to
branch. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC8">BONSAI TROWELS </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Miniature versions of<b> trowels (Chapter 5)</b>
and scoops, usually made of one piece of metal.</p>

<p>USE: Careful moving of soil in <b>Bonsai planters (below)</b>.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC9">BONSAI PLANTER </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Shallow oval and rectangular dish, usually of
glazed ceramic material but also of plastic, with drainage holes.
Commonly sold with matching saucer.</p>

<p>USE: Growing bonsai plants.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC10">FLORAL FOAM </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Oasis (actually a popular brand name), foam
brick, floral base, floral foam brick</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Green stiff styrofoam block, sold in cubes about
6&quot; on a side, that can be cut to size, treated with a floral
preservative. May come with adhesive on one side. Dry floral foam
is similar, but intended for use with dried and silk flowers (and
plastic flowers, too, if you must). A similar product that is
less common is <i>floral clay,</i> which works in much the same
way as foam.</p>

<p>USE: Holding the stems of cut flowers in the bottom of a
floral arrangement. Stems are merely stuck into the foam at any
angle. Foam is first floated on the water until it is saturated,
then held down with waterproof adhesive <b>floral tape</b> <b>(below)
</b>made for this purpose.</p>

<p>BUYING TIPS: Helps retain water and extend flower life.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC11">FLOWER HOLDERS </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Flower pins, needlepoint flower holder, kenzan
(Japanese), floral holder</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Small, heavy, flat or domed disk or rectangle
with many 1&quot; spikes, usually green enameled or brass. Round
ones are as small as 1&quot; in diameter, with 4&quot; a common
size. May have a lead-weighted base surrounded by rubber. Some
models on adjustable pedestals are made for putting short-stemmed
flowers in with longer ones. An older version with notched copper
hooks that look like hairpins instead of spikes is called a <i>flower
frog </i>or a <i>hairpin frog.. </i></p>

<p>USE: Holding the stems of cut flowers in the bottom of vases
for floral arrangements. Domed models are for splays of flowers.</p>

<p>BUYING TIP: Permanent and re-usable, as opposed to <b>floral
foam (above). </b>Brass spikes are the most desirable, though
galvanized steel does fine.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC12">CUT FLOWER PRESERVATIVE </a></h2>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: Cut flower food</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: A type of fertilizer and conditioner for cut
flowers in granular form.</p>

<p>USE: When mixed with water in a vase, can preserve cut flowers
an extra week or so by cutting down on bacterial growth, which
also keeps the water clear. </p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC13">FLOWER ARRANGING ACCESSORIES </a></h2>

<p>TYPES:</p>

<p><i>Floral Tape</i></p>

<p><i>Floral Wire</i></p>

<p><i>Floral Picks</i></p>

<p><i>Floral Adhesive</i></p>

<p>ALSO KNOWN AS: </p>

<p><i>Floral Tape:</i> Stemming</p>

<p><i>Floral Wire: </i>Florist's wire</p>

<p>DESCRIPTION: A variety of items which are convenient
ingredients of floral arrangements. </p>

<p>USE: Making wet or dry flower arrangements (powders and sprays
are available for drying flowers). Floral wire (green, straight
or coiled) holds flowers in place in arrangements and corsages;
floral tape conceals the wires, especially on corsages; short,
thin floral picks hold stems in foam; floral adhesive, usually in
1&quot; wide tape form, holds the foam in the bottom of the vase.</p>

<h2><a name="RTFToC14">CEMETERY CONE </a></h2>

<p>DESCRIPTION: Small plastic cone, about the size of a jumbo
ice-cream cone, filled with a small bouquet of plastic flowers.</p>

<p>USE: Attaches permanently to gravestones.</p>

<p>BUYING TIPS: Usually carried only by those garden centers
located near a cemetery.</p>

<h3 align="center"><a href="10_misc4.html">Click Here for Next
Page</a> </h3>
