<HTML><TITLE>National Commission on Retirement Policy</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3spcproj.gif"></p><br><p>

<H2><p align="center">America's Looming Retirement Financing Crisis<br>
and the National Commission on Retirement Policy</p></H2><p>

<table cellpadding=15><tr>

<td valign=top width=150><font size="2">
<i>For information about specific aspects of the project:</i><p>
<b>Overview:</b><br>
<a href="#signif">Project Significance</a><p>
<a href="#object">Statement of Objectives</a><p>
<a href="#description">Project Description & Methodology</a><p>
<a href="#structure">Organizational Structure</a><p>
<a href="#outreach">Public Education & Outreach</a><p>
<a href="#impact">Policy Impact</a><p>
<a href="#timetable">Timetable</a><p>
<a href="#plans">Plans for Continued Support</a><p>
<a href="#about">About CSIS</a><p><hr>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/members.html">Members Biographies</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/mission.html">Mission Statement</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/facts.html">Fact Sheet</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/press.html">Press Advisory</a><p>


</font></td>

<td>
	<font size="5"><b>L</b></font>ooming on the horizon are a number of "economic time bombs," which, if not defused now, threaten the prospects of a secure retirement for many Americans.  The imminent retirement of the "Baby Boom" generation soon after the turn of the century will strain our nation's fiscal capacity and could imperil the standard of living for future generations.  Quite simply, we as a nation and as individuals are ill-prepared to meet the financial challenges of the twenty-first century.  We are confronted with a rapidly aging population, an actuarially unsound Social Security system, unsustainable levels of spending for government programs for senior citizens, under-funded private pension plans, and unacceptably low levels of private savings.  We have promised too much and set aside too little.  As a result, the "three-legged stool" ó Social Security, personal savings, and public and private pension plans ó that has traditionally financed Americans' retirement is increasingly unstable and threatens to collapse.<p>

	The Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) proposes to launch a major policy initiative that will address the retirement financing challenge facing the United States early in the next century.  A critical aspect of this initiative will be the establishment of a bipartisan National Commission on Retirement Policy comprised of leaders from the public and private sectors.  The mission of the eighteen-month project will be to highlight the urgency of this potential crisis and recommend comprehensive and politically viable solutions to address it.  Public education will be necessary to help galvanize a political consensus for implementation of the necessary policy reforms.  In the project's first phase, CSIS will bring together key members of Congress and business leaders in a series of public forums in Washington and around the country to highlight the magnitude of the problem and educate the American public about the tradeoffs involved in addressing these problems.  In the second phase, CSIS will convene a series of  roundtable discussions and hearings to examine in-depth potential policy responses to the retirement financing crisis.  The project will culminate in the publication of a major policy report that will provide a blueprint for action.<p>
<hr width=200><br>
<i>"We owe it to those who will retire after the turn of the century to be given sufficient advance notice to make what alterations in retirement planning may be required.  The longer we wait to make what are surely inevitable adjustments, the more difficult they will become."</i><br>
	-- Alan Greenspan, Chairman, Federal Reserve Board<p>
<hr width=200></td></tr>

<tr><td width=150>
<hr>
<i>To make good on promised benefits in the next century, it is estimated that Social Security payroll taxes would have to increase between 33% and 50%</i><hr>
</td><td valign=top>

<b><a name="signif">Project Significance</a></b><p>

	For the past half century, a secure retirement has been part of the American dream.  Now, however, as the result of immutable demographic changes, unsustainable fiscal trends, and imprudent governmental policy and individual choices, this dream may elude many Americans -- or become an untenable tax burden on the next generation.  Simply put, America is growing older.  The aging of America has profound implications -- both economic and social -- for the nation as a whole and for the individual and household financing of retirement.<p>

 	America is growing older.  Today, one in eight Americans is age 65 and older.  However, as the Baby Boom generation begins to retire in 2010, the percentage of older Americans will increase significantly.  By 2040, one in four will be in that age group.  At the same time, life expectancy continues to rise.  These demographic changes will place tremendous fiscal pressure on federal entitlement programs for the elderly.  Furthermore, due to a declining birthrate, there will be a comparably smaller workforce to help bear those costs in the future.<p>

 	We have promised too much.  Entitlement programs consume an ever increasing share of our national resources.  Mandatory spending on entitlements (principally Social Security and Medicare) has more than doubled since 1963, and now accounts for almost half of federal outlays.  By the government's own figures,at the current rate of federal spending, entitlements are projected to exceed all government revenues by 2030.<p>

 	We are saving too little.  As a nation and as individuals, we are not saving enough to meet future consumption needs.  The rate of personal savings has declined significantly since the 1960s to historically low levels -- from 11.3% in 1965 to 2.7% in 1993 -- which is insufficient to meet the future retirement needs of most Americans.<p>

	These trends are unsustainable.  Without significant public policy and social responses to the impending challenges, the standard of living for retirees after the first quarter of the 21st century could decline.  Society simply cannot afford all the retirement promises we have made.  A failure to act boldly with structural reforms now will dramatically raise the costs and the sacrifices necessary ten to twenty years down the road.  It is imperative that the fiscally unstable three-legged stool be significantly revised and strengthened:<p>

<ul>
<li><i>The Social Safety Net.</i>  Presently, inflows to the Social Security system exceed benefits paid out.  However, the program's trust fund will begin paying out more in benefits than it collects in payroll taxes by 2013.  Most analysts agree that if no action is taken now, the fund will be entirely depleted by 2029.  Most young Americans don't believe that Social Security will be there for them.  Medicare is in even worse shape, anticipated to be insolvent by 2001.  In fact, over the long term, the combined unfunded liabilities of  Medicare and Social Security will be nearly $1.8 trillion by 2030 and over $20 trillion by 2070. <p>

<li><i>Private Pensions.</i>  Currently, less than half of all workers are covered by a pension plan.  During the 1980s, companies discontinued 40,000 pension plans, and more firms are likely to follow suit as the Baby Boom generation nears retirement.  According to the Pension Benefit Guarantee Corporation, total under funding of corporate pension plans stands at $64 billion -- twice the level from 1995.  Furthermore, over the last decade employers have shifted away from defined benefit to defined contribution plans, which has shifted risk to individuals and forced them to take more responsibility for investment decisions. <p>

<li><i>Personal Savings.</i>  Shortfalls in meeting retirement expenses will have to be supplemented with personal savings.  Current levels of retirement saving, however, are not nearly large enough to compensate for the projected drops in benefits from Social Security and pension plans.  Personal savings has fallen, from almost 12 percent of GDP in 1965 to about five percent in 1995.  According to a recent study by Merrill Lynch, the oldest Baby Boomers are saving just one-third of what they will need to maintain their current standard of living during retirement.</ul><p>


<b><a name="object">Statement of Objectives</a></b><p>

	The goals and objectives of the project and the National Commission on Retirement Policy are as clear as the CSIS mission statement:  policy impact.  It is our intention to see the work of this project influence the development of policy choices necessary to protect the American retirement dream.  The product of the Commission's efforts will be a legislative blueprint for a national retirement policy that will enable the United States to meet the fiscal challenges of the 21st century.<p>

	Before this can happen, however, there must be a great deal of public education and informed policy debate.  After raising crucial public awareness, the ultimate objective of the project will be formulating the policy options and recommendations for Congress, the Administration and the public.  With the strong bipartisan leadership and wealth of expertise of the Commission, CSIS is confident the project will yield tangible results and policy impact.<p>


</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top width=150>
<hr>
<i>The project will follow a three-pronged strategy: raise public awareness, stimulate dialogue for solutions, and build grassroots support on policy recommendations.</i><hr>
</td><td valign=top>

<b><a name="description">Project Description & Methodology</a></b><p>

	The project will provide leadership and expertise in studying the challenges to retirement financing.  This will be accomplished through the establishment and work of the National Commission on Retirement Policy.  The purpose of the Commission will be to:<p>
<ul>
<li>Facilitate discussion of critical issues among policymakers, experts and stakeholders;
<li>Educate the public about those issues;
<li>Deliberate policy options to address the challenges to a secure retirement; and,
<li>Promote a blueprint of recommendations on what must be done.</ul>

</td></tr>

<tr><td valign=top width=150>

<font size="2"><a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/members.html"><b>Members:</b></a><p>
<i>Congressional Co-chairs</i><p>
         
The Honorable Judd Gregg <br>								United States Senate<p>
The Honorable John Breaux<br>  
United States Senate<p>
The Honorable Jim Kolbe<br>
U.S. House of Representatives<p>
The Honorable Charles W. Stenholm <br>
U.S. House of Representatives<p>

<i>Private Sector Co-chairs</i><p>

Donald B. Marron<br>
Chairman and CEO, Paine Webber Group Inc.<p>
Dr. Charles A. Sanders<br>
Retired Chairman and CEO, Glaxo, Inc.<p>

<i>Commission Members:</i><p>

Warren Batts <br>
Ronald E. Compton	<br>
Fred Goldberg<br>
Lanny Hall<br>
Beth Kobliner<br>
Estelle James<br>
Rudolph G. Penner<br>
Robert C. Pozen<br>
Stanford G. Ross<br>
Dallas L. Salisbury<br>
Robert J. Shapiro<br>
Eugene Steuerle<br>
Josephine Tsao<br>
David M. Walker<br>
Murray Weidenbaum<p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a><br>
Executive Director<p>
Mark Weinberger<br>
Senior Advisor and Counsel<p>
</font></td><td valign=top>

<b><a name="structure">Organizational Structure</a></b><p>

	In order to provide credibility and visibility to the project, and to position the project's deliverables to be the basis of subsequent policy action, it is critical that this initiative be led by respected and knowledgeable leaders from both the public and private sectors.  CSIS will directly engage, on a bipartisan basis, leading members of Congress who have developed expertise in retirement issues, and with whom CSIS has long-established ties. <p>

	A critical aspect of the project will be the establishment of a high-level National Commission on Retirement Policy that will oversee the project.  Its leadership will include  key Members of Congress as Commission co-chairs: Senators Judd Gregg (R-NH) and John Breaux (D-LA), and Representatives Jim Kolbe (R-AZ) and Charles Stenholm (D-TX).  These members are ideally suited to lead this initiative.  Senator Gregg chairs the Senate Aging Subcommittee and will pick up the baton from former Senator Alan Simpson on Social Security reform.  In addition to serving in the Democratic leadership, Senator Breaux serves on the Finance Committee, which oversees Social Security and tax law.  Representatives Kolbe and Stenholm co-chair the House Pension Reform Caucus which has provided great leadership on this issue.  Two widely respected industry leaders, Donald B. Marron and Dr. Charles A. Sanders will serve as private sector co-chairs.  Mr. Marron is the chairman and chief executive officer of PaineWebber, Inc., one of the leading financial services firms in the country.  Dr. Sanders is the recently retired chairman of Glaxo, Inc, one of the world's largest pharmaceutical companies.  The Commission itself will be comprised of 15-20 business leaders and public policy experts from around the country.<p>

	<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, domestic policy director at CSIS, will be the executive director of the project.  He is former counsel to the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs and  also served as legislative director and general counsel to Senator John McCain.  Mr. Belt has written and lectured extensively on a wide-range of economic policy issues. Mark Weinberger, former chief of staff of the Bipartisan Commission on Entitlements and Tax Reform and chief tax counsel to former Senator Jack Danforth, will act as senior advisor and counsel to the project.  He has also written and lectured extensively on tax and economic policy issues.  They will be assisted by Greg D. Kubiak of the CSIS Domestic Policy program who previously worked as legislative director for Senator David Boren.<p>

	In addition to the direction from the Commission's Congressional and private sector leadership, the project will also draw upon the CSIS family of specialists and experts to assist with the effort, including the Center's Advisory Committee on Tax Replacement and the International Research Council.<p>


<b><a name="outreach">Public Education & Outreach</a></b><p>

	Critical to the success of this initiative -- in terms of ultimate policy impact -- is the design and implementation of  an aggressive outreach and public education campaign that will seek to inform the American electorate about the scope and magnitude of the problem and the costs and benefits of various policy options.  In this regard, the project will follow a three-pronged strategy: raise public awareness, stimulate dialogue for solutions, and build grassroots support on policy recommendations.  <p>

	Following establishment of the Commission, there will be an initial plenary meeting, open to the public and press, that will serve as the kick-off event for the project.  At this two-day symposium, recognized policy experts will discuss the critical issues that have to be addressed in order to avoid a systemic fiscal crisis.  These presentations will provide a broad review of the issues to be examined as the Commission prepares for the forums and roundtables that will take place around the country during the project's life span.<p>

	Approximately three to four months after the project's start, CSIS will raise public awareness with a pamphlet to graphically highlight the tremendous fiscal pressures associated with the pending retirement of the Baby Boom generation early in the next century.  This policy report will describe, in an easily comprehensible manner, the key economic and demographic trends that threaten to destabilize America's retirement system.  The format of the report ó from traditional brochure to the world wide web ó will be such that the general public will be able to understand the critical issues and challenges involved.  The ultimate goal will be to reach as broad an audience as possible, since retirement financing is a policy challenge that impacts everyone and requires a consensus for action that crosses both political and generational lines.<p>

	In a series of policy forums to be held around the country, the Commission will stimulate a public discourse about the issues relating to the retirement financing crisis and begin to build grassroots support for appropriate policy changes.  In regional forums and town hall meetings the project will involve diverse interests in building awareness and seeking politically realistic solutions to the challenges.  These will take place in the home state's of the Commission's Congressional leadership and other appropriate venues as a way to maximize media coverage.  The project will also raise the visibility of these issues "outside the Beltway" by engaging governors, state legislatures, mayors, and city councils in workshops, briefings, and seminars around the country. <p>

	Publications and media coverage will be an integral part of this entire process.  Experts and briefing materials should be made available to and through: talk radio, talk T.V., national news magazines, local newspapers, and the Internet.<p>


<b><a name="impact">Policy Impact</a></b><p>

	After building public support and knowledge and laying the intellectual foundation for consensus policy recommendations, the Commission will continue its deliberative process, working toward a final report with the goal of policy impact.  This essential element of the project will educate policymakers and opinion leaders about the issues.  To do this will require bridge-building between key constituencies and facilitating, coordinating, and leading current and new initiatives between CSIS programs and other outside organizations, including other think tanks and various trade and professional associations.<p>

	The substantive work of the Commission will be forums and roundtable discussions covering the full-range of issues on retirement financing, including the future of the pay-as-you-go Social Security system, the impending insolvency of the Medicare program, under funding and termination of certain corporate pension plans, the shift from defined benefit to defined contribution plans, and the inadequate levels of private saving and biases against such saving in the federal tax code.  The Commission will deliberate the issues and seek remedies and reforms that can be translated into legislation that can attract bi-partisan support and eventually be enacted.<p>

	With this final report, CSIS will aggressively promote the Commission's recommendations, much the way it did with its well-received <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/pubsecon.html#soa">Strengthening of America (SOA) Commission report</a>.  The release of the SOA Commission's report during the 1992 Presidential campaign served as a catalyst for the subsequent national policy debates on achieving a balanced budget by the year 2002 and replacing the current tax system with a new consumption-based tax system - two of the principal recommendations of the SOA Commission. <p>


<b><a name="timetable">Timetable</a></b><p>

	CSIS intends to announce the project during the early part of the first session of the 105th Congress.  The exact timing will depend on the arrangements and schedules of Congressional co-chairs and the agreement to participate by other Commission members.<p>

	By late March, the first plenary session with full Commission membership will take place in Washington, DC.  Its function will be to outline the issues and set forth the plans and objectives of the project.  The session will be a public hearing at which a variety of stakeholders and constituencies can discuss the magnitude of the crisis and provide input as to the appropriate course of action.  Working groups or subcommittees will be established and charged at this meeting.<p>


	In conjunction with or immediately following the first plenary session, CSIS will publish a descriptive brochure outlining the challenges to the future of retirement security.  The brochure will "paint the picture" of the impending crisis with  facts, figures, and graphic illustrations. <p>

	From late Summer through Fall 1997, the Commission will undertake a nationwide series of public forums to describe the challenges to retirement security and invite public input for potential solutions.  The Commission will then sponsor a series of public forums in Washington to examine the issues and policies affecting retirement in the 21st century.  This would occur between fall 1997 and January 1998.  Testimony will be taken from various experts in the field, covering each of the distinct components of the retirement financing crisis. <p>

	In Spring 1998, deliberative sessions of the Commission will be held to find consensus on a blueprint of legislative and policy options addressing retirement security.  It is then expected that by June 1998, a comprehensive, final report of the National Commission on Retirement Policy will be issued, with a strategic effort to maximize exposure to media outlets, Capitol Hill and the public.  Thereafter, CSIS will continue to monitor, follow-up and provide necessary leadership on the resulting recommendations from the Commission.<p>


<b><a name="plans">Plans for Continued Support</a></b><p>

	As with other similar initiatives, CSIS is committed to supporting the Commission's work on an on-going and active basis.  The CSIS Strengthening of America Commission is one example of the type of follow-through intended.  That commission was formed in January 1991, and its <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/pubsecon.html#soa">first report</a> released in September 1992.  As specific tax policy and health care reform recommendations were paramount in that report, two major reports were published to follow-up the effort:  <i><a href="http://www.csis.org/html/pubsheal.html#principles">Principles for Health Care Reform:  The Second Report of the CSIS Strengthening of America Commission</a></i> (April 1994); and <i><a href="http://www.csis.org/html/pubsecon.html#income">Replacing the Income Tax: Principles of a New Tax System</a></i> (January 1996).   Furthermore, the only, fully-conceptualized, bipartisan proposal to fundamentally reform the income tax was sponsored by the Commission's co-chairs, Senators Nunn and Domenici.  "The Unlimited Savings Allowance Tax of 1995," was co-sponsored by Senators Kerrey, Bennett and Dodd.  CSIS intends to be equally aggressive in pursuing appropriate policy changes.<p>

	In like manner, CSIS will continue to support the project's recommendations through activities that further the Commission's objectives.  This can be accomplished in a number of ways.  First, CSIS would maintain necessary working groups -- a gathering of experts from both within and outside of CSIS -- which would continue to study and monitor activities and issues associated with retirement security.  Furthermore, the CSIS Domestic Policy Program will continue to study the related issues and promote the ideals surrounding the Commission's goals.  This will occur through published studies and opinion/editorial pieces as well as policy forums and conferences.<p>


<b><a name="about">About CSIS</a></b><p>

	Over its 34-year history, CSIS has established a strong reputation tackling difficult national public policy challenges.  Pete Peterson, author of the acclaimed new book, <i>Will America Grow Up Before It Grows Old?</i>, recently stated that CSIS is uniquely well positioned to undertake a project of this kind to help think through the difficult transitions and form political coalitions critical to solving this problem.  First, we bring a track record of "policy impact" to the table.  It was CSIS that brought together the integral players, including four former Presidents and Secretaries of State, involved in the formation and passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) through our NAFTA and Beyond Commission. It was the CSIS Strengthening of America Commission that catalyzed the national policy debate on achieving a balanced budget by the year 2002 and replacing the current tax system.  There are numerous other efforts whose products can be seen in actions, recommendations and legislative proposals.<p>

	Second, CSIS has a reputation for bringing together recognized thinkers on critical domestic and international policy issues.  From the Congressional leadership already on-board this project to the diverse nature of other stakeholders, CSIS is well positioned to be a convener of experts and organizations and others to address this major challenge.  The involvement of bipartisan political leaders has long been a hallmark of CSIS policy work.  CSIS believes this effort must be broad-based, non-partisan, and independent to have the desired impact on policymakers.<p>

	Finally, and perhaps most importantly, this effort will look at the overall magnitude of the challenges to retirement security.  We enter this debate with no preconceived notions as to an outcome of the Commission's recommendations. While some policymakers and entities bring parochial views and narrow objectives to this debate, CSIS will look at the future of retirement in its totality.  Others limit their study to remedies for Social Security's insolvency, how tax reform might bolster savings, or other related issues.  The CSIS approach is panoramic, inclusive and aimed at policy impact.</td></tr> </table>
<HR width=300>

