<HTML>
<TITLE>CSIS Projects on the United States and the Federal
Government</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>

<H2><p align="center">Projects on the United States and 
the Federal Government</p>
</H2><HR>


<table cellpadding=20>
<tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">

<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#defense21">Defense for the Twenty-first Century</a><p>
<a href="#e4e">Enterprise for the Environment</a><p>
<a href="#fiscal">Fiscal Timebomb:</a> America's Looming Retirement Financing Crisis<p>
<a href="#milstrat">Military Strategy Forum</a><p>
<a href="#missile">Missile Defense:</a> Bridging Tomorrow's Technology Gaps Today<p>
<a href="#undersea">Strategic Assessment</a> of Twenty-first Century Undersea Warfare<p>
<a href="#soa">Strengthening of America Commission</a> - Chairman's Update<p>
<a href="#taxforum">Tax Policy Forum Series</a><p>
<a href="#dib">U.S. Defense Industrial Base:</a> "Restructuring the Base" Working Group<p>
<a href="#mdb">U.S. Policy</a> toward the Multilateral Development Banks (MDBs)<p>
<a href="#pme">U.S. Professional Military Education</a><p>
<a href="#incometax">U.S. Tax Policy</a> - Replacing the Income Tax<p>
<a href="#innercity">Using Military Capabilities</a> To Help Inner Cities/Urban Areas

</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="defense21">Defense for the Twenty-first Century</h3></a><p>
 This effort is organized into a four-dimension project intended to take a comprehensive look at what must be done to provide a credible, capable defense of the nation, its interests, and its friends. The first dimension of the project extends the Political-Military program's early, ground-breaking analysis of the ongoing defense budget crisis. The second dimension focuses on defining the U.S. defense posture for the next century, following on the work done by CSIS in conjunction with the former Congressional House Wednesday Group. The third dimension is a re-examination of the 1947 National Security Act determining what changes in structure, organization, and national security planning processes and management are needed to face new threats and obligations. The fourth dimension capitalizes on the work accomplished in the Information-Based Warfare project described on page 18.<p>
 <i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cambone.html">Stephen Cambone</a>, Senior Fellow, Political-Military Studies Program, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="e4e">Enterprise for the Environment</h3></a> CSIS has launched this project to engage key stakeholders (business, environmental, labor), experts, and political leaders in an effort to build a consensus on systemic reform of the nation's environmental management system, encompassing the activities of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, other levels of government, and the regulated community. In 1996 and 1997, the initiative will conduct its work through a series of conferences and action group meetings and will deliver recommendations to the next administration and Congress.<p>
 <i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fairban.html">Richard Fairbanks</a>, Managing Director, Domestic and International Issues, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hausker.html">Karl Hausker</a>, Project Director and Senior Fellow)</i><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2environ.html">For expanded coverage of Enterprise for the Environment</a>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="fiscal">Fiscal Timebomb: America's Looming Retirement Financing Crisis</a></h3> America's "baby boom" generation will begin to retire soon after the turn of the century, threatening the solvency of federal retirement programs, including Social Security and Medicare. When combined with the continued erosion of pension plans and inadequate levels of private savings, the ability of future retirees to meet their post-retirement expenses and live comfortably is in doubt. To address the major public policy challenge, CSIS proposes to launch a new major initiative under the leadership of leading private sector executives and key members of Congress that will highlight the urgency and magnitude of this problem and develop concrete policy recommendation. The project would examine in detail all aspects of the looming retirement financing crisis, including solvency of the Social Security and Medicare programs, ERISA, corporate pension plans, and private savings. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, Director, Domestic Policy Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="milstrat">Military Strategy Forum</a></h3>
 An ongoing series of meetings that give senior military leaders, policymakers, and academics the opportunity to present their views about present and future challenges to U.S. military
strategy. <p>
<i>(Lt Col David Mauldin, USMC, Visiting Military Fellow, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="missile">Missile Defense: Bridging Tomorrow's Technology Gaps Today</a></h3>
 CSIS has initiated a project that will study the technology needs of evolving missile defense architectures and identify international partners that can provide critical technologies in collaboration with the United States. In addition to receiving input from international partners, CSIS will explore congressional points of view on missile defense policy and technology and international collaboration.<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="undersea">Strategic Assessment of Twenty-first Century Undersea Warfare</a></h3>
The vast majority of submarine and undersea warfare analysis since the dissolution of the Soviet Union has focused on near-term trends and issues. This project will identify and assess long-term strategic trends to determine their potential impact on U.S. maritime and national security interests. The project will also assess the ability of the United States to counter future undersea threats to those interests and will suggest policy recommendations and undersea warfare force structure options to ensure their protection. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="soa">Strengthening of America Commission - Chairman's Update</a></h3>
The Chairmen of the CSIS Strengthening of America Commission, Senators Sam Nunn (D-GA) and Pete Domenici (R-NM), will publish a report that assesses (1) to what extent the challenges outlined in the Commission's First Report have been addressed, and (2) the progress that has been made in implementing the recommendations of the Commission.  Given that various circumstances have changed since the First Report was published, the Chairmen will also make new proposals in their update. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fairban.html">Richard L. Fairbanks</a>, Managing Director, Domestic and International Issues)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="taxforum">Tax Policy Forum Series</a></h3>
Through this series of roundtable discussion, CSIS brings together key policymakers, economists, business leaders, and tax experts to assess the impact that fundamental tax reform would have on specific industry sectors such as manufacturing, small business, financial services, and the housing industry. The forum also sponsored a debate by proponents of the leading tax reform alternatives, Senator Sam Nunn (D-GA), Senator Richard Lugar (R-IN), and House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-TX), and hosted a meeting of the Kemp Commission.  <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, Director, Domestic Policy Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="dib">U.S. Defense Industrial Base: "Restructuring the Base" Working Group</a></h3>
This group provides a monthly forum for industry leaders and policymakers to discuss the evolution of the nation's defense industrial base during this time of declining defense spending. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="mdb">U.S. Policy toward the Multilateral Development Banks (MDBs)</a></h3>
 The flow of official development assistance no longer conforms to the bipolar system of alliances. Moreover, public transfers have now been surpassed by private investment flows. To explore these changes and their implications, this project will generate a book-length critique of the U.S. policymaking process relating to the MDBs. In addition, the project will bring together policymakers in a task force cochaired by Senator Bill Bradley (D-NJ) and Representative John Kasich (R-OH) to look impartially at U.S. interests in the MDBs in terms of what MDB functions are currently needed and whether the MDBs are effectively performing them.  The task force will focus on two sets of issues about which significant concerns have been raised: (1) The ways and extent to which the functions of MDBs have changedóor should changeónow that private financial flows are much more readily available to developing countries that pursue sound policies; and (2) the role, if any, of the MDBs in poverty reduction and whether these institutions are currently pursuing effective strategies. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4upton.html">Barbara Upton</a>, Project Director, U.S. and the MDBs Task Force)
</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="pme">U.S. Professional Military Education</a></h3>
This initiative engages a panel of experts and leading citizens, chaired by former secretary of defense Dick Cheney, to address issues about the education of U.S. military officers. With the post-cold war reductions of U.S. military force structure, there is concern that investment in human capital, particularly officer education, may suffer to provide funding for other needs.<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4taylor.html">William J. Taylor, Jr.</a>, Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="incometax">U.S. Tax Policy - Replacing the Income Tax</a></h3>
 One of the principal recommendation of the CSIS Strengthening of America Commission was to replace the current federal income tax with a new consumption-based tax designed to encourage savings and investment. The Commission's work led to the introduction of the "Unlimited Savings Allowance" (USA) tax reform proposal in 1995 by Senators Pete Domenici (R-NM) and Sam Nunn (D-GA). CSIS continues to be actively involved in the national debate on fundamental tax reform. Members of the CSIS Advisory Committee on Tax Replacementórecognized experts on federal tax policyóregularly provide advice and counsel to members of Congress and groups such as the National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform (the Kemp Commission). CSIS has also published a major policy report entitled "Replacing the Income Tax: Principles for a New Tax System," which describes the basic principles that should guide the tax reform debate. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, Director, Domestic Policy Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="innercity">Using Military Capabilities To Help Inner Cities/Urban Areas</a></h3>
 This project addresses the potential use of U.S. military capabilities, particularly the Reserve and National Guard components, to address the nation's inner-city problems. The project focuses on several issues: what needs to be done in the inner cities, what specifically the military can offer directly and indirectly via its training institutions, how should military support be coordinated, and the likely implications of such efforts for both the military and society. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4taylor.html">William J. Taylor, Jr.</a>, Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i><p>
</td>

</tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:webmaster@csis.org">webmaster</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
</font>

