<HTML><TITLE>Pacific Forum CSIS Projects</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>
<H2><p align="center">Pacific Forum CSIS Projects</p></H2>
<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#change">Change and Renewal:</a> Japan-U.S. Security Relationship into the Twentieth-First Century<p>
<a href="#coop">Cooperation among Japan, China, and the United States</a> on East Asian Security<p>
<a href="#cscap">Council for Security Cooperation</a> in the Asia Pacific (CSCAP)<p>
<a href="#human">Human Smuggling:</a> The New Threat to America's Immigration Tradition<p>
<a href="#wiseman">Korea:</a> U.S.-Korea Wiseman Council<p>
<a href="#schina">Regional Implications</a> of Conflict in the South China Sea<p>
<a href="#usjapsec">Restructuring the U.S.-Japan Security Relationship</a><p>
<a href="#seniorsem">Senior Seminar on Asia-Pacific Security</a><p>


</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="change">Change and Renewal: Japan-U.S. Security Relationship into the Twentieth-First Century</a></h3>
The Pacific Forum CSIS, in collaboration with the Japan Institute for International Affairs, has convened two in a series of major conferences, in March 1995 and in January 1996, to address the viability and rationale of the bilateral relationship in the coming decade. Cochaired by James A. Kelly and Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga, the conference brings together leading policymakers and scholars to investigate security and economic issues affecting the U.S.-Japan alliance. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kelly.html">James A. Kelly</a>, President)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="coop">Cooperation among Japan, China, and the United States on East Asian Security</a></h3>
Through a series of working groups and multilateral conferences in Tokyo, Beijing, Washington, D.C., and Hawaii, this three-year project will help air national security policies and strategies of the three countries and attempt to shape a better understanding of the national policies that are necessary for peace and stability in Northeast Asia. The Forum is undertaking this joint project with the Research Institute for Peace and Security in Japan and the China Institute for International Strategic Studies. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kelly.html">James A. Kelly</a>, President)</i>

<p><hr><p> 

<h3><a name="cscap">Council for Security Cooperation in the Asia Pacific (CSCAP)</a></h3>
In June 1993, the Pacific Forum CSIS and nine East Asian policy research institutes established CSCAP as the first regionwide organization to promote multilateral security dialogue. Activities have included the establishment of broad-based member committees in each country and international working groups on topics such as confidence and security-building measures (CSBMs), maritime security, and cooperative security frameworks. In addition, the forum manages the U.S. CSCAP committee, which convenes biannually in Washington, D.C., and both the international working group and parallel U.S. task force on CSBMs, which also hold biannual meetings. The CSCAP Steering Committee meets biannually, usually in Kuala Lumpur. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cossa.html">Ralph A. Cossa</a>, Executive Director)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="human">Human Smuggling: The New Threat to America's Immigration Tradition</a></h3>
The growth of Asian migrant trafficking into the United States by smuggling organizations poses an array of problems that are too complex for law enforcement to solve alone. This project is examining the issues from a multidisciplinary perspective, including the "push" and "pull" factors of smuggling, as well as aspects of human rights, organized crime, international law, and U.S. immigration policy. Papers and analysis from a research conference convened in July 1996 will be published in a volume that sheds light on possible solutions. <p>
<i>(Paul Smith, Adjunct Fellow)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3>
<a name="wiseman">Korea: U.S.-Korea Wiseman Council</a></h3>
Co-organized by the Pacific Forum CSIS and the International Trade and Business Institute in Seoul, the council brings together a small, select group of senior individuals from both countries to exchange views and analyses on bilateral relations. The group's deliberations are conveyed to the Blue House and the White House and to cabinet secretaries. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4jordan.html">Amos A. Jordan</a>, President Emeritus and Counselor)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="schina">Regional Implications of Conflict in the South China Sea</a></h3>
Cosponsored by the Pacific Forum CSIS and the Manila-based Institute for Strategic and Development Studies, this project convenes experts from the region to examine the potential responses should military conflict occur between two or more of the six claimants to the Spratly Islands. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cossa.html">Ralph A. Cossa</a>, Executive Director)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="usjapsec">Restructuring the U.S.-Japan Security Relationship</a></h3>
This two-year project deals with the changing rationale in Japan and the United States for the U.S.-Japan security relationship, as well as changing views throughout East Asia on this issue. Cosponsored with the Okazaki Institute and the Policy Study Group, the project involves young economic and political leaders and journalists in a series of seminars and conferences in Hawaii, Tokyo, and Washington, DC. A series of seminars is ongoing in the United States and Japan, including most recently a major bilateral conference in Washington in May 1996 to be <i>followed by a conference in Tokyo in January 1997. <p>
(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4patters.html">Torkel Patterson</a>, Senior Associate)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="seniorsem">Senior Seminar on Asia-Pacific Security</a></h3>
This seminar, held annually in Hawaii since 1993, brings together more than 25 civilian and military officials from the defense and foreign affairs ministries throughout the region for a week of debate and analyses on regional security issues. The seminar features lectures by senior experts, a crisis game, and informal discussions with the goal of developing new ideas to enhance regional security and forge new links among regional decision-makers. The Forum cosponsored the most recent seminar in April 1996 with the East-West Center and the Asia-Pacific Center for Security Studies. <p>
<i>(Ralph A. Cossa, Executive Director)</i>




</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:webmaster@csis.org">webmaster</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
</font>

</BODY>
