<HTML><TITLE>Bradley D. Belt</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG border=0 align=right hspace=10 vspace=5
SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/5belt.gif">
<H2>BRADLEY D. BELT</H2>
Director<BR>
Domestic Policy Issues<BR>
International Financial Markets Project<P>
Office:  (202) 887-0200<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:beltb@csis.org">email: beltb@csis.org</A><HR>

Expertise:     Domestic economic policy; securities and banking
               law; capital markets and global finance;
               international competitiveness; legislative and
               regulatory process.<HR>

Bradley D. Belt is director of Domestic Policy Issues at CSIS, responsible for overseeing the Center's ongoing economic policy initiatives.  He is also director of the Center's capital markets project, which examines the financial markets regulation in the United States and abroad.  Mr. Belt came to CSIS from Capitol Hill where he served as minority counsel to the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs; minority chief counsel to the Securities Subcommittee; and legislative director and general counsel to Senator John McCain.  He also served in senior staff positions at the Securities and Exchange Commission, including counsel to Commissioner Charles Cox and special counsel to the Commission's mergers and acquisitions unit and has been in private practice as managing director and general counsel of the Commomwealth Group and president of the Washington Capital Group.  Mr. Belt has written and lectured on capital markets, regulatory, and legislative issues.  His recent articles include <I>From the Industrial Age to the Information Age: Rethinking the Regulation of Securities Markets</I> and <I>Replacing the Income Tax: Principles for a New Tax System</I>, and his op-eds have appeared in national publications such as <I>Barron's</I>, the <I>Christian Science Monitor</I>, <I>Investor's Business Daily</I>, the <I>Washington Post</I>, and the <I>Chicago Tribune</I>.  He received his law degree from Georgetown University, and is a member of the bar of the State of New York, District of Columbia, and U.S. Supreme Court.
<HR>


<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a></BODY></HTML>

