<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3newseve.gif"></p><BR>
<H1>Press Advisories</H1>



For Information Contact:<BR>
Nancy Nugent <BR>
(202)775-3176<BR>
<A HREF="mailto: nfn@csis.org">email: nfn@csis.org</A><HR>

<P>


	<h2><p align="center">CSIS and Congress Announce <br>The National Commission on Retirement Policy</p></h2>


<b>WHAT:</b>		<blockquote>CSIS will announce the establishment of a bipartisan <a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/">National Commission on Retirement Policy</a> comprising leaders from the public and private sectors.  The Commission will address the retirement financing challenge facing the United States.</blockquote>

<b>WHO:</b>		<blockquote><i>Congressional co-chairs:</i><br>

			Senator Judd Gregg (R-NH)<br>
			Senator John Breaux (D-LA)<br>
			Representative Jim Kolbe (R-AZ)<br>
			Representative Charles W. Stenholm (D-TX)<p>

			<i>Private sector co-chairs:</i><br>

			Donald B. Marron, Chairman and CEO, PaineWebber<br>
			Charles A. Sanders, Europa Center<p>

			<i>Executive Director:</i><br>

			<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Brad Belt</a>, Director, CSIS Domestic Policy Studies<p>

			<i>Senior Adviser and Counsel:</i><br>

			Mark Weinberger, Partner, Washington Counsel, P.C.</blockquote>

<b>WHEN:</b>		<blockquote>Wednesday, January 29, 1997<br>
			9:30 a.m.- 10:30 a.m.</blockquote>



<b>WHERE:</b>		<blockquote>U.S. Capitol<br>
			HC6</blockquote>

<b>WHY:</b>		<blockquote>How the United States will finance the future care of its senior citizens, especially when the Baby Boom generation begins to retire, is the most important and pressing public policy challenge facing the country.  Though several proposals have been advanced to address aspects of the retirement financing crisis, there is not yet a consensus on an appropriate and politically achievable course of action.<p>

			The mission of the National Commission on Retirement Policy is to build this consensus.  Guided by strong, bipartisan leadership from Capitol Hill and distinctive expertise from Commission members, the Commission will hold a series of roundtables, conferences, and townhall meetings in Washington and around the country.  It will seek to engage all affected constituencies, special interests, and the American public in a national debate about the scope and magnitude of the challenge facing the nation.</blockquote>
<p>

	<b>WASHINGTON, DC, JANUARY 29 --</b>  CSIS announced today the formation of the National Commission on Retirement Policy, a panel to be headed by strong, bipartisan leadership from both houses of Congress as well as leaders from the private sector.   The Commission will focus on four primary goals during its 18-month mission, as outlined at a U.S. Capitol press conference.  (1)  It will facilitate discussion of retirement financing issues among policymakers, experts, and stakeholders; (2)  activate a public education campaign about those issues; (3)  analyze policy options to address the impending crisis; and, (4)  build a political consensus around a blueprint of recommendations on what must be done.<p>

	"This challenge cannot be met without strong, bipartisan leadership," said CSIS President <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4abshire.html"></a>David Abshire regarding the Commission's formation, "and we have that with the four Members of Congress who will help lead this effort."  Serving as Congressional co-chairs will be Senator Judd Gregg (R-NH), Chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Aging and Chair of the Republican Retirement Security Task Force; Senator John Breaux (D-LA), Deputy Democratic Whip and Finance Committee member; and Representatives Jim Kolbe (R-AZ) and Charles Stenholm (D-TX).  Kolbe and Stenholm co-chair the 40-member bipartisan Public Pension Reform Caucus, which they founded in August 1995.<p>

	Joining the Members of Congress, as private sector co-chairs, will be Donald B. Marron, Chairman and CEO of Paine Webber Group Inc. and Dr. Charles A. Sanders, retired Chairman of Glaxo, Inc.  Mr. Marron noted, "Social Security as currently structured will soon fall victim to a powerful shift in demographics.  Our aim is to focus on public education and bipartisan legislative action that will reform the current system into an economically viable safety net for all Americans."  Mr. Marron brings over 45 years of leadership in the financial industry to the Commission.  His record of public service includes affiliations with such entities as the Council on Foreign Relations, Inc., the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, the Museum of Modern Art, the President's Private Sector Survey conducted by the Grace Commission and the New York Governor's Council on State Priorities.<p>

	Likewise, Dr. Sanders, brings established leadership credentials and a long record of public service to the Commission.  Dr. Sanders said, "The timebomb of our Social Security system, combined with our poor savings habits, threatens the promise of a secure retirement for our grandchildren and their children.  This initiative provides the means by which they may look forward to as good or better retirement than this generation will have."<p>

	The National Commission on Retirement Policy will hold a series of policy forums around the country to stimulate a public discourse about the retirement financing crisis and to build grassroots support for policy changes.  These and other mediums to raise the visibility of retirement issues will be a central focus of the project.<p>
	The objective, according to <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, director of domestic policy at CSIS and the executive director of the Commission, is "to engage the American public, special interest groups, and all affected constituencies in a national debate on these issues."  The basic problem, he said, is that, "The government has promised too much and Americans are saving too little."  Noting that the imminent retirement of the Baby Boom generation and increasing life expectancy will strain the federal budget with higher Social Security and entitlement spending, Mr. Belt said, "It is critical that we begin to address our long-term structural deficit now rather than later." <p> 

	In a speech late last year, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan also pointed out the need to work on the challenge now. "We owe it to those who will retire after the turn of the century to be given sufficient advance notice to make what alterations in retirement planning may be required."  Mr. Greenspan continued, "The longer we wait to make what are surely inevitable adjustments, the more difficult they will become."	<p>

	While other efforts and recommendations have addressed Social Security's pending insolvency and other aspects of retirement policy, the initiative by CSIS brings new hope to the mammoth challenge.  First, it brings together a bipartisan commission of leaders and experts on retirement issues who will look at practical and politically viable solutions.  Second, it will study the entire range of issues impacting retirement income: Social Security, pensions, and personal savings.  And finally, after promoting broad-based educational initiatives to heighten awareness and after analyzing the constructive approaches forwarded by special interest groups and general members of the Social Security constituency, the commission will seek to forge the political consensus necessary to effect a comprehensive, responsibly funded retirement policy for the 21st century.<p>

	An Internet website has been established for the CSIS project and the National Commission on Retirement Policy: <a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/">http://www.csis.org/retire/</a><p>

	CSIS is a public policy research institution whose mission is policy impact.  It is located in Washington, D.C., with an affiliated Pacific Forum CSIS office in Honolulu.  Founded in 1962, CSIS now has a resident staff of 180.  Its work is nonpartisan and nonproprietary.<P>


