<td valign=top>


<h3><a name="bridge">The China Telecom Bridge Project</a></h3> The project includes research, analysis, forums, and briefings on specific aspects of China's complex telecommunications, broadcast and computer-based technology, and service issues. It is unique in that it actively involves hands-on, senior-level Chinese officials with diverse international communications industry expertsótwo parties that have a stake in the role of communications in China's economic development. The project helped to create the Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development (CIIED), the first independent, nonpartisan research institution established in China involving policy experts from both Chinese government agencies and the international communications industry. CIIED is overseen by the International Advisory Board, cochaired by Dr. Liu Guoguang of CASS and Diana Lady Dougan of CSIS. The Advisory and Governing Boards are composed of key officials from the relevant Chinese ministries and commissions and diverse international communication industry leaders. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4dougan.html">Diana Lady Dougan</a>, Senior Adviser and Chair, International Communications Program)</i><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2bridge.html">For more on the <i>China Telecom Bridge Project</i></a>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="chinfut">China's Future: Implications for the United States, Europe, and Japan</a></h3>
The restructuring of China's agricultural system is the main topic of this new project. The study will assess the current and future impact of China's agricultural policy reforms on Chinese political and economic stability. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hartlan.html">Penelope Hartland-Thunberg</a>, Senior Associate, International Business and Economics Program) </i><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2chinfut.html">For more on the <i>China'S Future</i></a>
<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="vietcong">Congressional Working Group on Vietnam and Southeast Asia</a></h3>
Under strong congressional leadership, this group meets on Capitol Hill to discuss the merits of different policy approaches to developments in Southeast Asia and Vietnam, as well as regional dynamics involving the fast-growing political economies of Southeast Asia. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair in China Studies and Director, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="eastasia">East Asia Working Group</a></h3>
This group covers issues in the Pacific Rim, including the Korean peninsula, China, Taiwan, Japan, and the countries that constitute ASEAN. Issues addressed include strategic and regional military concerns in the context of economic and political trends. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4taylor.html">William J. Taylor, Jr.</a>, Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="easiafin">East Asia's Economic and Financial Future</a></h3>
The first three monographs in this series invited leading economists from Beijing, Taipei, and Hong Kong to develop regional comparisons through a cross-analysis of global and regional economic contingencies and competitive strategies from their respective perspectives. The findings were presented to congressional and executive branch decision-makers, corporate leaders, and others in the Washington policy community in March 1995. CSIS will continue the series with monographs on other Asian countries. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair in China Studies and Director, Asian Studies Program, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik Peterson</a>, Vice President and Director of Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="global">Global Dimensions of U.S.-Japan Relations</a></h3>
This briefing series attempts to provide a forum of information and discussion on global issues that affect Japan as well as U.S.-Japan relations. Speakers are selected from CSIS and Pacific Forum CSIS specialists. <p>
<i>(William Breer, Japan Chair)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="hongkong">Hong Kong Core Group</a></h3>
In light of significant U.S. interests in Hong Kong, CSIS is launching this new initiative to broaden and deepen U.S., China, and Hong Kong personal and professional ties prior to, during, and after the transition. In the interest of greater mutual understanding and to identify and target specific issues, the Core Group will contribute to advancing U.S.-China-Hong Kong relations; review Hong Kong's transition, including developments in its economic prospects and investment climate, legal system, and civil service; and present findings through the full CSIS network involving a diverse group of policymakers, congressional representatives, business leaders, and policy experts. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="indicong">India: Congressional Task Force</a></h3>
The CSIS India Program and the India Caucus of the U.S. House of Representatives have created a task force on India to educate members and staff, disseminate information, and deliberate on issues related to India and the Indo-U.S. relationship. In February 1996, the Task Force hosted a meeting on Indo-Chinese relations that featured Ambassador William Clark, Jr., Representatives Frank Pallone, Bill McCollum, and Sherrod Brown, and Ambassador Chas Freeman, former U.S. assistant secretary of defense. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4clark.html">William Clark, Jr.</a>, Senior Adviser on Asia and Director, India Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="indiecon">India: CSIS India Economic Watch</a></h3>
The watch is an economic analysis report providing a comprehensive overview of Indian domestic and international economic indicators. The report is designed to provide real-time insight into the impact of a given situation or development and examines both short- and long-term effects on India's domestic scene and its international standing. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4clark.html">William Clark, Jr.</a>, Senior Adviser on Asia and Director, India Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="indiamtg">India Meeting Series</a></h3>
The India Program regularly brings together diverse groups of individuals from the policy community, corporations, academia, the media, and other interest groups to participate in meetings with visiting senior Indian officials, South Asia experts, and interest group representatives. Recent speakers have included Harvard University professor Jeffrey Sachs, Indian National Human Rights Commissioner Ranganath Misra, Under Secretary of State for Arms Control and International Security Lynn Davis, and the Sri Lankan and Japanese ambassadors to the United States, Jayantha Dhan<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4clark.html">apala and Takakazu Kuriyama. <p>
<i>(William Clark, Jr.</a>, Senior Adviser on Asia and Director, India Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="japcong">Japan: Congressional Staff Working Group</a></h3>
Created in 1989, the CSIS Congressional Staff Working Group on Japan brings together more than 70 senior congressional staff members and executive branch officials bimonthly to help improve interagency dialogue within the U.S. government through expert briefings on a wide range of U.S.-Japan issues. <p>
<i>(William Breer, Japan Chair)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="koreapen">Korean Peninsula Developments</a></h3>
The CSIS Asian Studies Program, together with the Seoul-based Research Institute for National Unification and other leading Korean research institutes, will continue a series of meetings focusing on trends and developments on the Korean peninsula, including the U.S.-North Korea Agreed Framework, North-South talks, and the prospects for Korean reunification. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program)
</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="indiapol">Political Almanac on India</a></h3>
The composition of the new government in India reflects the dramatic shifts that have been taking place within the Indian landscape during the last decade, particularly the shift of political power from the center to the states. Given the complexity of Indian politics, the India program will produce a comprehensive, yet simple, political almanac of Indian politics, which will provide a useful reference source for those in the business community interested in investing in India. The almanac will describe the main national and regional political players and also analyze the political trends that have emerged in recent years at both the national and state levels and what they portend for the future. The main focus will be on state-level government, as these are the institutions that businesses will deal with when investing. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4clark.html">William Clark, Jr.</a>, Senior Adviser on Asia and Director, India Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="prcseminar">PRC, Hong Kong, and Taiwan Seminars</a></h3>
Frequent seminars, with participation from policy experts and business leaders from Hong Kong, Taiwan, the PRC, and Washington, D.C., monitor domestic issues and developments in Hong Kong, Taiwan, and the PRCóand U.S. policy toward them. Major topics include the 1997 transition in Hong Kong, cross-Strait relations, economic and political developments in the PRC, and U.S.-China relations. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies, and Karen Wong, China Projects Coordinator, Asian Studies Program)
</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="sasia">South Asian Corporate Roundtable</a></h3>
Composed of corporate representatives with an interest in India, the Roundtable meets bimonthly in Washington, D.C., to discuss issues related to India with leaders from the political, legislative, diplomatic, academic, and business communities. Each meeting features a given theme and also serves as a resource for participants by providing an informal opportunity to raise issues of concern. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4clark.html">William Clark, Jr.</a>, Senior Adviser on Asia and Director, India Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="taipei">Taipei Roundtable</a></h3>
CSIS will continue its Taipei Roundtable series in 1997 at the request of a group of Taiwan business leaders. The Roundtable provides a forum for CSIS experts, government officials, business leaders, and scholars in Taiwan to work through current U.S. and Taiwan issues relating to U.S.-China relations, U.S. policy toward Asia, and developments in the PRC and Hong Kong. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<h3><a name="uschina">U.S. China Policy Task Force</a></h3>
The Task Force analyzes legislative, executive, business, and Washington policy community perspectives to determine a policy structure that could serve as the framework for U.S.-China relations in the coming decade. It is cochaired by Senators Max Baucus (D-MT), Frank Murkowski (R-AK), and Charles Robb (D-VA); Representative Jim Kolbe (R-AZ); Harold Brown, CSIS counselor and former secretary of defense; and James Fligg, executive vice president of the Amoco Corporation. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program, and Karen Wong, China Projects Coordinator, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="uschong">U.S.-Chongqing Task Force on Energy/Environmental Technology Cooperation</a></h3>
The continued rapid growth of China's economy and population creates great challenges for energy and the environment. The Chongqing Task Force, established by CSIS and the National Bureau of Asian Research, will bring together U.S. private sector and government leaders with officials and planners in Chongqing and representatives of international agencies to identify and implement practical solutions to problems facing this major Chinese city. Chongqing (formerly Chungling) situated in Sichuan province, currently suffers from severe power shortages and air and water pollution. The city is due to be elevated to its own provincial status in the spring of 1997. The Task Force will be cochaired by Amos A. Jordan, president emeritus of CSIS, and Mayor Zhang Delin, Communist Party Secretary for Chongqing. The congressional chairs are Representatives Jim McDermott (D-WA) and Jennifer Dunn (R-WA).<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4wendt.html">David Wendt</a>, CSIS Fellow in Global Issues)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="usrokrel">U.S.-ROK Relations Task Force</a></h3>
Senator William V. Roth, Jr. (R-DE); Representatives Gary Ackerman (D-NY), Christopher Cox (R-CA), and John P. Murtha (D-PA); and David Roderick, chairman emeritus of the U.S.-ROK Business Council, chair this effort to assess how the United States might best strengthen relations with the ROK, given heightened security concerns, changing global trade environment, and South Korea's ongoing democratization. This group meets regularly with business leaders and Korea specialists to discuss the U.S.-North Korea Agreed Framework and North-South dialogue.<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="usroksec">U.S.-ROK Security Issues</a></h3>
This group performs continuing analyses of evolving near- and long-term threats to U.S. and ROK interests on and around the Korean peninsula and develops recommendations to counter those threats. Recent emphasis has been on the nature of the North Korean military threat in the context of a disastrous economy and pending widespread famine, progress on the nuclear Agreed Framework, and the potential for North Korean acceptance of proposed Four Party Talks. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4taylor.html">William J. Taylor, Jr.</a>, Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="ussing">U.S.-Singapore Consultative Group</a></h3>
CSIS established this senior-level consultative group to facilitate constructive interchange among leading figures in Singapore and the United States. As political and economic developments in both countries continue to converge, this bilateral group has created an alternative channel of discussion for potentially sensitive issues. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Freeman Chair and Director, Asian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="vietaids">Vietnam: HIV/AIDS Prevention</a></h3>
Building on the report of a CSIS working group on global AIDS and responding to the growing HIV/AIDS epidemic in Southeast Asia, CSIS is organizing a U.S.-Japan-Vietnam study group on AIDS prevention in Vietnam. The group will bring together senior U.S., Japanese, and Vietnamese policymakers and private sector leaders to examine policy challenges related to the spread of HIV/AIDS in Vietnam and to develop a strategy for international support of Vietnam's response. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4wendt.html">David A. Wendt</a>, CSIS Fellow in Global Issues)</i>
</td></tr></table>


