<html><TITLE>Christopher "Ryan" Henry</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2><B>CHRISTOPHER HENRY</B></H2>
Senior Fellow<BR>
Politcal-Military Studies<P>
Office: (202) 887-0200<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:ryan@csis.org">email: ryan@csis.org</A><HR>

Expertise: Information technology; national security; military operations.
<HR>

Captain Christopher "Ryan" Henry currently heads the Information-Based Warfare Study as CSIS.  Capt. Henry's professional career spans 2 wars and 24 years of vigorous involvement in national security, warfare analysis,  appropriations process, operational
 activities, RDT&E and the academic aspects of naval service.  Over the past five years he conducted work in the fields of national security, legislation, public policy, critical technology development, program management, and military operations.<P>

Born in 1950, Capt. Henry graduated from the Naval Academy, earning a Bachelor of Science Degree (with distinction) in 1972.  He subsequently acquired Masters of Science Degrees in Aeronautical Systems (1974), Systems Management (1981), National Security 
Resourcing (1992) and a Masters of Public Administration (1995).  He is presently completing his doctoral dissertation in Public Policy.  His published articles are in the field of transformal technologies, naval operations, grand strategy, force structur
e, national resources, public policy, advanced manufacturing and experimental flight testing.  He is a distinguished graduate of both the US Navy Test Pilot School and the National Defense University where he won the Armyís Award for Outstanding Researche
r in a Senior Service School.<P>

Capt. Henryís five sea tours include eight extended deployments to:  the South China Sea during the Vietnam War; the Western Pacific, Indian Ocean and North Arabian Sea; and the Arabian Gulf during Desert Shield/Storm.   His has extensive experience with 
the maintenance and operation of naval guns, missiles, and aircraft; the warfare training of flight crews; and the leadership of sailors and officers.  His squadron pioneered numerous operational capabilities, set an unprecedented number of performance re
cords, and won the first ever sweep of all 12 competitive awards for which it was eligible.<P>

During shore duty assignments Capt. Henry served as: 1) a Professional Staffer on the Senate Appropriations Committee, 2) the Advanced Research Projects Agencyís Information Systems Architect and 3) Manager of Special Programs; 4) an experimental test pil
ot, 5) the head of the Naval Air Test Centerís Sea-Strike Division Head and 6) Deputy Commander for Force Warfare Integration; and 7) the first commanding officer of the Sea-Based Weapons and Tactics School.<P> 

 In 1983 Capt. Henry was selected as the Navy's Test Pilot of the Year, selected as the Navyís astronaut candidate, honored as winner of the Adm. O'Neill Award, and selected as Junior Officer of the Year. He was the only member of the naval service to be 
selected as a National Finalist for a White House Fellowship in 1984. Capt. Henry has been awarded the Legion of Merit, Bronze Star (with combat V), Meritorious Service Medal, Individual Air Medal (three), Strike Flight Air Medal (two), Navy Commendation 
Medal (three), Navy Achievement Medal (two), and numerous combat, campaign, and unit citation awards. 

<HR>


