<html><TITLE>Ralph A. Cossa</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG border=0 align=right hspace=10 vspace=5 
SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/5cossa.gif"><H2><B>RALPH A. COSSA</H2></B>
Executive Director<BR>
Pacific Forum/CSIS<P>
Office:<BR>
(From the continental U.S.) (800) 628-5353<BR>
     (From Hawaii or overseas) (808) 521-6745<HR>

Expertise:     Asian security issues; U.S.-Asia policy and 
military developments; Northeast and Southeast Asia
 political-military and economic affairs; Middle 
East and Southwest Asian security affairs; Russian-Asian/Third World policies; U.S. national security affairs and strategy development.<HR>

A retired USAF colonel and political-military affairs specialist, Mr. Cossa joined the Pacific Forum in 1993 and, among other projects, manages various activities of the Council for Security Cooperation in the Asia-Pacific (CSCAP).  His last active duty position was as director of a special study group that assisted the commander in chief, U.S. Pacific Command (USCINCPAC) in the formulation and articulation of national security policy and strategy for the Asia-Pacific-Indian Ocean regions.  He previously served as chief of the USCINCPAC policy division and, in earlier assignments, was an executive assistant to two other USCINCPACs.  A former national security affairs fellow at the Hoover Institution and deputy director for strategic studies at the Institute for National Strategic Studies, Cossa has written and lectured widely on Asia-Pacific and Middle East/Southwest Asian security issues and is the editor of several volumes, most recently <I>Confidence and Security Building Measures in the Asia Pacific</I> (CSIS Significant Issue Series, 1994).  He holds a B.A. in international relations from Syracuse University, an M.S. in strategic studies from the Defense Intelligence College, and an M.B.A. in management from Pepperdine University.
