<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 19,

December 10, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Subcontinental Divide</h1>

<h3>India has a bright economic future, but faces cloudy days in the interim . . .</h3>

 
Despite efforts by the United Front government to maintain growth since it took office six months ago, the Indian economy appears to have entered a protracted downturn.  According to CSIS India Project scholars, macroeconomic conditions in India tell the tale of an ailing economy struggling with declining production, a sagging export market, overburdened infrastructure, and a rising fiscal deficit.<p>  

Currently, the government's total domestic liabilities account for 58.8% of GDP, while some 46% of fiscal revenues are consumed by debt servicing.  Although generally cited at 5.7% of GDP, India's fiscal deficit is actually in the neighborhood of 10% of GDP when the country's federal, state, and public sectors are combined.  The trade deficit is expected to rise from $4.5 billion to more than $7 billion in 1996-97. <p>

Unchecked government spending continues to consume much of India's available domestic capital, in turn pushing interest rates higher and causing  experts to warn of an impending debt trap.  India's rate of inflation(hovering around 6.35%) is also on the rise, fueled by government spending and long-overdue price corrections, such as the government's recent hike in petroleum prices. <p>

<b>Industrial Growth:</b> Despite a buoyant 25% growth in turnover and profits last year, corporate India's meteoric expansion in 1995 was financed on borrowed time. With other critical macroeconomic fundamentals also depressed -- including low consumer demand, limited capital, and an overburdened infrastructure -- Indian industry found itself at the start of the current fiscal year with piling inventories and overdue receivables.<p>

<b>Exports:</b> Overall growth of Indian exports recorded a sharp drop in the first part of FY1996 declining to 9.8% for April-August 1996 compared with 30% for the same period last year.  For example, export of computer software fell to $10.2 million in April 1996, down some 63% from the corresponding figure of $27.4 million last year.  Based on the latest data, the Center for Monitoring the Indian Economy predicts that overall Indian exports will decline from 21% in 1995-96 to 13%.<p>

<b>Investment:</b> With the prospect of slower than expected growth prompting share sell-off, the BSE's benchmark index has lost nearly a quarter of its value since touching a high this past June.  In particular, foreign institutional investment (FII) dropped 25% for April-August 1996, the largest sell-off since India's economic reforms began.  In a recent report by Morgan Stanley, India ranked among the weakest emerging economies, down 8.2% in September and down more than 17% for the third quarter.  With India in need of some $8 billion in infrastructure investment this year alone, market conditions could well impede efforts to remove one of the principal impediments to the vitality of the Indian economy.<p>

Nonetheless, the United Front has taken a number of positive actions to attract investment and improve economic growth:  <p>

<ul><li>The Reserve Bank of India announced a 2% cut in the bank Cash Reserve Requirement, which will release $2.4 billion into the banking system over the next four months.  
<li>The government has cleared more than 500 projects consisting of foreign direct investment (FDI) worth $4 billion.
<li>In an attempt to lower the fiscal deficit, the United Front is pushing  public sector disinvestment, hoping to raise a budgeted target of around $1.4 billion in FY 1996-1997.  Many believe, however, that even half this target may not be met.</ul> <p>
    
In 1996, India is expected to receive FII inflows of  $3.5 billion, half the total inflows since financial markets were opened to FII in 1993.  Recent anouncements allow for investment by individual FIIs of up to 10% of the equity capital of investee companies, investment in unlisted companies, and an easing of restrictions on investments by FIIs in debt securities.<p>

Though the United Front government's stability and commitment to reform is still uncertain,  some analysts maintain that India's economic outlook is very positive.  Despite the slight slowdown, they note, the economy is fundamentally strong, exhibiting a trend toward better integration into global markets and an ability to attract significant FDI and FII in the coming years.
<p><hr>


<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

