<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 14,

May 14, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>To Helms-Burton and Back</h1>

<h3>Two interpretations of America's Cuba policy</h3>

Two CSIS scholars are at loggerheads over the recent passing of the Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity (LIBERTAD) Act of 1996 -- better known as the Helms-Burton Act. The bill, which tightens the economic sanctions against Cuba, is particularly controversial for its extraterritorial nature.  Ambassador Ernest Preeg doubts the legality and economic wisdom of the bill, while Dr. Georges Fauriol, director of the Latin American Studies program, believes it is a solid strike against the Castro regime.<P>

The bill has a number of notable provisions, which include the following:<P>

<UL><LI>   Title III, which  "makes any person that traffics in property confiscated by the Cuban Government on or after January 1, 1959 liable for money damages to any U.S. national who owns claims to such property."  The pressing question is how the term "trafficking" will be interpreted.  Preeg believes it will be defined as any new investment or expansion of an existing investment that occurs after passage of the bill (which became law on March 12).  It is estimated that Title III could bring billions of dollars in lawsuits to the courts.  The president, though, has the right to waive this for six months at a time in the name of national interest.  His timing will be significant in regard to the Cuban-American vote.  He could either waive the provision immediately or allow a few cases to begin beforehand to score points in Florida.<P>

<LI>   Title IV, which stipulates that any person (or immediate family) trafficking in the aforementioned property will be denied entry into the United States.  The rule could affect numerous businessmen, as well as many students currently in the United States.<P>

<LI>   Title I, the Russian aid provision.  It states that if the Russian government continues funding of a nuclear reactor or an intelligence listening station in Lourdes, Cuba, the United States will cut aid to Russia.  The president also can waive this provision within 90 days of passage, which he may well do so as not to enflame nationalist passions before Russia's June elections.<P></UL>

Preeg is concerned about the bill on a number of counts.  First, he thinks the extraterritoriality of the
bill is contrary to both WTO and NAFTA commitments.  The consequences will result in a loss of political clout and economic bargaining power in the global trading system. Already, Canada, Mexico, and many EU countries have threatened to retaliate. <P>

Although Helms-Burton will restrain investment by foreign companies, Preeg maintains it will have little effect on Castro's political control. In fact, Castro has seized the moment to whip up anti-American fervor on the island.  He has reigned in reforms and further repressed human rights.  This in turn increases the likelihood of violent transition in Cuba.<P>

In general, Preeg fears that Helms-Burton will only shackle U.S. foreign policy to a hard line stance, at the loss of U.S. business and political maneuverability.<P>

By contrast, Georges Fauriol views Helms-Burton as a sage political move.  Although the bill may not speed Castro's departure, it will force companies to decide between trading with the United States, the largest economy in the world, and a poor island of 11 million people operating under the failed doctrine of communism.  The diminutive size of the Cuban economy only reinforces the point, he asserts, that a few business opportunities should not affect U.S. foreign policy.<P>
Fauriol believes that the sanctions will only increase pressure on Castro, whom he perceives as having no real interest in improving relations with the United States.  Helms-Burton will further strain Cuba's ability to interact with the rest of the world, leading only to further isolation.  He doubts Cubans will gladly accept that predicament.  Although there is political support for Castro, it "doesn't mean there's a mandate to lead Cuba into the dark ages."<P>

He also foresees no long-term ill effects for the United States from the bill.  In spite of all the U.S.-Cuba tension of the past three decades, the United States remains a source of political prestige throughout Latin America.  What bitterness the United States may have engendered with Helms-Burton will quickly be swept away by the economic opportunities after Castro.<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 5/14/96</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

