<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 18,

October 22, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Retooling in Africa</h1>

<h3>Perspectives on Zambian financial reform . . .</h3>


Can Zambia reverse its economic downswing to develop a successful market economy?  Judging from recent meetings hosted by the CSIS African Studies program, there are indications of hope. <B>Dr. Jacob Mwanza</B>, governor of the Central Bank of Zambia, commented on the state of affairs in his country's institutions, with varying levels of good news to report.<P>

Zambia's economic progress in the last five years is surprising.  When <B>Frederick Chiluba</B> took power in 1991, the government owned nearly 80% of the economy, the (hyper)inflation rate was hovering around 100%, the budget deficit was 12% of GDP, external debt was $7.1 billion and the country was stifled by price controls.  The new government attacked the myriad of economic obstacles with determination.  It created a flexible, easily administered tax code and established the Zambian Revenue Authority to collect taxes more effectively.  Top corporate and income tax rates were cut roughly in half, from 60% and 65% to 30% and 35%, respectively.  Tariffs were standardized and reduced, with maximum rates falling from 150% to 40%. <P>

Monetary policies were revamped.  Interest and exchange rates, once dictated by state policy, are now determined by the market.  The Central Bank significantly streamlined its operations, cutting its staff by 50%.  At the same time, the Banking and Financial Services Act expanded Central Bank authority to regulate the country's commercial banks.<P>

The fruits of reform began to appear in 1996: tax revenue collection tripled, and Zambia's persistent deficit turned into a surplus of 0.6% of GDP.  But none of these reforms will continue to produce results without capital, and capital means privatization.  The Zambian government has made a good start.  More than 140 formerly state-owned companies -- including sugar, cement, and beer companies -- have been privatized in the last two years.  Even Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, the largest parastatal firm, is being sold to private
interests.  The government is beginning to improve the attractiveness of the investment climate -- whether it is enough to steady the nation's economy remains debatable.<P>

The state of affairs on the political side of the equation is not as encouraging.  Presidential elections will be held on November 18, and <B>Kenneth Kaunda</B>, the six-time former president and founder of independent Zambia, will be a strong contender if he is allowed to run.  His popularity stems from the people's disillusionment with the government's austere  economic reforms -- not from any successes he had in the waning years of his reign.  Nonetheless, the question of his candidacy may be moot. A recently passed law decrees that all presidential nominees must be third-generation Zambians -- and Kaunda's parents came from Malawi.  Such political wrangling has caused international criticism of Chiluba, leading some countries to withhold aid. <P>

Mwanza stated that the decisions confronting the new Chiluba government were stark. Economic reforms contributed to high unemployment and an increase in the cost of living for the poor, but the choice between continued drift with even greater poverty and reform with the hope of recovery was clear: reforms had to be undertaken whatever the short-term cost.  Now, as inflation has fallen to 28 percent and external debt has decreased to $6.2 billion, Zambia aspires to complete its transition to a full-fledged market economy.  With the economy forecast to grow 5.4% in 1996, aspirations may well become reality.  The country has made an amazing economic turnaround, according to <A HREF="http://www.csis.org/html/4freeman.html"><B>Constance J. Freeman</B></A>, director of African Studies at CSIS.  But it is not the first time it has done so.  Staying the course will be key and investors are acutely aware of that.

<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 10/29/96</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

