<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 15,

June 24, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Requiem for the Intermediary?</h1>

<h3>Wall Street faces its future at a CSIS conference on finance & technology</h3>

We are about to witness a paradigm shift of proportions similar to that accompanying the introduction of the telephone, posited SEC Commissioner Steven Wallman during a recent CSIS conference on the intersection of finance and technology.  <P>

What has caused this shift?  The answer is information technology.  It has the potential to revise the way investors manage their money, how brokerage houses operate, how capital is mobilized, and how government regulates. Furthermore, the Internet is the first example of two-way mass communications - it combines the telephone's interactivity with the television's ability to transmit information to an audience of millions.  With it, huge amounts of data can be relayed around the globe instantaneously. <P>

<I>Infotech influx.</I>  Michael Brown, Microsoft CFO, addressed the dynamics of information technology.  He noted that computer memory, which used to cost $10,000 per million instructions per second (MIPS), is now only $2 per MIPS.  The dramatic decrease in costs, combined with ever-shrinking cycle times, have caused massive changes in finance.  Some of the more powerful changes include:<P>

<I>Investor freedom. </I> As financial services expand over the internet, individuals will be able to invest their money at the press of a button, at a fraction of current costs.  Moreover, consumers will receive the same attention once only afforded to institutional investors.  There are drawbacks, however.  With freedom comes responsibility.  The former monitoring role of the financial intermediary will become the burden to the individual.  There will be other side effects.  For example, the price of some companies' stocks have fluctuated wildly based largely on the current buzz in electronic chat rooms.  The anonymity of the internet enables fraudulent information to circulate uncensored. <P>

<I>Intermediaries under pressure.</I>  If profit margins shrink interminably, and fewer companies utilize underwriters for their initial public offerings, what will happen to the financial intermediaries of today?  The threat of becoming an arcane institution looms, and many predict a diminished role.  But, as John Heimann of Merrill Lynch cautioned, it is dangerous to predict the death of the financial intermediary. The intermediary represents a value-added that would be difficult for any web site to offer.<P>

<I>Capital mobilization</I> stands to be drastically revamped.  After the success of Spring Street Brewery, which raised $1.6 million via its web site, numerous start-up companies are eager to use electronic means to find inexpensive financing.  Wallman pointed out one obstacle, though: while one start-up on the ënet is novel, when there are 14,000, few will receive the attention they desire.<P>

<I>Regulators under fire.</I>  When asked whether regulators were up to the task of monitoring tomorrow's financial markets, a consensus among panelists was an equivocal "no . . . maybe." <P>

The government will have a difficult time regulating and supervising the new global commerce.  With IPOs on the Internet, financial services merging and blending into one another, and new "exchanges" developing daily, it will be nigh impossible for regulators, with increasingly limited resources, to maintain order with laws created in the 1930s. As David Shaw, chairman, D.E. Shaw & Co. pointed out, regulators need to have the same capabilities and same understanding of risk management and technology that the private sector has.  But the track record of policymakers adapting regulation to market developments is not good.  Glass-Steagall reform, for example, has been debated since the mid-1970s.  Rep. Michael Oxley (R-OH) noted that recent legislative initiatives are only the first step in modernizing regulation.  According to Wallman, the next iteration of laws should be goals-oriented, affecting the end result of the transaction.  Thus, whatever blending of banking, securities, and insurance products that may occur will not render laws useless.<P>
------<P>
Elaine La Roche, managing director of Morgan Stanley, speculated, "The next five years will be more challenging than the last twenty."  For the most part, the United States is the sole country even beginning to take advantage of the new technological tools. The rest of the world will require years to catch up.  Nonetheless, Bradley Belt, director of the CSIS capital markets project, warned, "While it is almost certain that the U.S. capital markets will continue to be the market of choice . . . we must be careful to recognize and respond to the changing environment to ensure the continued health and vibrancy of U.S. markets."<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/27/96</i>

