<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 11,

July 20, 1995</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Japan: Facing Down the Banking Crisis</h1>

<h3>The fallout of the banking crisis will transcend current financial troubles. . . </h3>

How severe is the ongoing financial decompression in Japan?  Very serious, according to four well-respected analysts who addressed the issue at the CSIS Washington Roundtable earlier this week.<P>

The magnitude of the banking crisis in itself is bad enough.  According to many estimates, the scale of the problem is some five times larger than the S&L crisis faced by this country.  And the resulting "deflationary dynamic" at work in Japan is unprecedented since the time of the Great Depression.<P>

But it could go beyond that.  The financial distress could easily generate new and perhaps unmanageable pressures on the current political alignment in Tokyo.  It could propel new and possibly nationalistic figures to the political fore and change popular attitudes about trade and finance in the process.  All this has major implications for the U.S. economy and exchange-rate policy, U.S.-Japan relations, and political and economic dynamics in Asia.<P>

At issue is what to do about 80 trillion yen (some $900 billion) in "problem" assets.  The government is faced with the prospect of a massive bailout, but the Japanese taxpayer and the Diet have served notice that they will not tolerate such a solution.  What, then, can the government do?  There is no good solution, argues David Hale, chief economist at Kemper Financial Services.  The government will have to assume some part of the assets.  On top of that, it will have to create far more generous tax allowances for loan losses--a new phenomenon that will be extremely hard to sell politically.<P>

In the end, the derivative effects of the banking crisis may be even more significant.  Susan Dentzer, chief economics correspondent of U.S. News and World Report, notes that the deflation is driving up unemployment quickly.  Accustomed to jobless levels at two percent, Japan now faces the prospect of a doubling of that rate in 1996.  That may not seem like much to Americans, but it is extremely significant to the Japanese; Dentzer suggests that rising unemployment and other dislocation generated by the deflation could strengthen distrust of trade and foreigners in general.<P>

Hale raises the possibility that economic nationalism could rise as a result of the financial distress.  Already, he suggests, there is some evidence of a political realignment in the appointment of Dr. Eisuke Sakakibara as the new director general of the International Finance Bureau in the Ministry of Finance.  In the past, Sakakibara has taken an aggressive position relative to the United States, including threats of financial retaliation in trade talks.<P>

How will these dynamics affect the United States?  Robert Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman Sachs International, points to potentially conflicting financial effects here at home.  Continued meltdown in Japan would impel Japanese institutions to pull money out of the United States, but the resulting loss of confidence in Japan would increase flows to the United States from elsewhere.  The probability of such a crisis is low, he stresses, but both sides need to be prudent.  Hormats also raises the possibility of the spread of the banking crisis to the United States through the interbank market.  If there were a large failure of a Japanese bank that owns a bank in the United States, it could lead to reverberations in the U.S. banking system.<P>

Michael Berman, president of Nomura Securities International, also points to a more cautious attitude by the Japanese in playing the U.S. markets, especially in the T-bill auctions.  In equities, bonds, and real estate, look for the Japanese to be sellers rather than buyers, he says.<P>

There was general agreement that the financial woes in Japan are putting the spotlight on vulnerabilities not only in its banking system, but also in the regulatory framework and the tax code.  The restructuring necessary to address these vulnerabilities is a tall order, and it is by no means clear whether the current political leadership in Japan is up to the task.  Until it is, however, the decompression will continue.<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/10/96</i>

