<h3><a name="canada">Canada and International Peacekeeping</a></h3>
Joseph T. Jockel<p>
"In this well written and concise overview, Joseph Jockel examines the evolution of the Canadian role in international peacekeeping and the role peacekeeping has played in Canadian political and military life." - Canada Institute of International Affairs<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	94 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-245-2      		$9.50</i>


<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="corporate">Corporate Diplomacy: Principled Leadership for the Global Community</a></h3>
Robert Trice, Miyako Hasegawa, Michael Kearns, editors
Contributors: Arthur R. Barron, John Charlton, Amitai Etzioni, Kenneth E. Goodpaster, Jeffrey Joseph, Ryuzaburo Kaku, Edward Legasey, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4montvill.html">Joseph Montville</a>, Delwin Roy, Craig Smith
This report examines ways in which corporations can play a more proactive role in community building. More specifically, what role can corporations assume in filling the resulting leadership gap_at the local, national, and international levels_given cross-border economic, cultural, technological, and informational transactions that have made the task of governing more difficult? 
<i>CSIS Report	51 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-282-7 		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="forpol21">Foreign Policy into the 21st Century: The U.S. Leadership Challenge</a></h3>
Zbigniew Brzezinski, Representative Lee Hamilton, Senator Richard Lugar, project cochairs<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4johnsto.html">Douglas Johnston</a>, project director and editor<br>
Steering Committee: Carter Beese, Judith Bello, Harold Brown, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4burt.html">Richard Burt</a>, William Clark, Chester Crocker, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fairban.html">Richard Fairbanks</a>, Jonathan Howe, Max Kampelman, Dave McCurdy, Robert Murray, Robert Neumann, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest Preeg</a>, John Reinhardt, Stephen Solarz, Richard Soloman, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4zoellic.html">Robert Zoellick</a><p>
This report represents the culmination of a two-year study on U.S. foreign policy. Prompted by the absence of any comprehensive U.S. foreign policy agenda for the post-Cold War era, the report describes the kind of world the United States should be moving toward and suggests how it should go about doing so. <p>

	The study group assessed trends, defined and prioritized U.S. national interests, and formulated policy recommendations in the geographic areas of greatest strategic importance to the United States_Asia, Europe, Russia and the Newly Independent States, and the Middle East_and in three functional areas as well: international security, international economics, and "global problems and opportunities." The report provides a uniquely bipartisan perspective and a much needed wake-up call at a time of diminished public interest in international affairs.<p>

"A bipartisan panel of foreign policy experts says America should strengthen its global leadership and overcome an unfocused, divisive and partisan approach to international affairs. . . . Beyond all else, strong presidential leadership in international affairs will be the critical prerequisite for the kind of world we would like to pass to future generations', says the 160-page study released this week by the Center for Strategic and International Studies." - Gene Kramer, Associated Press, AP Online, October 4, 1996<p>
<i>CSIS Report	176 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-292-4		$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="shadows">From Shadows to Substance: An Action Plan for Transatlantic Defense Cooperation</a></h3>
<b>Conference Summary and Background Report of the CSIS Atlantic Partnership Project</b><p>
The Rt. Hon. Sir Geoffrey Pattie, MP, and Michael T. Smith, Atlantic Partnership cochairs<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, project director<p>
Based on a conference held on Capitol Hill in February, this report sets the agenda for the future of this important endeavor. The report highlights consensus over mutual U.S.-European interest in the future of defense cooperation with emphasis on the current favorable political climate and the globalization of economic activity. Additionally, the conference identified specific project activities that are conducive to fostering transatlantic defense cooperation.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	42 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-276-2 		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="dilemma">The Haitian Dilemma: A Case Study in Demographics, Development, and U.S. Foreign Policy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest H. Preeg</a><p>
The study relates longer-term Haitian development prospects to short-term U.S. policy objectives. The analysis focuses on the powerful demographic forces at play -- rapid population growth in the countryside, the relentless rural/urban migratory flow, and building pressures for outward migration to the United States. The central policy conclusion is that foreign policy actions, such as the international embargo to help restore the Aristide presidency, can have a devastatingly negative impact on the demographic and development outlook.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series 	133 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-277-0		$14.95</i>

<hr><p>

<h3><a name="haiti">Haitian Frustrations: Dilemmas for U.S. Policy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, editor<br>
Contributors: Elliott Abrams, Diego Arria, Thomas Carothers, Andrew S. Faiola, Georges Fauriol, Ian Guest, David Healy, Stephen Horblitt, Robert Maguire, Lawrence Pezzullo, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest H. Preeg</a>, Lawrence Theriot, Sally Yearwood<p>
This up-to-the-minute analysis outlines the difficult road ahead for Haiti and U.S.-Haitian relations. Many important historical documents are included, as well as a chronology of events from the 1990 elections to Aristide's return.<p>

"The work is a very elaborate analysis of the background, development and perspectives raised by the Haitian crisis. . . .Each phase of the conflict is analyzed in detail, with the relevant documents and statistics appended." - NOD & Conversion<p>
<i>CSIS Report	236 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-259-2 		$24.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="leadership">Leadership - Is Gender an Issue? 
Women's Leadership in the 21st Century</a></h3>

The pioneer International Women's Leadership Forum brought together for the first time in history women leaders from all segments of society, including 8 present and former heads of states. The group convened in Stockholm, Sweden in May 1996 to address the broad spectrum of leadership experiences at the community, national, and international levels, and a group of 15 young, rising women leaders began a summer fellowship program at CSIS. This report presents their dialogue on women and leadership.<p>
<i>Panel Report      c. 30 pp.		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-290-8		$9.95 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="transatl">Making Transatlantic Defense Cooperation Work</a></h3>
<b>Findings and Recommendations of the CSIS Atlantic Partnership Project</b><p>
The Rt. Hon. Sir Geoffrey Pattie, MP, and Michael T. Smith, cochairs<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Robin Niblett, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4earnest.html">David Earnest</a>, research staff<p>
This report recommends legislative and regulatory approaches to strengthening cooperation between U.S. and European defense industries. The project's findings, formulated by a steering committee of 15 leading U.S. and European defense CEOs and corporate leaders, suggest to governments on both sides of the Atlantic ways to provide defense industries with new incentives to collaborate on the development and production of next-generation military technologies and systems.<p>
<i>Panel Report	45 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-286-X		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nato">NATO's Role in European Stability</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cambone.html">Stephen A. Cambone</a>, editor<br>
Contributors: <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4burt.html">Richard Burt</a>, Zbigniew Brzezinski, Stephen A. Cambone, Stephen J. Hadley, Robert E. Hunter, John Kornblum, Richard G. Lugar, Walter Slocombe, Gebhardt von Moltke, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4zoellic.html">Robert Zoellick</a><p>
This report presents U.S. and European views on the crucial issues facing the Atlantic alliance in the post-cold war era.  At a time when many are calling for expansion of the alliance while others argue that it is obsolete, experts and senior officials from throughout the alliance offer their interpretations of recent events and predictions for the future. <p>
<i>CSIS Report	70 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-324-6		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="natosummit">The NATO Summit and Beyond</a></h3>
<b>A Consensus Report of the CSIS Senior NATO Policy Group</b><p>
Alexander Haig and Harold Brown, project cochairmen<br>
Don M. Snider, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cambone.html">Stephen A. Cambone</a>, project  codirectors<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4serfaty.html">Simon Serfaty</a>, rapporteur<p>
<i>Panel Report	23 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-262-2 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="euratom">Negotiating a U.S.-EURATOM Successor Agreement:
Finding Common Ground in Nuclear Cooperation </a></h3>
<b>A Consensus Report of the CSIS U.S.-EURATOM Senior Policy Panel</b><p>
James R. Schlesinger, project chairman<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Dan GourÈ</a>, project director<p>
<i>Panel Report	33 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-258-4		      $14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="religion">Religion: The Missing Dimension of Statecraft</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4johnsto.html">Douglas M. Johnston</a> and Cynthia Sampson, editors<br>
Foreword by former president Jimmy Carter<br>
Contributors: Stanton Burnett, Harvey Cox, Douglas Johnston, Ron Kraybill, David Little, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4luttwak.html">Edward Luttwak</a>, Bruce Nichols, Barry Rubin, Cynthia Sampson, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4steele.html">David Steele</a>, William Vendley, Henry Wooster<p>
Religion plays a crucial role in many international conflicts, yet for the most part, diplomacy either ignores or misunderstands that role. This unified collection of case studies and theoretical pieces attempts to restore this missing dimension to its rightful place in the conduct of international diplomacy and offers the first systematic account of modern cases in which religion has played a role in preventing or resolving conflict and achieving nonviolent change. A distinguished roster of scholars gives examples from Europe, Central America, Asia, and Africa. Additional essays bring out the implications of these case studies for foreign policy and the religious community.<p>

"Anyone concerned about the causes of failed American diplomatic efforts in Vietnam, the Lebanon civil war, Iran and the Sudan, or eager to know the behind-the-scenes successes of what Joseph Montville has called "Track II Diplomacy" in Rhodesia, the Philippines, and in post-World War II France and Germany, will find this book a fascinating and exciting read." - The Social Contract <p>
<i>Copublished Book/Oxford University Press	350 pp.       1994<br>
ISBN 0-19508-7348 (hb)		$35.00<br>
0-19510-2800 (pb) 		$17.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="un50">
The United Nations at Fifty:
Sovereignty, Peacekeeping, and Human Rights</a></h3>
Don M. Snider and Stuart J.D. Schwartzstein, editors<br>
Contributors: HÈdi Annabi, Richard J. Evraire, John M. Flanigan, James C. O'Brien, John Shattuck, Robert F. Turner, Sarasin Viraphol<p>
Since the end of the Cold War, UN activities have grown in size and scope to encompass new missions. After initial U.S. support, particularly from the Clinton administration, a chorus of criticism of such missions has arisen. Administration and UN officials, along with experts from around the world, examine what the UN's role should be in the future and provide a close look at the three most controversial issues that directly affect the level of U.S. support. <p>
<i>CSIS Report (With the Robert R. 
McCormick Tribune Foundation) 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-268-1	74 pp. 	$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="fourhorsemen">U.S. Foreign Policy and the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse: Humanitarian Relief in Complex Emergencies</a></h3>
Andrew S. Natsios<p>
The incidence of complex humanitarian emergencies has been accelerating since the late 1980s. Two U.S. presidents have committed military forces to five of these emergencies_Kurdistan, Somalia, Bosnia, Rwanda, and Haiti. U.S. bilateral aid in response to foreign disasters and crises rose from $300 million in 1989 to more than $1.3 billion in 1994. Without strong, effective U.S. leadership, such emergencies will result in great loss of life and permanently paralyze social systems. In the post-Cold War world, the U.S. national interest must be redefined to include complex humanitarian emergencies even when no geostrategic interest exists. Natsios recommends this redefinition involve a national debate of the kind that reevaluated the U.S. role in the world after World War II.<p>

<i>Washington Papers/Praeger  c. 210 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-275-95921-X (pb)	$18.95 Est.<br>
     0-275-95920-1 (hb)	$55.00 Est.</i>

</td></tr></table>

