<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Succession in Russia and Western Business</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<img align=right src="http://www.csis.org/images/psp.gif">
<center>
<H3>Post Soviet Prospects, vol. IV, #11, November 1996</H3><HR>

<H2>The Succession in Russia and Western Business</H2>

<H4>by
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a></H4></center><HR>


Thanks to unprecedented disclosure by Russian and foreign medical doctors, the world learned more about President Boris Yeltsin's condition than it ever did about the health of any Soviet-era leader. According to the director of the medical center of the president's main administration, Mr. Yeltsin was suffering from ischemic disease, angina pectoris, cardiosclerosis, post-hemorrhagic anaemia, and thyroid disfunction. On November 5, the president underwent multiple heart bypass surgery. The official prognosis is that he should return to full health and vigor by February 1997. Many Russians, however, are not convinced: they expect the president, if he survives the immediate aftermath of the operation, to be a part-time head of state for many months or years to come, appearing in carefully edited film clips and having decrees signed for him. Few expect him to serve out his four-year term. It is hardly surprising, therefore, that the race to succeed the ailing president has started.<p>
If  Yeltsin dies shortly after surgery, there are currently four horses in the race to succeed him: two - Lebed and Chernomyrdin - are leading the field with the two
others - Zyuganov and Luzhkov - close on their heels. A fifth figure - Chubais - may play a key role. 

<b>Aleksandr Lebed.</b> This formidable ex-paratroop general has been in politics for less than two years, and yet polls taken before his ouster showed him to be by far the most trusted political figure in Russia. Lebed is given to uttering apocalyptic assertions on a whole range of domestic and foreign issues to the media. He or his aides then often discount the quotation or deny that any interview has taken place. If a presidential election were held tomorrow, Lebed would surely win, given his current popularity ratings. But it will not be held tomorrow: indeed, the earliest conceivable date is February 1997. In the meantime, Lebed lacks a nationwide organizational base, with only the Congress of Russian Communities, the Truth and Order, and Honor and Motherland movements to call upon. He lacks money, apart from a tenuous connection through General Aleksandr Korzhakov to funding from the arms export business. And he lacks sympathetic access to the media, with all three main TV channels savaging him after his dismissal. Lebed as president could be disquieting news for the West. The blunt and outspoken general is unpredictable, and he has changed his position on many sensitive issues such as Chechnya, NATO expansion, Bosnia, and trade with the West. He has little grasp of economics and relies heavily on Sergei Glaziev, his economic aide and former head of the economic security department of the Security Council. Almost single-handedly, Glaziev emasculated the Production-Sharing Agreement before it was passed by the Duma in the runup to the December 1995 election. He has campaigned tirelessly for the reduction in the number of sites open to commercial exploitation by Western firms, and he has called for protecting the domestic agricultural sector and the military-industrial complex through further subsidies. Foreign direct investment would probably remain at a low level under a Lebed administration, especially if Glaziev were given a key post.<p>

<b>Viktor Chernomyrdin.</b> The 1993 Constitution stipulates that, in the event of the president's death or his "long-lasting inability to exercise his duties owing to his state of health," the current prime minister shall assume the duties of acting president and shall order a new presidential election within 90 days. Thus, if Boris Yeltsin dies or is clearly incapacitated, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will become acting president for up to three months. During that period, he could do a great deal with the powers of incumbency combined with the financial backing of leading industrial firms and banks. He lacks charisma and is a poor speaker, and his well-heeled bloc, Our Home is Russia, captured only 10.3 percent of the vote in the December 1995 parliamentary elections, against 22.7 percent for the Communist Party of the Russian Federation (CPRF). In recent opinion polls he has hardly appeared in the spectrum. Chernomyrdin is nevertheless seen as a reassuring, competent, managerial figure. He is certainly the candidate favored by governments and business interests in the West, where he is a known quantity, having established close ties with the U.S. administration through the activities of the Gore-Chernomyrdin Commission. As president, he could be expected to oversee the continued slow and erratic progress toward a democratic system and a market economy.<p>

<b>Gennadii Zyuganov.</b>  After it was disclosed that President Yeltsin had suffered a heart attack or a stroke prior to the July 3 presidential election runoff, the leader of the National Patriotic Union of Russia (which embraces the CPRF) has repeatedly complained that the election was unfair because the electorate did not know they were voting for an inoperative candidate. He certainly has a point. In a recent poll, 65 percent of the respondents said that they would not have voted for Yeltsin had they known about his condition. Despite his loss of ground since July, Zyuganov has made it clear that he will run again for president, hoping to keep the support of the 30 million who voted for him on July 3 and adding many of the 40 million who voted for Yeltsin but who have since become even more disenchanted. Despite the CPRF candidate's reassuring words to Western investors and business executives during the first half of 1996, a Zyuganov presidency would be catastrophic for the Russian economy. His manifesto implied attempts to restore central planning, widespread nationalization, controlled retail prices for staples, protection for agriculture and heavy industry, a foreign trade monopoly, and huge subsidies. The attempts would fail, but the already faltering transition toward the market would be set back by several years.<p>

<b>Yurii Luzhkov.</b> The mayor of Moscow has not officially thrown his hat into the ring, but he has spoken and acted in recent months remarkably like a candidate for the highest office. Luzhkov has done a great job in transforming the city from a decaying and shabby Soviet-style metropolis to something beginning to resemble a capital city. He is appreciated for his hands-on style and won 90 percent of the vote in the mayoral election on June 16. Because he has run Moscow so well, he has been given a free hand in privatizing the enterprises and real estate there, with a program running counter to the nationwide privatization effort of Anatolii Chubais. It is uncertain how much support he could attract from the rest of the country. He can certainly call on massive financing from financial and business circles and is in a position to be kingmaker, even if he delays his own run for the presidency for a few more years. Some of his recent utterances on topics like Sevastopol and Chechnya and his ruthless crackdowns on dark-skinned merchants and the homeless suggest that he would make an assertive and forceful president, but he has done much to attract foreign capital and business to his own city.<p>

<b>Anatolii Chubais.</b> This impressive economist was the only leading reformer of the original Gaidar team to survive in high office as head of the privatization program throughout most of the Chernomyrdin administration. In January 1996, he was fired by Yeltsin, ostensibly for losing the parliamentary elections because of the inequities of the privatization process. He soon regained Yeltsin's favor and, in personal collaboration with Yeltsin's daughter, Tatiana Dyachenko, brilliantly managed the president's reelection campaign. For this he was rewarded with the position of chief of staff_a key function in a part-time presidency. Chubais is generally seen as an unlikely candidate for the presidency in the short term because of widespread disenchantment with the privatization program, but his position gives him great scope for influencing the contest and positioning himself for high office at a later stage. He has repeatedly spoken in favor of increased foreign investment in Russia and for improving the environment for Western business ties. <p>

What cannot at present be determined is the possibility or probability of alliances between the leading candidates. There have been rumors, for instance, of an accommodation between Chernomyrdin and Zyuganov. Other reports speak of a Chernomyrdin-Luzhkov alliance. And whereas Lebed has vowed that there can be no return to the past and has frequently been critical of Zyuganov, in his most recent utterances the former general seems to have spared the National Patriotic Union of Russia and its leader. It might also be recalled that Lebed was outspokenly dismissive of Yeltsin until a few weeks before the first round of the presidential election on June 16.  <p>

The West, of course, has no say in who will succeed Boris Yeltsin. Indeed, well-meaning intervention by international agencies such as the International Monetary Fund can backfire. Foreign assistance programs can, however, continue to help Russia develop democratic institutions and the market infrastructure in the hope that any succession that takes place does so within a constitutional framework. Under present circumstances, the most desirable outcomes from the point of view of the West probably would be a Boris Yeltsin restored to health and vigor, a Yeltsin figurehead regime with Chernomyrdin managing the store, or, failing that, a Chernomyrdin presidency in which Chubais and like-minded colleagues play a major role. In contrast, a victory for Lebed or Zyuganov would mean that all bets are off.
<P>

<hr>
  <a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a></BODY>


