<html>
<title>China Bridge</title>
<body text="#000000" body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></center>
<p>
<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/china2.gif" align=left>
<center><h2>China Telecom Bridge Project</h2>
<p>
<a href="#Overview">China Bridge Program Overview</a><br>
<a href="#Interaction">Government Industry Interaction</a><br>
<a href="#Capabilities">China-Based Capabilities</a><br>
<a href="#r&a">Research & Analysis</a> | <a href="#briefings">Briefings & Initiatives</a><br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/chinteam.html">China Bridge Team</a>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="Overview"><h4>China Bridge Program Overview</h4></a>
The CSIS International Communications Studies Program (ICS) has established a special in-depth project focused on China.  It draws on the ICS Program's extensive experience and track record in assisting government and industry leaders in addressing the economic, political, and technological challenges of electronic communications worldwide.
<p>
The CSIS China Telecom Bridge Project includes research, analysis, forums, briefings, and study tours on specific aspects of China's complex telecommunications, broadcast, and computer-based technology and service issues.  The China Bridge project is unique in that it actively involves hands-on, senior level Chinese officials with diverse international communications industry experts.  Designed to be a two-way street, the China Bridge Project benefits both policymakers in China and international companies that have a stake in the role of communications in China's economic development.
<p>
The targeted analysis, briefings, and forums go beyond traditional avenues of information sharing, research, and analysis.  This special CSIS project has become an interactive "bridge" between policy and market decision-makers.  In the process it provides unparalleled opportunities for top-level industry and government interaction on the broad range of technology, policy, and investment issues affecting China's complex and fast-growing market both internally and externally.
<p>
The China Telecom Bridge Project's purpose is threefold:
<ul>
<li>to provide a framework for senior-level information exchange, analysis, and discourse involving diverse international industry experts and relevant Chinese officials;</li>
<li>to assist in developing policies and initiatives that promote the effective roles of information technologies and services in support of China's integration into the global market economy; and</li>
<li>to enhance domestic and foreign understanding of diverse telecommunications, computer, and broadcast applications and services in China.</li>
</ul>
<a name="Interaction">
<h4>Unique Government Industry Interaction</h4></a>
The China Telecom Bridge Project capitalizes on the momentum generated by the highly successful "China Telecom and Information Industry Forum" (CTIIF) that CSIS convened in Beijing in 1993 and 1994.  These CTII Forums and workshops brought together for the first time in history senior industry leaders from the United States, Europe, and Japan with more than 60 Chinese officials for in-depth discussions on key aspects of China's communications industries and policies.  These included numerous aspects of government policy, plans for telecommunications, and broadcast-based networks and services, electronic commerce, manufacturing, and standard setting, as well as long-term investment involvement of foreign corporations.
<p>
The impact of the CSIS China Telecom Bridge Project is already measurable.  At the invitation of the prestigious Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), the CSIS International Communications Studies Chair was invited in 1994 to establish a permanent center in China.  Because CASS works directly with the State Council, plays a key role in China's overall economic planning process, and has institutes in every Chinese province, it is uniquely suited to extend the "bridge" capabilities to a strategic diversity of constituencies in China.  The new Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development (CIIED) was announced at the Great Hall of the People in November l994 and officially commenced work in the summer of 1995.
<p>
<a name="Capabilities"><h4>China-Based Capabilities</h4></a>
The <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/2ciied.html">Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development (CIIED)</a> is the first independent, nonpartisan research institution established in China involving policy experts from both Chinese government agencies and the international communications industry.  CIIED provides an on-the-ground Beijing base for corporate members of the CSIS China Telecom Bridge Project.  CIIED is overseen by the International Advisory Board cochaired by Dr. Liu Guoguang of CASS and
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4dougan.html">Ambassador Diana Lady Dougan</a> of CSIS. <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/advboard.html">The Advisory Board and Governing Council</a> are composed of key officials from the relevant Chinese ministries and commissions and diverse international communication industry leaders.
<p>
<a name="r&a"><h4>Timely Research and Analysis</h4></a>
In addition to its own targeted work, the CSIS <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/chinteam.html">China Telecom Bridge Team</a> works directly with CIIED in undertaking specific projects on issues relevant to the roles of telecommunications, broadcasting, and information technologies in the context of diverse aspects of China's economic policies and plans.  At its initial meeting in June 1995, the CIIED Advisory Board and Governing Council concluded that the lack of clarity on current policies and processes is a major impediment in China.  Accordingly they recommended, as a first priority, that CIIED develop a comprehensive "Overview of China's Information Infrastructure Policy Process, Networks, and Services."
<p>
This initial year-long <a
href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/chinares.html">research project</a> that began in June 1995 will be completed in three phases: (1) documentation and inventory of China's telecom industry, policies, and regulations, and analysis of the current policy responsibilities of government bodies; (2) assessments of new telecom plans and initiatives in targeted provinces; and (3) comparative analysis of policies and plans in other countries.
<p>
Phase one of the project, data collection and preliminary analysis, was completed under the supervision of Professor Zheng Youjing of CIIED and involved three full-time researchers and representatives of 15 ministries and commissions.  A draft report was reviewed by the CIIED Board at its March 1996 meeting and was followed by a series of workshops and review sessions involving corporate members of the CSIS China Telecom Bridge Project.  Phase two and three will include extensive interaction with international experts under the auspices of the CSIS China Telecom Bridge Project.  Given the unprecedented cooperation that CIIED is receiving from all the important government entities involved in electronic communications, the project promises to provide an invaluable framework for follow-on research and analysis in specific areas.

<a name="briefings"><h4>On-Site Briefings and Other Special Initiatives</h4></a>

In March 1996, CIIED joined with the Ministry of Electronics and Industry and the People's Bank of China in helping to organize the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2giic.html">Global Information Infrastructure Commission</a> "Challenge Hearing" on Electronic Commerce.  The forum focused on regulatory, policy, and legal issues of EFT, EDI, and other electronic technology applications worldwide.  CIIED also helped organize the senior-level seminar on Constructing a Global Electronic Commerce Strategy at PBC, which brought together some 50 senior officials and industry people from China and other countries to address global electronic commerce strategy-related issues and to initiate cooperative efforts to meet the challenges of the electronic age.  In the same month, the CIIED Advisory Board plenary meeting, held in Beijing, reviewed past CIIED activities and planned future endeavors.
<p>
CIIED is planning several special initiatives for CSIS Telecom Bridge Corporate Sponsors and the founding Corporate Members of CIIED.  One of the initial focus projects planned for the summer 1996 is on "Policy, Financial, and Technology Challenges in the Western Provinces."  As part of this, CIIED will conduct special briefings and a study tour to targeted provinces of interest to Corporate Members.  Included will be in-depth sessions with key provincial officials.  Participation will be limited to Corporate Members of CIIED.
<p>
Contingent upon funding, other planned activities include special guest lectures, workshops, and the <i>CIIED Quarterly</i> which will publish articles, interviews, and reports on key information infrastructure-related issues.  The journal will be circulated to relevant ministries and agencies at the provincial and national levels.  CSIS has also been invited to coordinate a management training program in the United States for chief executives heading both large city and provincial Telecom Bureaus across China.
<p>
Return to the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/">ICS Home Page</a>
<p>
