<HTML><TITLE>CSIS Projects in Europe</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>
<H2><p align="center">Projects on Europe</p></H2>
<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#amerukra">American-Ukrainian Advisory Committee</a><p>
<a href="#cbsbalkan">Corporate Briefing Series</a> (The Balkans and Central Europe)<p>
<a href="#democracy">Democracy Forum in Sarajevo</a><p>
<a href="#transarms">European Studies Working Group</a> on Transatlantic Arms Sales to Third Countries<p>
<a href="#euagenda">The European Union Agenda</a> and Its Impact on U.S. Interests<p>
<a href="#yugoslavia">The Former Yugoslavia:</a> Project on Religion and Conflict Resolution<p>
<a href="#neweurope">New European States</a><p>
<a href="#newitaly">New Italy Project</a><p>
<a href="#pfie">Polish Federation</a> of Independent Entrepreneurs (PFIE)<p>
<a href="#eeurope">Political Parties in Eastern Europe:</a> A Guide to Politics in the Post-Communist Era<p>
<a href="#senioreuro">Senior European Discussion Group</a><p>
<a href="#slovakia">Slovakia:</a> Project on Democratic Pluralism in Slovakia</a><p>
<a href="#atpat">The Atlantic Partnership</a><p>
<a href="#turkish">Turkish Briefing Series</a><p>
<a href="#poland">U.S.-EU-Poland Action Commission</a><p>
<a href="#usfrench">U.S.-French Bilateral Roundtable</a><p>
</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="amerukra">American-Ukrainian Advisory Committee</a></h3>
 Under the chairmanship of CSIS Counselor Zbigniew Brzezinski, an informal group has been established to identify opportunities for closer political and economic cooperation between the two countries. The committee, which meets at least once a year, makes concrete recommendations at the highest political level to the two governments to assist Ukraine in consolidating its independence and in undertaking the transition to a market economy. The third meeting of the committee, held in New York in November 1995, focused on furthering Ukrainian economic and financial reform and improving the climate for foreign investment by inviting U.S. business leaders to the deliberations. The next meeting is scheduled to take place in Kyiv in October 1996. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bugajsk.html">Janusz Bugajski</a>, Project Director, East European Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="cbsbalkan">Corporate Briefing Series (The Balkans and Central Europe)</a></h3>
 The East European Studies Project has launched this initiative to describe, clarify, and analyze the developments in the region most pertinent to the business community. The series focuses on two areas of Europe: the Balkans and Central Europe. The "Balkans Assessment" component is organized to provide crucial information on the Balkans, especially the former Yugoslavia. The "Emerging Markets of Central Europe" component is designed to cover developments in Central Europe (Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, and Sloveniaóa market of some 67 million persons) for the business community by providing up-to-date assessments of political developments as they affect local economies; relations with Western institutions, including prospects for EU membership; regional security issues and their impact on investment; and identification of potential threats and risks. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bugajsk.html">Janusz Bugajski</a>, Project Director, East European Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="democracy">Democracy Forum in Sarajevo</a></h3>
 The East European Studies Project, working with on-ground facilitators in Bosnia-Hercegovina, is convening a three-day Democracy Forum in Sarajevo in October 1996. The Forum, consisting of six focused workshops, will assemble nongovernmental representatives from the diverse regions of Bosnia, including both the Bosnian Federation and the Serb Republic, to determine priorities for developing a pluralistic, civic society in Bosnia and to help establish concrete joint initiatives. Among the planned initiatives will be a proposal to establish an NGO Coordinating Center in Sarajevo that would facilitate the development of independent civic activities throughout the country. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bugajsk.html">Janusz Bugajski</a>, Project Director, East European Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="transarms">European Studies Working Group on Transatlantic Arms Sales to Third Countries</a></h3>
 This group will examine whether there can be some agreement in the United States as to what can be done to regulate such sales in coordination with our European allies. Second, assuming an agreement, can it be made more compatible with the Europeans' preferences and needs? Third, if this can be achieved, can the agreement be enforced in such a way as to be extended to other countries that are making indiscriminate weapons sales their new growth industry? <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4serfaty.html">Simon Serfaty</a>, Director, European Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="euagenda">The European Union Agenda and Its Impact on U.S. Interests</a></h3>
 A series of meetings, briefings, and publications discusses and assesses the overall agenda for the Intergovernmental Conference of 1996, including its mandate and the enlargement of EU membership. This "EuroWatch" includes a small group of 25 leading European experts who meet biweekly to discuss significant issues involving the nation states of Europe, as well as the institutions to which these nations belong or wish to belong. Working groups provide additional, in-depth assessment of ongoing or emerging Euro-Atlantic issues. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4serfaty.html">Simon Serfaty</a>, Director, European Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="yugoslavia">The Former Yugoslavia: Project on Religion and Conflict Resolution</a></h3>
 Directed by David Steele, this project is being carried out in the former Yugoslavia, where integrated conflict resolution training workshops are being conducted for religious leaders and lay representatives from the Catholic, Protestant, Orthodox, Jewish, and Muslim faiths. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4steele.html">David A. Steele</a>, Fellow, Religion and Conflict Resolution Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="neweurope">New European States</a></h3>
This project, established in January 1995, examines the challenges facing the countries of Central EuropeóPoland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, and Sloveniaóas they aspire to membership in European political, economic, and security structures. The profound and wide-ranging implications of EU expansion and NATO enlargement have not been adequately addressed by the governments and institutions concerned. To address these issues, the East European Studies project at CSIS will build on the work already begun by continuing its roundtable meeting series involving a broad array of Washington-based participants from the government, NGO, diplomatic, corporate, and policy institution communities. The project will also conduct in-depth political assessment missions to the region and cooperate closely with two independent policy institutions: the Libra Institute in Ljubljana, Slovenia, and the Foundation to Support Local Democracy in Bratislava, Slovakia. As a companion to the project, CSIS produces the Central Europe Roundup, a monthly brief on political and economic events designed to cover issues that will have a significant impact on the region's development.  <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bugajsk.html">Janusz Bugajski</a>, Project Director, East European Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="newitaly">New Italy Project</a></h3>
Italy is experiencing dramatic economic, social, political, and institutional changes that seem to be shaping a "new" Italy. This project will explore the dynamics of change and offer a perspective on the realities of Italy's ongoing transformation. Through a series of lectures, conferences, and seminars, the project will seek to inform government and private sector leaders by highlighting emerging actors in Italian public life. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4luttwak.html">Edward Luttwak</a>, Chairman, and Empedocle Maffia, Director)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="pfie">Polish Federation of Independent Entrepreneurs (PFIE)</a></h3>
PFIE is a small- and medium-sized employers association in Poland. Its mission is to be the voice for small businesses on public policy matters that concern their present vitality and future growth. The federation also disseminates financial, legal, and networking information to the grass-roots level. PFIE is based on the premise that a strong and growing small- and medium-sized enterprise sector will form the backbone of Poland's middle class and will assure the country's continued democratic development. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4sulliva.html">Paige Sullivan</a>, Research Associate, Office of Dr. Zbigniew Brzezinski)</i>

<p><hr><p> 

<h3><a name="eeurope">Political Parties in Eastern Europe: A Guide to Politics in the Post-Communist Era</a></h3>
This project investigates the emergence of new political parties vying for power and influence within the process of democratization in Eastern Europe. This study, which will result in a book, will outline the political evolution 
of each state, provide a listing of all the major political parties, including their origins, programs, and leadership, and assess the impact of a broad spectrum of political forces on national developments. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bugajsk.html">Janusz Bugajski</a>, Project Director, East European Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="senioreuro">Senior European Discussion Group</a></h3>
This group is a high-level forum for senior government officials, European diplomats, academics, and others to discuss challenges facing U.S.-European and intra-European relations. A parallel discussion group has been established in Brussels by the European Commission. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4serfaty.html">Simon Serfaty</a>, Director, European Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="slovakia">Slovakia: Project on Democratic Pluralism in Slovakia</a></h3>
CSIS has a three-year grant to implement conflict resolution processes for the Slovak-ethnic Hungarian-Gypsy relationship in three towns in Slovakia. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4montvil.html">Joseph Montville</a>, Director, Preventive Diplomacy Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="atpat">The Atlantic Partnership</a></h3>
In a consensus report published in May 1996, the Atlantic Partnership Steering Committee of 15 leading U.S. and European defense industrialists recommended that the United States and its allies develop a Framework Agreement for transatlantic collaborative programs. This Framework Agreement would offer incentives to industry while creating more predictability for transatlantic collaborative programs by removing a number of barriers to the collaborative process. During 1996-1997, the project will host regular working groups that will identify opportunities for collaborative activities, program schedules, and complementary and unique technical and manufacturing capabilities that European industry can offer. The Atlantic Partnership also will establish a series of monthly seminars that will bring together U.S. and European government industry leaders to discuss today's challenging and contentious issues in transatlantic defense industrial relations. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="turkish">Turkish Briefing Series</a></h3>
Launched in June 1994, the meetings have addressed various aspects of Turkish foreign policy and Turkish economic and domestic politics. Speakers have included the chief adviser to the prime minister, two under secretaries of the Turkish Foreign Ministry, the leader of the main opposition Motherland Party, and the leader of the New Democracy Movement, as well as a number of leading Turkish political commentators and a member of the U.S. National Security Council. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4aliriza.html">Bulent Aliriza</a>, Director, Turkey Project)</i>

<p><hr><p> 

<h3><a name="poland">U.S.-EU-Poland Action Commission</a></h3>
The commission, chaired by CSIS Counselor Zbigniew Brzezinski and cochaired by John Pepper, chairman and CEO of Procter & Gamble; Percy Barnevik, chairman and CEO of ABB Asea Brown Boveri; and Cezary Stypulkowski, president of Bank Handlowy, has been working for the past four years to assist Poland's economic, political, and security development. Twenty-eight initiatives actions have been completed, and 14 initiatives are being developed by nine working groups focused on key areas, including European Union integration, transportation, infrastructure, foreign investment, pension and tax policy, and civil-military relations. New groups are being organized on energy policy and telecommunications. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4handy.html">George W. Handy</a>, Director)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="usfrench">U.S.-French Bilateral Roundtable</a></h3>
This group meets twice annually (most recently in October 1995 and April 1996) to address the current and future state of U.S.-French security relations. The program plans to assemble a number of similar roundtables during 1996. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4serfaty.html">Simon Serfaty</a>, Director, European Studies Program)</i>




</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:webmaster@csis.org">webmaster</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
</font>

</BODY>
