<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 17,

August 20, 1996</h4>
<HR>
<h1>Investing in India</h1>

<h3>Patience is a virtue . . .</h3>


Tarun Das, director-general of the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII), is widely considered to have his fingers on the pulse of India's economy and government.  At a CSIS India Program meeting, he had a message for U.S. businesses: Invest in India, but be prepared for the long haul.

To outsiders uneasy with the fragility of the nation's United Front coalition government, Das emphasized that even if the government collapses, economic policy will not.  "The most encouraging thing for Indian businesses today is that no matter what party is in power, there will be continuity in economic policy."  Despite the rhetoric, all parties know that the economy must continue to open.<P>

Following the unveiling of a new budget on July 22, CII, India's largest industry and trade association, has projected that GDP will grow by 7.5 percent and industrial output by 13 percent for fiscal year 1996-1997, and that by the year 2002 India should see 9 percent GDP growth and 15 percent industrial growth. <P>

<B>Deficit is Primary Concern</B><BR>
But the economy won't take off if the government can't cut spending.  Das acknowledged that the fiscal deficit is the primary concern.  India's reformist finance minister, P. Chidambaram, aims to reduce the deficit to 5 percent of GDP this year, but most experts doubt he'll reach his target.  The deficit will keep interest rates high, liquidity tight, and businesses hesitant.<P>

<B>Public Sector Reform</B><BR>
Because the budget anticipates greater spending, particularly for social programs, the government is relying on raising most of its revenue through foreign investment.  It also plans limited privatization and streamlining of public sector enterprises through a newly constituted Disinvestment Commission.  But what the government did not do was to open up the insurance sector to private investment, a move that was widely anticipated in Chidambaram's budget.  "We need insurance opened up for Indian business," not just for foreign investors, Das says.  India needs to mobilize private savings for development, particularly in infrastructure.  The new government, in power for less than two months, felt it could not formulate an effective policy to privatize insurance in time for this budget.  But, according to Das, it will be done by the next budget, only six months away.<P>

On banking sector reform, Das acknowledged that deregulation has not gone far enough, but said that Chidambaram will open up the banking sector and allow increased licensing of foreign banks.  Meanwhile, telecommunication liberalization has been a "very stop, go, fall, get up, fall again process" but he sees a "new political will to take this deregulation further." <P>

<B>Foreign Investment</B><BR>
India aims to attract US$10 billion in FDI per year, up from $4.5 billion last year.  Das thinks the goal is achievable: "It is going to happen if we get our policies right.  There are investors out there, and there is a market in here."  The Foreign Investment Promotion Board has been restructured to spur faster clearances of foreign investment proposals; 64 foreign investment projects were approved August 7.  In addition, the government has promised to expand the list of industries that can have 51% foreign equity holding.  The markets, however, do not seem as optimistic about the pace of reform: stocks fell after the budget came out, and the important BSE index has fallen 12 percent since July 22.<P>

<B>The States</B><BR>
As foreign investors deliberate where to invest in India, the country's 25 states are vying for attention.  "Increasingly, the states are free to promote investment, develop infrastructure, give approvals, and market themselves," Das says. The greater devolution of authority made possible by the current government means that foreign businesses should evaluate the states individually.  Traditional investor-friendly states like Maharashtra, Gujarat, and Karnataka have been joined by previously less active Orissa and Andhra Pradesh in their hunt for foreign dollars.<P>

Das cautioned, "In India, whether it's infrastructure or other economic issues, please don't expect miracles tomorrow.  It's going to be a slow, steady process with a lot of questioning, a lot of debate, a lot of discussion. . . . I always advise my U.S. business visitors to be patient because the market is going to grow and grow and grow."<P>

William Clark, Jr., director of the CSIS India Program, termed Das' speech "an upbeat, realistic view of India's mood and prospects."
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 10/29/96</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

