	Author: Guild Copeland
	
-->
<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 20,

December 17, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>The Era of Entitlements</h1>

<h3>Unsustainable Promises </h3>

Amid the oft-cited statistics of doom surrounding the looming entitlements crisis, there have been few offers of practical solutions. A recent panel at CSIS, however, had much to say about the situation and many suggestions on how to fix it.  The group -- consisting of Carla Hills as moderator, Pete Peterson of the Blackstone Group, Susan Dentzer, Senior Writer and Chief Economist, U.S. News & World Report, Judd Gregg, Senator (R-NH), and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley Belt</a>, Director, Domestic Policy Program -- challenged policymakers to address the entitlement issue now, before the costs associated with change become too daunting.<p> 

The problem is a massive one.  America is aging rapidly.  Government population estimates predict a nation of Floridas: the United States will soon have 50 million people over the age of 85.  By 2030, entitlement spending will consume all government revenue.  Many see such problems as intractable, but there is some evidence to the contrary: only 30 years ago, the United States was not the earth's greatest consumer or borrower but its greatest creditor.  Also, it is unconscionable to abandon future generations of Americans for the sake of the next 20 years.  The transformation that must occur will require significant changes in American culture -- first and foremost, increased savings. <p>

Without structural reforms, the country faces a Hobson's Choice: Should it raise taxes to support the current system of benefits, or should it reduce benefits?  If it were to raise payroll taxes, the increase would have to be 35%-55% above current rates.  As to reducing benefits, a number of methods were discussed by the panel:<p>

<ul><li><b>Tinker with the system -</b> One step could be to raise the retirement age before baby boomers age their considerable numbers into senior citizenship.  In only the last 25 years, life expectancy in the United States has increased by 4 years.  By raising the age of retirement 3 months per year over 20 years, pension costs can be lowered significantly with little shock to the extant system.  Affluence testing is another manner by which costs can be brought down incrementally. <p>

<li><b>Mandatory savings accounts -</b> Inspired by the successful model of the privatized pension system in Chile, the panelists imagined forcing the population to prepare for its future. Proposals ranged from privatizing the surplus from Social Security (currently about 1% of the total fund) to the entire system.<p>

<li><b>Tax systems that encourage savings -</b> ¿ la the Nunn-Domenici Unlimited Savings Allowance (USA) tax plan, a progressive tax system that spurred savings and investment would contribute to warding off fiscal difficulties 30 years from today.<p>

<li><b>Recalibrate the CPI -</b> A partial  solution that came to the fore last week was  lowering the consumer price index (CPI) by as much as 1.1%.  The resultant saving would be significant in Social Security payments, debt payments, and more.  Some analysts, however, doubt that the overestimation of inflation is nearly so high.<p>

<li><b>Do nothing -</b> If the system is left as is, benefits will not drop to zero when the Social Security trust fund is empty 34 years from now.  Payroll taxes will still provide benefits at about 75% of today's levels.  Of course, this would require individual investors to save more to make up the difference.<p></ul>

As ill-starred as the Social Security system might be, the panel agreed that Medicare may fare worse. Costs are rising 10% per year, while government funding increases are down from 20% to 3%. The United States spends 6% more of its GDP than any other country on health.  Medical costs must be reined in, but the questions of how to "ration" health care and whether to cap costs are politically frightful.<p>

CSIS is tackling the issue of entitlements in an upcoming project directed by Belt.  A critical aspect of the initiative will be the establishment of a National Commission on Retirement Policy, composed of leaders from both private and public sectors.  The mission of the 18-month project will be to highlight the urgency of the emerging crisis and recommend comprehensive and politically viable remedies to address it.
<p><hr>


<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

