<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 12,

Novemeber 22, 1995</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Polish Elections</h1>

<h3>Business as usual?</h3>

In run-off elections held in Poland this past Sunday, Aleksander Kwasniewski, the leader of the Left Democratic Alliance (SLD), was elected to a five-year term as president.  Given the trend in Eastern Europe--former communists rising to high-level positions in government--the results were not really a surprise, notes CSIS Director of East European Studies Janusz Bugajski. <P>

Although the political landscape in Poland has changed--the coalition of former communists and the Polish Peasant party now control the presidency and government--it does not mean a revolutionary transformation in key policies.  Bugajski contends that "Kwasniewski's victory at the polls does not mark a retreat away from free-market reforms and a reversion to the traditional, old-line communist system; economic reforms in Poland will not be derailed." <P>

The significance of the former communist leader's success only six years after the fall of communism is more symbolic than substantive.  Striking similarities existed in the political platforms of Kwasniewski and former Polish president and Solidarity leader Lech Walesa--both support market reform and privatization, as well as Poland's integration into the European Union and NATO.<P>

The growing political presence of former communists within Poland and Kwasniewski's victory has occurred for a number of reasons.  In the eyes of the Polish electorate, the younger generation of former communists have genuinely changed to Western European-style Social Democrats.  These "transformed" individuals have inherited a substantial political apparatus and monetary resources.<P>

Second, the political climate in Poland is anti-incumbent.  Bugajski argues that Poles may have grown tired of Walesa, who was seen as "unsophisticated and controversial."  By contrast, although Kwasniewski espouses the continuation of market reform, he is perceived as a more educated, competent, and  articulate leader; one who will present a better image of Poland abroad.<P>

At a meeting of the CSIS U.S.-Europe-Poland Action Commission in December 1994, Kwasniewski noted that his coalition was committed to the reform process and stressed the need for maintaining fiscal discipline and promoting higher levels of foreign investment.<P>

But perhaps the most significant reason the Left prevailed in the Polish presidential election stems from the deep divisions on the right of  the political spectrum.  With Kwasniewski capturing only 52% of the vote, there is a large constituency to be mobilized on the right-- something that Walesa has pledged to accomplish after leaving office.<P>

<I><B>Future Outlook :</B></I><BR>
Despite the dominance of former communists in the Polish government, the reforms continue.  Most recently, a large-scale privatization program, involving more than 400 major enterprises, was approved by the parliament.<P>

Bugajski points out that other former communist countries are continuing down the path of reforms.  In Hungary, for example, a coalition of liberals and socialists have implemented a major austerity package, cutting back on social security to meet IMF guidelines. <P>

A more important landmark than the presidential election in Poland's long road from a command to a market-based economy will be the Parliamentary ballot scheduled for 1997.  Bugajski concludes that "in the longer-term, the Socialist program will need to be monitored, particularly the passage of future budgets and any inclination to increase spending for social services that may result in a higher public deficit.<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/10/96</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

