<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 10,

April 17, 1995</h4>
<hr>
<h1>India: Slowly but Surely</h1>

<h3>The CSIS International Financial Contingencies Group looks at India's prospects. . . </h3>

In light of the changing political balance in the lead-up to general elections next spring, what is the outlook for continued economic and financial reform in India?  Members of the CSIS International Financial Contingencies Group (IFCG)--chaired by Bill Schreyer, chairman emeritus of Merrill Lynch and chairman of the CSIS Executive Committee--addressed this question last week.  Their verdict: Reform will go forward, although at a slower rate, and the prospects for continued growth are good.<P>

There is little doubt about how far India has come since 1991, when it came dangerously close to a payments crisis.  The Narasimha Rao government has since embarked on a number of important reforms, including reworking the taxation system, privatizing minority shares of state-owned enterprises, reducing import duties, liberalizing key sectors such as tele-communications, lifting foreign exchange controls, and licensing private banks.  Still, much more needs to be done:<P>

 <LI><I>State Enterprise Reform</I>:  The government has sold minority positions in state enterprises, but eventually it will also have to divest itself of its majority position to advance the privatization process and reduce nagging public deficits.<P>

<LI><I>Insurance Sector</I>:  The government is reviewing a proposal to end the state monopoly in the  industry.  There may be incremental progress in some areas--such as licensing--in the near term, but no big changes will come until after the elections.<P>

 <LI><I>Labor Laws</I>:  Strict limitations on the right of employers to fire employees--in both public and private enterprises--constrain the drive for increased efficiency and higher levels of foreign investment.  The government has postponed action on proposed changes, but larger enterprises are downsizing. <P>

<LI><I>Banking Sector</I>:  For the first time in two decades, 10 privately held banks have been licensed.  But the government still holds a majority share in existing banks and a minority share in the new ones. Continued privatization of the banking sector is a precursor to more efficient mobilization of capital.<P>
<LI><I>Fiscal Management</I>:  Last month's budget increased subsidies to small farmers and the poor.  Although it reduced tariffs from 65% to 50%, the budget deficit was 6.7%.  This  may serve to reverse the current decline in inflation, which has dropped to 10.5%.
Progress in all these areas is clouded by an uncertain political outlook.  The ruling Congress (I) Party has suffered significant losses in recent state elections, including in investor-receptive Maharashtra and Gujarat, and there is now concern that the government will be less inclined to push the reform agenda.  Members of the IFCG noted, however, that the reforms enjoy  broad-based political support.  The current political volatility could slow--but will not stop--the reform process.  One IFCG member asserted that the election results reflect an antipolitician--rather than an antireform--mood in the country.
Rao should survive the current political damage and emerge as leader of yet another coalition government a year from now. <P>

On balance, look for India to pursue an incremental reform strategy until after the general elections.  In the meantime, India's strong economic fundamentals--including a high domestic savings rate, low inflation, and internally funded capital markets--will continue to make it a good target for "discriminating" international capital flows.  On the whole, the IFCG members are enthusiastic about India's short-term outlook and long-range potential.<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/10/96</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
</html>

