<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 16,

July 16, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Gathering Speed</h1>

<h3>Argentina anticipates a rosy economic future . . </h3>

Look for economic growth in Argentina to recover somewhat this year to 2.5-3.0% and to rebound even more significantly next year.  That was the general conclusion of a distinguished group of Argentina-watchers who participated recently in the CSIS International Financial Contingencies Group (IFCG), chaired by CSIS Executive Committee Chairman and Merrill Lynch Chairman Emeritus Bill Schreyer.  But the capacity of the country to restore the high growth rates and economic dynamism of the early 1990s will depend on how well it handles unemployment, maintains fiscal discipline, restores consumer confidence, pursues labor reform, and sustains the economic reform process.  The rate of recovery will also depend on external linkages such as the policies of its main MERCOSUR partner, Brazil, and whether the U.S. Federal Reserve opts to raise interest rates to cool the U.S. economy.<P>

The economic turnaround in Argentina over the past seven years has been nothing short of profound.  Rapid economic reforms, among other things, obliterated hyperinflation and brought average growth of 7.75% during the 1991-94 period.  Then came the Mexican peso collapse and the tequila shock, which plunged Argentina into a growth contraction of 4.4% last year.  An unwelcome by-product of reform, high unemployment, made the contraction all the more difficult to tolerate.<P>

With congressional elections next year and the presidential election in 1999 looming, the operative question is whether the government can translate the current fragile recovery into sustained and more robust growth.  Variables identified by the group include:<P>

<I>Private consumption:</I> The re-entry of consumers into the Argentine economy is essential for any recovery.  Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo has attempted to encourage spending with a number of tax measures.  Nonetheless, consumption will increase only when consumers become confident that this period of stabilization will last.<P>

<I>Labor issues:</I>  Due to the massive layoffs incurred as newly privatized companies streamlined operations and a lingering recession, the unemployment rate stands at 17.4%.  However, productivity has risen in return, as evidenced by YPF, formerly a state-owned oil company now publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange.  It cut payrolls from 50,000 employees in 1990 to barely over 5,000 today.  In the same period, productivity increased 30%.<P>

<I>Trade:</I> Argentina's trade surplus hovers around $2 billion per year.  However, exports make up only 10% of its economy -- a figure that needs to grow to resolve Argentina's deficit.  Although the inclusion of Chile in MERCOSUR has obvious benefits, Brazil may be saturated with Argentine products  -- exports to Brazil increased 60% in 1995.  In response, Brazilian President Fernando Cardoso has offered a $2 billion incentive program to increase his country's exports.  On the positive side, corn and wheat prices are at a 15-year high (and expected to remain so), and industrial production increased 5% from May 1995 to May 1996.<P>

<I>Tax reform:</I> The recent drop in tax revenues have been primarily attributed to persistent tax evasion.  YoY tax receipts fell 3.2%, and an estimated 40% of the populace failed to pay social security taxes.  Improved tax collection is important if Argentina wants to effectively reduce its budget.<P>

<I>Politics:</I> The political situation looks good.  Many of the disputes between President Carlos Menem and Cavallo have been settled.  Furthermore, Cavallo's reforms, particularly the Convertibility Plan, are no longer under threat of dismantling.  Finally, both the ruling Peronists and the Radicals have come to espouse very similar political platforms, offering a political consistency unheard of for years in Argentina. <P>

With a normalized political environment, and assuming a stable international economy, Argentina should be poised for economic renewal within a few years.  In 1997, according to IFCG participants, the economy is anticipated to expand 5-6% as consumption and liquidity increase. <P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/27/96</i>

