<HTML><TITLE>CSIS Global Challenges</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>
<H2><p align="center">Projects on Europe</p></H2>
<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#capmarkets">Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project</a><p>
<a href="#finpolicy">Global Financial Policy Forum Series</a><p>
<a href="#giic">Global Information Infrastructure Commission</a><p>
<a href="#goc">Global Organized Crime</a><p>
<a href="#2002">Global Trends 2002</a><p>
<a href="#ecommerce">Globalization of Electronic Commerce</a><p>
<a href="#infowar">Information-Based Warfare</a><p>
<a href="#iiq">Information Intelligence Quotient - The IIQ©</a><p>
<a href="#ifcg">International Financial Contingencies Group</a><p>
<a href="#islamroots">Islamic Roots of Democratic Pluralism</a><p>
<a href="#nge">New Global Economy</a><p>
<a href="#nukes">Nuclear Weapons in a Transformed World</a><p>
<a href="#religion">Religion and Statecraft</a><p>
<a href="#cyberspace">Restructuring for Cyberspace:</a> Moving Countries from Theory to Reality<p>
<a href="#7revs">"Seven Revolutions" Project</a><p>
<a href="#statesmen">Statesmen's Forum</a><p>
<a href="#globalstrat">U.S. Global Strategy Group</a><p>

</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="capmarkets">Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project</a></h3>
Fundamental forces are transforming global financial markets and, in the process, are calling into question the ability of existing regulatory systems to cope with the rapid pace of change. This project brings together key government officials, industry leaders, economists, and legal experts to examine the regulation of capital markets in the United States and abroad, with a view to recommending appropriate changes to existing laws and regulations in light of the dramatic changes occurring in financial markets worldwide. Project principals have worked closely with Congress and regulatory agencies in support of modernization of U.S. financial services laws. In addition, the project focuses on the development of necessary capital markets infrastructure in emerging markets. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, Executive Director, Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="finpolicy">Global Financial Policy Forum Series</a></h3>
Under the auspices of the Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project and in conjunction with other CSIS programs, CSIS sponsors major policy conferences and off-the-record roundtable discussions on critical international finance issues, including the impact of technology on financial markets and the development of international accounting standards. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley D. Belt</a>, Executive Director, Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="giic">Global Information Infrastructure Commission</a></h3>
The GIIC was officially inaugurated in July 1995 at a 
meeting hosted by the World Bank. Its mission is to foster private sector leadership and private-public sector cooperation in the development of information networks and services to advance global economic growth, education, and quality of life. The Commission was established to respond to the recognition that traditional institutions and regulatory frameworks can no longer meet the increasingly complex challenges and opportunities of globalized information. The GIIC brings together 47 commissioners (mostly CEOs of major international corporations and World Bank and government representatives) from more than 20 developed and developing countries. The commission cochairs are Les Alberthal (chairman and CEO of EDS), Volker Guy (executive vice president of Siemens), and Minoru Makihara (president of Mitsubishi). <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4dougan.html">Diana Lady Dougan</a>, Chair and Senior Adviser, International Communications Program)</i>
<p><a href="http://www.gii.org/">For more on the GIIC</a>
<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="goc">Global Organized Crime</a></h3>
Organized crime has deeply penetrated the international economic and financial systems, and disparate criminal elements are integrating global operations in a way that strains national and international law enforcement and intelligence capabilities. Traditional prerogatives of national sovereignty not only are being challenged in cyberspace; they have largely ceased to exist. CSIS has responded to this threat by launching a major project that includes individual task forces on defensive information warfare (information technology security), terrorism, the nuclear black market, financial crimes, the narcotics industry, Russian organized crime, and Asian organized crime. The project recently published an extensive report entitled The Nuclear Black Market, which spawned an amendment to the National Defense Authorization Act. The project is chaired by Judge William Webster, directed by CSIS Senior Adviser <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, and codirected by CSIS Senior Adviser <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and CSIS Director of Studies <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, Senior Adviser)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="2002">Global Trends 2002</a></h3>
Designed to offer useful near-term insights to decision-makers in business and government, the project brings together CSIS experts to examine major world trends over the next decade and their implications for a number of key countries. Global Trends 2002 differs from Seven Revolutions (see page 19) in three primary ways: its shorter time frame, its more in-depth research and analysis, and its use of specific contingency analyses and country projections. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4mazarr.html">Michael J. Mazarr</a>, Director, New Millennium Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="ecommerce">Globalization of Electronic Commerce</a></h3>
"Electronic commerce" is becoming the dominant driver, not just a passenger, on the information highway. Given the ad-hoc, nonhierarchical structure of the Internet, new forms and extensions of commercial activity have evolved largely outside the traditional rules of trade, commerce, and sovereignty. Privacy, ownership, rights, tariffing, and access are just a few of the issues that take on new meaning in electronically generated or facilitated commerce. This project builds on the principles adopted in the Beijing Declaration and Call for Action Statement on "Advancing Globalized Electronic Commerce," (developed under the joint auspices of the GIIC, CIIED, the People's Bank of China, and the Ministry of Electronics Industry in the spring of 1996). They are: 1) increased private-sector leadership in cooperation with governments; 2) expanded access to the tools of electronic commerce for developing countries; 3) broad commitment to appropriate legal and regulatory frameworks; and 4) rapid transformation of banking and currency management systems.<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4garriso.html">William B. Garrison, Jr.</a>, Director, International Communications Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="infowar">Information-Based Warfare</a></h3>
As we approach the twenty-first century, the battlefield seems to be redefining itself. The coming "Information Age" will create new opportunities as well as new vulnerabilities that will have to be addressed by a re-engineered military. Although the use of information in warfare is not new, the advent of digitalization has greatly advanced its application on the battlefield. This study focuses on the future of Information-Based Warfare in the new, technology-intensive era. Through an electronic outreach program, Information Warfare forums, and an Information Warfare working group, the objective is to bring together key players in the academic, corporate, government, and military worlds to begin the critical task of framing policy for the future. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4henry.html">Ryan Henry</a>, Visiting Senior Fellow, Political-Military Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="iiq">Information Intelligence Quotient - The IIQ©</a></h3>
Electronic communication now reaches far beyond traditional networks, customers, and content providers. Current definitions and measurements of infrastructure, access, and use are inadequate and increasingly misleading in this rapidly changing environment. The Information Intelligence Quotient, or IIQ© is envisioned to replace outdated definitions and measurements of communication infrastructure development and use and to support more effective planning and policy development. This project will develop a framework for a flexible, comparative measurement that will support analysis, planning, cooperation, and decision-making. The IIQ© will be designed as a strategic tool for both governments and industry to measure and benchmark policies and technology options in three areas: (1) infrastructure, (2) access, and (3) use.<p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4dougan.html">Diana Lady Dougan</a>, Senior Adviser and Chair, International Communications Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="ifcg">International Financial Contingencies Group</a></h3>
Under the leadership of William A. Schreyer, chairman emeritus of Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc. and chairman of the CSIS Executive Committee, breaking international financial issues are covered by experts from around the world via telephone conference calls. Recent meetings have focused on India, China, and South Africa. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, Vice President and Director of Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="islamroots">Islamic Roots of Democratic Pluralism</a></h3>
This two-phase project will produce a scholarly book accessible to the educated lay public on the democratic and religiously tolerant values developed by the Prophet Muhammad and his companions in the seventh century formative or "constitutional" period of the Islamic community. The book should inspire and encourage Muslim democrats and demonstrate the shared fundamental values between Islam and the West. Phase two will be a major dissemination campaign for the book through the media and public conferences in Europe, the Middle East, Russia, and the United States. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4montvil.html">Joseph Montville</a>, Director, Preventive Diplomacy Program)</i>

<p><hr><p> 

<h3><a name="nge">New Global Economy</a></h3>
Global interest rates, labor trends, and markets have a major effect on economic trends in every state and locality. CSIS is launching a major initiative to assess the linkages between local and global markets and the implications for state and national policymaking. During the first phase of the project, a set of recommendations will be developed on how the United States can position itself at the federal level for the twenty-first century global economy. The second phase will focus on the impact of globalization on the southeastern region of the United States. <p>
<i> (<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, Vice President and Director of Studies)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nukes">Nuclear Weapons in a Transformed World</a></h3>
This study will examine the future of nuclear weapons in world politics. It consists of a detailed examination of a dramatic arms control proposal that has found increasing favor with analysts in the fieldóvirtual or dismantled nuclear arsenals. Through an edited volume and a program of international seminars, the study will examine whether virtual arsenals offer a realistic goal for the next century. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4mazarr.html">Michael J. Mazarr</a>, Director, New Millennium Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="religion">Religion and Statecraft</a></h3>
In 1994, Oxford University Press and CSIS copublished Religion: The Missing Dimension of Statecraft, with integrated essays by 17 authors from a range of disciplines. The book, which was coedited by Douglas Johnston and Cynthia Sampson, is already in its fourth printing. The outreach phase is ongoing, with seminar presentations and workshops on the book at universities, research institutes, public forums, and seminaries in the United States and abroad. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4johnsto.html">Douglas Johnston</a>, Executive Vice President)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="cyberspace">Restructuring for Cyberspace: Moving Countries from Theory to Reality</a></h3>
Over 50 countries are currently developing or implementing massive reform of their telecom laws and regulations to attract investment, infrastructure development, and service offerings. Companies and countries are also restructuring to respond to, or to co-opt, the new dynamics of multimedia market potential, on the one hand, and the still-remaining basic telephone network requirements on the other. This project facilitates direct dialogue and cooperative analysis among private and public sector decision-makers, promotes responsive policy options and "models that work," assesses "real world" impacts of telecom and broadcast restructuring in targeted countries, and enhances strategic planning capabilities of both government and industry. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4garriso.html">William B. Garrison, Jr.</a>, Program Director, International Communications Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="7revs">"Seven Revolutions" Project</a></h3>
In 1993, CSIS launched the "Seven Revolutions" initiative, a project to identify and analyze the issues that leaders will face in the year 2020. The project assesses trends in seven areas of revolutionary change: demography, environment, technology, knowledge, finance and economics, conflict, and politics and society. Trends in the Seven Revolutions, analysis of interlinkages among those revolutions, and the Center's contingency thinking have been woven together into a presentation that has been shown across the country. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4smith.html">Anthony A. Smith</a>, Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="statesmen">Statesmen's Forum</a></h3>
This ongoing address series is designed to provide heads of state and other high-level political leaders with a forum for presenting their views about critical policy issues to other members of the policy community. Audience participants include U.S. government executive and legislative branch officials, foreign diplomats, academic and regional experts, leaders from the corporate community, and the media. These events allow those who have professional responsibility for interpretation of the issues and policy determination an opportunity to assess the positions and perspectives of government leaders and to engage in dialogue following the address. The substantive focus is generally on political, economic, and security policy issues, and current international affairs. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4johnsto.html">Douglas Johnston</a>, Executive Vice President)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="globalstrat">U.S. Global Strategy Group</a></h3>
Under the chairmanship of CSIS Counselor and former national security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski, Senator Richard Lugar (R-IN), and Representative Lee Hamilton (D-IN), CSIS completed an ambitious project entitled "Foreign Policy into the Twenty-first Century: The U.S. Leadership Challenge." In the absence of a comprehensive foreign policy agenda for the post-cold war era, CSIS assembled a high-level group of 50 top government and private sector experts to determine what kind of world the United States should be moving toward and to suggest how it should go about doing so. In the process, they defined and prioritized U.S. national interests and formulated policy recommendations in seven geographical and functional areas: Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Russia and the Newly Independent States, international security, international economics, and global problems and opportunities. The project is now in its outreach phase with distribution of the final report to the foreign policy community, including the presidential candidates, members of Congress and executive branch officials. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4johnsto.html">Douglas Johnston</a>, Executive Vice President)</i>


</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
