<TITLE>New CSIS Publications</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3pubs.gif"></p><br><p>

<b>New Publication:</b><p>
<img align=left border=1 hspace=10 src="../images/phalanx.gif" width="150" height="236"><p>
<font size="4"><b>Breaking the Phalanx</b></font><br>
<b>A New Design for Landpower in the 21st Century</b><p>
By Douglas A. Macgregor<br>
Foreword by Donald Kagan<br>
Copublished with Praeger Publishers<br>
January 1997<br>
304 pp.; $24.95<p>

<blockquote><i>"Very provocative.  This is exactly the kind of thing that should be preoccupying us all."</i><br>
ó Brent Scowcroft, LTG, USAF (ret)</blockquote>

<blockquote><i>"The old ways and the old force, what's left of it, just won't cut it.  Macgregor, in </i>Breaking the Phalanx<i>, offers us cutting edge analysis of what's wrong, suggestions of how to fix it, and a great place to begin the debate."</i><br
>
	ó  Joseph L. Galloway, Senior Writer,
   U.S. News and World Report</blockquote>

<blockquote><i>"By any standard, this is a landmark contribution to the debate on the future of our military forces."</i>
ó  Raymond Macedonia, PhD, author
       of <i>Getting it Right</i></blockquote>


This work proposes the reorganization of America's ground forces on the strategic, operational, and tactical levels.  Central to the proposal is the simple thesis that the U.S. Army must take control of its future by exploiting the emerging revolution in 
military affairs.  The analysis argues that a new army warfighting organization will not only be more deployable and effective in joint operations; reorganized information age ground forces will be significantly less expensive to operate, maintain, and mo
dernize than the army's current Cold War division-based organization.  And while ground forces must be equipped with the newest weapons, new technology will not fulfill its promise of shaping the battlefield to American advantage if new devices are merely
 grafted onto old organizations that are not specifically designed to exploit them.<p>


<i>Contents</i>

<blockquote>Foreword by Donald Kagan<p>
1.	Introduction<br>
2.	Landpower & Strategic Dominance<br>
3.	Meeting the Demands of Revolutionary Change in Warfare<br>
4.	Organizing within the RMA Trendlines<br>
5.	Fighting with the Information Age Army in the Year 2003<br>
6.	Shaping Landpower for Strategic Dominance<br>
7.	Streamlining Defense to Pay for Strategic Dominance<br>
8.	Final Thoughts and Future Prospects<p>
Appendices<br>
Selected Bibliography<br>
Index</blockquote>


Douglas A. Macgregor, a Lieutenant Colonel in the U.S. Army, was commissioned in 1976 after one year at the Virginia Military Institute and four years at the U.S. Military Academy.  He holds an M.A. in comparative politics and a Ph.D. in international rel
ations from the University of Virginia and wrote Breaking the Phalanx while serving as Army Fellow at CSIS.  Presently, he is assigned to the U.S. Army Combined Arms Center at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.<p><hr><p><hr><p><br><p>



<img align=left border=1 hspace=10 src="../images/nafta.gif" width="145" height="226">
<b><font size="4">NAFTA and Sovereignty:</font><br>
Trade-offs for Canada, Mexico, and the United States</b><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hoebing.html">Joyce Hoebing</a>, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a>, editors<p>
Contributors: Charles Doran, Jonathan Heath, Federico Reyes Heroles,
Murray Smith, Denis Stairs, Sidney Weintraub<p>

Significant Issues Series 		December 1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-322-X		$20.00<p>


<i>About the Book</i><p>

The process of economic integration in North America involves more political cooperation than ever before.  The distinction between domestic and international policy is becoming increasingly blurred.  This study approaches this process from a national vie
wpoint rather than focusing on narrowly defined themes.  Two authors from each North American country examine their country's "hang-ups" regarding sovereignty, one from an economic perspective and the other from a political one. <p>

<i>Contents</i><p>

Canada<br>

	1. The Canadian Dilemma in North America - Denis Stairs<br>
	2. Canada and Economic Sovereignty - Murray Smith<p>

Mexico<br>

	3. Sovereignty: Concepts, Facts, and Feelings - Federico Reyes Heroles<br>
	4. Economic Sovereignty in Mexico - Jonathan Heath<p>

United States<br>

	5. Sovereignty Political - Charles Doran<br>
	6. NAFTA and U.S. Economic Sovereignty - Sidney Weintraub<p>



<i>About the Authors and Editors</i><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a> is senior fellow in the CSIS Americas program and director of the CSIS Mexico Project.<p>

Charles  Doran is Andrew W. Mellon Professor of International Relations at the School for Advanced International Studies (SAIS) at the Johns Hopkins University and director of SAIS's Center of Canadian Studies.<p>

Jonathan Heath is an economist specializing in the Mexican economy and the author of  The Impact of Mexico's Trade Liberalization.<p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hoebing.html">Joyce Hoebing</a> is assistant director of the CSIS Americas Program and editor of the program's Election Study Series and Policy Papers on the Americas.<p>

Federico Reyes Heroles is director of the magazine Este Pais and a regular contributor to the political editorial sections of the Mexican newspapers Reforma and El Norte.<p>

Murray Smith, an independent consultant, was previously the director of the Centre for Trade Policy and Law, Carleton University and the University of Ottawa.<p>

Denis Stairs is professor of political science at Dalhousie University in Halifax, Nova Scotia and a former president of the Canadian Political Science Association.<p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a> holds the William E. Simon Chair in Political Economy at CSIS and is Dean Rusk Professor of Internationl Affairs at the University of Texas at Austin.<p>



