<HEAD><TITLE>CSIS News & Events</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><IMG SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/3neweven.gif"></p><BR>

<p align="center"><i><b>A review of key CSIS events from recent weeks:</b></i></p>

<HR>

<table><tr>
<td><td colspan=2><td width=160 valign=top>
<P><H1> </H1><BR><P>
<font size="-1">

<a href="#oped"><I>Articles & Op-eds</I></a><p>
<A HREF="http://www.csis.org/html/calendar.html"><I>Calendar of Events</I></A><P>

<a href="#bosnia">Bosnia:</a> Building Democracy in a Divided Society<p>
<a href="#carib">Caribbean:</a> Leadership into the 21st Century<p>
<a href="#china">China:</a> Progress in Telecommunications Reforms<p>
<a href="#europe">Europe:</a> Ambassadors Discuss Baltic States' Membership in NATO<p>
<a href="#ias">International Accounting Standards</a><p>
<a href="#iran">Iran:</a> U.S. Policy Questioned<p>
<a href="#mexico">Mexican Political Stability:</a> To Be or Not To Be?<p>
<a href="#mexico2">Mexico:</a> Mexico and U.S. Immigration Policy<p>
<a href="#mideast">Middle East:</a> Rebuilding Lebanon<p>
<a href="#net">Middle East Net Assessment:</a> U.S. Policy Revisited<p>
<a href="#nato">NATO:</a> Facing New Challenges<p>
<a href="#oil">Persian Gulf Oil:</a> No Alternative<p>
<a href="#russia">Russia and the West:</a> A Relationship in Search of a Strategy<p>
<a href="#safrica">South Africa:</a>  Will the South African Economy Live Up to Expectations?<p>
<a href="#sweden">Sweden:</a> Telecom Minister Hails Swedish Liberalization and Outlines Future Plans<p>
<a href="#tanzania">Tanzania:</a>  A Conversation with President Benjamin Mkapa<p>
<a href="#turkey">Turkey:</a> Political and Economic Difficulties<p>
<a href="#turkey2">Turkey:</a> Unwilling to Undertake Austerity Measures<p>
<a href="#ukraine">Ukraine:</a> Progress on Many Fronts<p>
<a href="#us">United States:</a> Defense Restructuring for the 21st Century<p>


</td></font><P>

<td><td valign=top>


<UL>

<li><b><a name="bosnia">Bosnia: Building Democracy in a Divided Society.</a></b>  Bosnia-Hercegovina faces a long uphill struggle for democracy and civil rights.  The democratic and multiethnic option has been significantly weakened in both halves of the 

country following the September general elections.  The ballot not only legitimized the ruling nationalists but helped to consolidate ethnic division.  This was the prognosis of democratic activistsópoliticians, journalists, civic group organizers, educat

ors, and women's leadersófrom both Bosnian entities assembled by CSIS at a major forum in Sarajevo.  Participants concluded that lack of unity, agenda, and direction among opposition leaders contributed to the victory of ethno-nationalists.  The stark rea

lity is that "pluralism" in Bosnia remains a facade preserved for the benefit of the international community, which has failed to implement the civilian provisions of the Dayton accords.<p>

	Despite the pessimism, participants at the forum reached a number of concrete conclusions on how to proceed in the post-election period.  It is important for democratic parties and civic organizations to expand cooperation within and between the two enti

ties.  Without such a concerted effort, democrats will remain divided and marginalized.  Mergers between similar parties will also be necessary; otherwise, many will vanish by the next general elections.  The creation of an anti-nationalist civic bloc is 

also imperative to encompass a broad spectrum of parties, civic organizations, and local initiatives.  And, of course, a stronger network of alternative mass media, spanning the entire country, is essential to develop communication, dialogue, and civic ed

ucation across the ethnic divide.  In this process, the international community must play a more prominent and tangible role; otherwise, the premise of the Dayton accordsóthe restoration of a single multiethnic stateóremains a dead letter.  <i>(East Europ

ean Studies)</i><p>


  <li><b><a name="carib">Caribbean: Leadership into the 21st Century.</a></b>  Guiding the Caribbean into the next century will require greater understanding among the various sectors of each country's societyóprivate and public sectors, nongovernmental o

rganizations, community leaders, academiaóas well as among the different countries of the region, according to the CSIS Caribbean Leadership Group.  The group, composed of young, emerging leaders from the Caribbean, agreed that the next generation of lead

ers must do a better job of (1) articulating the difficult steps the region must take  to remain economically competitive in a global marketplace and retain its strong democratic traditions, and (2) identifying the long-term benefits of such a strategy.  

Over the next 12 months, participants will examine various issues, including:<p>

     <ul><li>the need to balance the benefits of greater economic and political cooperation with the inevitable loss of some sovereignty;
 	<li>the obstacles to forging a common Caribbean ideology and identity; and,
 	<li>the necessity of defending democracy against the influence and corruption of narcotics trafficking.</ul><p>

	Of particular concern to many of the participants was rising apathy among youth and the lack of economic opportunities, which may result in either a "brain drain"óthe emigration of a majority of the most-able populationóor the increased attractiveness of

 drug trafficking. When polled, 65 percent of young people in the English-speaking Caribbean did not believe their lot would improve significantly over the next five years.<p>

	Finally, the leaders questioned how the sometimes crisis-driven U.S.-Caribbean relationship might evolve.  Many envision, and fear, the potential for a competitive community of nations in the Caribbean.  This remains a key challenge for small, open, demo

cratic societies.  As one of the participants stated, "Having a vision of the future is essential, but having one alone is not enough." <i>(Americas Program)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="china">China: Progress in Telecommunications Reforms.</a></b>   At a CSIS conference in Beijing, Reed Hundt, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), applauded China's efforts in telecommunications services and stressed th

e need for competition and choice in the market.  Addressing an audience of key policymakers from diverse agencies and ministries involved in China's informatization, Hundt outlined U.S. regulatory processes and goals.  He emphasized the United States' su

ccess with competition, which has resulted in better and lower-priced services for consumers.  "If we are to harness the enormous potential of the information age . . . we must be guided first and foremost by two principles: open markets and choice." <i>(

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/">International Communications Studies
Program</a>, CSIS's Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development, Beijing)</i><p>


  	<li><b><a name="europe">Europe: Ambassadors Discuss Baltic States' Membership in NATO.</a></b>  The Baltic countries are committed to becoming full members of NATO and share a common perspective on this issue, stated the Estonian, Latvian, and Lithuani

an Ambassadors at a recent CSIS forum.  In a joint speech at CSIS, the ambassadors argued that all applicant countries should be allowed to join NATO and that the accession of some states should not block that of others.  Furthermore, they hold that the B

altics are as well prepared for NATO membership as are the Central European states, which are widely speculated to be the first new members.  Other Western institutions such as the European Union, the West European Union, and the Organization for Security

 and Cooperation in Europe are not viable substitutes for NATO.<p>

	Inclusion of the Baltic countries in NATO raises the problem of a Russian reaction.  NATO would like to expand slowly because there is hope for a new relationship with Russia.  The Baltic countries, however, do not share this optimism.  They believe that

 their bid for membership is not provocative but rather preventive; it will act as a deterrent to Russian intervention in the Baltics.  As long as there is an unstable Russia, they argue, the Baltics will be at risk.  While NATO is proceeding with caution

, then, the Baltic countries remain worried that a first round of enlargement that excludes them will render the region perilously volatile.  <i>(European Studies Program)</i><p>


  <li><b><a name="ias">International Accounting Standards.</a></b>  As the pace of cross-border securities activity has quickened in recent years, the issue of disparate regulatory standards has taken on heightened importance. While market participants an

d regulatory authorities generally concur that the development of acceptable international standards would facilitate the continued growth of truly global financial markets, progress in reaching standards has been slow.  A number of critical issues remain

 unresolved. <p>

	During a roundtable session at CSIS, participants discussed the status of the International Accounting Standard Commission's (IASC) project to develop a core set of internationally acceptable standards and qualitative and quantitative comparisons between

 U.S. Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) and non-U.S. standards.  They also debated whether U.S. listing standards should be modified to accommodate foreign issuers who do not reconcile with U.S. GAAP.  The Securities and Exchange Commission 

(SEC), although supportive of the IASC's undertaking to develop an acceptable set of international standards, believes that U.S. GAAP provide more useful information and greater transparency than other existing standards do.  The Commission emphasized the

 essential role of high-quality accounting standards in preserving both investor protection and the preeminent global position of U.S. capital markets.  Foreign issuers, on the other hand, expressed the view that U.S. GAAP are unduly detailed and overly c

omplicated.  In addition, other participants argued that there is a lack of empirical data to support the argument that U.S. standards are superior to international standards.  (<i>Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project)</i><p>


  <li><b><a name="iran">Iran: U.S. Policy Questioned.</a></b>  The U.S. government must reassess its current policy toward Iran.  Containment solves nothing; instead, it intensifies the friction and worsens relations between the two countries.  This was t

he message delivered by several speakers during a CSIS conference on Central Asia.  Although it is in the U.S. national interest to assist the nations of Central Asia in achieving growth and political stability, the current U.S. policy toward Iran may ins

tead help throw those nations back into the not-so-tender arms of Russia.  <i>(Energy and National Security Program)</i><p>


<li><b><a name="mexico">Mexican Political Stability: To Be or Not To Be?</a></b> The economic policy that Mexico has followed for the last decade has failed to meet the needs of the average Mexican. Economic liberalization alone has not, and will not, sol

ve Mexico's social problems, asserted a group of U.S. and Mexican specialists during a discussion at CSIS on Mexico's political stability.  The uneven distribution of the benefits reaped from economic liberalization, coupled with the adverse effects of th

e 1994 peso crisis, has led to frustration and heightened social tensions.  Media reports disclosing flagrant abuses of public office and illicit self-enrichment have further exacerbated the problem. The analysts agreed that these escalating tensions come

 at a time when Mexico is navigating through what could be a defining moment in its political historyóa political opening that, if realized, could end the ruling party's 67-year reign.<p>

	Doubts about the ability of Mexico's political party system to represent the interests of the average Mexican have prompted some Mexicans in marginalized parts of the country to consider guerrilla movements as alternative channels of political expression

.  Although some of the analysts suspect that the guerrilla movements have been used in part by anti-reform factions interested in altering the balance of power, they do not dismiss the possibility that such activity could also be symptomatic of a more pr

ofound change in Mexico's traditional political apathy.  Those who have a stake in Mexico's political future must not lose sight of the great strides that the country has taken toward economic and political transparency.  Mexico's rapid decentralization i

s likely to cause particular pendulum swings in the future, which are typical of any confederation.  The upcoming mid-term elections in July 1997 will serve as a bellwether of Mexico's political evolution.  <i>(Mexico Project)</i><p>


<li><b><a name="mexico2">Mexico: Mexico and U.S. Immigration Policy.</a></b>  More fences and expanded border patrols are unlikely to alter the number of Mexicans who illegally cross the border, except perhaps at isolated venues.  Experts at a CSIS confer

ence on U.S.-Mexican immigration issues concluded that stronger sanctions against employers who knowingly hire illegal immigrants would be a more effective solution. The de facto migration policy of each country must also change to accommodate the new pol

itical and economic conditions in the bilateral relationship. To do this, a bilateral approach is needed under which each country is willing to make concessions acceptable to the other.  For example, the United States could foster more legal immigration f

rom Mexico; and Mexico, for its part, needs to recognize that the internal political and economic policies that lead to the emigration of its nationals will require modification.  <i>(William E. Simon Chair in Political Economy and University of Texas)</i

><p>


<li><b><a name="mideast">Middle East: Rebuilding Lebanon.</a></b>  Progress in the peace process would significantly bolster the political and economic reconstruction of Lebanon.  Prime Minister Rafiq B. Hariri of Lebanon, speaking at a recent CSIS States

men's Forum, asserted that parliamentary elections were successful and that economic recovery is proceedingóthe Lebanese pound is stable and inflation is under control.  Hariri stressed, however, that foreign investment in Lebanon was critical in the next

 stage.  The U.S. ban on travel to Lebanon has affected confidence and prevented American investors from taking advantage of profitable opportunities in Lebanon. Yet despite the ban, thousands of Americansómost Lebanese-Americanóare traveling to Lebanon e

very year.  The prime minister spoke to President Clinton about lifting the travel ban after the U.S. elections because, he claims, there are no security problems.<p>

	Hariri said that Syrian forces in Lebanon have helped the central government maintain security.  There can be no "Lebanon first" in the peace process because neither Syria nor Lebanon would abandon the other.  The withdrawal of Israel's defense forces fr

om southern Lebanon in accordance with UN Resolution 425 would be a meaningful initial step.  Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed militia in southern Lebanon, continues to resist Israeli occupation.  Although the prime minister has many political differences wi

th Hezbollah, he recognizes that foreign occupation always prompts citizen resistance.  <i>(Middle East Studies)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="net">Middle East Net Assessment: U.S. Policy Revisited.</a></b>  The United States faces growing problems in sustaining its efforts to contain Iran and Iraq.  Although the United States has had considerable success in its efforts to conta

in the build-up of Iranian and Iraqi military forces, Arab, European, and Asian support for economic sanctions for Iraq is steadily diminishing, noted Tony Cordesman, codirector of CSIS Middle East Studies in recent testimony to the Senate Armed Services 

Committee.  Furthermore, there is minimal support for U.S. efforts to enforce economic sanctions on Iran. The United States has also failed to address the contradictions between the U.S. energy policy that calls for a major expansion in Iranian and Iraqi 

oil production and a containment policy that attempts to block investment in Iran's and Iraq's capability to expand and sustain their petroleum exports. <p>

	The United States needs both a near-term and a much clearer, long-term strategy for maintaining its power projection capabilities in the Gulf.  In the short run, Cordesman believes, the key to dealing with Iraqi and Iranian military capabilities will be 

a continued military alliance between the United States and the southern Gulf states.  No deal with Iraq is likely to last longer than the U.S. military presence in the Gulf or be any stronger than a combination of southern Gulf military forces and U.S. p

ower projection capabilities.  Diplomacy at best will be an extension of force by other means.  As is the case with Iran, the threat from Iraq can ultimately be contained or countered only by U.S. and allied war fighting capability.  <p>
	At the same time, the long-term strategy must address issues in other areas, including:<p>

   <ul><li>reconciling U.S. containment policy with U.S. energy policy;
 	<li>realizing that economic sanctions against Iraq are punishing the Iraqi people, not the leadership;
 	<li>devising a strategy for strengthening southern Gulf allies that looks far beyond arms sales and burden-sharing and focuses on political stability and military effectiveness;
 	<li>creating a strategy for dealing with local political and economic problems and the issue of Islamic fundamentalism; and
 	<li>developing a strong counterterrorism policy tailored to the threats in the Gulf and preparing for unconventional warfare.</ul><p>  <i>(Middle East Studies)</i><p>


<li><b><a name="nato">NATO:  Facing New Challenges.</a></b>  The process of adapting NATO to today's European security context is marked by three challenges.  First, NATO must define new roles and a new mission for itself and respond to crises such as Bos

nia.  Second, NATO must reform to accommodate a stronger European security and defense identity and to settle the issue of the Southern Command.  Third, NATO must look carefully at the issue of expansion.  This final challenge raises poignant questions th

at remain to be settled: How do we justify the claim that NATO enlargement increases security?  What to do with the countries that are not invited to join immediately, or not at all?  How to handle Russia?  These questions were addressed at a recent CSIS 

Eurowatch Group meeting.<p>

	Exactly which Central and Eastern European countries will be invited to join NATO remains an open question.  The United States is keen to keep the requirements for NATO membershipóa stable democratic system, a growing and stable economy, civilian control

 of the militaryóvery high, yet others criticize this approach as exclusive and divisive.  Enlargement is an open process, however, and membership in NATO should be used as an incentive to encourage potential members to conduct reforms that they otherwise

 would not be willing or able to implement.  <i>(European Studies Program)</i><p>


  <li><b><a name="oil">Persian Gulf Oil: No Alternative.</a></b>  Oil-importing nations have been searching for years for an acceptable alternative to Persian Gulf oilóthat is, supplies considered more secure and less subject to political manipulation.  F

ollowing the dissolution of the Soviet Union, foreign oil companies were invited to explore for and develop the rich oil potential of the Caspian Sea Basin.  The potential of this basin has caught the eye of virtually every major international oil company

.  Tens of billions of dollars are to be invested in the Caspian in production and pipeline infrastructure.  But has an alternative to Persian Gulf oil been found?  Unfortunately for those oil-importing nations, it has not, stated Bob Ebel, director of th

e CSIS Energy and National Security Program at a CSIS conference on Central Asia.  Consequently, the U.S. relationship with Persian Gulf producers will be just as important in the years ahead as it is today.  In fact, growing U.S. dependence on Persian Gu

lf oil seem inescapable.  <i>(Energy and National Security Program)</i><p>


 	<b><a name="russia">Russia and the West: A Relationship in Search of a Strategy.</a></b>  Russia and the West are fast approaching a critical moment that will significantly influence the course of their relations long into the future.  As Russia attempt

s to define its national interests following the collapse of the Soviet empire, the opportunities for the United States and its European allies to help integrate Russia politically and culturally into the West have never been greater.  At the same time, t

he West has an opportunity to enhance stability in Central Europe by extending NATO's security umbrella eastward.  The United States and its allies face a paradoxóeither they can go forward with NATO expansion and confront an alienated and possibly hostil

e Russia in the future, or they can restructure NATO into a political alliance lacking any substantial deterrent capability.  This second option would accommodate Russian concerns and prevent what could be a crisis in relations between Russia and the West

, but at the cost of undermining NATO's role as a central instrument of military stability in Europe.<p>

	Dr. Michael St&uuml;rmer, director of the research institute Stiftung Wissenschaft und Politik in Germany, recently discussed at a CSIS briefing the choices faced by the West and the potential Russian response.  He noted that although Russia cannot stop 

NATO's acceptance of new members, it can turn NATO expansion into a high-risk gamble for the West in the long term.  Among its many options, Russia could (1) threaten the Baltic states by raising tensions over the treatment of ethnic Russians in the regio

n, (2) conduct large-scale military exercises along Russia's borders with Central Europe to frighten off potential investors from NATO's new former Communist members, or (3) call back credit extended to Ukraine to create an economic crisis there.  As NATO

 prepares to announce its intentions in the coming months, the West must anticipate Russia's reaction and be aware of the risks and dangers that lie ahead.  <i>(Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="safrica">South Africa:  Will the South African Economy Live Up to Expectations?</a></b>  South Africa's political miracle must now be matched by an economic miracle, according to Dr. Conrad Strauss, chairman of South Africa's Standard Ban

k Investment Corporation.   Political and social uncertainty have created a wait-and-see stance among potential foreign investors.  Despite successful and democratic local elections throughout the country, a reduction in political violence, and the increa

sing accountability of its civil service, South Africa is still at a transitional stageóinstitution-building takes time.<p>

	Among the most tenacious and fundamental economic challenges facing South Africa are a flat and sticky growth rate of three percent, dwindling foreign exchange reserves, and a low gross domestic savings rate.  Designed to strike at the heart of the probl

em is the new "Growth, Employment, and Redistribution" program (GEAR) that targets budget and tax reform, job creation, worker training, and privatization.  The program does little, however, to create social action programs for the poor, a gap Deputy Pres

ident Thabo Mbeki is now trying to fill.  Strauss believes that GEAR will ultimately succeed, thanks to an emerging partnership between government and the private sector and the commitment of both to create conditions necessary for growth.  <i>(African St

udies Program)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="sweden">Sweden: Telecom Minister Hails Swedish Liberalization and Outlines Future Plans.</a></b>  The Swedish telecom market is one of the most open in Europe.  With the upcoming revision of the 1993 Telecom Act, Sweden promises to lead E

urope in liberalization, stated Swedish Minister for Transport and Communications Ines Uusmann during a CSIS conference.  "The experience of the liberalization of the Swedish telecom market shows that a lower level of regulation is preferable to a higher 

one. As a result of the liberalization, the Swedish market is very dynamic."  <p>

	The Swedish Telecom Ministry is now working with dominant carrier Telia and the telecom regulatory authority on the planned July 1, 1997 revision of the current telecom law. This revision is necessary for two reasons: (1) failure of the original legislat

ion to address contentious issues such as interconnection, and (2) new EU regulations and directives aimed at European telecom harmonization.  <i>(International Communications Studies Program)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="tanzania">Tanzania:  A Conversation with President Benjamin Mkapa.</a></b>  Tanzania continues its struggle to move beyond its one-party socialist legacy and strengthen its democratic institutions.  Economic reforms are bringing about deb

t relief, increased foreign investment, and privatization.  At its peak, Tanzania had 400 state-owned enterprises; today many of these enterprises have been privatized, and the government is actively trying to sell others at a reasonable price.  Identifyi

ng himself as a representative of this new style of leadership in Africa, President Benjamin Mkapa described these ongoing positive reforms during a CSIS briefing.<p>

	New African leaders are committed to establishing more market-oriented economies and promoting sustainable development.  Mkapa emphasized that African nations do not need endless aid, but rather logistic and technical support that will facilitate self-re

liance and development.  Successful reform can be initiated only by the African people; however, international support for debt relief, privatization, and foreign direct investment is still necessary.  As an influential global leader, the United States mu

st continue to push the political and economic reform process.  <i>(African Studies Program)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="turkey">Turkey: Political and Economic Difficulties.</a> </b> The two wings of the current coalition government, the Islamist Welfare Party and the secular, center-right True Path Party, have continued to pull in different directions, eve

n as their joint interest in staying in power has led them to downplay their differences in order to maintain the partnership.  Visiting speakers at CSIS focused on the basic contradictions in the government and pointed out the dangers for Turkey's future

.<p>

	Although Halis Komili, president of the Turkish Industrialists and Businessmen's Association (TUSIAD), underlined the need for an enhanced role for his organization and the entire Turkish private sector in the effort to find a solution to the problems af

flicting Turkey, he was not optimistic that the worsening economic situation or other Turkish woes could be solved in the near future. Emre Gonensay, the former foreign minister who resigned from the True Path Party because of his opposition to the curren

t coalition, spoke about the need for structural reforms in the Turkish economy and political institutions and called for an end to the potentially dangerous drift away from the West.  He pointed to the related delay of the Turkish effort to build support

 for a Baku-Ceyhan pipeline.  <i>(Turkish Studies)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="turkey2">Turkey: Unwilling to Undertake Austerity Measures.</a></b>  Turkey's proposed 1997 budget is unrealistic and fails to tackle the root causes of Turkey's economic problems, concludes the latest issue of CSIS's Turkey Update.  The 

Welfare Party, with its populist policies designed to maximize its chances of coming to power alone in early general elections, is unwilling to alienate its core supporters at the bottom of the economic scale by tightening the Turkish economic belt. With 

the IMF talks on this issue stalled, Turkey is moving toward a credit crunch and further financial and political convulsions. <i>(Turkish Studies)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="ukraine">Ukraine: Progress on Many Fronts.</a></b>  Ukraine has clearly made progress in its transition to a marketplace democracy, as evidenced by recent signs of economic stabilization in the country and the adoption of a new constituti

on.  In addition, the recent formation of the Al Gore-Leonid Kuchma Commission, a milestone in the development of Ukrainian-American relations, demonstrates that the strategic partnership between America and Ukraine is becoming a reality.  <p>

	During the CSIS American-Ukrainian Advisory Committee (AUAC) meeting in Kiev, committee members recommended that both governments begin the task of prioritizing and defining more clearly the concrete political, security, and economic content of the new U

krainian-American strategic partnership.  To assist this effort, the following chief recommendations were made:<p>

 <ul><li>If Russia is invited to next year's NATO summit, Ukraine should be invited as well;
 <li>	Cooperation between Ukraine and NATO should be upgraded.  The Ukrainian government should take a number of specific steps to that end;
 <li>	Both countries should express concern over the ongoing political developments in Belarus;
 <li>	Economic reforms in Ukraine should be intensified and accelerated in a number of specific ways;
 <li>	The United States and the European Union (EU) should work to enhance Ukraine's relations with the EU;
 <li>	The United States should henceforth refer to Ukraine in its official statements not as a NIS but as a Central European state; and,
 <li>	Contact with and between U.S. members of Congress and Ukrainian parliamentarians should be intensified.</ul><p>
  	     <i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2europe.html#amerukra">American-Ukrainian Advisory Committee</a>)</i><p>


 <li><b><a name="us">United States: Defense Restructuring for the 21st Century.</a></b>  The Quadrennial Defense Review (QDR) has the potential to fundamentally shake up the U.S. defense structure and defense policy.  At the first CSIS Military Strategy F

orum on QDR, Dr. Edward Warner, assistant secretary of defense for strategy and requirements, discussed the Defense Department's ambitious undertaking that will produce a blueprint for U.S. defense posture into the next century.  The QDR will examine five

 basic elementsóthe strategic environment in the near future, the U.S. force structure, modernization, readiness, and the defense infrastructure.  Although the review is mandated by law, its timing is very appropriate because of the changes the defense co

mmunity is confronting.  <p>

	In the face of large cutbacks in funding and manpower, the Department of Defense is attempting to craft a leaner, more effective military that will be able to meet the uncertain challenges of the post-Cold War era.  Rapid advances in technology are also 

presenting policymakers with a host of new weapons systems, from nonlethal weapons to the Joint Strike Fighter, that are competing for limited resources.  The review will be formally launched this December with the final report due in May, after which it 

is passed over to the National Defense Panel (NDP) for a critique.  In addition to critiquing the QDR, the NDP has been tasked by Congress to conduct a separate study called the Alternative Force Structure Assessment (AFSA), which will be presented to Con

gress in December 1997.  <i>(Political-Military Studies)</i><p>

</UL><P>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/news1196.html">November's News & Events</a><p>
<td></tr></table>



