<HTML><TITLE>National Commission on Retirement Policy</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3spcproj.gif"></p><br><p>

<H2><p align="center">The
National Commission on Retirement Policy</p></H2><p>
<h3><p align="center">Fact Sheet</p></h3>

<table cellpadding=15><tr>

<td valign=top width=150><font size="2">
<i>For information about specific aspects of the project:</i><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/">Overview</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/members.html">Members Biographies</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/press.html">Press Advisory</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/mission.html">Mission Statement</a>


</font></td>

<td>


<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>We are growing older. In 1950, only 7.9% of the population was over 65.  By 2010, that number will grow to 19.4%. </blockquote> 

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>We are living longer.  When Social Security was enacted in 1935, the life expectancy of Americans was under 65 years of age.  Today, it is over 75 years of age, which means that benefits are paid out for more years.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>Current levels of spending on entitlement programs are not sustainable.  Under current law, by 2015, spending on entitlement programs and net interest on the debt will absorb all federal revenues.  By 2070, the unfunded liability of Social Security and Medicare will be over $20 trillion.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>Fifty years ago, over 40 workers paid in to Social Security for every beneficiary.  In 14 years, when Baby Boomers begin to retire, there will be fewer than three workers per beneficiary.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>Fewer future workers will be contributing to sustain these federal entitlement programs.  The birth rate has declined from the Baby Boomer peak average of over 3.6 to just over 2 births.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>Social Security is a "pay as you go" system, in which current payroll taxes fund current benefits.  With the retirement of the Baby Boom generation, the benefits will begin to exceed revenues by 2012.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>Only half of American workers are covered by a pension plan.  Last year alone, there was a $64 billion unfunded liability, or shortfall in these funds.  In 1979, "defined-benefit" plans made up 90% of all employer pension programs.  By 1990, this dropped to just over 60%.  This shift to "defined-contribution" plans [e.g. 401(k)'s] has created an investment education gap.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>The American people are not saving like they used to.  The personal savings rate, over 11% in 1965, has decreased to under 3% in 1993.  Half of American families have below $1,000 in net financial savings.</blockquote>

<b>FACT:</b>	<blockquote>The National Commission on Retirement Policy is sponsored by CSIS, a public policy research institution dedicated to "policy impact."  This initiative will look at all aspects of the retirement financing crisis.  It has no pre-ordained outcome in mind.  The effort is broad and bipartisan ó headed by leading members of Congress and the private sector.  The goals are to analyze the various policy options, educate the public on the issues, and build a political consensus on what must be done, ending with the formation of new legislation.</blockquote>


<i>Sources:  OASDI Board of Trustees Report, 1996; Social Security Advisory Council testimony, and CSIS.</i>
  

</td></tr> </table>
<HR width=300>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p>
</body>
