<HTML>

<TITLE>CSIS Projects on Africa</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>
<H2><p align="center">Projects on Africa</p></H2>
<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#converse">"Conversations" with African Heads of State</a><p>
<a href="#finance">CSIS Working Group on Finance in Africa</a><p>
<a href="#notes">CSIS Africa Notes</a><p>
<a href="#angola">CSIS Angola Study Group</a><p>
<a href="#finance">CSIS Working Group on Finance in Africa</a><p>
<a href="#nigeria">CSIS Nigeria Working Group</a><p>
<a href="#south">CSIS Working Group on South and Southern Africa</a><p>
<a href="#discuss">Discussions on African Regional and Functional Topics</a>
</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>
<h3><a name="converse">"Conversations" with African Heads of State</a></h3>
 The African Studies Program hosts conversation-style meetings with visiting heads of state and other senior government officials. Recent sessions have included President Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania, JosÈ Eduardo dos Santos of Angola, President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of Ethiopia, President Frederick Chiluba of Zambia, President Jerry Rawlings of Ghana, and Prime Minister Kengo wa Dondo of Zaire. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4freeman.html">Constance Freeman</a>, Director, African Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="finance">CSIS Working Group on Finance in Africa</a> </h3>
African economies emerging from the rigors of structural adjustment and economic policy reform are vibrant with new opportunities in key financial sectors, but taking advantage of them requires knowledge as well as an adventurous spirit. To help interested companies become familiar with this world, the African Studies Program has launched a new study group exploring targeted markets, the transition to open economies, the regionalization of the African marketplace, the mechanics of banking/stock markets/exchange rates and the financial products needed to support growth. Featuring key African actors and their business partners from other parts of the world, this group plots the transition from donor-based to private economies and helps its members take advantage of the numerous opportunities for profit in this capital-scarce environment. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4freeman.html">Constance Freeman</a>, Director, African Studies Program, and Stephen Cashin, Financial Consultant)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="notes">CSIS Africa Notes</a></h3>
 A briefing paper series published monthly since 1982 to serve the special needs of decision-makers and analysts with Africa-related responsibilities in governments, corporations, the media, research institutions, universities, and other arenas. Recent and projected examples of the range of topics addressed: "African Democratization: An Update," "The Information Revolution Comes to Africa," "U.S. Priorities in Sub-Saharan Africa: Looking Toward the Twenty-first Century," and "Angola's Elusive Peace."<p> 
<i>(Editor: <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kitchen.html">Helen Kitchen</a>, Chair, African Studies Program)</i><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/afrnews.html">What's New in CSIS Africa Notes</a>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="angola">CSIS Angola Study Group</a></h3>
 Cochaired by Senator Nancy L. Kassebaum (R-KS), Chester Crocker, Landegger Distinguished Research Professor at the Georgetown University School of Foreign Service, and Maurice Tempelsman, this forum has continued to meet frequently since it was organized in February 1991. The roster of guest speakers at the periodic half-day sessions includes key Angolan leaders from across the political spectrum; senior UN, Portuguese, and U.S. officials; corporate analysts; and academic specialists.<p> 
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kanstei.html">Walter Kansteiner</a>, CSIS Senior Associate)</i>

<p><hr><p> 

<h3><a name="nigeria">CSIS Nigeria Working Group</a></h3>
 Cochaired by President Richard Matzke of Chevron Overseas Petroleum, Pauline Baker, president of the Fund for Peace, and Representative Cynthia McKinney (D-GA), the Nigeria roundtable, organized in 1993, examines a broad range of assessments from various key actors and analysts of the prospects for political stability and responsible governance in sub-Saharan Africa's most populous country. Plans are underway to expand activities in October 1996 to search for solutions to the current Nigerian dilemma. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cowan.html">L. Gray Cowan</a>, CSIS Senior Associate)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="south">CSIS Working Group on South and Southern Africa</a></h3>
 This roundtable forum meets frequently with distinguished guest speakers representative of a broad spectrum of perspectives to assess local, regional, and intercontinental implications (political, economic, and social) of the post-apartheid transition in South Africa.  Cochairs are Ambassador Donald McHenry of Georgetown University, Wayne Fredericks of the Carnegie Corporation, and Daniel O'Flaherty, vice president of the National Foreign Trade Council and executive director of the U.S.-South Africa Business Council. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4schneid.html">Witney Schneidman</a>, CSIS Senior Associate)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="discuss">Discussions on African Regional and Functional Topics</a></h3>
 The program convenes audiences to participate in discussion on a wide range of African issues and countries. In 1996 a series of sessions on Africa's Great Lakes Region was launched; the roster included U.S. ambassadors to Uganda and Zaire, Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame, Ugandan Defense Minister Amama Mbabazi, and U.S. Special Envoy to Burundi Peace Negotiations Howard Wolpe. A series of events examining the countries of the CFA zone has also been inaugurated.  <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4freeman.html">Constance Freeman</a>, Director, African Studies Program)</i>

</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:webmaster@csis.org">webmaster</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
</font>

