<head><TITLE>CSIS Business Alert</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/alert.gif"><P>

<h4>Number 13,

January 30, 1996</h4>
<hr>
<h1>Not So Fast</h1>

<h3>Don't expect another stampede into emerging markets in 1996</h3>

Will there be a resurgence in international portfolio investment to the emerging markets this year?  Members of the CSIS International Financial Contingencies Group (IFCG), chaired by Bill Schreyer, chairman emeritus of Merrill Lynch, addressed this issue yesterday.  Their conclusion: A restoration of portfolio flows is in the cards, but not at the record level of 1993.  After the "reality check" that the December 1994 collapse in Mexico inflicted on them, international investors will be much more discriminating.<P>

The circumstances for increased capital flows to the emerging markets appear to be favorable.  Interest rates are down in the industrialized countries.  Global capital liquidity, according to industry reports, is the highest it has been for three years.  Emerging markets are still showing faster growth rates than the highly industrialized countries, and many of their shares offer more attractive p/e-to-growth ratios.  That, coupled with the perception that U.S. markets may not be able to match last year's performance, suggests that foreign portfolio investment may rebound -- by one account to $50 billion, as compared with the peak of more than $60 billion in 1993.<P>

Asia continues to represent the most attractive investment target, particularly for capital investment, but the picture there is mixed.  Korea is embroiled in political crisis; allegations of political payoffs have now escalated into charges of treason.  In China, the heavy-handed policies enacted by the government to restrict business-oriented information have cast a shadow over the explosion of private sector activity.  India faces elections in April and is locked in political crisis over corruption issues.  By contrast, the outlook for the Philippines, Indonesia, and Thailand is encouraging.<P>

In Latin America, reform is holding up well.  The Mexican government is persevering politically with its austerity program, and today's $1.3 billion initial repayment of the U.S.-led assistance package is a positive sign.  Argentina has also registered significant
 progress in restoring fiscal discipline and investor confidence. Brazil and Peru are both experiencing high growth rates, though the string of elections over the next three years suggests potential obstacles.  The Chilean market is solid, though there is some concern about the possibility of falling world copper prices.<P>

South African financial markets surged at the end of last year, and if the last remaining currency controls are lifted, it will reinforce the recent trend of large foreign capital inflows.<P>

In the face of this menu of investment options, investors are likely to discriminate on the basis of several clear criteria.  First, they will look at market size.  Many of the emerging markets are thin, and those low levels of capitalization will serve as a disincentive.  Investors will not want to get caught again in small markets in which their liquidity is reduced.  Second, they will look for good economic fundamentals.  Investors will need clear evidence that they are solidly on the reform track and positioned to "earn" the foreign investment they receive with good performance.  Third, in the wake of the Mexican meltdown, investors no longer believe that the emerging markets are not correlated among themselves and will tailor their diversification strategies accordingly.<P>

The bottom line: Investors rushed into the emerging markets in 1993 and rushed out after the poor returns of 1994 and the Mexico crisis.  Now they seem poised to return, albeit selectively.  As one participant argued, "the 1993 bubble has been pricked."  It now remains to be seen how quickly flows will resume.<P>
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 6/10/96</i>

