<HEAD><TITLE>CSIS News & Events</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><IMG SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/3newseve.gif"></p><BR>

<H1>News&amp;Events</H1>

<B>A review of key CSIS events from recent weeks</B><BR><P><HR>

<table><tr>
<td><td colspan=2><td width=160 valign=top>
<P><H1> </H1><BR><P>
<font size="-1">

<a href="#oped"><I>Articles & Op-eds</I></a><p>
<A HREF="http://www.csis.org/html/calendar.html"><I>Calendar of Events</I></A><P>

<a href="#casp">Caspian Sea:</a> Dynamics of Caspian Energy Resources.<P>
<a href="#euro1">Europe:</a> "Euro-Focus"<P>
<a href="#euro2">Europe:</a> Rationalizing and Coordinating the Sale of Conventional Armaments<P>
<a href="#france">France:</a> Experts Review New Telecom Law<P>
<a href="#korea">Korean Peninsula:</a> Change and Challenge<P>
<a href="#kwaz">KwaZulu-Natal:</a> Is There Hope for ANC-Inkatha Reconciliation?<P>
<a href="#nafta">NAFTA and the U.S. Election:</a> A Trinational Assessment<P>
<a href="#nato">NATO's Future:</a> Looking Eastward<P>
<a href="#nkor">North Korea:</a> Testing the Waters<P>
<a href="#nuke">Nuclear Black Market<P>
<a href="#priv">Personal Information Privacy</a><P>
<a href="#reg">Regulatory Reform:</a> Capital Markets<P>
<a href="#russ">Russia:</a> The Fate of a Country<P>
<a href="#slov">Slovakia:</a> Developments in Democratic Pluralism<P>
<a href="#tech">Technology Renders Regulatory Systems Obsolete</a><P>
<a href="#zaire">Zaire:</a> What Next for the "Big Man" of Central Africa?<P>
</td></font><P>

<td><td valign=top>


<UL><li><B><a name="casp">Caspian Sea:</a>  Dynamics of Caspian Energy Resources.</B>  The presence of oil fosters crises; it does not resolve them.  That was the central message that Bob Ebel, director of the CSIS Energy and National Security Program, carried to a recent international conference on "Post-Dayton Balkans in Europe." The Balkans will serve as transit countries for Caspian Basin oil moving to markets in Europe, and many of the nations are anxious for international pipelines to be built across their borders.  Not only would they earn substantial transit fees, but the availability of oil and the need for the supporting infrastructure also offer prospects of jobs and fuel for their economies.  In addition, oil pipelines have become highways of influence and points of leverage for the countries whose territory they traverse.  Ebel warned that pipelines are also attractive targets for dissident activity.  The presence of oil does not soothe political friction; rather, it does just the opposite.  <I>(Energy and National Security Program)</I><P>


 <LI><B><a name="euro1">Europe:</a>  Euro-Focus.</B>  Aspects of change in Europe and U.S.-European relations are addressed in the current issue of Euro-Focus.  After analyzing the implications of the anticipated Labor victory in next year's British elections, the first article concludes that a new Labor government will pursue some policies that are more supportive of European integration.  The second discusses Polish economic and political reforms that are aimed at preparing the country for membership in NATO and the European Union and asserts that the West must provide Poland with an unequivocal commitment for membership by a certain date.  The final article reviews European reactions to the Helms-Burton Act and D'Amato bill and argues that transatlantic trade is not seriously threatened despite the recent strain that these initiatives have brought to U.S.-EU trade relations. <I>(European Studies Program)</I><P>


  <LI><B><a name="euro2">Europe:</a>  Rationalizing and Coordinating the Sale of Conventional Armaments.</B>  Can the United States and Europe create a cooperative venture within the transatlantic alliance on conventional arms sales to the Central and East European Countries (CEECs)? According to participants in a CSIS working group, the major obstacle to transatlantic cooperation is the disparity in size between the American and European defense industries.  European industry needs to consolidate so that its arms manufacturers can deal with their American counterparts on an equal footing.  Although such a consolidation will not totally eliminate the size disparity, cooperation is nevertheless possible because the Europeans hold a political card: Because many CEECs want to join the European Union, Brussels will play a significant role in negotiating the terms of arms sales to these countries.<P>

	As the expansion of both NATO and the EU looms large on the political horizon, the key task is to develop a broad vision of U.S.-EU cooperation in the sale of arms to CEECs.  Such a vision must define a mix of government and private-sector participation to integrate CEECs into Western institutions.  At present, there is little consensus within the transatlantic alliance on a specific definition of this mix, with some favoring strong governmental leadership and others advocating market-led strategies.  Although agreement on an appropriate approach will be difficult to reach, the importance of the problem makes it imperative to hold open and constructive dialogues.  <I>(European Studies Program)</I><P>


  <LI>	<B><a name="france">France:</a>  Experts Review New Telecom Law.</B>  The new French telecommunications law should make it easier for American firms to compete in France's growing telecom market, according to a panel convened by the CSIS International Communications Studies Program.  The panel reviewed provisions of the law, passed by the French parliament in June, that mandate a more competitive telecommunications framework.  The law was in part a response to a European Union regulation setting a January 1998 deadline for extensive competition in regional telecommunications services, including voice telephony.  Damien Regnault of the French Embassy characterized the law as "a real liberalization" of French telecom.<P>

	Charles Tievsky of Teleglobe International indicated that there is some concern about delays in implementing the law's provisions.  He said that Teleglobe was particularly interested in the fact that there appears to be a big demand for closed-user services.  "We're ready to act," he added.  Mary Lee Allen of MFS International noted that her company was already offering telecom services in France and other European countries.  MFS International's reaction to the law is very positive, she said.  The company's French license is on an experimental basis, providing competitive fiber-optic services in Paris.  The company has filed applications for both domestic and international licenses.  <I>(<A HREF="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/">International Communications Studies Program</A>)</I><P>


   <LI><B><a name="korea">The Korean Peninsula:</a>  Change and Challenge.</B>  The structural flaws in the North Korean economy are so serious that only radical market reforms coupled with massive foreign assistance will save the country.  That was the conclusion reached by U.S. and South Korean policymakers and scholars who recently examined the situation in North Korea and discussed the regional security fallout from the instability in that country.  Observers were divided on the likelihood of a regime change.  Some suggested that the military might take control of the country in the next two to three years; others concluded that North Korea will somehow "muddle through" for the next five.  <P>

	Participants also discussed the process and potential impact of Korean reunification.  A Korean scholar argued that a unified Korea would act as a balancer in East Asia through multilateral security cooperation, dispelling fears of a unified Korea that may gravitate toward China and antagonize Japan.  In his examination of the missile threats from North Korea, a U.S. scholar explored the implications of a theater missile defense (TMD) system for South Korea and Japan and concluded that such a system could neutralize the North's missile threats.  <I>(Asian Studies Program in conjunction with the Research Institute for National Unification [RINU], Seoul)</I><P>


  <LI>	<B><a name="kwaz">KwaZulu-Natal:</a>  Is There Hope for ANC-Inkatha Reconciliation?</B>  After years of bitter and often violent rivalry between the African National Congress (ANC) and the Inkatha Freedom Party, party leaders realize that they share common goals and that trust and cooperation must be established between them if South Africa is to prosper.  That was the central message of a delegation from the parliament of South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal province, representing both the ANC and the Inkatha, in their discussion at CSIS on the challenges of nation-building and the constitutional process in their country's nascent democracy.  While the parties disagree on key issues such as land reform and the role of traditional leaders in government, they foresee a new era of improved interparty relations and note that political violence in KwaZulu-Natal has steadily diminished in recent months.  Centralization of government power was a major theme of the delegation's discussion; Inkatha advocates a more decentralized government than does the ANC.  Nonetheless, Inkatha representatives pledged their support for South Africa's draft constitution and promised to abide by it despite their objections to some of its provisions.  Neither party predicts significant changes to the document before it goes into effect.  <I>(African Studies Program)</I> <P>

<LI> 	<B><a name="nafta">NAFTA and the U.S. Election:  A Trinational Assessment.</a></B>  The relative silence on NAFTA in this year's general election campaign stems from the agreement's success to date and proves that the arguments of NAFTA opponents were "over-hyped," concluded a panel of experts from the United States, Canada, and Mexico.  The panel, chaired by CSIS William E. Simon Chairholder Sidney Weintraub, agreed that the preliminary data were favorable:<P>

<UL>
<LI>U.S. trade increased with both Mexico and Canada, $56 billion and $132 billion respectively since NAFTA took effect.

<LI>Contrary to Ross Perot's predicted "giant sucking sound" of U.S. jobs disappearing, more than 260,000 new American jobs were created as a direct result of NAFTA during its first 30 months.

<LI>Now that the aftershocks of the Mexican peso crisis are over, Mexico is repaying its loans on time and, in fact, never drew on the full credit offered it by the U.S. Treasury.

<LI>Most critical, NAFTA has grown to become the crown jewel in America's strategy to promote free and equal trade both in this hemisphere and in the world.
</UL>
<P>

	Panel members agreed that NAFTA's success could translate favorably into other free trade initiatives.  The results of the U.S. elections this November, however, will determine whether NAFTA leads to further progress in trade liberalization.  <I>(The Americas Program)</I><P>


 <LI> 	<B><a name="nato">NATO's Future:</a>  Looking Eastward.</B>  NATO enlargement is best thought of as an ongoing, open process consisting of several stages.  Poland, the Czech Republic, and Hungary are the most likely candidates for inclusion in the first round, concluded participants at a recent CSIS conference.  Although these countries support a robust NATO defense posture, their ambitions must be tempered to avoid provoking a Russian reaction.  Prospects for the second and third rounds of expansion, however, are plagued with serious dilemmas.  If the Balkan states are not assured of inclusion, anti-Western groups in many of those countries may exploit a domestic backlash.  Conversely, Russia is likely to pose even firmer resistance to future rounds, especially if they include the Baltic states.  Facing these dilemmas, the highest priority in the enlargement process is to establish a NATO-Russian partnership for achieving the common goal of stability in Central and Eastern Europe.<P>

	The United States has an interest in supporting a NATO enlargement that leaves room for the reintegration of Russia into the new European security context.  Many European NATO members may lack determination on the issue, but will ultimately follow American leadership.  That leadership, in turn, must be clearly articulated to the American public in terms of important national security interests if it is to overcome the divisive debates that enlargement occasions.  <I>(Political-Military Studies in conjunction with the European Studies Program)</I><P>


  <LI>	<B><a name="nkor">North Korea:</a>  Testing the Waters.</B>  North Korea's recent submarine incursion into South Korean territorial waters was not just another instance of Pyongyang's traditional strategy of brinkmanship.  Rather, it was part of the continuing, dangerous pattern of North Korean infiltration of special operations forces into the South.  These North Korean forces have two primary missions: to infiltrate activist student groups and labor unions and to perform reconnaissance on high-value targets in South Korea that the North would destroy quickly in the event of war.  These were the conclusions of Bill Taylor, CSIS senior vice president, in recent media appearances and in testimony before the Senate Foreign Affairs Committee, Subcommittee on East Asia and the Pacific.  According to Taylor, Pyongyang has misread recent events in the Southóstudent riots, the sentencing of former political figures, and heated debates among political partiesóas signs of weakness.  The North's leaders do so at their own peril.  <I>(Political-Military Studies Program)</I><P>


 <LI> 	<a name="nuke"><B>Nuclear Black Market.</a></B>  "I believe it is a godsend for us," commented Senator Pete Domenici, referring to the CSIS report on the nuclear black market.  The findings and recommendations of this report contributed substantially to the Nunn-Lugar-Domenici amendment (Nunn-Lugar II) to the National Defense Authorization Act for fiscal year 1997.  (Both houses of Congress unanimously passed the amendment.)<P>

	The report proposed measures aimed at making nuclear theft and trafficking as costly, risky, and complex as possible so as to deter nuclear terrorism and to discourage organized crime from becoming further involved in nuclear smuggling.  Among the specific recommendations were: devising innovative ways to address warhead security; providing a layered defense against nuclear trafficking; developing healthy synergistic partnerships between law enforcement and intelligence here and abroad; taking a case-by-case approach to bilateral interdiction cooperation; enhancing deployment of technical sensors; specialized training of border control and other law enforcement officials; and detailed sharing and joint analysis of relevant intelligenceóespecially human intelligenceóthroughout the countries of origin, transit, and potential destination.  <I>(Global Organized Crime Project)</I><P>


 <LI> 	<a name="priv"><B>Personal Information Privacy.</B></a>  The new era of cyberspace and computer networking has led to growing concerns over the fair and appropriate handling of name-linked information.  The global nature of information flows has also highlighted the critical need to involve developing countries in establishing data protection regimes to prevent the advent of "data havens"ócountries or regimes that have lenient jurisprudence on privacy protection.  Data havens foster long-term barriers to the free flow of information because countries with established data protection laws would restrict their inflow and outflow of data to prevent groups located in data havens from misusing it.<P>

	Technological advances have rendered conventional data protection legislation obsolete.  Two major questions have now surfaced: Does the current legislation provide necessary safeguards against the misuse of personal information, and what roles must the private and public sectors play in protecting individual privacy.  "GIIC Personal Information Privacy PolicyóRecommended Actions," is an attempt to prompt companies and governments in both developed and developing countries to adopt appropriate policies and guidelines that ensure just and proper handling of name-linked data.  The paper specifies flexible measures to guide the collection and distribution of personal dataóincluding the participation of individuals in the use, processing, and quality of their informationóand also emphasizes the equal accountability of governments and the private sector in maintaining a high level of personal data protection within their own operations.  <P>

	The Coalition of Service Industries, a major industry group consisting of multinational service corporations, lauded the efforts of GIIC in preparing a truly globally oriented set of principles that can be endorsed by both corporations and governments around the world.  Data protection officials at the 18th International Conference on Privacy and Data Protection in Ottawa, Canada also acknowledged the contribution of the GIIC initiative in promoting private sector codes of protection and in raising awareness of this issue in developing countries.  <I>(<A HREF="http://www.gii.org/">Global Information Infrastructure Commission</A>)</I> <P>


<li>  <a name="reg"><B>Regulatory Reform:</a> Capital Markets.</B> The CSIS Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project recently sponsored a roundtable discussion focusing on the development of an acceptable set of international accounting standards.  As the pace of cross-border securities activity has quickened in recent years, the issue of disparate regulatory standards has taken on heightened importance. While market participants and regulatory authorities are in general accord that development of acceptable international standards would facilitate the continued growth of truly global financial markets, progress has been slow and a number of critical issues remain unresolved.  Participating in the the forum were many of the key players in this important policy debate, including SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt; Commissioners Steve Wallman and Isaac Hunt; the SEC's Chief Accountant, Michael Sutton; Dennis Beresford, Chairman of the Financial Accounting Standards Board; representatives of the International Accounting Standards Committee; as well as senior executives from leading domestic and foreign companies.  Issues discussed included the status of the IASC's project to develop a core set of internationally acceptable standards, qualitative and quantitative comparisons between U.S. GAAP and non-U.S. standards, and whether U.S. listing standards should be modified to accomodate foreign issuers who do not reconcile with U.S. GAAP.  For more information on this forum and well as related events, please contact <A HREF="mailto: beltb@csis.org">Bradley D. Belt</A>, Executive Director of the Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project.


<LI>  	<a name="russ"><B>Russia:</a>  The Fate of a Country.</B>  The burning topic across the world has been the state of health of Boris Yeltsin.  In view of the enormous powers conferred on the president by the 1993 constitutionówhich was tailor-made for Yeltsinóand his own management style of concentric and slightly overlapping subordinate spheres of power, the great ship of state has been drifting without a pilot since early July.  In numerous international media appearances, Keith Bush, senior associate of the Russian Studies Program, has addressed the succession scenarios should new elections be held in Russia.<P>

	If General Lebed makes a political comeback, the consequences for the West would be unpredictableóhe has changed his position frequently on key issues.  Furthermore, should his current economic adviser, Sergei Glaziev, be given a key post, the outlook for Western investment and business would be dim.  Gennadii Zyuganov will almost certainly try againóhis presidency would be catastrophic for the Russian economy and for Russia's relations with the West.  The other leading candidate, Yurii Luzhkov, would prove to be too assertive and aggressive as president.  He has, however, done much to attract Western business and capital to Moscow, and he would presumably continue such a beneficial policy for all of Russia.  A Chernomyrdin victory would be the most preferable outcome for the West, where he is a known quantity and is also seen as a reassuring and competent managerial figure. <P>

	The change in the business and investment climate in Russia since the presidential election is a second area of concern, especially for those Western and Japanese corporations thinking of doing business in Russia.  Russian government officials and business executives have been assuring their Western counterparts that 1996 will see a new tax code, which would reduce the number of taxes from about 150 to about 30, and a new and improved Production-Sharing Agreement to replace the defective document of December 1995.  These assurances have not been well-founded.  Given the composition of the new Duma, the allocation of key committee chairmanships to the Communists or their allies, and the spoiling powers of Sergei Glaziev, Lebed's economic adviser, the prospects for rapid forward movement in these two key areas are remote.  <I>(Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</I><P>


 <LI> 	<a name="slov"><B>Slovakia:</a>  Developments in Democratic Pluralism.</B>  Given the heritage of apathy and helplessness from more than 40 years of Communist rule and the lack of any sense of community in their towns, both Slovaks and ethnic Hungarians from diverse social and functional sectorsówomen, youth, clergy, business, teachersóhave responded warmly to a CSIS initiative to promote democratic pluralism in Slovakia.  They welcomed the chance to begin making a difference in the future of their towns and were ready to learn and then model not only inter-ethnic tolerance but also cooperation as members of a community building civil society and democratic pluralism.<P>
	During the project, participants will come together and (1) define a vision of the best possible future for their respective town, (2) identify social, structural, political, and economic problems standing in the way of this vision, and (3) design projects to begin solving these problems.  The unusual and highly original aspect of the project is that there will be concrete products of the community-building leadership initiatives.  Participants expressed the hope that their successes in the project could set an example for the rest of the country.  <I>(Preventive Diplomacy Program)</I> <P>


<LI>	<a name="tech"><B>Technology Renders Regulatory Systems Obsolete.</a></B>  Regulatory systems have failed to keep pace with the technologically driven changes in global financial markets, thereby raising concerns about the ability of regulatory authorities to manage potential systemic crises.  There are several constraints on regulatory effectivenessóthe large and growing power of the global financial market system, which handles more than one and one-half trillion dollars of financial flows daily; the ability and willingness of market participants to engage in regulatory arbitrage; greater technical capabilities and financial resources in the private sector; and much longer decision-making cycles.  In the lead editorial in Global Investment magazine, Bradley D. Belt, director of the CSIS Capital Markets Regulatory Reform Project, also suggests that a fundamental reexamination of the existing scheme for regulating financial markets is required.  To accommodate marketplace developments, legal and regulatory standards across markets should be harmonized and consideration should be given to the creation of a supranational regulatory framework.  <I>(Domestic Policy Program)</I><P>


  <LI><B><a name="zaire">Zaire:</a>  What Next for the "Big Man" of Central Africa?</B> Zaire's first national election scheduled for next May and June will make 1997 the most crucial period in Zaire's history since its independence from Belgium in 1960, asserted U.S. Ambassador to Zaire Daniel H. Simpson at a CSIS briefing.  Zairians realize that help from the international community and the success of private ventures, including privatization, are dependent on a democratic political transition.<P>

	Optimistic about the elections, Ambassador Simpson believes that obstacles such as communications difficulties and the refugee crisis in Eastern Zaire need not prevent a free and fair vote and that Zairian "human capital" remains strong, despite years of oppressive government.  Civil society is gearing up for the polls, the campaign process is developing and becoming more sophisticated, and President Mobutu will likely face a serious challenge in the presidential election when voters confront a choice on the second ballot between the status quo and a new direction.  He warned, however, that the United States and the international community would not tolerate a rigged process.  <I>(African Studies Program)</I><P>

</UL><P>
<td></tr></table>



