<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left>        <b>Number 165,

September 27, 1996</b><hr>

<h1>Time is running out for IFOR</h1>

<h3>What happens when the United States withdraws?

</h3>

The first effort to stop the bloodshed and ethnic cleansing in BosniaóUNPROFOR (the United Nations Protection Force)óproved unsuccessful; the fighting continued.  Then it was NATO's turnóenter IFOR (Peace Implementation Force).  With the December deadline for U.S. troop withdrawal fast approaching, IFOR's time is almost up.  What next?  Attention is shifting to the post-IFOR operation in Bosniaóspecifically, who will remain involved and whether they can maintain stability.  Janusz Bugajski, director of CSIS East European Studies, asserts, "If the world wishes to avoid regressing to the ineffective days of UNPROFOR, continued U.S. presence on the ground in Bosnia is essential." <P>


<B>IFOR Today</B><BR>
From a military standpoint, the IFOR operation has been a successóthe fighting between the Bosnian Serbs and the Muslim-Croat Federation has ceased, and IFOR has maintained inter-entity boundaries, kept roads open, and continued to monitor weapons in depots.  From a political and institution-building perspective, however, the results are not encouraging.  Bugajski contends that the shortcomings of the operation are clear.  IFOR has frozen realities on the ground without <P>

<UL><LI>reversing the effective ethnic cleansing in Bosnia;

<LI> weakening the hold of the nationalist parties that began the war; or

<LI>removing the war criminals who are responsible for the atrocities committed during the war.</UL>

In essence, IFOR is consolidating the process of the partition and division of Bosnia, and there remains a strong possibility of future wars among the three entities.  <P>


<B>Without Continued U.S. Involvement</B><BR>
An IFOR successor mission without direct support from the United States will place the entire operation under a European umbrella.  A "European IFOR-2," Bugajski warns, will be similar to an UNPROFORóalthough troops will not be subject to direct military attack, the Bosnian factions could start fighting again.  "The Bosnians do not respect European military power," Bugajski remarks.  "They believe that each European country has distinct great power interests in the area that favor one or another faction, interests Bosnians do not perceive the United States as having."<P>

Given this scenario, the longer-term prospect is that the country will splitóthe Croat side will drift to Croatia, the Serb side to Serbia, and what will be left is a radicalized Muslim statelet.  At this point, European troops will be caught in the middle of three emerging states with diametrically different interests.  Although the force probably will not be under military threat, it may find itself legitimizing the split into three entities.<P>


<B>The U.S. Difference</B><BR>
The NATO air strikes called for by the United States last year and the fact that U.S. soldiers are on the ground demonstrate that the United States is serious about its mission in Bosnia.  Bugajski notes, "There has always been a respect for the United States in Eastern Europe.  The United States will not stitch Bosnia back together; however, U.S. presence on the ground gives encouragement to the forces in Bosnia who want a multiethnic state.  This successor force would resemble more of an IFOR, not an UNPROFOR, operationóthe troops would not be threatened, and any major military action between forces would be highly unlikely during the course of NATO involvement. The ethnic division, however, will continue." <P>


<B>Impact on NATO</B><BR>
U.S. resistance to participating in a second IFOR-type operation could also challenge Alliance unity.  A U.S. troop withdrawal is likely to create resentment among the French and British in particular because they have had troops on the ground throughout both the UNPROFOR and IFOR operations.  Without U.S. participation, they may now be asked to shoulder most of the responsibility for Bosnian stability.
<p><hr>

