<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center">
<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



        



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 

vspace=10 hspace=10>        
<h4>Number 157, May 10, 1996</h4>



<h1>Bob Dole's Vision</h1>

         

<h3>Setting a new agenda for the United States in Asia</h3>

 

Speaking at the CSIS Statesmen's Forum yesterday, Senate Majority Leader and presumptive Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole sharply criticized President Clinton's Asian policy, calling it weak, incoherent, and indecisive.<P>



Dole then outlined his strategies for promoting strong U.S. leadership in Asia, citing the U.S.-China relationship and U.S. security relations with the Korean Peninsula and Japan as issues of primary importance.<P>



<H3>U.S. Policy toward China</H3>

Dole articulated his perspective on the salient issues of the U.S.-China relationship, including:<P>



 	<B>Most-Favored-Nation (MFN) Status.</B><BR>

  Dole advocated extending MFN status to China as the best way to promote U.S. national interests in the region.  Denying Beijing MFN privileges, Dole noted, "would not free a single dissident, halt a single missile sale, prevent a single threat to Taiwan

, or save a single innocent Chinese life."  Instead, he said such action would undermine U.S. interests in the region by sending the wrong signalónamely, that the United States is withdrawing from the region.  Such a message, Dole believes, would "set bac

k our relations [with China] more than two decades."  It would also have serious repercussions for U.S. relations with its allies throughout Asia and the Pacific. <P> 



 	<B>Taiwan.</B><BR>  The majority leader emphasized that U.S. policy on the Taiwan issue must be unequivocal, stating that "if force is used against Taiwan, America will respond. . . . The United States is lawfully committed and morally obligated to help

 Taiwan maintain the capacity to deter any effort to determine its future through violence."  Dole also called for sharing ballistic missile defense information and technology with Taipei.<P>  



 	<B>WTO Membership.</B><BR>  Addressing China's repeated violations of international trade rules, Dole specifically highlighted China's abuse of intellectual property rights laws, which cost U.S. businesses $2 billion annually.  He stated that China shou

ld be allowed into the WTO only after Beijing agrees to accept and adhere to the rules of the GATT system. <P> 

	Dole did not rule out imposing sanctions against China as a U.S. response to future Chinese transgressions. <P> 



<H3>U.S. Security Policy in Asia</H3>

 	<B>Expanding Defense Cooperation.</B><BR>

  Dole promoted a plan calling for close U.S. cooperation with Japan, South Korea, and other Asian allies for the purpose of developing, testing, and deploying ballistic missile defense systems to bolster current defense capabilities.  "It is time to anno

unce [U.S.] willingness to license exports of systems such as THAAD - Theater High Altitude Air Defense - and in the interim make operational prototypes available to our allies.  It is time to invite interested friends to send military personnel to train 

with U.S. army units already formed for THAAD launch."<P>



	The proposed "Pacific Democracy Defense Program" would counter the present security threat in Asia, i.e. the weapons proliferation policies of North Korea and China.  Furthermore, Dole asserted that this strategy would not only deter China and North Kore

a, it would also reduce incentives to produce ballistic missiles.<P> 



 	<B>Promoting a Harder U.S. Stance: North Korea.</B><BR>

  Dole delivered a scathing critique of current U.S. policy in the Korean Peninsula.  The administration, he remarked, is "showering [North Korean rulers] with aid, bilateral diplomacy, and technology" - offerings the North does not deserve - over objecti

ons from our true ally, South Korea.<P> 



	Dole called for the cessation of relations between the United States and North Korea until Pyongyang resumes discussions  with Seoul.<P> 



The presumptive Republican presidential candidate concluded his discussion with a call for the continued presence of the United States in Asia.  The U.S.-Asian relationship, Dole asserted, is indispensable to the U.S. national interest; cries to abandon o

ur commitment to our Asian allies must be vigorously opposed.  

<p><hr>



