<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left>        <b>Number 168,

November 19, 1996</b><hr>

<h1>Opening China's Telecom Industry</h1>

<h3>A place at the table for foreign investors? 
</h3>

Current developments in China belie the government's official law governing the telecommunications industry, concluded CSIS experts in the <a href="http://www.csis.org/ics/">International Communications Studies</a> ProgramóDirector <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4garriso.html">Bill Garrison</a>, Senior Associate <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4pipe.html">Russell Pipe</a>, and Research Fellow <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fan.html">Xing Fan</a>.  

Officially, the Chinese government prohibits foreign firms from holding network equity ownership in the telecom industry and from direct involvement in network operation and service provisions.  "The fact is, however, that China's national informatization programóthe adoption of widespread applications of information technology for China's economic development and social progressórequires an enormous amount of capital that is beyond the nation's financial capability.  If China is to successfully complete this endeavor, the government must find a mechanism that will allow foreign capital infusions," asserts Garrison.  "My guess is that the Chinese government already knows this; it's just not saying so." <p>

Recent developments indicate that China will soon be compelled to open its telecommunications industry to investors. <p> 

	A number of provincial administrations are planning new wire-line networks primarily for the purpose of information-intensive applications instead of the traditional voice telephony.  This is significant because it represents a reversal of past priorities.  The Chinese now seem to be much more interested in advanced data applications; they are looking at technologies that would accommodate multiple service providers on their networks.  This then begs the question: If China is to have a structure where only one operator is providing these services, why is there so much interest in technology that would accommodate multiple service providers?<p>

One reasonable answer, Garrison concludes, is that network planners anticipate operating in an environment that will accommodate other service providers on the wire-line networks.  "Network planners don't operate in theoretical vacuums.  Someone had to tell them that this will be the government's priority; otherwise, they would not be wasting their time talking to multiple equipment vendors." <p>

Pipe adds that China is gearing up for high-capacity networks and rather large and practical applications that will require new structures in communication networks.  "Consequently, China will have to revamp its present telecommunications structure to accommodate such changesóthe pressure on China to be more open and more flexible in the telecommunications industry is intensifying."   <p>

How foreign firms fit it.  Although the most likely beneficiaries will be domestic competitors, foreign firms may be allowed to enter into joint ventures.  According to Fan, loopholes in the telecommunications legislation exist.  "The ownership issue is quite complex, and as more foreign companies enter the market and form alliances with Chinese enterprises, the demarcation of ownership between the two players will become even more blurred."  For example, China United Telecommunications Corporation (China Unicom), China's second national network operator and service provider, has recently signed more than 200 joint venture memorandums of understanding (MOUs).  In recent interviews, company officials estimated that more than 50% of the investment in Unicom has been from foreign sources.  "Unicom's strategy," explains Fan, "is to encourage foreign businesses to enter into joint ventures with local Chinese enterprises; in this way, foreign firms can invest in Unicom's projects without violating current rules." <p> 

There is another successful strategy that allows foreign firms to participate in the expansion of China's telecommunications capabilities.  According to this practice, referred to as BTA (build-transfer-assist), a foreign firm (1) builds a telecom facility or network with its investment and technology; (2) transfers the title to a local company; and (3) "assists" in the operation in terms of technical or management support.  "Technically the local enterprise operates the facility," states Pipe.  "However, because the Chinese have yet to define the word ëassist,' foreign firms have also been participating in the actual ëoperation' of the facility." <p>   

The bottom line, conceded Garrison, Pipe, and Fan, is that to keep up with the rapidly expanding demands on telecommunication infrastructure and sustain the health of the industry, foreign involvement will be required.  The long-term outlook for foreign investors and service providers is promising.                                          
<p><hr>

