<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 152,                        

                      
March 1, 1996</h4>

<h1>U.S.-Japan Security Cooperation</h1>
         
<h3>The time for a broader approach?</h3>
 
The United States must broaden the scope of its security dialogue in East Asia.  It now has the opportunity to moderate the perception of distrust and frustration in its security relations with Japan.  It can achieve this by injecting longer-range issues of special concern across the Pacific into bilateral security agendas, such as the changing energy outlook in Asia.  This view is shared by three CSIS experts on U.S. relations with Japan: Princeton professor and <I>CSIS adviser Kent Calder</I>, <I>Pacific Forum CSIS Senior Associate Torkel Patterson</I>, and <I>CSIS Senior Adviser Bill Clark</I>.

At issue is the explosion of energy demand in Asia, which could eventually translate into a major Asian security and economic concern with implications for both Japan and the United States.  Unlike the disputes currently bedeviling U.S.-Japanese relations -- auto parts, photo film, semiconductors, U.S. military bases in Japan -- the energy issue offers a chance for constructive cooperation.  The April U.S.-Japan summit meeting between President Clinton and Prime Minister Hashimoto may be an appropriate staging point for exploring approaches with concrete benefits for both sides.<P>

Looming Energy Issues:  The economic surge in Asia is transforming the longer-term, global energy supply and demand calculus.  High growth rates are generating new, energy-intensive industries and creating a burgeoning regional middle class with increasing energy consumption.  Increased demand will soon mean higher levels of dependence for traditional energy importers.  It will also mean that several regional key energy exporters will become net importers.<P>

This dramatic increase in regional energy dependence will present a number of new security challenges in the region.  The new dynamics will also affect exporters and importers, and security relations between them, across the world.<P>

The sharp increase in demand affects virtually all the Asian economies apart from Japan:<P>

   At the core of the explosion is "greater China," consisting of China, Hong Kong, Macau, and Taiwan.  At present, China's population of 1.2 billion has a per capita energy consumption level only 40% of the world average.  But as consumer demand increases, energy demand will skyrocket.   According to Calder, whose definitive book, Pacific Defense: Arms, Energy, and America's Future in Asia,  has just been published, China could reach an oil import level of 1 million barrels a day (mbd) by the turn of the century and 2.5-3 mbd in 15 years (even assuming they will continue to burn coal mostly for electric power and home use).  If this level of oil demand materializes, greater China will account for more than 28% of the region's dependence by 2010.<P>

   Energy demand can also be expected to grow rapidly in India, the other regional giant, says Clark.  Increased consumption, coupled with the inability of the government to implement higher efficiencies in field management or in end-user energy consumption, will mean steadily upward energy requirements. <P> 

   In South Korea, the Energy Institute of Korea forecasts that aggregate energy demand will rise 128% from 1992 levels by the year 2010.  This increase in demand accounts for current conservation efforts, an expanded nuclear program, and extensive use of natural gas.  The figure could be higher, Calder adds, if tensions with North Korea are relaxed significantly or if unification occurs--making Korea's prospective energy challenges among the most significant in Asia.<P>

   The asean countries are also contributing to surging demand in Asia.  By Calder's calculations, Indonesia will become a net importer around the year 2002. Demand is also rising sharply in Thailand and Singapore.<P>

The Security Dimension:  All this points toward an added set of security challenges and concerns in Asia.  Currently, levels of 11 mbd of oil are moved each day by tankers from the Middle East to the region.  That level could increase to 17 mbd by the year 2005.  This raises the possibility of a "tanker-pipeline" stretching from the Middle East to Asia and highlights the dangers of the potential chokepoints in the Strait of Hormuz, the Indian Ocean, the waters around the Malay Peninsula (including the Malacca Strait), and the South and East China Seas.<P>

This is an important reason for the military shift in China from the development of a continental to a maritime force.  And such a shift suggests why the leading interests of the U.S. Navy need to be in the Pacific.<P>

It also helps explain the escalating security threats arising from competing territorial claims.   Clark notes that tension over the overlapping claims of Japan and Korea on the Takeshima/Tokdo islets could escalate over the next few weeks.  Calder pointed out that the Chinese have also recently had a drilling ship in Japanese-claimed waters near the Senkaku Islands (which have major offshore oil potential).  The potential for conflict over these zones may rise as energy pressures increase.<P>

Higher Asian oil dependence on the Middle East and other producers could also bring policy differences among the United States, Japan, and other Asian countries into sharper focus:<P>

   It places renewed emphasis on energy development in Central Asia, the pipeline politics there, and relations among Tokyo, Moscow, and Beijing.<P>

  It spotlights, as Calder points out, the "China-Iraq-Iran relationship" and the divergence between Washington's "dual containment" position and the policies of the Asian countries toward Tehran and, potentially, Baghdad.<P>

    And it brings into focus efforts by Tokyo to diversify its energy sources around the world, from the Middle East to Latin America.<P>


Exploring New Approaches: The stakes for Japan and the United States are significant.  Both have important national security interests in the outcome of this altered global energy calculus.  Both have high oil import levels--99% of total demand, in Japan's case.  And both can gain from fresh thinking and new joint approaches to issues of mutual concern.<P>

Says Calder: The political impact could also be important in Tokyo as a gesture of recognition of the sort of political-economic insecurities that the Japanese feel most deeply.<P>

Such new thinking could make energy efficiency a staging point.  The two countries could explore joint efforts to make new energy-efficient technologies available in Asia.  In the process, they could relieve some of the regional demand pressure.<P>

Another area of potential cooperation is in production, in which U.S. advanced drilling technology and other measures aimed at increasing production could be tied to Japanese expertise in end-user consumption savings and implemented with the support of both countries.  This is an important opportunity, says Patterson, for the United States "to plug into energy development in Asia" with big benefits to the U.S. economy.<P> 

Clark argues that we need to avoid a mere "Okinawa bandaid," and focus on meaningful strategies such as a joint energy strategy.  He notes: "This is an attractive idea because it is a way for the United States to introduce economic aspects into U.S.-Japanese dialogue without Tokyo's perceiving it as a U.S. threat to use energy as a weapon of persuasion."<P> 

It remains to be seen whether discussion of such a strategy will take place during the April summit.  But one thing is clear: To improve bilateral security relations scarred by Okinawa and trade tensions, the time for a broader approach has come. 
<p><hr>

