<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 160,                        

July 26, 1996</h4>

<h1>Vietnam Puts on the Brakes</h1>
         
<h3>Implications for foreign investment . . .</h3>

 

Vietnam's much-anticipated Eighth Communist Party
Congress, which concluded its four-day deliberations
on July 1, 1996, brought little cheer to foreign
investors. Frustrated by a government that had yet to
demonstrate the political will to tackle major
impediments to investmentóa lack of transparency in
decision-making, inadequate legal and financial
infrastructures, and rampant corruptionóinvestors
found greater reason to worry as Vietnam's leaders
announced intentions to pursue a more cautious and
socialist line.<P>

Vietnam's paramount leader Do Muoi assured foreign
investors that they are integral to economic
development. Although the mood of the congress belied
this message, Keith Eirinberg, CSIS Fellow in Asian
Studies, believes that opportunities still exist for
businesses willing to invest their time, effort, and
money.<P>

<B>Ten Years of Doi Moi.</B><BR> The Party Congress
provided the
Communist leadership with the opportunity to review
the impressive results of 10 years of Vietnam's
economic reform program, doi moi: <P>
<UL>
<LI> 	inflation has plummeted from 774% in 1986 to
under 13% in 1995 and only 4-5% today;
<LI> 	GDP has nearly doubled and is at $93 billion;
<LI> 	economic growth rates between 1991 and 1995
have consistently remained above 8%; and
<LI> 	Hanoi has licensed more than 1,700 foreign
investment projects since 1988, with approved
projects worth more than $20 billion.</UL><P>

                       <B>The Next Five-Year
Plan.</B><BR>
Perhaps the most important message from the Party
Congress was that the economic reform program will
continue at a rapid pace. In fact, the new plan
outlined ambitious economic goals:<P>

<UL><LI>	annual GDP growth averaging 9-10%;
and
 <LI>	industrial output growing at 14-15% per
year.</UL><P>

                       Hanoi, however, intends to
support the large, inefficient state-owned firms that
siphon precious resources from the fledgling private
sector. Critics perceive such a strategy as
sabotaging Vietnam's plans for economic growth.<P>

<B>Septuagenarian Troika Remains.</B><BR>  Despite
rumors of a
transition to a younger leadership structure, the
country's ruling triumvirateóParty Secretary General
Do Muoi, 79, President Le Duc Anh, 76, and Prime
Minister Vo Van Kiet, 73ówas left in tact, but the
Politburo was expanded to 19 members, with only 4
recognized reformers among them. The increase of
high-level army and internal security officers in the
Party's ruling body reflects the new mood of
retrenchment, consolidation, and centralization.<P>

                       	<B>Yet Another Layer of
Bureaucracy?</B><BR>  Another significant development
of the
Congress, Eirinberg notes, was the formation of a
five-member Standing Committee for the Politburo.
Composed of the country's top three leadersóMuoi,
Anh, and Kietóthe political chief of the People's
Army, Le Kha Phieu, and Vice Interior Minister Nguyen
Tan Dung, this "super politburo" is weighted on the
side of the hardliners (Anh, Phieu, and Dung).
Although it remains to be seen what function this
committee will playóofficials claim its focus will be
only on day-to-day Party issuesóit could interfere in
decision-making on foreign investment projects,
especially in light of conservative concerns about
investors bringing in harmful cultural and social
influences. Eirinberg believes military and internal
security forces want greater control over reform,
perhaps to develop their own vested interests.<P>

	<B>Negative Signals for Foreign
Investors</B><P>

<UL><LI> 	The Congress failed to address the
key issue
of bureaucratic reform.

<LI> 	Party cells will be placed in foreign joint
ventures to complement those in Vietnamese partner
companies. The cells will relay workers' sentiments
to authoritiesóperhaps a result of recent labor
troubles in Korean and Taiwanese firms in Vietnam or
a way to watch militant trade unions closely. Foreign
firms, however, may see this effort resulting in the
politicization of the workplace and serving as an
intelligence source for Party bosses.

<LI> 	The Party is focusing on import substitution
and will apparently try to steer foreign investment
to specific areas in order to protect local
industries.</UL><P>

<b>On A More Positive Note</B><P>

<UL><LI> 	Minister of Planning and Investment
Do Quoc
Sam announced that revisions will be made to the 1987
Law on Foreign Investment this October that will
include simplifying procedures for obtaining land-use
permits and construction licenses.
<LI> 	The Party's final political report, compared
with the earlier draft, was less hard-line, with the
xenophobic rhetoric toned down considerably.<P>
</UL>










<p><hr>

