<td valign=top>
<h3><a name="colombia">Colombian Policy in the Mid-1990s</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fleishe.html">Lowell Fleischer</a> and Eduardo Lora <p>
<i>CSIS Report	62 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-272-X 		$12.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="dilemma">The Haitian Dilemma: A Case Study in Demographics, Development, and U.S. Foreign Policy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest H. Preeg</a><p>
The study relates longer-term Haitian development prospects to short-term U.S. policy objectives. The analysis focuses on the powerful demographic forces at play -- rapid population growth in the countryside, the relentless rural/urban migratory flow, and
 building pressures for outward migration to the United States. The central policy conclusion is that foreign policy actions, such as the international embargo to help restore the Aristide presidency, can have a devastatingly negative impact on the demogr
aphic and development outlook.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series 	133 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-277-0		$14.95</i>

<hr><p>

<h3><a name="haiti">Haitian Frustrations: Dilemmas for U.S. Policy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, editor<br>
Contributors: Elliott Abrams, Diego Arria, Thomas Carothers, Andrew S. Faiola, Georges Fauriol, Ian Guest, David Healy, Stephen Horblitt, Robert Maguire, Lawrence Pezzullo, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest H. Preeg</a>, Lawrence Theri
ot, Sally Yearwood<p>
This up-to-the-minute analysis outlines the difficult road ahead for Haiti and U.S.-Haitian relations. Many important historical documents are included, as well as a chronology of events from the 1990 elections to Aristide's return.<p>

"The work is a very elaborate analysis of the background, development and perspectives raised by the Haitian crisis. . . .Each phase of the conflict is analyzed in detail, with the relevant documents and statistics appended." - NOD & Conversion<p>
<i>CSIS Report	236 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-259-2 		$24.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="tradeoffs">NAFTA and Sovereignty: Trade-offs for Canada, Mexico, and the United States</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a>, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hoebing.html">Joyce Hoebing</a>, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, editors<br>
Contributors: Charles Doran, Jonathan Heath, Federico Reyes Heroles,  Murray Smith, Denis Stairs, Sidney Weintraub<p>
The process of economic integration in North America involves more political cooperation than ever before.  The distinction between domestic and international policy is becoming increasingly blurred.  This study approaches this process from a national vie
wpoint rather than focusing on narrowly defined themes.  Two authors from each North American country examine their country's "hang-ups" regarding sovereignty, one from an economic perspective and the other from a political one. <p>
<i>Significant Issues Series 	176 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-322-X		$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="naftadebate">The NAFTA Debate: Grappling with Unconventional Trade Issues</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, editors<br>
Contributors: Jan Gilbreath, Timothy J. Kehoe, Soledad Loaeza, Howard Rosen, Alan M. Rugman, John Benjamin Tonra, Howard J. Wiarda <p>
<i>Copublished Book/	211 pp.	 1994<br>
Lynne Rienner Publishers<br>
ISBN 1-55587-464-9 (hb) 	$38.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="naftanext">NAFTA: What Comes Next?</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a><p>
"With so many titles available, one wonders if yet another book will have any effect on clarifying NAFTA's complexities. However, in this case, the answer is a resounding yes
. . . .The book is highly recommended." - Business Information Alert<p>

"Anyone trying to decipher the myriad claims about NAFTA would be well advised to read this book." - CHOICE<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger	132 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-275-95119-7 (pb) 	$14.95<br>
0-275-95118-9 (hb) 	$49.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="rediscover">The Rediscovery of America: The Story of the Free Trade Agreement</a></h3>
Hermann von Bertrab<p>
Rarely before in the history of the Western Hemisphere has such monumental change occurred, as the United States, Mexico, and Canada have integrated their economies and united their destinies under the NAFTA agreement.  Three countries that had isolated t
hemselves during the last few centuries have rediscovered their common roots and interests under this modern treaty.  This insightful book, written by the chief Mexican representative for NAFTA in the U.S., offers an insider's perspective on the dramatic 
and arduous process of how NAFTA became a reality.<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger       c. 205 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN	0-275-95935-X (pb)	$18.95 Est.<br>
	0-275-95934-1 (hb)	$55.00 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="resurgence">Resurgence and Uncertainty in Argentina, Brazil, and Chile</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a><p>
In Latin America, Argentina, Brazil, and Chile all have gone through profound political and economic changes during the past decade. For the first time in this century, there is legitimate reason to hope that all of them can escape from the authoritariani
sm and, over <i>time, the underdevelopment that has been their lot.<p>
The Conference Board	20 pp. 	1995<br>
Global Business White Paper 	$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="uscarib">U.S.-Caribbean Relations into the Twenty-first Century</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, project director<br>
G. Philip Hughes, senior editor<br>
Contributors: Anthony T. Bryan, Nellis Crigler, G. Philip Hughes, Stephen Lande, Douglas W. Payne, Lloyd Searwar<p>
There is strong feeling of unease in the region. Propelled by the globalization of politics and economics, the dynamics of regionalism in the Western Hemisphere is leading to a reconceptualization of U.S. policy. Among several possible configurations, the
 United States is likely to draw the most interest from those countries that are closest to it geographically, economically, and socially. In its broadest framework, this lends support to an expanded vision of a North American community.<p>
<i>Americas Studies Report	66 pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-235-5 		$14.95</i>

<p>

</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:books@csis.org">bookstore</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
</font>

