<HEAD><TITLE>CSIS Asia Publications</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3pubs.gif"></p>
<H2><p align="center">Asia</p></H2>

<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#asiapac">Asia Pacific Confidence</a> and Security Building Measures<p>
<a href="#changekorea">Change and Challenge</a> on the Korean Peninsula: Developments, Trends, and Issues<p>
<a href="#chinainfo">China in the Information Age:</a> Telecommunications and the Dilemmas of Reform<p>
<a href="#china">China's Domestic Economy</a> in Regional Context<p>
<a href="#consensus">Developing A Consensus for the Future</a><p>
<a href="#common">Factors Affecting East Asian Views</a> of the United States: The Search for Common Ground<p>
<a href="#hongkong">Hong Kong's Economic and Financial Future</a><p>
<a href="#human">Human Smuggling:</a> Chinese Migrant Trafficking and the Challenge to America's Immigration Tradition<p>
<a href="#japanus">Japan and the United States:</a> Revving Up for the Information Superhighway<p>
<a href="#koreatrends">Korean Peninsula Trends</a> and U.S.-Japan-South Korea Relations<p>
<a href="#remember">Remembering and Forgetting:</a> The Legacy of War and Peace in East Asia<p>
<a href="#usjapsec">Restructuring the U.S.-Japan Security Relationship</a><p>
<a href="#sochina">Southern China, Hong Kong, and Taiwan:</a> Evolution of a Subregional Economy<p>
<a href="#uskorea">Strengthening U.S.-Korean Relations</a> in the Coming Years<p>
<a href="#taiwan">Taiwan's Economic Role in East Asia</a><p>
<a href="#trilateral">Trilateral Forum</a> on North Pacific Security<p>
</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="asiapac">Asia Pacific Confidence and Security Building Measures</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cossa.html">Ralph A. Cossa</a>, editor<br>
Contributors: Ralph A. Cossa, Kwa Chong Guan, Liu Huaqiu, Robert A. Manning, Margaret (Peggy) Mason, Oh Kwan-chi, M. Susan Pederson, Brad Roberts, Robert S. Ross, Stanley Weeks<p>
Are multilateral confidence and security building measures (CSBMs) appropriate to the Asia-Pacific region in the post-cold war era?  In recent years, regional attitudes regarding the acceptability or applicability of CSBMs appear to be changing.  This volume supports the assumption that CSBMs, if properly crafted and carefully applied, are indeed appropriate to the region and offers recommendations about the best ways to pursue them.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	172 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-307-6 		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="changekorea">Change and Challenge on the Korean Peninsula: Developments, Trends, and Issues</a></h3>
Jae H. Ku and Tae Hwan Ok, editors<br>
Contributors: Dong-bok Lee, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4mazarr.html">Michael Mazarr</a>, Tae Hwan Ok, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4taylor.html">William J. Taylor Jr.</a><p>
This volume examines developments  since the signing of the Agreed Framework between the United States and North Korea in 1994.  It provides an overview of relations between South Korea and North Korea; perspectives on the future of North Korea; the impact of regional and global developments on the Korean peninsula; and challenges and opportunities in U.S.-South Korean relations.<p>
<i>Asian Studies Report	81 pp. 	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-342-4		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="chinainfo">China in the Information Age: Telecommunications and the Dilemmas of Reform </a></h3>
<a href="http://www.scils.rutgers.edu/people/faculty/mmcv.html">Milton Mueller</a> and <a href="http://istweb.syr.edu/Project/Faculty/Tan.html">Zixiang Tan</a> <p>
This is the first comprehensive scholarly examination of China's economic reforms in the telecommunications sector. The book probes the inherent tension between global liberalization trends in telecommunications and information markets and the Chinese government's attempt to maintain a "socialist market economy" with centralized, one-party political control.
". . . a sophisticated, well-researched, and sensitive analysis of the enormous potential and contradictions in the Chinese telecommunications system. . . . It is a fascinating description of the complex Chinese process of modernization, reform, and reaction." - James R. Lilley, Former Ambassador to the People's Republic of China<p>

"China is an awakening economic giant but an information-age dwarf. Mueller and Tan examine China's torturous road to advanced information highways and provide a long-needed comprehensive volume on China's telecommunications system." - Eli M. Noam, Director, Columbia Institute for Tele-Information, Columbia University Graduate School of Business<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger 	165 pp.	1997<br>
ISBN 0-275-95829-9 (pb)	$16.95<br>
          0-275-95828-0 (hb)	$49.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="china">China's Domestic Economy in Regional Context</a></h3>
Ding Jingping<p>
Ding Jingping offers a perspective from Beijing as part of CSIS's East Asia Economic and Financial Outlook series. He analyzes the prospects for continued high growth and economic reform in the People's Republic of China. The role of external economic relations in China's economic development, particularly with Taiwan, Hong Kong, the United States, and Japan, is a<i>lso discussed.<p>
Significant Issues Series	84 pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-318-1 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="consensus">Developing A Consensus for the Future</a></h3>
<b>A Report of the U.S. China Policy
Task Force</b><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, executive director<p>
This Task Force report coordinates legislative, executive, business, and Washington policy community perspectives to delineate the consensus that could serve as the framework for long-term U.S.-China relations. Section one examines China's economic development and trade interactions with Taiwan and Hong Kong. It also focuses on the challenges facing U.S.-China economic relations. Section two reviews U.S. human rights policy in China and China's human rights developments. The third section addresses security concerns within China, as well as current U.S. China policy on security-related issues.<p>
<i>Panel Report	93 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-285-1		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="common">Factors Affecting East Asian Views of the United States: The Search for Common Ground</a></h3>
David I. Hitchcock<p>
Based on more than 90 interviews in 7 East Asian countries, the author describes how positive images of the United States are fading in that region. East Asians still admire the United States' innovative spirit and idealism_even concerning human rights_and would welcome greater exchange and cooperation on social problems facing both the United States and the region. This would help attain a goal both deeply value: creation of a "civil society."<p>
<i>CSIS Report	c. 70 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-296-7	$14.95 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="hongkong">Hong Kong's Economic and Financial Future</a></h3>
Y.F. Luk<p>
This volume in the East Asia Economic and Financial Outlook series assesses Hong Kong's phenomenal economic performance of the last few decades and, in particular, its special relationship with the People's Republic of China. The author also examines the changing domestic economic policies and political institutions that have played crucial roles in Hong Kong's growth and asks whether this spectacular growth will continue into the next decade.<p>

"This 77-page treatise on Hong Kong is very well done and very readable." - Manufacturing Competitiveness Frontiers<p>

<i>Significant Issues Series	91 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-306-8 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="human">Human Smuggling: Chinese Migrant Trafficking and the Challenge to America's Immigration Tradition</a></h3>
Paul J. Smith, editor<br>
Contributors: Ko-lin Chin, Anthony DeStefano, Jack Goldstone, Marlowe Hood, Li Ling, Willard Myers,  Paul J. Smith, Su Xiaokang,  Kenneth Yates<p>
Trafficking in human beings from the People's Republic of China has emerged as a major immigration and security problem for the United States and other countries. More than three years after the smuggling ship, Golden Venture, carrying nearly 300 Chinese migrants ran aground off Queens, New York,  Chinese migrant trafficking into the United States not only persists but shows no sign of abating.  This illegal immigration is organized by highly effective alien smuggling organizations that use routes involving more than 30 countries,  according to the United Nations, and earn hundreds of millions of dollars. Moreover, it is a human rights tragedy -- those unable to pay their full transportation fees once they reach the United States are frequently locked up in "safe houses" where they are subjected to physical abuse until they can pay. The authors of this volume focus on the roots of this growth industry and examine the various "push" and "pull" factors_such as population pressures and, ironically, China's opening to the outside world -- that are fueling the current Chinese exodus.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-291-6</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="japanus">Japan and the United States: Revving Up for the Information Superhighway</a></h3>
Kristin A. Juffer<p>
<i>International Communications Report 	102 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-314-9 		$25.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="koreatrends">Korean Peninsula Trends and U.S.-Japan-South Korea Relations</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, Seizaburo Sato, and Tae Hwan Ok, editors<br>
Contributors:  Woo Sik Kee, Tae Hwan Ok, Seizaburo Sato, Robert Scalapino, Akihiko Tanaka, Nathaniel Thayer<p>
North Korea's resistance to dialogue with the International Atomic Energy Agency, the lack of forward motion in resuming North-South dialogue, and North Korea's testing of the Rodong 1, a missile with a 1,000-km range all clearly underscore the need for continued trilateral consultation in addressing these issues. Two other volumes on Korean peninsula developments and issues (1993) are also available. The cost of each report is $9.95.<p>
<i>Asian Studies Report 	156 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-255-X 		$9.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="remember">Remembering and Forgetting: The Legacy of War and Peace in East Asia</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, editor<br>
Contributors: Chas. W. Freeman Jr.,<
Charles Hill, William Lee Howell, Anne Simone Kleinman, Dong-bok Lee, Lucian W. Pye<p>
Conflicts that have divided parts of East Asia for the past 50 years remain unresolved: competing claims between China and Taiwan, past Japanese militarism and colonialism in the region, and the division of Korea into two ideologically opposed states.  Memories of the events that gave rise to these conflicts are contested.  Key to working through these memories, within and between nations, is the dialectical process of remembering and forgetting, which will deeply influence international relations in the region into the next century.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series 	142 pp.	 1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-284-3		$15.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="usjapsec">Restructuring the U.S.-Japan Security Relationship</a></h3>
Richard Douglas, editor<p>
Highlighted by the views of Mitsubishi CEO Ben Makihara and former assistant secretary of defense Carl Ford, this book examines the security challenges facing the world (notably the growing saliency of China and the volatile Korean peninsula) and the role the U.S.-Japan security relationship might play in confronting them. The alliance pressures caused by economic disputes, Japan's unique prohibition on collective self-defense, and the significant U.S. base presence in Japan are explored by an expert group with first-hand, real-world experience in managing this vital security relationship.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-294-0</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="sochina">Southern China, Hong Kong, and Taiwan: Evolution of a Subregional Economy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4khanna.html">Jane Khanna</a>, editor<br>
Foreword by Robert A. Scalapino<br>
Contributors: Chen Dezhao, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4khanna.html">Jane Khanna</a>, J.A. Miller, Robert S. Ross, Sally Stewart, Sung Yun-wing, Milton D. Yeh<p>
The emergence of subregional economies_"natural economic territories"_raises serious questions about nation-state sovereignty.  In this examination of the subregional economy made up of Taiwan, Hong Kong, and China's southern provinces, the authors seek to capture points of rift and accord at the governmental and provincial levels even as economic flows seem to be outpacing the central governments' abilities to manage them.<p>

"This book, written by specialists in the field of international politics and relations, offers a timely collection of perspectives on the origin and prospects of this NET. Published in 1995, its insights throw a surprisingly illuminating light on events that have taken place in 1996." - China Information<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series  	108  pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-321-1 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="uskorea">Strengthening U.S.-Korean Relations in the Coming Years</a></h3>
<b>A Report of the CSIS U.S.-Korea Task Force</b><p>
Senator William V. Roth, Representative John Murtha, and David Roderick, project cochairmen<br>
John Yochelson and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4gong.html">Gerrit W. Gong</a>, project codirectors<br>
Keith Eirinberg and Scott Boller, authors<p>
<i>Panel Report	48 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-263-0 		$16.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="taiwan">Taiwan's Economic Role in East Asia</a></h3>
Chi Schive<p>
As part of the series on East Asia's economic and financial future, Chi Schive assesses the role of  Taiwan within the regional and global economy. He analyzes the strategies that have generated Taiwan's rapid development and the resulting shifts in regional and international economic and financial linkages, with particular attention to Taiwan's economic restructuring, cross-strait trade and investment with the People's Republic of China, and Taiwan's potential for serving as a regional operations center for East Asia.<p>

"The book is short but elegant." - China Information<p>

<i>Significant Issues Series	117 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-319-X 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="trilateral">Trilateral Forum on North Pacific Security</a></h3>
Vladlen A. Martynov, Nobuo Matsunaga, and Paul D. Wolfowitz, project cochairs<br>
Contributors: Sergei Blagovolin, Masashi Nishihara, Stephen Sestanovich<p>
The Forum was established in 1993 by CSIS, the Japan Institute of International Affairs, and the Russian Institute of World Economy and International Relations to foster candid discussion of regional and international security issues among private experts and policymakers. The Forum sessions have served to advance understanding of national perspectives on a variety of proposals to improve mutual confidence_particularly in the realms of military transparency and enhanced contacts. This report expresses the joint conviction that a trilateral framework can improve bilateral relations among the three nations and promote broader stability.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	27 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-279-7 		$10.95</i>




</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
<p align="center"><i>E-mail the <a href="mailto:books@csis.org">bookstore</a></i></p>
<p align="center"><i>Center for Strategic and Interntaional Studies - 1996</i></p>
