<HTML><TITLE>Russian and Eurasian Projects</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>

<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p><br><p>
<H2><p align="center">Russian and Eurasian Projects</p></H2>
<hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#caspian">Caspian Sea</a> Oil Study Group<p>
<a href="#centasia">Central Asian and Caucasian Briefing Series</a><p>
<a href="#cbs">Corporate Briefing Series</a><p>
<a href="#fsumulti">FSU:</a> Multilateral Assessment of Energy Challenges</a><p>
<a href="#fsunukes">FSU:</a> Nuclear Power Safety Issues<p>
<a href="#netassess">Net Assessment of the Russian Economy<p>
<a href="#psp">Post-Soviet Prospects</a><p>
<a href="#russjap">Russia-Japan Briefing Series</a><p>
</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>
<h3><a name="caspian">Caspian Sea Oil Study Group</a></h3>
This ongoing group focuses on foreign investor developments in oil production in Kazakstan and Azerbaijan and on moving this new oil to market, taking into consideration current political and economic climates. Since the series began in April 1994, there have been a number of meetings on the transport of Caspian Sea oil to markets, including presentations by the U.S. deputy secretary of energy, the director of global economic affairs at the State Department, the chief adviser to the president of Azerbaijan, the deputy foreign minister of Azerbaijan, the former chairman of the Azeri National Oil Company, the deputy under secretary for economic affairs at the Turkish Foreign Ministry, and the director of transportation of Turkish petroleum. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a>, Director, Energy and National Security Program, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4aliriza.html">Bulent Aliriza</a>, Director, Turkey Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="centasia">Central Asian and Caucasian Briefing Series</a></h3>
These meetings provide corporate executives and U.S. policy-makers with critical information on Central Asia and the Caucasus, including business opportunities, political developments, foreign relations, and the role of the military. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a>, Senior Associate, Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="cbs">Corporate Briefing Series</a></h3>
This series focuses on the latest developments in Russia and the other countries of the former Soviet Union, as well as on U.S. policy toward the region. Leading experts in the field and speakers from key government agencies address an audience of corporate executives with interests in Russia and the other former Soviet Republics. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a>, Senior Associate, Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="fsumulti">FSU: Multilateral Assessment of Energy Challenges</a></h3>
This ongoing project focuses on energy challenges within the former Soviet Union, with special emphasis on the oil and gas sector and export pipeline construction. A study of the Russian energy sector was published in 1994. A similar study on the energy sector of the Near Abroad (the other republics of the former Soviet Union) is scheduled for completion in 1996. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a>, Director, Energy and National Security Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="fsunukes">FSU: Nuclear Power Safety Issues</a></h3>
The focus of this project is on the 15 Chernobyl-style nuclear reactors still operating in Russia, Ukraine, and Lithuania and their energy and safety implications. The published report on nuclear energy safety challenges in the former Soviet Union defined policy optionsóand procedures to implement those optionsófor the acceptable resolution of the nuclear power safety issues facing the former Soviet Union. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a>, Director, Energy and National Security Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="netassess">Net Assessment of the Russian Economy</a></h3>
Updated every workday, this report provides corporate sponsors and policymakers with the most current overview of a fast-changing economy. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a>, Senior Associate, Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="psp">Post-Soviet Prospects</a></h3>
This bulletin, published 12 times a year, analyzes political, economic, and social developments in Russia and the former Soviet Union. Contributors include leading CSIS and external specialists.  <p>
<i>(Editor: <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a>, Senior Associate, Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i>
<p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/psp.html">To see issues of <i>Post-Soviet Prospects</i></a>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="russjap">Russia-Japan Briefing Series</a></h3>
This project examines political and economic developments in Russia for Japanese businessmen, diplomats, and journalists. The primary topics of discussion include insights into economic reform, the dynamics of political power in Moscow, and trends in Russian foreign policy. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4bush.html">Keith Bush</a>, Senior Associate, Russian and Eurasian Studies Program)</i>


</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
