<HEAD><TITLE>Get Involved!</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3outreac.gif"></p><BR>

<table cellspacing=10>
<tr><td valign=top width=20%>

<font size="2"><b>
<a href="#intern">The CSIS Intern Program</a><p>
<a href="#minority">The CSIS Minority Internship in International Affairs</a><p>
<a href="#armstrong">The Anne Armstorng Leadership Award</a><p>
<a href="#alumni">The CSIS Alumni Network</a>
</b></font>


</td>
<P><HR>

<td valign=top width=80%>
<H2><a name="intern">The CSIS Intern Program</a></H2>

The Center for Strategic and International Studies offers full and part-time volunteer internships in the fall, spring and summer semesters for students interested in a hands-on learning experience with a public policy research institute.<P>

Interns serve in the following areas:<P>

<ul>
<li>International Communications, Social and Economic Development, Business and Economic Policy, Domestic Issues, Political-Military Affairs, and Regional Studies (Africa, Asia, the Americas, East European, Russia and Eurasian, and the Middle East).<p>

<li>Additional internships in the Development, Library, Government Affairs Office, Public Affairs Office, Publications and Marketing Office, Conference Office, Human Resource Office and the Finance & Accounting Office are also available.</ul><p>

Internships in regional studies often require a language ability.<P>

Responsibilities are assigned by the individual project directors and will vary according to program needs.  Both research and clerical duties can be expected -- from collecting data at government and non-government agencies such as the Library of Congress, State and Commerce Departments, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and foreign embassies--to conference and seminar organization, answering phones, and xeroxing.  In addition, summer interns have the opportunity to participate in the Center's softbal
l program.<P>

<B>ELIGIBILITY:</B><P>
Applicants must have at least a college freshman standing at the time of application.<P>
<B>APPLICATION PROCESS:</B><P>

Students are asked to submit a cover letter that details their interests, college coursework, and availability, one copy of a current resume and a writing sample on a topic related to their field of study. A personal interview may be requested but, a telephone interview can often suffice.<P><HR>


	<h2><a name="minority">CSIS Minority Internship in International Affairs</a></h2><p>

<b>Purpose</b><p>

	CSIS Minority Internships in International Affairs are offered to provide opportunities for financially disadvantaged minority students to gain experience and explore career interests in international affairs.  Two internships are offered each semester (fall, spring, summer) at the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), an internationally-recognized foreign affairs research center in Washington, D.C.  Each internship carries a $3,000 stipend for living expenses and a $3,000 stipend for educational assistance.<p>

<b>Eligibility</b><p>

	Internships are open to graduate or undergraduate students of minority extraction with U.S. citizenship, a clearly demonstrated financial need, demonstrated academic potential as indicated by a grade-point average of at least 3.0, and an interest in international affairs.  Applicants should also have strong written and oral communication skills and demonstrated leadership potential as depicted by their involvement in community and extracurricular activities.<p>

<b>Application</b><p>

	Applicants should submit items listed below in an envelope marked "CSIS Minority Internships in International Affairs" to the Intern Coordinator:<br>
<ul>
<li>Resume
<li>Statement of financial need (from financial aid officer)
<li>Official transcript
<li>Essay (850 words or less):  Why should policymakers be concerned with the greater involvement of minorities in the formulation and execution of U.S. foreign policy?  Give some examples from current events or recent history of how in your view U.S. foreign policy could be or could have been improved by more effective integration of minority perspectives.  How do you feel you personally could bring an important minority perspective to the work of a policy research organization such as CSIS, and what would you expect to gain from this experience?
<li>Two letters of recommendation (including at least one from teacher, faculty advisor, or other academic colleague; other letter can be from employer). </ul><p>

<b>Deadline</b><p>

	Applications must be received by November 15 for spring 1997 semester, April 15 for summer 1997 semester, and July 15 for fall 1997 semester. <p>

<hr><p>


<H2><a name="armstrong">The Anne Armstrong Leadership Awards</a>
</H2><P>
<B>Purpose</B><P>

	The purpose of the award is to recognize undergraduates who demonstrate strong potential for leadership in the field of international affairs.  The award ($3,000) is given twice a year, and it is used to enable the recipient to serve as a full-time intern at the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) during any fall, spring, or summer term during the recipient's undergraduate career.  If the recipient works less than full-time at CSIS, the award will be prorated.<P>

<B>Eligibility:</B><P>

	Candidates for the award must be undergraduate students with outstanding academic records and a minimum grade point average of 3.5 in their area of concentration with at least sophomore standing at the time they apply.   Graduating seniors must pursue their internship within the following six months of the award.  Major field/s of study should be related to public policy and/or international affairs.  Applicants are expected to have strong written and oral communication skills, interest in international a
ffairs, and demonstrated leadership potential as depicted by their involvement in extracurricular activities.<P>

<B>Application:</B><P>

If you would like to be considered for an Anne Armstrong Leadership Award, please submit the items listed below in an envelope marked "Anne Armstrong Leadership Award" to the the Intern Coordinator:<P>

<UL>

<LI>Resume
<LI>An opinion essay of no more than 1100 words briefly illustrating an event within the last 12 months in world politics in which individual leadership made a difference in the outcome of that event
<LI>An official original transcript
<LI>List of courses constituting your major
<LI>Two letters of recommendation.  At least one letter to be from a faculty member, the second letter to be from an employer or a non-related colleague/friend.
<LI><B>NOTE:</B> Failure to follow the above guidelines will result in disqualification of your application</ul><P>

<B>Deadline:</B><P>

	All applications must be in our office by April 1st and November 1st annually.  Faxed applications will not be accepted.  Former and current CSIS interns and staff are not eligible for the award.<P>

<B>About Ambassador Armstrong:</B><P>

	The Anne Armstrong Leadership Awards were established in honor of the former ambassador to the Court of St. James's and current chairman of the CSIS Board of Trustees to honor her achievements and leadership in diplomacy and international affairs.  While raising a family of five children, she began a political career in 1956 that, by 1971, earned her the signal honor of becoming the first woman to keynote the Republican Party's National Convention.  In 1973, she became the first woman Cabinet-level presid
ential counsellor and, subsequently, the first woman to serve as the U.S. ambassador to Great Britain.<P><HR>

<H2><a name="alumni">CSIS Global Alumni Network </a></H2>

	In today's competitive job environment, networks of contacts have become increasingly valuable assets, and CSIS alumni form a group of contacts unparalleled in experience in every field of business, government and academia.  CSIS has hundreds of former staff, fellows, associates and interns in nearly every region of the world, and each year this circle of professionals expands to even more corners of the globe.  So that CSIS can continue to be connected with alumni and to let alumni know what CSIS is doin
g, we have established the CSIS Global Alumni Network, composed of former CSIS'ers.  We hope that you will join this network of distinguished colleagues and friends.<P>

	The <B><I>CSIS Global Alumni Network</I></B> is administered by the Alumni Coordinator from CSIS' senior level staff.  The Alumni Coordinator is the liaison between CSIS and alumni and has developed an exciting and informative program specifically for CSIS alumni:<P>

<UL><LI> CSIS Global Alumni Network Updates from the Alumni Coordinator will include membership lists and contact information as well as information about the network, upcoming alumni events, and alumni profiles<P>

<LI>  The quarterly CSIS Newsletter which keeps everyone up to date on the Center's activities, programs and projects

<LI>  An annual CSIS Program Products Sampler which includes the year's best CSIS Africa Notes, Post-Soviet Prospects, CSIS Watch, CSIS Business Alert, Significant Speeches and other CSIS publications

<LI> CSIS Global Alumni Network Reunions including special briefings by senior CSIS staff for alumni members

<LI> CSIS Alumni Ad Hoc Meetings for local and visiting alumni centered around briefings by CSIS senior staff

<LI> CSIS End of the Month Parties are also open to CSIS alumni</UL><p>


<b>How do I join?</b><P>

	The CSIS Global Alumni Network is open to all former CSIS'ers, including staff, fellows, associates and interns.  All members will have access to a world wide group of contacts and can keep in touch with CSIS.  If you would like to join this network of former colleagues and new contacts, please send email to <A HREF="mailto:alumni@csis.org">alumni@csis.org</A>.  You can also contact the Alumni Coordinator at 202/887-0200. <P><HR>

</td></tr></table>

