<HEAD><TITLE>CSIS in the News</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><IMG SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/3newseve.gif"></p><BR>
<H1>CSIS in the News</H1><P><HR><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>"The Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) in Washington was instrumental in fostering legislation that effectively reorganized ther Joint Chiefs of Staff.  Yet CSIS in this instance worked on this issue in cooperation with key members of Congress, where members and their staff are more open to ideas from the outside."<BR>  
<B><I>- The Christian Science Monitor</I></B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"[CSIS] specialises in foreign policy but, since the collapse of the Soviet Union, has recognised that  'some of America's biggest trouble spots are not abroad but at home.'  It argues that deep-seated social and economic problems at home can be solved only if the US develops a bipartisan consensus on policies, similar to that forged national security in previous decades." <BR>   
<B><I>- Financial Times</I></B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"[The Center for Strategic and International Studies] believes that policy emerges from discussion, that ideas are honed in debate, and that there must be continuing efforts to build consensus out of shifting opinions."<BR>
<B><I>- The Idea Brokers: Think Tanks and the Rise of the New Policy Elite</I> by James A. Smith</B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"The Center for Strategic and International Studies [is] a Washington research institution with a reputation for harboring tough-minded scholars and diplomats.  But tough-mindedness isn't always what it seems.  Scholars and diplomats affiliated with the center have just produced a study saying religion has been systematically neglected as a factor in international affairs.  They contend that policy makers, embassy aides, strategists-and journalists, too-have given minute attention to economic assets, military forces and social and political rivalries while scarcely noting the role of religion."<BR>
<B><I> - The New York Times</I></B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"The Future Years Defense Plan [FYDP] is in fact the long view on defense.  It's where the cost of procuring big ticket items like aircraft carriers and airplanes is planned and budgeted over many fiscal years, as compared with the one fiscal year Congress is currently squabbling over.  According to a recent study by the Center for Strategic and Internatonal Studies (CSIS), the current FYDP "translates into potential shortfalls of anywhere from $177 billion to $488 billion..." through 2001 and "will enter a period of major risk between 2005 and 2010..."<BR>
"This is a long term problem and requires a long term soluton.  And it gets tougher.  Just about the time the FYDP reaches its most critical period is when the budget is supposed to be balanced.  While it's almost certain that the U.S. will not allocate the 4.5% of GDP to defense that the CSIS study recommends, those in Congress truly interested in a strong defense should begin formulating some sort of plan soon."<BR>
<B><I> - The Wall Street Journal</I></B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"A 'presidential decision directive' recently signed by President Clinton declares all-out war against organized criminal activity that is now 'global and threatening.'  The directive, PDD-42, calls transnational criminal syndicates a 'threat to U.S. national security' and to countries and regions all over the world...<BR>
	"The dimensions of the threat and preliminary recommendations on coping with it were supplied to the White House by the Center for Strategic and International Studies, which started a major project on global organized crime a year ago."<BR>
<B><I> - The Washington Times</I></B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR>

