<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>

</head>



<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 

src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



        



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 

vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 156,                        



May 7, 1996</h4>



<h1>The Second Coming of Facsism</h1>

         

<h3>Walter Laqueur on the potential of a new threat . . .</h3>

 

When the Communist empire collapsed, the final victory of liberal democracy was widely predicted. Events since then, however, do not bear out this optimism. Walter Laqueur, CSIS Kissinger chairholder, cochair of the CSIS International Research Council, and widely respected commentator on contemporary history, concludes that movements and regimes in the general tradition of the dictatorships of the 1930s (although not mere copies of Nazism and Italian fascism) could again come to power in various parts of the world. (FASCISM: Past, Present, Future, Oxford University Press, 1996) <P> 



<B>European Neo- and Post-Fascism</B><BR>  

Neo- and post-fascist parties are once again influential in Europe, particularly in Italy, France, and Austria. Despite discontent in these Western societies - rising crime rates, increasing unemployment, especially among the younger generation, and tension caused by the influx of millions of immigrants - Laqueur regards these present day neo-fascist parties as only a weak, second infusion of historical fascism, lacking both its extremism and dynamism. "Even if they are basically anti-democratic, they hide their true characterówhich fascism never didóto try to appear respectable and proclaim their attachment to democratic values and institutions."<P> 



Broadly speaking, asserts Laqueur, neo-fascism in Europe after 1945 has been a failure.  Post-fascism, however, finds fertile ground in the former Soviet empire and even more promising conditions in what was once the Third World, particularly in those countries where extremist religious movements have appeared.<P>



<B>Clerical Fascism</B> <BR>

Islamic fundamentalism (Iranian-style) has emerged as one of the most potent forces in the Middle East and parts of Africa, particularly in North Africa.  According to Laqueur, "there is an unmistakable kinship between Muslim radicalism and fascism; sometimes the affinities are uncanny." Common features of both movements include<P>



<BLOCKQUOTE>    - rejection of modernism and secularism;<P>

   - populist movements, totalitarian in nature, based on the resentment of an underclass that has not benefited from modernization but instead feels left out; <P>

   - absence of an economic doctrine, but opposition to Western-style capitalism (although not the ownership of private property), and distrust of the markets; and,<P>

   - use of violence to promote their message and achieve goals.  Extremist movements have turned to alternative measures such as terrorism and surrogate warfare.</BLOCKQUOTE>



<B>Post-Communist Fascism </B> <BR>

Present conditions in Russia - social tensions, economic difficulties, strong nationalist sentiments, the lack of deeply rooted democratic notions, and the political and ideological vacuum left by the collapse of communism - have created the opportunity for the extreme Right to successfully assert itself in the Russian political landscape.  And it has done so, in an alliance with the neo-Communists.<P>  



Laqueur notes that between 1991 and the present, a rapprochement between the anti-Communist Right and the neo-Communists "on a doctrinal level and also for practical reasons" has blurred their dividing lines.  Both groups now share a common enemy, and they understand that a joint effort is crucial to their success in Russia's uncertain political future. This alliance could well be the decisive factor in the coming Russian presidential elections this June.<P>  



<B>Prospects </B> <BR>

Laqueur concludes that although the victory of post-fascist regimes is not foreordained, it must now be seriously considered. The preconditions for fascism's second coming - a time of economic, social, and political crisis, when the current regime is incapable of dealing with urgent problems - are widely evident in the contemporary world, yet actions to alleviate current societal frustrations and citizen disenfranchisement are absent.  The progress of fascist movements, under different names and in different political attire, must be watched - especially at a time when means of mass destruction are far more accessible than in the past.  

<p><hr>



