<HTML><TITLE>Enterprise for the Environment</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3spcproj.gif"></p><br><p>

<H1><p align="center">Enterprise for the
Environment</p></H1><p><br><p>


Chaired by former EPA Administrator Bill Ruckelshaus, the Enterprise for the
Environment is attempting to forge a bipartisan consensus among key environmental
protection stakeholders in support of comprehensive,
concrete policy recommendations that will
lead to enhanced national environmental performance.<p><br><p>

<h3><p align="center">PROJECT OVERVIEW</p></h3>


<table cellpadding=15><tr>

<td valign=top width=150><font size="2">
<i>For information about specific aspects of the project:</i><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/summary.html">Project Summary</a><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/ruckbio.html">Ruckelshaus Biography</a><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/steercom.html#stake">Stakeholder Roster</a><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/steercom.html">Steering Committee Membership</a><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/actiongp.html">Action Group Topics and Co-Chairs</a><p>

<a href="#relevant">Relevant Documents</a><p>

</font>
<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/keystone.gif" width="100" height="85"></p>
<p align="center"><a href="http://www.lmi.org/napa/"><img border=0 src="http://www.csis.org/images/napa.gif" width="100" height="101"></a></p></td>

<td>
By building a bipartisan consensus among the stakeholders in environmental protection, the project intends to develop comprehensive, concrete policy recommendations for
enhancement of national environmental performance.  As reflected in the
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/summary.html">Project Summary</a>,
these policy recommendations -- to be presented to Congress and the Administration in 1997 -- would focus on three areas:
(1) transformation of the regulatory system administered by the Environmental Protection Agency;  (2) promotion of higher levels of stewardship in businesses regulated by EPA;  and (3) modification of key economic policies that drive public and private de
cisions
affecting the environment.  The outcome of adoption of those recommendations, it is envisioned, would be the attainment of "cleaner, cheaper, fairer"
environmental results.<p>

<b>Project Leadership</b><br>
The project is chaired by <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/ruckbio.html">Bill Ruckelshaus</a>, who
twice served as EPA Administrator, the first time when the Agency
was founded in 1970 and the second when the Agency needed revitalization in 1983.   Appointees of both
political parties are among the three other former Administrators -- Doug Costle, Lee Thomas and Bill Reilly -- and two former Deputy Administrators who have joined him in the project.<p>

<b>Stakeholder Members</b><br>
The project includes over 90 members, selected to be representative of the
diverse stakeholder interests in environmental protection.   Included in the
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/steercom.html#stake">Stakeholder
Roster</a> are government officials
(Members of Congress from both Houses and both political parties, State Governors and Attorneys General, local Mayors, and directors of State environmental regulatory and related agencies);  representatives of regulated businesses, environmental
and conservation organizations, organized labor, and the environmental justice movement;  and experts from
Universities and other policy forums.   The project has the support of EPA, which is represented by the Agency's Deputy Administrator, Fred Hansen.<p>

<b>Institutional Partners</b><br>
The project involves collaboration by three institutions:  the Center for Strategic & International Studies (CSIS);  the Keystone Center;  and the <a href="http://www.lmi.org/napa/">National Academy of Public Administration (NAPA)</a>.  (1) CSIS convened



the stakeholder process and is providing overall project direction, analytical support and financial development through the Project Director, Karl Hausker, Ph.D, and his staff.  (2) Keystone designed and is facilitating the stakeholder process, with its



staff efforts directed by John Ehrmann, its Executive Vice President.  (3) NAPA (which previously prepared a report, commissioned by the Congressional Appropriations Committees, about the environmental protection system administered by EPA) will
provide analytic support to the stakeholder process through staff directed by DeWitt John, Director of the Center for the Economy and the Environment.  The NAPA work will include a case study report, overseen by an independent panel, on recent efforts by
EPA
and others to promote more effective and efficient environmental management. <p>

<b>Organizational Structure</b><br>
The stakeholders have divided themselves among various <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/actiongp.html">Action Groups</a> to work on specific topics under the direction of designated co-chairs.  The Action Groups, in turn, take guidance from a <a href



="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/steercom.html">Steering Committee</a> of some 35 stakeholders.  The Action Groups will present points on which they concur, or competing options, to the Steering Committee,
which will seek to agree upon a set of recommendations to present
to the stakeholders for endorsement. <p>

<a name="relevant"><b>Available Documents</b></a><br>
Under the project's groundrules, in an effort to promote
free
exchange of ideas in this consensus-building endeavor, participants agree
not to
attribute suggested ideas or proposals to other participants and not to circulate draft "works in progress"
that have not yet won approval by the group-at-large.  Accordingly, few if
any working papers generated by the project are currently available to
interested outside parties. The
participation of representatives of the various stakeholder interests is intended to
provide the vehicle for the incorporation of a wide range of viewpoints.
Once project recommendations emerge, they will be subject to full public
review before adoption. <p>

Those documents that are accessible either were already identified in the preceding paragraphs or may be categorized as follows: <p>

<ul>
<li>Reports and analyses that might help the reader put the project in context:  (1) the 1995 NAPA report, and its <a href="http://www.lmi.org/napa/setprior.html">Executive Summary</a>, entitled "Setting Priorities, Getting Results:  A
New Direction for EPA";  (2) the "Stopping the Pendulum" speech delivered by Mr. Ruckelshaus in receiving the Environmental
Law Insitute's Annual Award in October, 1995, and later
published under the same title in ELI's Environmental Forum of November/December 1995;  and (3)
the March, 1996 report of the <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/pcsd/index.html">President's
Council
on
Sustainable Development</a>, entitled "Sustainable America: A New Consensus for Prosperity, Opportunity and a Healthy Environment."

<li>Communications from Chairman Ruckelshaus describing the project and reflective of its evolution:  (1) his February 29, 1996 testimony to the Senate Appropriations Subcommittee on VA-HUD-Independent Agencies;  (2) the accompanying CSIS/Keystone/NAPA <a



 href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/press417.html">press release</a> annnouncing the launching of the project;  (3) his April 17, 1996 testimony to the House Appropriations Subcommittee on VA-HUD-Independent Agencies, reflecting a broadening of the projec
t
scope; (4) his speech to a Resources for the Future forum in 1996, describing the project's evolution; and (5) a series of <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/update.html">"project updates"</a> sent at intervals during 1996 to those interested in
 the project's progress.

<li>Informational documents reflecting the efforts of the project's "International Perspectives Project" to analyze the environmental protection sysytems of other countries and to draw lessons that might be instructive for the U.S.  These documents, which



 did not undergo any consensual  process within the project, include (1) <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/rndtable.html">summaries of various roundtable discussions</a> that were held, and (2) a
manuscript by the Netherlands' Director-General for Environment describing the workings of the Dutch system in great detail.
</ul><p>

<hr width=150>

The current schedule calls for the final project recommendations to be made in April, 1997.  Once issued, those recommendations, as well as the NAPA panel's case study report, will be acccessible through this site.</td></tr> </table>
<HR>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p>
</body>
</html>




