<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=145 height=179
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 164,

September 10, 1996</h4>

<h1>The Iraqi Thorn</h1>

<h3>CSIS analysts assess
developments in Iraq .  .  . </h3>

<I>In more than 120 television appearances and radio interviews throughout the past week, CSIS analysts provided a thorough analysis of the crisis in Iraq. A summary of their thinking follows:</I><P>

<I>Tony Cordesman, Co-Director, Middle East Studies:</I><BR>
                       "Given the constraints that the United States facesóand the fact that there are no good optionsóthe president has acted wisely.  There is no instant, moral, and lasting solution to the Iraqi problem.  The frustrating game of  ëchallenge and response' will arise repeatedly, and we need to be prepared to react to subsequent, low-level confrontations with similar proportionate responses."<P>

"What is equally important is that Saddam Hussein is scarcely our only problem.  As long as aggressive, authoritarian regimes rule Iraq and Iran and continue to search for hegemony in the Gulf, the United States and the international community will face similar situations.  The Gulf region has 60 percent of the world's oil reserves, and we need to accept the fact that we must contain Iran's and Iraq's aggressiveness until fundamental political changes occur within those countries."  <P>

<I>Judith Kipper, Co-Director, Middle East Studies:  </I><BR>
"The latest U.S. action in Iraq was entirely appropriate.  It demonstrated that the United States will act decisively when challenged by Saddam Hussein's aggressive military actions.  Military force is the only language Saddam understands."  

"However, the failure of the United States to protect the Kurdish population from Saddam Hussein and U.S. abandonment of northern Iraq is morally, politically, and strategically unacceptable.  We may see an even more threatening situation in the near future in an area that the United States has assumed responsibility for protecting."<P>

"The recent crisis clearly illustrates the inconsistency of U.S. Gulf policy.  Dual containment is merely a slogan.  An effective policy should aim to integrate both Iran and Iraq into a Gulf security mechanism instead of having them constantly challenge it."  <P>

<I>Bill Taylor, Director, Political-Military Studies: </I><BR>
"The U.S. response to Iraq's latest military incursion was justified but insufficient.  U.S. leadership and credibility were at stake.  Given that we are the main force behind Operation Provide Comfort, Saddam Hussein will continue to test our resolve and attempt to divide the coalition that won the Gulf War.  He understands power politics and will respond favorably only to overwhelming force."<P>

"Some states may condemn the United States for its use of military force in Kurdistan.  They would, however, join forces with us again to prevent Iraq from killing our allies in the Gulf region and seizing oil fields."<P>

<I>Daniel GourÈ, Deputy Director, Political-Military Studies:</I><BR>
"The crisis demonstrates that after five-and-a-half years of Saddam Hussein, the United States still lacks an effective policy for dealing with Iraq.  The administration's responseó44 cruise missilesówas driven by domestic electoral concerns and short-term tactical military considerations.  It was a tactical blunder and a strategic disaster."<P>

"Consequently, we must realize that the implications are significant.  U.S. action marks a watershed in our policy toward Iraq and the Northern Persian Gulfóit has exacerbated the fraying of the Gulf War coalition.  If we don't change our policy, we should expect to see our strategic situation, our ability to influence events, and our military and defense presence in the Gulf deteriorate."<P>   

<I>Ryan Henry, Senior Fellow, Political-Military Studies:</I><BR>
"Given what the U.S. objectives wereóto demonstrate our leadership and to ensure stabilized delivery of petroleum products out of the Gulfóthe U.S. response was appropriate.  In addition, the United States accomplished a long-term military goalótightening the noose around Saddam Hussein to prevent him from any attempt to move to the south and threaten his oil-rich neighborsóby using the problem of Kurdistan as an excuse to intervene in Iraq."<P>

"Unfortunately, the implications of this situation are long-lasting.  What we will see is Saddam's continued attempts to redefine the boundaries of the box in which he has been confined by the United Nations.  In turn, the United States will use every such opportunity to further compress that box while supporting our strategic interests in the region." <P>

"As long as the Kurdistan region straddles oil fields and oil transportation points, it will not become a sovereign nation-state.  Furthermore, the United States must refrain from getting involved in this situation.  Kurdistan is a Bosnia-in-waitingóthere is no viable exit strategy and once the United States pulls out, the fighting will resume."
<p><hr>

