<head>
<title>CSIS Constituencies</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3missio.gif"></p>
<h1>What constituencies does CSIS serve?
</h1>
     The answer is straight-forward: decision-makers across the 
world.  Leaders in 
Congress, the Executive Branch, and in parliaments abroad; leaders 

in the international private 
sector; leaders in academia and research communities representing 
diverse countries and 
perspectives; opinion leaders in the media; and the general 
public: 

<blockquote>
<p><b>Congress: </b> Last year, more than 100 members of the U.S. 
Congress were actively 
engaged in CSIS projects ranging from the NAFTA and Beyond 
Commission to the Center's work on 
global organized crime.  Members of Congress and their aides draw 
regularly from the real-time 
analysis and the examination of long-term issues by Center 
scholars.</p>

<p><b>Executive Branch:</b>  The U.S. Executive Branch faces the 
challenge of overcoming 
compartmentalization, short-term focus, lack of initiative, and 
bureaucratic inertia.  CSIS, 
with its catalytic and synergistic approach, is an invaluable 
resource for government officials 
in every agency.  Last year, hundreds of Executive Branch 
officials participated in CSIS 
projects.</p>

</p><b>Leaders from Other Countries:</b>  Policymakers from other 
countries also play an 
important role in the Center's projects.  The Center engages 
political leaders ranging from 
heads of state to parliamentarians by providing forums for 
discussion of key issues.</p>

<p><b>Business Community: </b> A major priority at CSIS is to 
bring private-sector expertise 
and experience to bear in addressing international policy issues.  

Last year, more than 100 
CEOs from more than 30 countries took part in CSIS action-oriented 

projects designed to achieve 
concrete results.  The international private sector also draws 
extensively on CSIS insight on 
all areas of the world.</p>

<p><b>Academic/Research Community: </b> Apart from its in-house 
experts, CSIS draws from the 
insight of world-class universities in several countries through 
the eminent scholars 
participating in its International Research Council.</p>

<p><b>Media/General Public: </b> In terms of public education on 
policy issues, CSIS analysts 
appears regularly on television and radio and author opinion 
pieces, articles, and books in the 
print media across the world.</p>

<UL>
<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission1.html">What is CSIS? </A>

<li><a href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission2.html">What is the mission of CSIS?</a>



<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission3.html">How does CSIS implement this 
vision?</A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission4.html">What are
CSIS values?  What does it believe? </A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission5.html">What constituencies
does CSIS serve? </A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission6.html">What
criteria does CSIS have for selecting
projects? </A></UL>
<hr><i>File Created: 9/15/95</i>
</blockquote>


