<HTML>
<TITLE>CSIS Projects in the Americas</TITLE>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a><br><p>

<p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></p>
<H2><p align="center">Projects on the Americas</p></H2><hr>

<table cellpadding=20><tr>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">
<i>Project Titles:</i><p>
<a href="#brazil">Brazil and South America</a><p>
<a href="#canada">Canada Project</a><p>
<a href="#carib">Caribbean Studies</a><p>
<a href="#mexcong">Congressional Study Groups</a> on Mexico and Canada<p>
<a href="#meltdown">Decision-making and Policy Implications</a> of the Mexican Financial Meltdown<p>
<a href="#democracy">Democracy in the Western Hemisphere</a><p>
<a href="#mexico">Mexico Project</a><p>
<a href="#auto">North American</a> Auto Industry Study<p>
<a href="#mercosur">U.S.-MERCOSUR</a> High-Level Working Group<p>
</font>
</td>


<td valign=top>
<h3><a name="brazil">Brazil and South America</a></h3>
Brazil is returning to its traditional status as a significant counterpart to U.S. policy initiatives in the Western Hemisphere. This appears particularly the case with Brazil's leadership in MERCOSUR. CSIS is expanding its assessment of these dynamics and also expecting the impact of these developments for South America's other key actors: Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Peru, and Venezuela. Guiding this initiative will also be interaction of the agenda with U.S. congressional interest. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="canada">Canada Project</a></h3>
This project provides policymakers, corporate strategic planners, and international media with timely analysis of Canada and U.S.-Canadian relations. Issues such as trade and investment, the environment, energy, and the competitiveness of the post-NAFTA auto industry are addressed through regular seminars, publications, congressional outreach, and business briefings. Additional outreach includes the CSIS Canada Briefing, a monthly roundtable that offers an in-depth assessment of trade and economic issues. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="carib">Caribbean Studies</a></h3>
The issues at the core of this initiative include the emerging global trend toward free market economics and democratic political governance, a decrease in foreign aid, increasing threats from narcotics trafficking, and major leadership changes. A new project attempts to identify the character and sources of the new generation of leaders and will include a group of emerging young leaders who will be engaged on a broad range of issues. In addition to this core research agenda, the Center is devoting special attention to the decade-long crisis in Haiti and is continuing its long-standing monitoring of Cuban policy. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="mexcong">Congressional Study Groups on Mexico and Canada</a> </h3>
The Study Group on Mexico has more than 15 active members, including Senators John McCain (R-AZ) and Bob Graham (D-FL) and Representatives Jim Kolbe (R-AZ) and Bill Richardson (D-NM). The Study Group on Canada is chaired by Representatives John McHugh (R-NY) and Jim Oberstar (D-MN). Each group brings together members of Congress for off-the-record briefings, as well as larger meetings geared toward a broader audience on bilateral issues such as elections, trade, environment, transportation infrastructure, democratization (Mexico), and national unity (Canada). <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a>, Deputy Director, Americas Program and Director, Mexico Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="meltdown">Decision-making and Policy Implications of the Mexican Financial Meltdown</a></h3>
The project is designed to examine the decision-making by the Mexican government, the U.S. government, and the IMF during the 18 months prior to the devaluation of the peso on December 20, 1994. The main purpose of the project is to determine why certain decisions were made and why a policy of increased vulnerability was tolerated for so long. The project will make recommendations for future financial policy for Mexico and will suggest a more orderly way for the international community to deal with future financial rescues. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, William E. Simon Chair in Political Economy)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="democracy">Democracy in the Western Hemisphere</a></h3>
Although the Western Hemisphere has opened up politically over the past decade, the environment remains fragile. To chart this trend, the CSIS Western Hemisphere Election Study Series has issued more than 125 analyses of presidential and local elections since 1982, with eight studies in 1995. Americas Program staff have also participated in election observation delegations, testified before Congress, and held pre- and post-election briefings. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="mexico">Mexico Project</a></h3>
This project addresses critical issues on the U.S.-Mexican agenda, such as free trade, democratization, the environment, immigration, judicial reform, and counternarcotics efforts. The project's policy roundtables, congressional briefings, and publication series have engaged prominent Mexican and U.S. private sector leaders, policymakers, and academics. Mexico is undergoing profound economic and political transformations, which underscore the strategic significance of the U.S.-Mexican relationship. In addition, a new study, "NAFTA: Two-and-one-half Years Later," being undertaken by the Simon Chair and the Mexico Project, will demonstrate that NAFTA largely protected U.S. exports to Mexico in the aftermath of the peso collapse. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a>, Deputy Director, Americas Program, and Director, Mexico Project)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="auto">North American Auto Industry Study</a></h3>
No sector is more important to the success of NAFTA than the auto industry. Motor vehicles and parts are the largest item in bilateral trade between the United States and Canada, the United States and Mexico, and even between Canada and Mexico. NAFTA acknowledged the high degree of integration in the auto sector, but also made it imperative that the three governments rethink their policy approaches to the regulation and promotion of auto manufacture, research and development, and trade with a view toward greater trilateral cooperation, coordination, and harmonization. Guided by a private sector task force made up of the chairmen of General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler as well as major automotive suppliers such as TRW, this study will tackle key issues in the areas of labor, environment, trade policy, market integration, and the future role of Canada and Mexico in automotive production. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4fauriol.html">Georges A. Fauriol</a>, Director, Americas Program, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, William E. Simon Chair in Political Economy)</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="mercosur">U.S.-MERCOSUR High-Level Working Group</a></h3>
CSIS launched this working group to strengthen U.S. relations with the five MERCOSUR countriesóArgentina, Brazil, Chile, Paraguay, and Uruguay. The group emphasizes business, financial, and economic relations among the five countries. To accomplish its goals, the group triggers country-specific and regional initiatives, such as the U.S.-Argentine Caucus. A specialized counterpart for U.S.-Brazilian relations, which will include a bilateral congressional component, is in formation. <p>
<i>(<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4handy.html">George W. Handy</a>, Director)</i>
</td></tr></table>

<hr width=150>
<font size="2">
