<!--
	Author: Guild Copeland
	Date: 	9/6/95
-->
<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 162,

August 20, 1996</h4>

<h1>Tapping the Caspian</h1>

<h3>The stakes are high .  .  . 
</h3>

Six years after the collapse of communism, territorial claims to the Caspian Sea have yet to be resolved.  The Caspian, once the domain of the Soviet Union and Iran, is now surrounded by five sovereign statesóRussia, Iran, Azerbaijan, Kazakstan, and Turkmenistanówith conflicting interests.  A major issue of contention is whether the Caspian is a sea or a lake.  <P>

The distinction is significant.  If the Caspian is considered a lake, all five of the riparian states must reach a consensus before development of its resources can commence.  As a sea, however, jurisdiction is divided according to the Law of the Sea, which would give each state its own sector of the waters.  <P>

Of the five players, Russia has the most to lose if the Caspian is officially deemed a sea: the largest oil and gas reserves, readily accessible to the Russian market before the collapse of the Soviet Union, are located in Azerbaijan, Kazakstan, and Turkmenistan. <P> 

The potential of the Caspian basin's oil and gas deposits and the fact that most of the oil to be produced will be for the export market have also piqued the interest of multinational oil companies from the United States, Great Britain, and Norway. <P> 

<B>Impediments to Development.</B>  Given that three of the five littoral states are landlocked, pipelines to transport the oil and gas to foreign markets are a major priority.  Unfortunately, determining routings has become nearly impossible.  "Pipeline politics have become the issue of the day," says Bob Ebel, director of the CSIS Energy and National Security Program.  "It seems no matter which direction planners might look, each prospective route faces political challenges from dissident or separatist activity."  In the case of Azeri oil, for example, the two best options for pipeline routings pass either directly through the heart of Chechnya or within a few kilometers of the disputed enclave Nagorno-Karabakh. <P> 

Kazakstan faces similar challenges.  Although the best route for transporting oil from the offshore Tengiz field to the Black Sea port of Novorossiisk passes through politically quiescent territory in Russia, Kazakstan must contend with Russia's desire to control the oil.  Other options are less viable.  To the west, civil wars in the Caucasus Mountains create a precarious situation, and to the south lies politically controversial Iran. <P>    

Ebel underscores that Russian involvement is essential.  "It is quite evident that there can be no game unless Russia is invited to play.  That has held true for oil field development offshore Baku, for developing the giant Tengiz field in Kazakstan and the building of an export pipeline to Novorossiisk, for the future of the Karachaganak gas condensate deposit in Kazakstanóprobably the largest such deposit in the world, and for Turkmen natural gas."<P>

<B>Russia's Internal Schism.</B>  Recognizing that Russian participation is critical in tapping the wealth of the Caspian Sea is a step in the right direction.  Bulent Aliriza, director of the CSIS Turkish Studies Project, notes, however, "what Russia wants is not clear; the government lacks any unifying policy."  The Russian Foreign Ministry opposes the current development plans because they do not grant Russia a special status in any littoral country's oil or gas production projects.  In addition, the ministry does not want the former Soviet states to gain the economic independence that would result from oil and gas revenues.  On the other hand, the Ministry of Fuel and Energy is willing to allow the oil to reach foreign markets on Russian terms; a position also held by Russia's oil and gas industry. <P>

<B>U.S. Involvement.</B>  In addition to the U.S. energy industry, which has invested heavily in Caspian Sea development projects, the U.S. government also has a vested interest in ensuring that Caspian resources are exported to foreign markets, with Russia's consent.  "There is massive, yet discreet, U.S. involvementófrom Vice President Al Gore on down.  Day-to-day cooperation occurs between the U.S. government and the Russian Ministry of Fuel and Energy," Aliriza remarks.  "The U.S. government has staked a lot of prestige on integrating Russia into the international free trade system." <P> 

Aliriza believes the United States is trying to demonstrate that the Russians want to be involved in the global free market by persuading them to allow the oil to reach the market with Russia's blessing, albeit at a cost.  "Such a resolution, if successful, could set the stage for the post-Soviet relationship between the Western economic system and the economic systems of Russia and the former Soviet states; it could potentially help fashion the post-Cold War world."  
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 9/6/96</i>

