<h3><a name="assess">Assessing Data Privacy in the 1990s and Beyond</a></h3>
<b>Report of the Global Information Infrastructure Commission</b><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4pipe.html">G. Russell Pipe</a>, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4charles.html">Carol Charles</a>, and Symon Visser, editors<p>
This report discusses the results of a questionnaire that was presented to the International Conference of Data Protection Commissioners in Copenhagen, Denmark in September 1995. The questionnaire assessed the adequacy of current data privacy legislation in light of increased privatization of networks and services, expanded global commerce, and rapid technological change. The report points to the need for rapid global harmonization of data protection policies and greater involvement of developing and newly industrializing countries in their framing. <p>
<i>International Communications Report	45 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-343-2		$18.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="chinainfo">China in the Information Age: Telecommunications and the Dilemmas of Reform </a></h3>
<a href="http://www.scils.rutgers.edu/people/faculty/mmcv.html">Milton Mueller</a> and <a href="http://istweb.syr.edu/Project/Faculty/Tan.html">Zixiang Tan</a> <p>
This is the first comprehensive scholarly examination of China's economic reforms in the telecommunications sector. The book probes the inherent tension between global liberalization trends in telecommunications and information markets and the Chinese government's attempt to maintain a "socialist market economy" with centralized, one-party political control.
". . . a sophisticated, well-researched, and sensitive analysis of the enormous potential and contradictions in the Chinese telecommunications system. . . . It is a fascinating description of the complex Chinese process of modernization, reform, and reaction." - James R. Lilley, Former Ambassador to the People's Republic of China<p>

"China is an awakening economic giant but an information-age dwarf. Mueller and Tan examine China's torturous road to advanced information highways and provide a long-needed comprehensive volume on China's telecommunications system." - Eli M. Noam, Director, Columbia Institute for Tele-Information, Columbia University Graduate School of Business<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger 	165 pp.	1997<br>
ISBN 0-275-95829-9 (pb)	$16.95<br>
          0-275-95828-0 (hb)	$49.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="globalizing">Globalizing Electronic Commerce</a></h3>
<b>GIIC Report on the International Forum on Electronic Commerce</b><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4charles.html">Carol Charles</a>, editor<p>
Electronic commerce is a key application driving the global economy. The Internet, e-mail, and electronic data interchange (EDI) are strategic tools that have expanded the scope of consumer choice and increased management control over applications from procurement to marketing.  This report on the GIIC International Forum on Electronic Commerce in Beijing, China reviews the policy, technology, and social challenges facing companies and policymakers around the world with regard to electronic commerce. <p>
<i>International Communications Report 	86 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-340-8		$25.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="infosec">Information Revolution and International Security</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a> and C. Edward
Peartree, editors<br>
Contributors: Lawrence E. Blume, James Der Derian, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4henry.html">Ryan Henry</a>, David Ronfeldt, James N. Rosenau, Michael Vlahos, M. Mitchell Waldrop<p>
This companion volume to The Information Revolution and National Security brings together a diverse set of experts from the business, military, government, and academic communities to consider the implications of new information technologies for international security. The focus is not so much on security in the strict military sense as it is on the global social, economic, and political changes occurring because of new information technologies and their potential effects on the international security environment_for example, the effects of speed and global networks on the conduct of diplomacy as well as conflict.  This provocative, informed exploration will be of interest to policymakers, legislators, and others involved with the global security issues accompanying this revolution.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-299-1</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="infonatlsec">The Information Revolution and National Security</a>
: Dimensions and Directions</h3>
Stuart J.D. Schwartzstein, editor<br>
Foreword by Adm. William A. Owens<br>
Contributors: C. Kenneth Allard, John Arquilla, Jeffrey R. Cooper,  James Der Derian, James B. Ferguson, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Ahmed S. Hashim, Alfred A. Jones, Brian Kahin, Michael R. Nelson, Admiral William A. Owens, George E. Pickett Jr., John W. Rendon Jr., David Ronfeldt, Larry Seaquist, Martin Shubik, Michael Vlahos, R. James Woolsey and Henrikas Yushkiavitshus <p>
Information and communications technologies are having a profound impact in a number of ways, domestically and globally, including how national security is maintained and how war is waged. There are also implications for civil liberties and how we, as a society, deal with new kinds of conflict. The issues that are raised are both far-ranging and complex.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	c. 296 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-288-6		$25.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="infowar">Information Warfare, Cyberterrorism, and Information Assurance</a></h3>
<b>A Report from the CSIS Global Organized Crime Task Force</b><p>
William H. Webster, project chair<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, project director<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, project codirectors<br>
Pat Gallagher, Task Force director and editor<br>
Frank J. Cilluffo, Task Force chairman and editor<p>
The United States is vulnerable to information warfare attacks and operations.  The capability to deny, disrupt, destroy, or steal information and systems is widely available and low in cost.  A dedicated adversary could seriously jeopardize our national and economic security as our dependence on information infrastructures continues to grow exponentially.  Composed of senior U.S. government officials and private-sector experts, the task force identifies the most critical infrastructures, assesses the threats to and vulnerabilities of these infrastructures, and makes recommendations on how best to mitigate the risks.<p>
<i>CSIS Report      c. 50 pp.		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-295-9		$16.95 Est.</i>


<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="japanus">Japan and the United States: Revving Up for the Information Superhighway</a></h3>
Kristin A. Juffer<p>
<i>International Communications Report 	102 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-314-9 		$25.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nii">National Information Infrastructure for Social and Economic Development in Asia</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4charles.html">Carol Charles</a>, editor<p>
What are the implications of the growth of the information superhighway for developing countries? This report focuses on the key issue of developing the information infrastructure in Asia to further social and economic progress. The main areas of discussion include current initiatives to construct national information infrastructures in the Asia-Pacific region, the application of information technology for development, and the role of government organizations and the private sector in developing an information infrastructure.<p>
<i>International Communications Report	116 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-339-4		$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nationalism">Nationalism, Regionalism, and Globalism in Building the Global Information Society</a></h3>
<b>GIIC Report on the Global Information Society and Development Forum</b><p>
Derrick L. Cogburn, editor<p>
As a platform for the public launching of the African Information Society Initiative, the Global Information Infrastructure Commission, the World Bank, and the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research in South Africa came together at the Information Society and Development (ISAD) Conference in Midrand, South Africa in May 1996. This volume brings together the various elements and background material that made the Initiative possible.<p>
<i>International Communications Report	138 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-341-6		$25.00</i><p>


</td></tr></table>

