<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 154,                        

                      
April 1, 1996</h4>

<h1>Transatlantic Defense Cooperation</h1>
         
<h3>An opportune time . . .</h3>
 
Slashed defense budgets, defense industry consolidation, and increasing involvement in coalition operations characterize the new post-cold war environment for players on both sides of the Atlantic.  Cognizant of these current trends and of the past failures in adopting transatlantic collaborative defense agreements, the CSIS Atlantic Partnership Project, a commission of leading defense industry executives, has cautiously crafted its final report, Making Transatlantic Defense Cooperation Work.  The recommendations outlined below represent an unprecedented multilateral consensus by the world's leading defense corporations.<P>

<B>The Rationale</B><BR>
 	The U.S.-European strategic alliance is increasingly defined by joint military participation in multinational operations.  This new dimension  underscores the increasing importance of U.S.-European military interoperability.<P>
 
 	Complete autarky in the development and production of defense systems is no longer feasible due to the severe and continuing contractions of U.S. and European defense budgets and the spiraling cost of developing new technologies.<P> 

 	Cooperation can save money by spreading the risk of technology development and providing economies of scale in production and logistics costs.  Cost sharing may also allow governments to continue with technological developments that otherwise would have been too expensive for them to undertake alone.<P>  

 	Cooperation can sustain expertise.  If an agreement can be reached that allows companies to receive a fair return approximately proportional to the national investment, then cooperation would help governments maintain employment and technology expertise that would otherwise have been lost.<P>  

 	In the long term, defense cooperation will be beneficial to both the United States and Europe.  Although the United States enjoys a defense trade surplus with Europe -- 1993 sales for the top 10 U.S. defense companies were approximately $6 billion versus $3 billion in sales for their top 10 European counterparts -- the movement in Europe toward defense industry integration and European governments' efforts to strengthen the "European preference" to make their firms more competitive will make it increasingly difficult for U.S. companies to penetrate the European defense market as successfully as they have in the past.<P> 

<B>Two Sets of Recommendations  </B><P>
(1) A framework agreement for specific programs on which governments have agreed to cooperate. <P> 

Participating governments would:<BR>
 <UL>
<LI>	coordinate technology transfer and security rules;

<LI> 	permit companies to determine the distribution of work content, technology development, and program management;

<LI> 	provide continued support for cooperative programs through clear and well-defined funding milestones;

<LI> 	approve an accounting system for contributions to the program; and

<LI> 	permit companies to export the collaborative system to third-country destinations that governments have identified in 
advance, without further legislative restrictions. 
</UL>
(2) A broad strategy to encourage the opening of domestic defense markets.  Opportunities are emerging from Europe's transition to a more integrated defense sector, including<BR>

 <UL><LI>	
European governments as more effective interlocutors with the United States on collaborative programs; and

 	
<LI>Greater consistency among the different national European procurement practices and policies that  enable U.S. and European firms to operate in a more transparent and predictable market.</UL>
  
It is time for governments on both sides of the Atlantic to take transatlantic defense cooperation more seriously. The United States and Europe cannot afford to risk a more pronounced polarization between their respective defense markets.<P> 

To work toward strengthening the U.S.-European defense relationship, European governments should ensure that their defense market remains open to competition and cooperation by avoiding new forms of protectionism, working to develop a more coherent and transparent defense market and continuing the process of rationalizing and privatizing European defense companies. <P>   

The U.S. government must refrain from adopting legislation  that insists on sole-sourcing from U.S. firms, strengthen and extend the exemptions from "Buy America" legislation for allied countries, and revise critical items lists and other mobilization base restrictions to allow European systems to compete in a broader range of U.S. programs requirements.<P>   
<p><hr>

