<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 161,

August 8, 1996</h4>

<h1>Gaining Momentum</h1>

<h3>South Africa proceeds
on the right track  .  .  . 
</h3>

The U.S.-South Africa Binational Commission (BNC) meetings held in Washington on July 22-23, 1996, signaled a high point in bilateral relations between the two countries.  The South African delegation, led by Thabo Mbeki, South Africa's deputy president, and its U.S. counterpart, led by Vice President Al Gore, deepened the impact of existing, creative programs in diverse areasóbusiness development, human resource development, agriculture, environment, energy, and science and technology.  Perhaps most significant were the developments in the commercial sector.  The U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation, for example, signed an agreement on July 22 establishing a $120 million fund to encourage investment in southern Africa, and both countries agreed to expand bilateral links in many sectors ranging from air travel to communications. <P>

During this third meeting of the BNC, Mbeki tackled the thorniest item on the U.S.-South African agenda, the Armscor case.  In the 1970s and 1980s, South Africa's state-owned weapons company, Armscor, purchased arms from a Pennsylvania corporation in violation of apartheid-era sanctions and U.S. law.  In 1991, a Philadelphia court indicted Armscor.  To this day, the issue remains an irritant in the relationship.  After a meeting between Mbeki and President Clinton on July 24, the two sides reached a tentative agreement to solve the problem, easing fears that more political tension could emanate from the affair.<P>

Since Nelson Mandela's African National Congress (ANC) government came to power over two years ago, South Africa has made progress toward creating an investor-friendly environment, reducing its budget deficit, and liberalizing exchange controls.  Foreign direct investment since 1994 has topped $4 billion, surpassing expectations, with half of that amount coming from U.S. businesses.  In addition:<P>
	
 <UL><LI>	Inflation is at 6.3 percent, the lowest rate in 20 years;
 <LI>	GDP growth of 3.5 percent is projected for 1996; and,
 <LI>	South Africa plans to reduce its budget deficit to 4 percent  	for 1997-1998 and to increase annual growth rates to 6 	percent by the turn of the century.</UL><P>

<B>The Post-Mandela Era.</B>  The international business community remains somewhat apprehensive, especially about political succession and South Africa's aggressive trade unions.  Witney Schneidman, Director of the CSIS Working Group on South and Southern Africa, contends that investors need not be jittery about the political stability after Mandela's term ends in 1999.  He points out that the next 
president will almost certainly be Mbeki, a Sussex University-trained economist with a long ANC career.  A pragmatic, strategic thinker, Mbeki was endorsed by Mandela as his successor in early July.  Although Mbeki may have less charisma than Mandela, the ANC's overwhelming popularity and Mandela's blessing will help him win the presidency and ensure a smooth transition.  More important, the institutionalization of South Africa's democracy will solidify political stability in the post-Mandela era.  <P>

<B>Cosatu, Crime, and Education.</B>  Mbeki has played an integral role in South Africa's economic reconstruction since 1994.  He was the principal author of the macroeconomic plan the government unveiled in June to reduce the fiscal deficit, create jobs, and attract foreign investment.  The plan was recently assailed, however, by the Confederation of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu), the largest federation of trade unions in the country and an important ally of the ANC.  With uncharacteristic inflexibility, Mandela told Cosatu that the economic plan is non-negotiable.  "Mandela's firmness with labor," Schneidman notes, "is a welcome signal to business."  Still, the relatively high cost of labor in South Africa will deter investors from an otherwise attractive emerging market.<P>

Another potential drawback to investing in South Africa is crime.  The surge in crime in the past two yearsó20,000 murders last year aloneódoes not hinder businesses now, but Schneidman warns that if not brought under control soon, it will inevitably lead investors to ask, "Who's in charge?"   South Africa may face an even greater challenge shoring up its education system, which severely discriminated against blacks under apartheid.  Without improvement, it will be difficult to maintain a capable management force and overcome the shortage of skilled workers. <P>

In the 28 months since Mandela was inaugurated as president, South Africa has made enormous strides toward achieving sustained economic growth and becoming an attractive destination for foreign investment.  Although the devaluation of the rand over the last several months underscores the sensitivity of South Africa's markets to the concerns of international fund managers, it is not an accurate reflection of the degree of political and economic stability that exists in the country.  Given the legacy of the apartheid era, South Africa has developed a durable political center and a broad national consensus on many critical issues.  The government has also taken significant steps in transforming this consensus into a cohesive set of relevant policies.   
<p><hr>

