<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left>        <b>Number 166,

October 11, 1996</b><hr>

<h1>"Re-engineering" U.S. Forces in Asia?</h1>

<h3>Tensions on Okinawa decline, 
but U.S. forces facing transition

</h3>

Although the U.S. and Japanese governments may have finally diffused the long-simmering crisis on Okinawa, the fundamental issue of U.S. military presence in Japan, and indeed throughout Asia, will inevitably resurface. Pacific Forum CSIS Senior Associate Torkel Patterson argues that the United States must begin discussions with its allies on alternative U.S. force structures in Asia now in order to secure the long-term stability of the Asia-Pacific region and America's critical role in it. "Failure to do so," Patterson warns, "will lead to the perception of an American strategic withdrawal from Asia within 5-10 years and a consequent significant rise in regional instability."<p>

Following September's summit between President Clinton and Prime Minister Hashimoto and the "2+2" meeting between the U.S. secretaries of state and defense and their Japanese counterparts, U.S.-Japan security relations seem to be back to "normal." Patterson notes that all outstanding base issues but one have been settled, and the lastórelocation of the controversial Marine Corps Air Station at Futenmaóis nearing successful resolution. Hashimoto, who faces elections this month, has bought time through his economic stimulus package for Okinawaóhis plan benefits mayors who support the U.S. bases in their towns. Governor Ota is expected to sign the action extending the base lease arrangements. <p>

<b>U.S. Interests in Asia.</b><br>
The Clinton administration remains committed to maintaining U.S. presence in the Asia-Pacific region. Its East Asia Strategy Report set the minimum number of U.S. forward-deployed forces in Asia "for the foreseeable future" at 100,000, and the administration has stalwartly defended that figure as the best way to demonstrate America's commitment to its allies. Although there is some fringe criticism of this strategy, the vast majority of policy activists regard any significant reduction of U.S. forces while tensions exist on the Korean peninsula as an irresponsible act that would send the wrong signal to North Korea.<p>

There is near uniform consensus that after the resolutionópeaceful or otherwiseóof events on the Korean peninsula, U.S. Army presence will be almost entirely withdrawn from areas west of Hawaii. Such a situation poses significant questions:<p>

<li>	What is the level of U.S. forward-deployed forces 
	that insures stability in the Asia-Pacific region? 

 <li>	At what point will the Japanese public believe the United States no longer has the will to defend them and as a consequence begin to significantly increase their defense spending? 

 <li>	What is the level and force mix below which a unified Korea might believe Japan will rearm?

 <li>	What is the minimum level of commitment below which the countries of East Asia might believe they had better make security accommodations with China rather than with the United States? 

Whether the answers to these questions include a Marine division in Okinawa is unclearóperhaps next year's Bottom Up Review, BUR 2, will provide clues. What is certain is that the core of America's continuing presence in Asia must be its air and naval forcesóthese are the equities that need to be protected over the long term. <p>

Some experts believe that events in Korea are beginning to move toward the denouement of the reunification issue, and that the process could in fact proceed rapidly. Others, such as Pacific Forum CSIS President James Kelly, believe that even a North Korea near starvation may survive for many years and continue to pose serious dangers. Both Kelly and Patterson agree that a unified Korea, awash in pride and nationalism, will urge the withdrawal of U.S. ground forcesóat which point, it would likely be too late to begin discussions on regional force structures.  The time to reevaluate U.S. military presence in Asia is nowówhile the region is relatively stable, China's military is unmodernized, and U.S. influence remains high. Intensive bilateral discussions with our allies should parallel American internal deliberations. Southeast Asian countries need to be engaged and their views listened to. China must be consulted.<p>

Former Pentagon Assistant Secretary Richard Armitage notes that governments are already beginning to recalibrate their security strategies in anticipation a waning U.S. commitment. The United States must counter thisónot by outlining specific force numbers that are indefensible over the long haul, but by initiating a strategic dialogue that demonstrates our long-term commitment.
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 10/4/96</i>

