<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 153,                        

                      
March 15, 1996</h4>

<h1>The Changing Nature of Middle East Security</h1>
         
<h3>Enter the demographics factor . . .</h3>
 
Population growth is the ticking time bomb in the Middle East and North Africa.  Given the region's current growth rate, its governments cannot afford to rank demographics as a low priority.  <I>Anthony Cordesman, codirector of Middle East Studies at CSIS</I>, emphasizes that for the governments to succeed in social and economic reforms, they must take measures to reverse the region's present demographic trends.<P>  

The chart below indicates the severity of the current demographic trends in the Middle East/North African region.  At its present rate, the population of the region will double every 26-29 years compared with every 42 years for the world as a whole and 162 years for advanced developed nations.  
Another significant aspect of this demographic trend is the extremely young population of the region.  About 43-45% of the population is 14 years of age or younger versus 31.6% for the world and 22% for developed countries like the United States.  The region's infrastructure, already overburdened, will not be able to accommodate the growing young population.  Cordesman notes that the region's governments cannot afford to effectively educate their citizens.  If current trends continue, the situation will steadily deteriorate and educational standards will inevitably drop.<P>  

The region already suffers from major unemployment problems, and the burgeoning young population will only exacerbate them.  By World Bank definition, direct unemployment in the region is about 12%.  Youth direct unemployment is at least twice as high, and disguised 

unemployment is often 40% of young males leaving school.  Cordesman notes that many young men in the Middle East have never held a job that really contributes to their nation's productivity and have no hope of getting one. <P> 

Further Economic Decline.  "Population pressures have already made the Middle East and North Africa an ëundeveloping region,'" Cordesman adds.  The average real per capita income dropped by nearly 25% during 1980-1993, and the once "oil rich" Gulf states saw a drop of over 40% during the period because of a combination of population growth and low oil prices. Other economic problems plague the Middle East and North Africa as well.  During 1980-1991, for instance, the region experienced a nearly 3% average annual decline in real per capita GDP -- the worst decline of any region of the world.  It was also the only region that experienced a drop in productivity (6% cumulative drop) over the 30-year period 1960-1990.  (East and South Asia gained 54%, the OECD gained 48%, even Latin America gained 12%.) <P> 

<B>Solutions?</B><BR>  A strategy that focuses solely on stimulating economic growth to accommodate the surge in population is neither adequate nor feasible.  Even the governments of the most wealthy Gulf oil exporting states can no longer afford to subsidize, provide non-jobs, or offer welfare to their citizens. <P> 

Cordesman argues that governments must include demographic reforms in their economic and social programs.  "They need to reduce annual population growth rates to levels of 2% or less.  They need to restructure their educational systems in order to train their youth effectively to compete in a regional and world market.  They need to stop wasting resources on subsidized, useless state jobs and focus instead on maximizing the growth of real jobs in the private sector." <P>

<B>Implications for Regional Security.</B><BR>  The demographic boom is adversely affecting development in the region and widening the gap between rich and poor.  The situation, Cordesman warns, "is an explosive recipe for the growth of political extremism.  There will be no long-term development or security in the region if it continues to ignore demographic trends."   
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 3/28/95</i>

