<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 158,                        

June 12, 1996</h4>

<h1>Turkey's Convulsion's</h1>
         
<h3>Ankara's political misfortunes continue . . .</h3>
 
Even the forces -- big business, the media, and the military establishment -- that made the initial agreement between Turkey's two main center-right parties possible after the inconclusive December elections were unable to prevent the inevitable collapse of the Motherland/True Path partnership.  On June 7, Mesut Yilmaz, the prime minister of the coalition government, resigned.  For the third time in the past nine months, Turkey's bickering political leaders find themselves incapable of establishing stability in the government.  Instead, they are scrambling to construct alignments and demonstrate their own dominance on the political scene.<P>  

The most vocal contender, once again, is Necmettin Erbakan, the leader of the Islamist Welfare Party (or Refah Party), who is currently conducting consultations to form the next government.  But Bulent Aliriza, CSIS Senior Associate in Turkish Studies, argues that the real action is taking place behind the scenes within the True Path and Motherland parties, despite Erbakan's visible attempts and the fact that Welfare holds the most seats in parliament (158 out of 550). <P> 

<B>Where to, Tansu?</B><BR>
The personal political predicament of Tansu Ciller, Turkey's prime minister between June 1993 and March 1996, continues to shape Turkish politics.  The votes cast last month in the Turkish National Assembly to investigate allegations in the so-called "Tedas" and "Tofas" cases, relating to the activities of Ciller during her tenure as prime minister, along with her personal finances, have effectively undermined her position as party leader.  Ciller retaliated against Yilmaz's exploitation of her problems by effectively scuttling the coalition. <P> 

Although True Path followed Tansu Ciller out of the coalition with Motherland, the question remains whether the party would follow her into an alternative partnership with the Welfare party.  Motherland and the two center-left parties have already indicated their unwillingness to enter into a coalition with Welfare.  True Path's position, however, is not so clear.<P>  

True Path party leaders, including Foreign Minister Emre Gonensay, oppose Ciller's stated willingness to consider a deal with Welfare.  They see it as a brazen negation of her declared secular principles to save her political skin, and have already stated that they will not serve with her should she decide to join forces with Welfare after her discussions with Erbakan scheduled for this Friday.<P>  


"It is looking more likely than ever that Ciller will begin to lose her iron grip over the True Path party," states Aliriza.  "Her previously impotent opponents may now be in a position to mount a successful challenge, especially after the disastrous showing by the True Path party in the municipal elections on June 2."  While the Welfare party polled over 34% of the vote and Motherland picked up 25%, the True Path vote was a desultory 12%.<P>

<B>Turkey's Paralysis</B><BR>
As a result of the ongoing political crisis, Ankara continues to be in a state of great uncertainty.  Important decisions relating to the economy are simply being put off.  A recent delegation from the IMF could not engage the officials they met in Ankara in serious dialogue.  The IMF team has produced an interim report on the situation in Turkey in which they warn of an imminent economic crisis.  In fact, Turkey is so preoccupied with its political crisis that even a public warning by the head of Standard and Poor's credit rating agency that Turkey's rating might soon be reduced failed to generate much interest.<P>

Turkish foreign policy is also in the doldrums.  Although Foreign Minister Gonensay was recently in Washington for talks, it is clear that Turkey will not be able to tackle its foreign policy agenda in earnest until its political crisis is resolved.<P> 

<B>In Search of a Third Candidate</B><BR>
If Welfare fails to form the next government, as Aliriza predicts, the most likely outcome will be intense pressure on both Ciller and Yilmaz that will force them to step aside and allow a third candidate to lead a coalition of True Path and Motherland successfully.  The two parties -- essentially ideological soulmates -- have been separated by the bitter personality clash between their current leaders.  Aliriza believes that the candidate best suited to fill the leadership vacuum may be former Speaker Ismet Sezgin, who was in Washington last Friday meeting with U.S. officials. <P> 

Should the current situation deteriorate to the point where new elections are unavoidable, an outright Welfare victory is likely.  The military establishment and the rest of the Turkish elite are genuinely concerned about such an outcome.  Aliriza warns that such a development would almost inevitably provoke a crisis for the regime itself.   
<p><hr>

