<head>
<title>CSIS Values</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<p align="center"><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3missio.gif"></p>
<h1>What are CSIS values?  What does it believe?
</h1>
     
<p>The work of CSIS is based on five overriding values, which have 

been at the core of the 
Center since it was established over three decades ago:</p>
<ol type="1">

<li>The need to "strengthen America" internally in order to be 
strong internationally.  
The responsibility of the United States to exercise and sustain 
global leadership requires us 
to put our domestic house in order.

<li>The need to build leaders of character across the globe.  This 

ranges from providing 
opportunities to young student-interns at CSIS itself to assisting 

public policy leaders at the 
highest levels of government around the world.

<li>The application of private-sector creativity to the solution 
of public policy problems.


<li>A commitment to representative government, pluralistic 
societies, and open markets.

<li>A "strategic" approach.  Long-range and anticipatory thinking 
is essential to 
addressing the challenges to leaders worldwide.</ol>

<UL>
<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission1.html">What is CSIS? </A>

<li><a href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission2.html">What is the mission of CSIS?</a>



<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission3.html">How does CSIS implement this 
vision?</A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission4.html">What are
CSIS values?  What does it believe? </A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission5.html">What constituencies
does CSIS serve? </A>

<LI><A href="http://www.csis.org/html/mission6.html">What
criteria does CSIS have for selecting
projects? </A></UL>



