<html><TITLE>Simon Serfaty</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG border=0 align=right hspace=10 vspace=5 
SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/5serfaty.gif"><H2><B>SIMON SERFATY</B></H2>
Director<BR>
European Studies<P>
Office: (202) 887-0200<HR>

Expertise:  European security and politics; the European Union and U.S.-EU relations; 		French politics and foreign policy; U.S. foreign policy during and after the cold war, with special emphasis on the European continent.
<HR>

Simon Serfaty directed the Johns Hopkins Foreign Policy Institute in Washington, D.C., from 1984 to 1992.  During his 20-year association with the Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies (SAIS), where he was a research professor in U.S. foreign policy, he served as director of the SAIS Center of European Studies in Bologna, Italy (1972-1976).  In 1993, he was named professor of international politics at Old Dominion University in Norfolk, Virginia.  Dr. Serfaty is the author, coauthor, and editor of 15 books, including Taking Europe Seriously (1992).  His articles have appeared in most leading professional journals in the United States and many countries abroad.  He has been a guest lecturer in about 40 different countries in Europe, Africa, and Asia and serves on the editorial board of GÈopolitique (France).  Dr. Serfaty holds a Ph.D. in political science from the Johns Hopkins University and has taught at the University of California at Los Angeles and the University of Virginia.  He speaks French fluently.<HR>

