<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 155,                        

April 5, 1996</h4>

<h1>Nuclear Hardball</h1>
         
<h3>Addressing nuclear safety issues in the former Soviet Union . . .</h3>
 
Ten years after the infamous Chernobyl disaster of April 26, 1986, the state of nuclear safety in the former Soviet Union can be characterized by the Lespe, a ship that has long been anchored off Murmansk on Russia's Kola Peninsula, loaded with large quantities of high-grade nuclear waste.  It is an accident waiting to happen.<P>

The sad fact, says Bob Ebel, director of the Energy and National Security Program at CSIS, is that a decade after the Chernobyl meltdown released vast amounts of radioactivity, the situation in the former Soviet Union is even more dangerous.  Fifteen Chernobyl-style reactors, without containment structures, continue to operate in Russia, Ukraine, and Lithuania.  What is more, the lack of financial resources in those states is leading to a breakdown in controls over nuclear materials and to reduced safety standards throughout the industry.  There is also the ubiquitous threat that some disgruntled nuclear employee will succeed in selling weapons-grade nuclear material to a rogue state or terrorist group.<P>

Despite all the publicity and policy attention of past 10 years, why has the situation been allowed to deteriorate?  Part of the answer is a dangerous game of nuclear hardball that Russia and Ukraine are playing with the West--and the G-7 in particular.  The next round is the G-7 meeting later this month.<P>

<I>Ukraine and the G-7</I>:  At the top of the G-7 list of priorities is the closure of the two operating reactors at the Chernobyl plant by the year 2000.  For the Ukrainian government, however, the political and social costs of replacing jobs and energy, in addition to repairing the leaking sarcophagus encasing the destroyed reactor No. 4, are prohibitive.  As a result, progress years after the disaster has been negligible. <P> 

Recognizing its leverage over the West (and assured of Western financial commitment to this effort), Ukraine has continued to raise the estimated costs for closing Chernobyl, lifting the price tag on numerous occasions to account for the creation of new jobs and the resettlement of workers as well as the loss in net profits over the lifetime of the reactor.  "Clearly, Ukraine is playing hardball with the West," notes Ebel.  
The reason is that Ukraine has its back to the wall.  To substitute for lost production, it would have to rely on natural gas or oil that it does not have.  And the Kiev government would have to weather the social impact associated with displacing the 6,000 Chernobyl employees.<P>

<I>Enter Moscow</I>:  Russia is also playing the game.  The Russian Ministry of Atomic Energy, experiencing low demand for new reactors within its own borders, is vigorously attempting to export its technology.  The West's concern is that the Russians, desperate to make profits, are indiscriminate in selling their nuclear energy technology.  This is manifest in Russia's deal with Iran--a deal that the United States unsuccessfully attempted to stop.  At present, Russia is negotiating an agreement with Cuba to finish the nuclear plant at Juragua over the next five years.<P>

Ebel warns that potential Russian deals to build reactors in China, India, North Korea, and possibly Pakistan, will inevitably result in confrontations between Moscow and Washington. <P>

<I>Policy Options</I>: In its most recent report, the CSIS Congressional Study Group on Nuclear Energy Safety Challenges in the Former Soviet Union determined that the traditional approach taken by the West in dealing with nuclear safety issues has been unsuccessful.  The Group recommends that the G-7 take a more active leadership role in the financing of the rescue efforts because the primary cause of the deteriorating safety is attributable to lack of funds for maintenance and safety upgrades.<P> 
<B>
Four Recommended Approaches to Financing:</B>
 	<UL>
<LI>Add surcharges to the monthly electricity bills of consumers in the EU and G-7 countries;

<LI> 	Use the Russian stockpile of refined uranium as a guarantor for loans;

<LI> 	Construct compensating generating capacities by Western companies on a "build-operate-transfer" basis; and

<LI> 	At the direction of the G-7, let the World Bank finance efforts such as electricity-generating projects that would allow the phaseout of the most 
antiquated power plants. </UL> 

Although the West currently lacks the political will to finance the effort to upgrade and eventually shut down all unsafe nuclear reactors in the former Soviet Union, the alternatives--ignoring the dangers or expecting the local governments to rectify them without help--are not feasible.<P>

Surely, says Ebel, it is not too costly for the citizens of the more industrially developed nations to pay a monthly surcharge equivalent to the price of two beers to ensure the safety of future generations.  What will it take for the West to realize the severity and urgency of the problem?  Perhaps another Chernobyl?  If the West does nothing to improve the safety of the plants in the former Soviet Union, the chances of another Chernobyl in this decade are quite good.  In fact, some experts place the odds at one in six.  Accidents, like the Lespe, are waiting to happen.   
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 3/28/95</i>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/cgi-bin/imagemap/button"><p align="center"><IMG width=515 
height=35 border=0 SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/button.gif" ISMAP></p></a>
</body>
