	Author: Guild Copeland
	Date: 	7/15/95
-->
<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=149 
height=179 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 159,                        

June 26, 1996</h4>

<h1>Debate in New Delhi</h1>
         
<h3>Will the United Front pursue economic reform?</h3>

 Before the May elections in India, the government of P.V. Narasimha Rao had undertaken economic liberalization that caught the attention of observers across the world. The fiscal and monetary reform pulled India back from the brink of a financial collaps
e in 1991 and moved the country toward a free-market economy.  The results were impressive.  In five years, annual foreign direct investment levels surged from $68 million to $2 billion, foreign portfolio investment increased, foreign reserves skyrocketed
 from $1 billion to $17.5 billion, and real GDP growth climbed from less than 1 percent to an unprecedented 6.2 percent last year.  Then Rao and his Congress party were handed the worst defeat in the party's history.  The key question now is whether econo
mic liberalization in India left with the Rao government.  The answer, says Ambassador William Clark, former U.S. ambassador to India and currently CSIS senior adviser on Asia, is a qualified no: the coalition government will not reverse reforms, but the 
process will move more slowly.<P>

<B>Whither Reform?</B><BR>
The fate of liberalization is in the hands of the coalition of 14 disparate regional, caste-based, and socialist parties that now rules India.  This United Front government, headed by Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda from the southern state of Karnataka, sm
oothly passed the parliamentary vote of confidence on June 12.  It was supported, but not joined, by the Congress party, which holds command of 141 seats in parliament despite its electoral losses.<P>

The ascendance of a left-leaning coalition initially caused business leaders to fear that the new government would turn back reform.  H.D. Gowda's selection of P. Chidambaram, a past architect of the Congress reform program, as finance minister largely al
leviated those fears.  Yet although it does not appear ready to undo reforms, the new government may not be able to take them to the next level.  A recently ratified Common Approach Minimum Program makes promises with contradictory implications.  On the o
ne hand, it calls for

 <UL><LI>a GDP growth rate of 7 percent annually over the next decade, up from 6.2 percent last year;

 	<LI>an increase in foreign direct investment from a record $2 billion last year to $10 billion in the coming year; and

 	<LI>a reduction of the public debt to less than 4 percent of GDP, down from 5.9 percent last year.</UL>




Yet, on the other hand, the United Front plans to encourage foreign investment only in the high-priority areas of infrastructure and technology, not in consumer goods.  In
addition, the government will limit privatization of state sectors and do little to reform the exit policy, which would make it easier to hire and fire public sector employees.  The prior Congress government also avoided these sensitive areas.  And the Un
ited Front, with its many lower-caste and poorer constituents, promises to spend more on anti-poverty measures, rural and social infrastructure, and education -- despite the fact that interest payments on public debt already consume about 45 percent of th
e central government's revenue.<P>

The government's budget, to be unveiled in late July, will spell out exactly how the United Front intends to resolve these contradictions.  On Monday, June 17, Finance Minister Chidambaram announced large government spending cuts geared toward curbing the
 fiscal deficit, including a cap on government hiring.  After leftist coalition parties threatened to withdraw their support, Chidambaram reassured them that current employees would not lose their jobs or see their wages frozen.<P>

Meanwhile, pressures from the regional parties that constitute one-third of the coalition may force the United Front government to increase spending on the state level, for example, by bailing out the nearly bankrupt southern state of Andhra Pradesh.  At 
the same time, Ambassador Clark believes that there may be advantages in India's move toward a more federal system: the devolution of authority envisioned, including the decentralization of administrative, political, and economic powers, should give state
s greater ability to raise revenue and compete for foreign investment.<P>

<B>High-Wire Act in New Delhi</B><BR>
Not only do the divergent interests and personalities among its members threaten to fracture the United Front, but the power held by Rao, who still heads the Congress party, can also make life difficult for Gowda.  Rao still commands enough seats to make 
political demands on the United Front; the opposition has already accused Gowda of soft-peddling corruption charges against Rao in order to retain Congress support.  With Congress at its back, and the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party waiting in the wings
 for another chance at power, the United Front faces a tricky political balancing act in the coming months. 
<p><hr>

<i>File Created: 7/15/96</i>

