<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left>        <b>Number 167,

November 4, 1996</b><hr>

<h1>General Elections in Japan</h1>

<h3>Reading between the lines . . . 
</h3>

What do the results of the October 20 general election in Japan signify?  For the third consecutive year, voter turnout was at a record low (59%), reflecting deep popular dissatisfaction with the recent pattern of coalition politics and voter disenchantment with the newer reform parties.  Those who did vote reverted to supporting the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) expanding the position of the LDP by 28 seats, from 211 to 239.  On the other hand, the New Frontier Party challenge to the LDP backfired, leaving the party with four fewer seats than before.  The LDP, however, is still short of an absolute majority in the 500-seat Diet and is now struggling to form another coalition.<p>

<b>More of the same?</b>  Yes and no.  Yes, the election was indeed a vote for the status quo (the LDP), according to CSIS Japan Chairholder William Breer.  And yes, the majority of voters continued to support moderate conservative politicians.  But there are key differences that deserve attention, says Breer:<p>

 <li>	First, the elections represent continuity.  It is highly likely that Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto will be reappointed on November 7.  That in itself is significant because it will be the first time in three years that a prime minister has served for more than a few months.  This has important implications for a range of issues important to the United States, including foreign affairs and defense policies.<p>

 <li>	Second, the election took place in the context of more general political change that marked a turning point in the Japanese electoral system.  The new electoral system, which combines a "winner-take-all," single seat contest with proportional representation in the Diet, is aimed at discouraging lavish campaigns and internal party conflicts.  Although the new system did not push Japanese politics as far toward an American two-party structure as some observers had hoped, it succeeded in producing increased representation for Japan's urban population.<p>

 <li>	Third, freed of the factional ties that cemented relationships in the past, we are likely to see a more fluid situation in the future while politicians sort themselves out more along party lines. </ul><p>

<b>Impact on administrative reform?</b>  Although virtually every party highlighted the need for administrative reform during the campaign, the election results do not reveal a public mandate to peel the layers of the Japanese bureaucratic onion.  Breer maintains that world economic conditionsónot Japanese politicsóare the key factor driving economic and administrative reform and deregulation.  To respond to those changing world conditions, however, politicians will ultimately need to wrest control of decision-making from the powerful bureaucracy.  <p>

<b>Implications for U.S.-Japan relations:</b>   The elections also signify a "steady-as-she-goes" position in relations with the United States.  Despite the potential for continued friction over trade issues, Breer asserts that prospects for favorable U.S.-Japan cooperation on a number of issues are good.  The goodwill on both sides, coupled with the personal relations that have developed between U.S. and Japanese leaders, suggests that the two countries will be able to build on the summit discussions held last April on their security relationship and security contingencies in East Asia.                                         
<p><hr>

