<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="phalanx">Breaking the Phalanx: A New Design for Landpower in the 21st Century</a></h3>
Douglas A. Macgregor<br>
Foreword by Donald Kagan<p>
This work proposes nothing less than the reorganization of America's ground forces on  strategic, operational, and tactical levels. Central to the proposal is the simple thesis that the U.S. Army must take control of its future by exploiting the emerging revolution in military affairs. The analysis argues that a new Army warfighting organization will not only be more deployable and effective in joint operations; reorganized information-age ground forces will be significantly less expensive to operate, maintain, and modernize than the Army's current Cold War division-based organization. It is not enough to rely on an infusion of new, expensive technology into the U.S. defense establishment to preserve U.S. strategic dominance in the next century; the United States must reform and reorganize its ground forces at all levels to meet the demands of the information age.<p>
<i>Copublished book/Praeger	304 pp.	1997<br>
ISBN	0-275-95794-2 (pb)	    $24.95<br>
         	0-275-95793-4 (hb)	$65.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="korea">Change and Challenge on the Korean Peninsula: Developments, Trends, and Issues</a></h3>
Jae H. Ku and Tae Hwan Ok, editors
Contributors: Dong-bok Lee, Michael Mazarr, Tae Hwan Ok, and William J. Taylor Jr.
This volume examines developments  since the signing of the Agreed Framework between the United States and North Korea in 1994.  It provides an overview of relations between South Korea and North Korea; perspectives on the future of North Korea; the impact of regional and global developments on the Korean peninsula; and challenges and opportunities in U.S.-South Korean relations.<p>
<i>Asian Studies Report	81 pp. 	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-342-4		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="china">China's Conventional Military Capabilities, 1994-2004:
An Assessment</a></h3>
John Caldwell<p>
<i>CSIS Report	28 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-257-6 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="defconv">Critical Issues in Defense
Conversion</a></h3>
<b>A Consensus Report of the Senior Group on Defense Conversion</b><p>
Harold Brown, project chairman<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a> and Debra van Opstal, project directors<p>
<i>Panel Report 	51 pp.	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-266-5 		$21.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="def1990">Defense in the Late 1990s: Avoiding the Train Wreck</a></h3>
Don M. Snider, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4cambone.html">Stephen A. Cambone</a>, project directors<p>
Based on the work of a December 1994 conference in Washington, D.C., this report examines the potential for a "train wreck" in defense: the endangering of future U.S. capabilities by the current overcommitment of U.S. military forces and by the failure to provide a strategy for reshaping the military to meet future requirements. The authors examine the short- and long-term options facing defense planners and propose alternatives for the future.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	25 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-316-5 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="goc">Global Organized Crime: The New Empire of Evil</a></h3>
Frank J. Cilluffo and Linnea P. Raine, editors<br>
Contributors: <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4abshire.html">David M. Abshire</a>, Jack A. Blum, Scott Charney, James Christy, Arnaud de Borchgrave, Louis J. Freeh, L. Dain Gary, Peter Grinenko, Carol Boyd Hallett, David A. Kay, Robert H. Kupperman, Patrick Leahy, Rensselaer Lee, William R. McLucas, Ronald D. Murphy, Donn B. Parker, Erik Peterson, Robert H. Rasor, Oliver Revell, Claire Sterling, David C. Veness, William H. Webster, R. James Woolsey<p>
Society is facing an entirely new challenge that cuts across national security, economic security, law enforcement, intelligence, and corporate security_global organized crime. This CSIS report has identified some of the dimensions of the problem: information superhighway vulnerability, counterfeiting of tender and credit cards, money laundering, trade in fissionable materials, drug trafficking and terrorism, Russian organized crime, and international gang activity. Unless we understand the nature and scope of today's problems, we cannot begin to counteract them.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	185 pp.	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-312-2		$24.95</i>



<h3><a name="infosec">Information Revolution and International Security</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a> and C. Edward
Peartree, editors<br>
Contributors: Lawrence E. Blume, James Der Derian, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4henry.html">Ryan Henry</a>, David Ronfeldt, James N. Rosenau, Michael Vlahos, M. Mitchell Waldrop<p>
This companion volume to The Information Revolution and National Security brings together a diverse set of experts from the business, military, government, and academic communities to consider the implications of new information technologies for international security. The focus is not so much on security in the strict military sense as it is on the global social, economic, and political changes occurring because of new information technologies and their potential effects on the international security environment_for example, the effects of speed and global networks on the conduct of diplomacy as well as conflict.  This provocative, informed exploration will be of interest to policymakers, legislators, and others involved with the global security issues accompanying this revolution.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-299-1</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="infonatlsec">The Information Revolution and National Security</a>
: Dimensions and Directions</h3>
Stuart J.D. Schwartzstein, editor<br>
Foreword by Adm. William A. Owens<br>
Contributors: C. Kenneth Allard, John Arquilla, Jeffrey R. Cooper,  James Der Derian, James B. Ferguson, <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4goure.html">Daniel GourÈ</a>, Ahmed S. Hashim, Alfred A. Jones, Brian Kahin, Michael R. Nelson, Admiral William A. Owens, George E. Pickett Jr., John W. Rendon Jr., David Ronfeldt, Larry Seaquist, Martin Shubik, Michael Vlahos, R. James Woolsey and Henrikas Yushkiavitshus <p>
Information and communications technologies are having a profound impact in a number of ways, domestically and globally, including how national security is maintained and how war is waged. There are also implications for civil liberties and how we, as a society, deal with new kinds of conflict. The issues that are raised are both far-ranging and complex.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	c. 296 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-288-6		$25.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="infowar">Information Warfare, Cyberterrorism, and Information Assurance</a></h3>
<b>A Report from the CSIS Global Organized Crime Task Force</b><p>
William H. Webster, project chair<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, project director<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, project codirectors<br>
Pat Gallagher, Task Force director and editor<br>
Frank J. Cilluffo, Task Force chairman and editor<p>
The United States is vulnerable to information warfare attacks and operations.  The capability to deny, disrupt, destroy, or steal information and systems is widely available and low in cost.  A dedicated adversary could seriously jeopardize our national and economic security as our dependence on information infrastructures continues to grow exponentially.  Composed of senior U.S. government officials and private-sector experts, the task force identifies the most critical infrastructures, assesses the threats to and vulnerabilities of these infrastructures, and makes recommendations on how best to mitigate the risks.<p>
<i>CSIS Report      c. 50 pp.		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-295-9		$16.95 Est.</i>

<h3><a name="nordic">Nordic-Baltic Security:
An International Perspective</a></h3>
Arne Olav Brundtland and Don M. Snider, editors<br>
Contributors: Clive Archer, Stephen A. Cambone, Helmut Hubel, Atis Lejins, Sergei Oznobistchev, Trivimi Velliste<p>
<i>Panel Report	132 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-256-8 		$16.95
</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="nukeblack">The Nuclear Black Market</a></h3>
<b>An Assessment of the CSIS Global Organized Crime Task Force on the Nuclear Black Market</b><p>
William H. Webster, project chair<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, project director<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, project codirectors<br>
Pat Gallagher, Task Force director and editor<br>
Frank Cilluffo, project coordinator<br>
Sarah A. Mullen, Task Force Chair, and Linnea P. Raine, Task Force executive secretary, editors<p>
Part of an effort projected to last two years, this assessment focuses on the supply, illicit trafficking, and demand for nuclear weapons and weapons-usable uranium and plutonium from the former Soviet Union. It sets forth some recommendations for mitigating the black market threat.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	49 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-287-8		$16.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="virtualnuke">Nuclear Weapons in a Transformed World: The Challenge of Virtual Arsenals</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4mazarr.html">Michael J. Mazarr</a>, editor<p>
This edited volume brings together more than a dozen of the world's most prominent arms control experts to assess a bold emerging concept in nuclear arms control:  virtual nuclear arsenals (VNAs).  In recent years, many respected U.S. former officials and academics have suggested that the United States would be safer in a post-Cold War world of far fewer or no nuclear weapons.  This concept tests the feasibility of such radical nuclear end-states by examining whether the dismantling of nuclear weapons and retention of their components, rather than full disarmament as traditionally understood, would achieve many of the advantages of a zero-nuclear-weapon world while avoiding some of its pitfalls.  Contributors offer a variety of answers to that question, some skeptical and some encouraging.  By promoting a detailed analysis of a specific policy option, this volume constitutes perhaps the most rigorous discussion of nuclear abolition yet published.<p>
<i>Copublished Book/St. Martin's	c. 359 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-312-162-02-2	$45.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="order">Order and Disorder after the Cold War</a></h3>
Brad Roberts, editor<br>
Contributors: JosÈ E. Alvarez, Barry M. Blechman, Lincoln P. Bloomfield, Shahram Chubin, James C. Clad, Alberto R. Coll, James R. Golden, Gerrit W. Gong, Penelope Hartland-Thunberg, Max Jakobson, Ryuzaburo Kaku, Zalmay Khalilzad, Joseph LaPalombara, Kishore Mahbubani, Marc Dean Millot, Erik R. Peterson, Bruce D. Porter, Ernest H. Preeg, John Gerard Ruggie, Paul W. Schroeder, Gerald Segal, Peter J. Spiro, John Stremlau, Karin von Hippel, Murray Weidenbaum, George Weigel, Thomas G. Weiss, Phil Williams<p>
This volume reviews the changing roles of the major powers, analyzes new challenges to international order, and concludes with a speculative assessment of the emerging world order.<p>
<i>Copublished Book/MIT Press	449 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-262-680882 		$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="usjapsec">Restructuring the U.S.-Japan Security Relationship</a></h3>
Richard Douglas, editor<p>
Highlighted by the views of Mitsubishi CEO Ben Makihara and former assistant secretary of defense Carl Ford, this book examines the security challenges facing the world (notably the growing saliency of China and the volatile Korean peninsula) and the role the U.S.-Japan security relationship might play in confronting them. The alliance pressures caused by economic disputes, Japan's unique prohibition on collective self-defense, and the significant U.S. base presence in Japan are explored by an expert group with first-hand, real-world experience in managing this vital security relationship.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-294-0</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="far">Road Map for Federal Acquisition (FAR) Reform</a></h3>
Debra van Opstal<p>
The federal procurement system is so complex that it defies simple reform. Yet reform of that system is an essential element in the success of many urgent national initiatives. The action agendas described in detail in this report offer solutions to current process problems and seek to address the greater challenge of structuring a viable procurement system for the twenty-first century.<p>
<i>Panel Report	74 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-320-3 		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="roc">Russian Organized Crime</a></h3>
<b>A Report from the Global Organized Crime Task Force</b><p>
William H. Webster, project chair<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, project director<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, project codirectors<br>
Pat Gallagher, Task Force director and editor<br>
Frank J. Cilluffo, Task Force chairman and editor<p>
Russian organized crime constitutes a direct threat to the national security interests of the United States by fostering instability in a nuclear-armed power.  Left unchecked, Russia is in jeopardy of becoming a criminal syndicalist state under the control of corrupt government bureaucrats, politicians, quasi-businessmen, and criminals.  Composed of senior-level U.S. government representatives and private-sector experts, the task force assesses the breadth and depth of Russian organized crime and corruption, addresses current U.S. policy, and makes recommendations on how  best to confront these challenges.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	c. 50 pp.	Forthcoming <br>
ISBN 0-89206-293-2	$16.95 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nukepeace">Toward a Nuclear Peace: The Future of Nuclear Weapons in U.S. Foreign and Defense Policy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4mazarr.html">Michael J. Mazarr</a> and Alexander Lennon, editors<br>
Contributors: William Arkin, Hans Binnendijk, Ivo Daalder, Daniel Ellsberg, Steve Fetter, Lawrence Freedman, Edward A. Kolodziej, Michael Mazarr, Michael Nacht, Sergei Rogov, Don M. Snider<p>
<i>Copublished Book/St. Martins	227 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-312-104-049	 	$39.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="trilateral">Trilateral Forum on North Pacific Security</a></h3>
Vladlen A. Martynov, Nobuo Matsunaga, and Paul D. Wolfowitz, project cochairs<br>
Contributors: Sergei Blagovolin, Masashi Nishihara, Stephen Sestanovich<p>
The Forum was established in 1993 by CSIS, the Japan Institute of International Affairs, and the Russian Institute of World Economy and International Relations to foster candid discussion of regional and international security issues among private experts and policymakers. The Forum sessions have served to advance understanding of national perspectives on a variety of proposals to improve mutual confidence_particularly in the realms of military transparency and enhanced contacts. This report expresses the joint conviction that a trilateral framework can improve bilateral relations among the three nations and promote broader stability.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	27 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-279-7 		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="ukraine">Ukrainian Security Policy</a></h3>
Taras Kuzio<p>
The economic crisis and mismanagement that engulfed Ukraine during 1993-1994 led many in the West and among Ukraine's neighbors to question the country's long-term viability as an independent state. Yet in 1995, Ukraine entered a new era reflecting its importance as a linchpin of regional security and stability in Europe. This study discusses Ukrainian security policies and their implications for Western policy. It makes a compelling case for greater Western aid and political support for Ukrainian independence and territorial integrity.<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger	168 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-275-95385-8 (pb)	$14.95<br>
	0-275-95384-X (hb) 	$49.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="civmil">U.S. Civil-Military Relations: In Crisis or Transition?</a></h3>
Don M. Snider and Miranda A. Carlton-Carew, editors<br>
Contributors: Paul Bracken, Miranda A. Carlton-Carew, Stephen J. Cimbala, Michael C. Desch, Mark J. Eitelberg, Peter D. Feaver, Curtis L. Gilroy, Douglas Johnson, Roger D. Little, James F. McIsaac, Steven Metz, David R. Segal, Don M. Snider, Naomi Verdugo<p>
The relationship between the U.S. military and civil society is undergoing rapid changes_the military because of its altered role and rapid downsizing; society because of the cumulative effects of changes in individual values, in familial structures, and in political priorities for the use of resources, including military power.  Leading academics, military professionals, and policy analysts address the traditional approaches and emphasize the need to develop new concepts.<p>

"This is an important book and essential reading for those dealing with military issues." - American Political Science Review<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	240 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-305-X 		$18.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="prolif">Weapons Proliferation in the 1990s</a></h3>
Brad Roberts, editor<br>
Contributors: Charles T. Allan, Gary K. Bertsch, Julio C. Carasales, Shahram Chubin, Avner Cohen, Richard T. Cupitt, Jonathan Dean, Lewis A. Dunn, Patrick J. Garrity, Paul R.S. Gebhard, Gary L. Guertner, Aaron Karp, David A. Kay, Pauline Kerr, Edward J. Laurance, Andrew Mack, Marvin Miller, Roger C. Molander, Michael Moodie, Harald M¸ller, Stephanie G. Neuman, Graham S. Pearson, George H. Quester, George Rathjens, John R. Redick, Mitchell Reiss, Brad Roberts, Paul W. Schroeder, Henry D. Sokolski, Peter A. Wilson, Paulo S. Wrobel, Victor A. Utgoff<p>
The proliferation of weapons of mass destruction has emerged as a major topic of international security in the post-Cold War world. This volume offers fresh thinking about the proliferation subject and the changing policy agenda.  It describes the changing nature of the problem in the 1990s, discusses new trends in nonproliferation and counterproliferation policy, identifies new arms control challenges at the regional and global levels, and concludes with a discussion of the global politics of proliferation.<p>

"Robert's book of essays, taken from The Washington Quarterly, is superior." - Foreign Affairs<p>
<i>Copublished Book/MIT Press	473 pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-262-680866 		$18.00</i>



</td></tr></table>

