<td valign=top>

<h3><a name="centasia">Central Asia since Independence</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hunter.html">Shireen T. Hunter</a><p>
Like all other post-Soviet societies, after becoming independent the Central Asian countries have faced a host of problems and challenges related to the process of nation building. These challenges have ranged from the need to find an alternative value system to the reinvigoration and reform of their badly sagging economies. To these challenges must be added that of forging new relations among themselves, with their immediate neighbors, and with the rest of the world.<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger Publishers	220 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-275-95539-7 (pb)	$18.95<br>
	0-275-95538-9 (hb)	$55.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="chernobyl">Chernobyl and Its Aftermath:  A Chronology of Events</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a><p>
Despite the tragedy of Chernobyl, comparatively little has been done, either by the former <i>Soviet Union or by the West, to minimize if not eliminate another accident.<p>
CSIS Report	43 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-302-5 		$9.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="russia">Energy Choices in Russia</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a><p>
"Ebel concentrates primarily on oil, his specialty and the foundation stone of the Russian energy economy. He also covers natural gas, another important export fuel, as well as coal, economically unproductive and socially explosive, and nuclear energy, whose growth remains adversely affected by Chernobyl. . . .[This book is] a good vade mecum for those interested in the challenges of the contemporary Russian energy situation." - The Russia Review<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	164 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-248-7 		$16.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="near">Energy Choices in the Near Abroad: The Haves and
Have-nots Face the Future</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a><p>
Of  the 14 republics that make up the "Near Abroad," only three_Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, and Azerbaijan_are rich in oil and natural gas. The others have been almost completely dependent on Russia for their fuel. Russia, with its own energy sector in difficulty, has been cutting back deliveries. The republics with substantial oil and gas resources are challenged to develop them in a timely and responsible fashion. Success will move them into the world of developed nations; failure will bring economic stagnation and political grief. <p>
<i>CSIS Report         c. 350 pp.		Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-271-1		$39.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="nukes">Nuclear Energy Safety Challenges in the Former Soviet Union</a></h3>
<b>A Consensus Report of the CSIS
Congressional Study Group on Nuclear Energy Safety Challenges in the Former
Soviet Union</b><p>
James Schlesinger, chair<br>
Senators Sam Nunn and Richard G. Lugar, Representatives Carlos J. Moorhead and John M. Spratt Jr., cochairs<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4ebel.html">Robert E. Ebel</a>, project director<p>
Fifteen nuclear reactors of the type that exploded at Chernobyl in April 1986 are still operating in Russia, Ukraine, and Lithuania.  The West, concerned about safety of operations, wants these reactors shut down, but the host nations refuse. The electricity these reactors supply is much too important for their economies, so the argument goes. The report defines policy options and procedures to implement those options for the acceptable resolution of the nuclear power safety issues facing the former Soviet Union.<p>
<i>Panel Report	96 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-301-7 		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="postcom">Post-Communist Politics: Democratic Prospects in Russia and Eastern Europe</a></h3>
<b>Creating the Post-Communist Order Series #4</b><p>
Michael McFaul<p>
"The only unsatisfying aspect of this monograph is that there is not more of it. . . .This is an important work because it discusses in clear and concise terms the nature of the revolutions that have occurred in Poland, Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic, and Russia, and the lessons one should draw from them." - Demokratizatsiya<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	151 pp. 	1993<br>
ISBN 0-89206-208-8 		$17.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="rethink">Rethinking Russia's National Interests</a></h3>
Stephen R. Sestanovich, editor<br>
Contributors: Anders ≈slund, Francis Fukuyama, Paul A. Goble, Henry A. Kissinger, Vladimir P. Lukin,  Sergei Rogov, Aleksandr Shokhin, Sergei B. Stankevich, Nikolai Travkin, Paul D. Wolfowitz<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	127 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-221-5 		$16.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="russiacis">Russia and the Commonwealth of Independent States: Documents, Data, and Analysis</a></h3>
Zbigniew Brzezinski and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4sulliva.html">Paige Sullivan</a>, editors<p>
What kind of state Russia is to become ultimately depends on its policies toward the "near abroad." This detailed chronology depicts Russia's internal "great power" debate over its vital geostrategic interests, the political and structural evolution of the CIS, and the reactions of the other CIS leaders to Russia's actions. It provides the informed reader with the necessary documents, statistics, and maps to analyze the content and meaning of CIS integration. Dr. Brzezinski's introduction and conclusion provide a penetrating analysis of whether we are witnessing Russia's "last gasp" or its "imperial restoration."<p>
<i>Copublished Book/M.E. Sharpe   896 pp.	1997<br>
ISBN 1-56324-637-6		$225.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="roc">Russian Organized Crime</a></h3>
<b>A Report from the Global Organized Crime Task Force</b><p>
William H. Webster, project chair<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4deborch.html">Arnaud de Borchgrave</a>, project director<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4kupperm.html">Robert H. Kupperman</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4peterso.html">Erik R. Peterson</a>, project codirectors<br>
Pat Gallagher, Task Force director and editor<br>
Frank J. Cilluffo, Task Force chairman and editor<p>
Russian organized crime constitutes a direct threat to the national security interests of the United States by fostering instability in a nuclear-armed power.  Left unchecked, Russia is in jeopardy of becoming a criminal syndicalist state under the control of corrupt government bureaucrats, politicians, quasi-businessmen, and criminals.  Composed of senior-level U.S. government representatives and private-sector experts, the task force assesses the breadth and depth of Russian organized crime and corruption, addresses current U.S. policy, and makes recommendations on how  best to confront these challenges.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	c. 50 pp.	Forthcoming <br>
ISBN 0-89206-293-2	$16.95 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="transcaucus">The Transcaucasus in Transition: Nation-Building and Conflict</a> </h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hunter.html">Shireen T. Hunter</a><p>
"As a description of how the Transcaucasian states have arrived at their present juncture, as an insightful analysis of this process and as a starting point, Hunter's latest work is well worth reading." - Journal of Peace Research<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	240 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-247-9		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="ukraine">Ukrainian Security Policy</a></h3>
Taras Kuzio<p>
The economic crisis and mismanagement that engulfed Ukraine during 1993-1994 led many in the West and among Ukraine's neighbors to question the country's long-term viability as an independent state. Yet in 1995, Ukraine entered a new era reflecting its importance as a linchpin of regional security and stability in Europe. This study discusses Ukrainian security policies and their implications for Western policy. It makes a compelling case for greater Western aid and political support for Ukrainian independence and territorial integrity.<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger	168 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-275-95385-8 (pb)	$14.95<br>
	0-275-95384-X (hb) 	$49.95</i>

<p>

</td></tr></table>

