<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>



<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=145 height=179
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 163,

September 5, 1996</h4>

<h1>Nuclear Weapons Testing</h1>

<h3>Will a comprehensive test
ban stop proliferation?
</h3>

An end to nuclear weapons testing?  Don't count on itóat least not in the near future.  The recent breakdown of negotiations on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), triggered by a veto from India, represents an enormous setback to more than two and a half years of talks at the United Nations Conference on Disarmament.  More fundamentally, the breakdown raises profound questions about whether a ban on testing will prevent further nuclear proliferation.<P>

<B>The Dimension from New Delhi.</B><BR>
  India has straight-forward reasons for objecting to the proposed agreement.  From India's standpoint, it allows the five declared nuclear states (P-5)óthe United States, Russia, China, France, and Britainóto continue developing and expanding their arsenals through advanced computer simulations in lieu of actual nuclear testing.  New Delhi has demanded a timetable for the elimination of existing nuclear weapons, a proposal rejected by the five nuclear powers and by a majority of the countries at the conference.  India's ambassador to the Conference on Disarmament, Arundhati Ghose, maintains that as long as the CTBT ignores the question of disarmament, the treaty is little more than a tool of the P-5 to further widen the gap between nuclear-weapon haves and have-nots. <P> 

New Delhi also objects to the "entry in force" provision that requires that the P-5 states, along with Israel, Pakistan, and Indiaóthe three threshold statesósign and ratify the treaty before it can take effect.  It claims that the provision impinges on its sovereignty and could subject it to punitive measures from the international community should it elect not to ratify the treaty when the UN General Assembly meets in October.<P>

Furthermore, the treaty does not provide security guarantees to India in return for forfeiting its nuclear option.  New Delhi has repeatedly expressed its regional security concerns vis-‡-vis China, Pakistan, and Russia. Thus far in the negotiations, however, no nuclear state has made such assurances to India.  It is highly unlikely that any will. <P>

<B>Cold War Relic or Useful Tool?</B><BR>
  In light of the breakdown in the test ban negotiations, it is time to ask whether efforts to eliminate testing still have any utility.  On this question, reactions by CSIS experts are mixed:<P>

   	According to Stephen Cambone, CSIS senior fellow in Political-Military Studies, the CTBT is an "anachronism."  He asserts that a ban on testing is a product of the perspective born in the 1940s, when bans were regarded as a way to halt the arms race and to marginalize the importance of nuclear weapons.  "Whatever value it had in that context," Cambone argues, "is much reduced in an era when proliferation is fueled by rapidly changing geopolitical circumstances, not vertical arms racing; a CTBT does not pose an insuperable obstacle to the development or acquisition of nuclear weapons."<P>

	Cambone views India's reluctance to sign the CTBT as an opportunity for the international community to consider whether the approach to nuclear safety and security, arms control, and disarmament on which the treaty rests is adequate given the realities of the post-Cold War strategic environment:  "If marginalizing nuclear weapons globally remains the aim of the West, then the CTBT may not be the right vehicle for accomplishing that goal."<P>

  	Mike Mazarr, director of the CSIS New Millennium Project, disagrees both with India's objections and with the idea that the CTBT is the relic of another era.  "The treaty is a major step toward India's avowed goal of disarmament; pressing for the complete goal at an early date," Mazarr contends, "is so unrealistic as to be disingenuous."  And, Mazarr notes, the entry-into-force provision is a common feature of treaties whose effect depends on the adherence of a specific group of states. <P>

	Mazarr also argues that the CTBT itself is more important than ever as a centerpiece of the effort to marginalize nuclear weapons in world politicsóa goal now championed in the United States by people from both sides of the political spectrum, including dozens of former high-ranking defense officials and military officers.<P>

William Clark, Jr., CSIS adviser on Asia and former U.S. ambassador to India, sees the current breakdown in the CTBT negotiations this way: "Although there is a certain logic and legitimacy to some of India's complaints, many other countries could certainly object on the basis of the same issues.  It is a shame to see India impeding the processóand potentially sinking itóbased on a certain set of concerns that other countries rightly could claim but have not."
<p><hr>

