<h3><a name="angola">The Angolan Economy: Prospects for Growth in a Postwar Environment</a></h3>
Shawn H. McCormick <p>
"As the subtitle of this readable study makes clear, this is a 'what if' book, referring to the political economy of Angola. . . . McCormick devotes a chapter to each resource in turn, which in itself is impressive in its scope." - British Bulletin of Publications<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	88 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-187-1 	  	$10.50</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="barricade">Breaking Down the Barricades: Reforming Export Controls to Increase U.S. Competitiveness</a></h3>
<b>Final Report of the Project on Export Controls in a Changing World</b><br>
Boyd McKelvain, project  chairman<br>
Irwin M. Pikus and David C. Earnest, project  codirectors<p>
<i>Panel Report	82 pp.	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-261-4 		$21.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="china">China's Domestic Economy in Regional Context</a></h3>
Ding Jingping<p>
Ding Jingping offers a perspective from Beijing as part of CSIS's East Asia Economic and Financial Outlook series. He analyzes the prospects for continued high growth and economic reform in the People's Republic of China. The role of external economic relations in China's economic development, particularly with Taiwan, Hong Kong, the United States, and Japan, is a<i>lso discussed.<p>
Significant Issues Series	84 pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-318-1 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="soa">The CSIS Strengthening of America Commission</a></h3>
<b>Chairmen's Report</b><p>
Senator Pete Domenici (R-N. Mex.) and Senator Sam Nunn (D-Ga.), cochairmen<p>
The cochairmen of the CSIS Strengthening of America Commission examine the progress made on the Commission's recommendations for fiscal, tax, and health care policy laid out in the Commission's 1992 First Report and its 1994 follow-up, Principles for Health Care Reform. The cochairmen then offer a blueprint for action in these areas to ensure the long-term economic prosperity of the United States.  Despite the recent progress in reducing the deficit, the report highlights the urgent need to address structural fiscal problems facing the U.S. economy in the twenty-first century, presents a framework for a new system of taxation to stimulate savings and investment, and details principles and options for market-based health care reform.<p>
<i>CSIS Special Report	  	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-325-4</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="soa1">The CSIS Strengthening of America Commission First Report</a></h3>
Senators Sam Nunn and Pete Domenici, cochairmen<br>
Debra L. Miller, commission director<p>
"You have to tip your cap to it. It's not the flag we're talking about this time, but the goal of budget balancing." - The Washington Post<p>

<i>CSIS Special Report	182 pp. 	$20.00<br>
Executive Summary 	  44 pp.	 $6.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="triad">The Future of the U.S.-EU-Japan Triad: How Dominant? How
Interdependent? How Divergent?</a></h3>
John Yochelson, editor<br>
Contributors: Pierre Jacquet, Harald Malmgren, Masahisa Naitoh, G. Russell Pipe, John R. Price, Bruce Stokes<p>
This CSIS report assesses the impact of global economic change on the U.S.-EU-Japan Triad and examines three key sectors_automotive, financial services, and information technology_in which new dynamics are being played out.  The report provides highlights from the Roundtable discussion of 50 private-sector leaders, senior government officials, and policy research experts, and includes more than 20 pages of analytical data.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	63 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-317-3 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="compete">Global Innovation/National Competitiveness</a></h3>
<b>A Report of the CSIS Senior Policy Group on National Challenges  and the CSIS Senior Action Group on National Investment Strategies</b><p>
Harold Brown and Charles Herzfeld, chairmen<br>
Debra van Opstal, project director<p>
The capacity to innovate will play a dominant, and probably decisive, role in determining which nations will succeed in the emerging globalized environment. Future U.S. competitiveness hinges on the ability to integrate the elements of innovation -- corporate competitiveness, world-class science and technology, a strong education system, and an investment-friendly environment -- into a national strategy for innovation. <p>
<i>Panel Report	104 pp.	1996<br>
ISBN 0-89206-289-4		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>	

<h3><a name="hongkong">Hong Kong's Economic and Financial Future</a></h3>
Y.F. Luk<p>
This volume in the East Asia Economic and Financial Outlook series assesses Hong Kong's phenomenal economic performance of the last few decades and, in particular, its special relationship with the People's Republic of China. The author also examines the changing domestic economic policies and political institutions that have played crucial roles in Hong Kong's growth and asks whether this spectacular growth will continue into the next decade.<p>

"This 77-page treatise on Hong Kong is very well done and very readable." - Manufacturing Competitiveness Frontiers<p>

<i>Significant Issues Series	91 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-306-8 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="mexico">Mexico: Politics and the Peso in Transition</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a><p>
The Christmas devaluation did not come as a complete surprise. The peso was under pressure throughout 1994 as polarized national elections took place under a cloud of assassinations and guerrilla movements, the trade deficit grew, and rumors of a debate over devaluation seeped out from the Zedillo campaign team as early as April 1994.<p>
<i>The Conference Board	17 pp. 	1995<br>
Global Business White Paper 	$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="nafta3">NAFTA at Three</a>: A Progress Report</h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a><p>
The North American Free Trade Agreement, now completing its third year of operations, was the most controversial trade agreement entered into by the United States since World War II.  It was sold by its supporters and condemned by its opponents with unusual hyperbole about how many jobs it would create (or sacrifice) and how valuable (or injurious) it would be for many U.S. industries.  The controversy picked up again in early 1995 when the United States mounted a $20 billion rescue of the Mexican peso, to which additional funds were provided by the International Monetary Fund.  To get at the complete picture, the author analyzes the actual performance of NAFTA.  He sets forth the main criteria by which the agreement should be assessed: Has it led to an increase in trade? Has it benefited both Mexico and the United States (plus Canada)? Did the agreement cause Mexico's economic crisis in 1995?  Did it help Mexico resolve that crisis?  He also notes that, contrary to the fears about general job loss,  the U.S. economy has been operating at full employment since NAFTA came into effect.  His main conclusion: NAFTA has performed well under difficult circumstances.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series  c. 120 pp. 	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-298-3		$15.95 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="naftadebate">The NAFTA Debate: Grappling with Unconventional Trade Issues</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4baer.html">M. Delal Baer</a> and <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a>, editors<br>
Contributors: Jan Gilbreath, Timothy J. Kehoe, Soledad Loaeza, Howard Rosen, Alan M. Rugman, John Benjamin Tonra, Howard J. Wiarda <p>
<i>Copublished Book/	211 pp.	 1994<br>
Lynne Rienner Publishers<br>
ISBN 1-55587-464-9 (hb) 	$38.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="naftanext">NAFTA: What Comes Next?</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a><p>
"With so many titles available, one wonders if yet another book will have any effect on clarifying NAFTA's complexities. However, in this case, the answer is a resounding yes
. . . .The book is highly recommended." - Business Information Alert<p>

"Anyone trying to decipher the myriad claims about NAFTA would be well advised to read this book." - CHOICE<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger	132 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-275-95119-7 (pb) 	$14.95<br>
0-275-95118-9 (hb) 	$49.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="newforces">New Forces in the World Economy</a></h3>
Brad Roberts, editor <br>
Contributors: J. Carter Beese Jr., Kenneth Berlin, Richard E. Bissell, Delia M. Boylan, Daniel F. Burton Jr., Steve Charnovitz, Thomas J. Duesterberg, Georges Fauriol, Richard E. Feinberg, James R. Golden, David D. Hale, Gary D. Hale, Gary Hufbauer, Jeri Jensen-Moran, Ethan B. Kapstein, Jeffrey M. Lang, Joseph LaPalombara, Raymond Paretzky, Erik R. Peterson, Ernest H. Preeg, Jeffrey J. Schott, Donald R. Sherk, Roy C. Smith, W.R. Smyser, Paula Stern, John D. Sullivan, Raymond Vernon, Murray Weidenbaum, Sidney Weintraub<p>

This volume examines the features of the new world economic order. It reviews the changing structure of the world economy with chapters on trade, investment, finance, and competitiveness. It then  reviews the policy debate, with chapters on major international institutions, prominent bilateral relationships, and the role of the private sector. <p>
<i>Copublished Book/MIT Press	437 pp. 	1996<br>
ISBN 0-262-68089-0		 $17.00</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="house">Putting America's House in Order: The Nation as a Family</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4abshire.html">David Abshire</a> and Brock Brower<p>
This book is a call to action for the leaders of this generation to endow their heirs with the kinds of values, prospects, and prosperity that has sustained the American family, personally and nationally, for 200 years. The authors' proposals are specific. They range from ways to reach a zero deficit budget to substituting a tax code that favors savings, investment, and growth. They also delineate the elements of leadership --local, state, and national -- that are necessary to meet the United States' greatest challenge since the winning of the cold war.<p>

"What most deeply moves David Abshire and Brock Brower is the rising commitment of ordinary Americans to a bipartisan course of action to end deficit profligacy and keep our country headed round toward economic growth that will bring real prosperity for all American families." - Warren B. Rudman, cochairman, Concord Coalition and former U.S. Senator<p>

"For the sake of our future, I earnestly hope that this eloquent plea and plan for the reconciliation of our national community will be read by as many Americans as possible. As a people, we desperately need to take action to implement the authors' common sense solutions to the underlying structural problems of our society." - David L. Boren, President, University of Oklahoma and former U.S. Senator<p>
<i>Copublished Book/Praeger Publishers  189 pp.	 1996<br>
ISBN 0-275-95431-5 		$19.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="rediscover">The Rediscovery of America: The Story of the Free Trade Agreement</a></h3>
Hermann von Bertrab<p>
Rarely before in the history of the Western Hemisphere has such monumental change occurred, as the United States, Mexico, and Canada have integrated their economies and united their destinies under the NAFTA agreement.  Three countries that had isolated themselves during the last few centuries have rediscovered their common roots and interests under this modern treaty.  This insightful book, written by the chief Mexican representative for NAFTA in the U.S., offers an insider's perspective on the dramatic and arduous process of how NAFTA became a reality.<p>
<i>Washington Papers/Praeger       c. 205 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN	0-275-95935-X (pb)	$18.95 Est.<br>
	0-275-95934-1 (hb)	$55.00 Est.</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="income">Replacing the Income Tax: Framework for a New Tax System</a></h3>
<b>A Report of the CSIS Domestic Policy Issues Program</b><br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html">Bradley Belt</a>, director<br>
Alexander T. Hunt, research associate<p>
The report presents basic principles and a framework for a new system of taxation. It discusses the economic and political rationale for replacing the income tax; explores various options regarding the tax treatment of items such as housing, education expenses, and gifts and bequests; and addresses key transition issues.<p>
<i>CSIS Report	42 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-281-9 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="resurgence">Resurgence and Uncertainty in Argentina, Brazil, and Chile</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4weintra.html">Sidney Weintraub</a><p>
In Latin America, Argentina, Brazil, and Chile all have gone through profound political and economic changes during the past decade. For the first time in this century, there is legitimate reason to hope that all of them can escape from the authoritarianism and, over <i>time, the underdevelopment that has been their lot.<p>
The Conference Board	20 pp. 	1995<br>
Global Business White Paper 	$20.00</i>

<p><hr><p>

<h3><a name="sochina">Southern China, Hong Kong, and Taiwan: Evolution of a Subregional Economy</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4khanna.html">Jane Khanna</a>, editor<br>
Foreword by Robert A. Scalapino<br>
Contributors: Chen Dezhao, Jane Khanna, J.A. Miller, Robert S. Ross, Sally Stewart, Sung Yun-wing, Milton D. Yeh<p>
The emergence of subregional economies_"natural economic territories"_raises serious questions about nation-state sovereignty.  In this examination of the subregional economy made up of Taiwan, Hong Kong, and China's southern provinces, the authors seek to capture points of rift and accord at the governmental and provincial levels even as economic flows seem to be outpacing the central governments' abilities to manage them.<p>

"This book, written by specialists in the field of international politics and relations, offers a timely collection of perspectives on the origin and prospects of this NET. Published in 1995, its insights throw a surprisingly illuminating light on events that have taken place in 1996." - China Information<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series  	108  pp.	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-321-1 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="taiwan">Taiwan's Economic Role in East Asia</a></h3>
Chi Schive<p>
As part of the series on East Asia's economic and financial future, Chi Schive assesses the role of  Taiwan within the regional and global economy. He analyzes the strategies that have generated Taiwan's rapid development and the resulting shifts in regional and international economic and financial linkages, with particular attention to Taiwan's economic restructuring, cross-strait trade and investment with the People's Republic of China, and Taiwan's potential for serving as a regional operations center for East Asia.<p>

"The book is short but elegant." - China Information<p>

<i>Significant Issues Series	117 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-319-X 		$14.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="tradepol">Trade Policy Ahead: Three Tracks and One Question</a></h3>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4preeg.html">Ernest H. Preeg</a><p>
The study examines the changing structure of world trade and investment and relates this to the current state of the "three-track trading system" (i.e., multilateral commitments, comprehensive regional free trade agreements, and selective bilateral arrangements) vis-‡-vis the World Trade Organization.  The author's analysis leads to a recommended course of trade policy based on the concept of a "three-convergent-track" strategy.<p>
<i>Significant Issues Series	85 pp. 	1995<br>
ISBN 0-89206-309-2 		$11.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="socialist">The Transition of Socialist
Economies: Lessons from Asia and Europe</a></h3>
<b>A Report of the Working Group on the Transition of Socialist Economies 
Global Forum: Leadership 2000</b><p>

<i>CSIS Report	34 pp. 	1994<br>
ISBN 0-89206-270-3 		$10.95</i>

<p><hr><p>


<h3><a name="mdb">The United States and the Multilateral Development Banks</a></h3>
<b>Report of the CSIS Task Force on 
Multilateral Development Banks</b><p>
Senator Bill Bradley and Congressman John Kasich, congressional cochairs<br>
Kenneth Lay and Lawrence Ricciardi, private-sector cochairs<br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4upton.html">Barbara Upton</a>, project director<p>
The five multilateral development banks (MDBs) were designed to operate in a far different environment than the one that prevails today with the end of the Cold War and explosion of private-sector financial flows to emerging markets. The broad-based CSIS Task Force looked at criticisms of the banks' operations and the extent to which the institutions responded. It provides extensive recommendations for refocusing MDB priorities and reforming their operating practices.<p>
<i>Panel Report	c. 60 pp.	Forthcoming<br>
ISBN 0-89206-326-2	$16.95 Est.</i><p>

</td></tr></table>

