<head><TITLE>CSIS Watch</TITLE>
</head>

<body><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p align="center"><img 
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3watch.gif"></p>

        

<img src="http://www.csis.org/images/watch.gif" align=left width=150 height=176 
vspace=10 hspace=10>        <h4>Number 152,                        

                      
February 16, 1996</h4>

<h1>Running on Empty</h1>
         
<h3>North Korea struggles to survive . . .</h3>
 
Mounting food shortages, increasing defections to the South, political factionalism among its leadership, and recent military maneuvers along the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) all suggest that North Korea (DPRK) is edging closer to the brink of collapse.  The situation is becoming more dangerous by the day.<P>

Pyongyang took an unprecedented step earlier this fall when it broke with its traditional juche ("self-reliance") system and asked the international community for assistance in overcoming food shortages.  Analysts have been tempted to proclaim this "opening" as a sign that North Korea is ready, out of necessity, to join the international community.  Not so, says <I>Bill Taylor, CSIS Director of Political Military Studies</I> and an expert on North Korea.  Rather, it is a North Korean tactic to rectify its steadily worsening domestic situation by attracting international aid.  The DPRK is attempting to accomplish its goals with a minimal amount of foreign influence, while simultaneously working to cut South Korea out of the action. <P> 
	
For the North Korean leadership, there is only one concern of importance: ensuring that the military, upon which the North Korean leadership relies as the cornerstone of its power, is kept well armed and well fed.  All informed estimates conclude that the North Korean military gets all it needs, even while the North Korean people go hungry.<P>  

North Korea has also been hit by increasingly high-level defections across its closed borders.  In the last two weeks, several prominent diplomats have applied for asylum to South Korea.  On Wednesday, a North Korean security agent shot and killed three DPRK agents in an attempt to find political asylum in the Russian embassy in Pyongyang.  While the effect this chain of events has on the North's leadership structure is unknown, it affirms that economic, social, and political conditions in North Korea are deteriorating rapidly. <P> 	




Political factionalism in the North Korean leadership ranks also is becoming more apparent.  The appeals for food aid this fall were widely seen as a symbol of increasing influence on the part of "moderates" in the North Korean Ministry of Foreign Affairs.  Last week, however, North Korean officials ordered that no further international food aid be requested.  Surprisingly, an unusually candid statement attributed to North Korea's U.N. ambassador Pak Gil Yon was that "the Pyongyang government would not ask for more food aid because of strong opposition from the military."  As opaque as the political situation in North Korea remains, it is clear that the military has the upper hand in all aspects of crucial decision-making processes. <P>  

Taylor is concerned that Pyongyang will try to divert the attention of the North Korean people away from their domestic plight by using propaganda to exaggerate the threat from the South, thereby creating a "state of siege" mentality.  They may also intend to take advantage of the ongoing political turmoil in South Korea. <P> 

Over the past two months, the North, which long has had about two-thirds of its military force forward-deployed near the DMZ, reportedly has moved another 120 fighter aircraft and a flight of bombers to three airfields along the DMZ -- only a five-minute flight from Seoul.  Apprehensive of the provocative situation in the North, Seoul has placed its forces on a higher state of alert. <P> 

The stakes are high for all the countries involved in the Korean peninsula.  With 60,000 Americans in South Korea, including 37,000 troops, the United States must work to ensure that the rhetoric does not spiral out of control.  It is at times of high tension that wars start by accident or miscalculation.  <I>CSIS Political Military Studies analyst Andrew Kelly</I> notes that tensions on the Peninsula are higher now than at any other point since the end of the Cold War.  Extreme caution must be exercised by the United States and South Korea as events unfold in the DPRK. 
<p><hr>

