<HTML><TITLE>CSIS National Commission on Retirement Policy</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org/images/3spcproj.gif"></p><br><p>

<H2><p align="center">CSIS National Commission on Retirement Policy</p></H2>
<h3><p align="center">Biographies of Members</p></h3>
<table cellpadding=15><tr>

<td valign=top width=150><font size="2">
<i>For information about specific aspects of the project:</i><p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/members.html">Project Overview</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/press.html">Press Advisory</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/mission.html">Mission Statement</a><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/retire/facts.html">Fact Sheet</a><p>


</font></td>

<td>


	<i><b>Congressional Co-Chairs:</b></i><p>

<b>The Honorable Judd Gregg</b> was elected as a Republican Senator from New Hampshire in 1992.  In addition to serving on the Senate Budget, Appropriations and Labor and Human Resources Committees, he currently chairs the Republican Retirement Security T
ask Force and heads a bipartisan working group on retirement security.  He was also appointed Chief Deputy Whip.  Senator Gregg served as a member of the Bipartisan Commission on Entitlement and Tax Reform in 1994 and chaired the Leadership's Working Grou
p on Non-Social Security Entitlement Reform, whose recommendations were incorporated in the Republican Balanced Budget Act.<p>
  	Senator Gregg holds a unique honor of being the first elected official in New Hampshire to serve the state in each of the following capacities: two terms as Governor, from 1989 to 1993; four terms as U.S. Representative from the 2nd District, from 1981
 to 1989; and one term as Executive Councilor from New Hampshire's 5th District.  His tenure in the Senator thus far has been marked by awards for his exceptional efforts to control the federal budget deficit.  His voting record to fight the deficit has b
een recognized by the National Taxpayers' Union, Citizens Against Government Waste, the National Federation of Independent Businesses, the Concord Coalition, Watchdogs of the Treasury, Inc. and <i>Congressional Quarterly</i>.<p>
	Senator Gregg holds degrees from Columbia University and Boston University Law School.  He is married with two daughters and a son.<p>

<b>The Honorable John Breaux</b> was elected to the United States Senate from Louisiana in 1986.  He currently serves as Chief Deputy Whip for the Democrats, a position he's held since 1993.  He also serves on the Senate Finance Committee, which oversees 
Social Security, Medicare and tax policy, as well as the Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation.   Senator Breaux was a founder and past chair of the Democratic Leadership Council, succeeding then-Governor  Bill Clinton.  He was elected to the 
U.S. House of Representatives in 1972 at the age of 28, where he served until being elected to the Senate. He was re-elected to his seat in 1992, gaining 74 percent of the vote, the largest margin of all senators running for re-election that year.  In 199
4, Campaigns and Elections magazine named him one of the 20 most popular public officials in America.  He has also served as chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee from 1988 to 1990.<p>
	Prior to his Congressional service, he worked as a legislative aide and district manager to U.S. Congressman Edwin Edwards and was also a practicing attorney.  The Senator is married with four children.<p>

<b>The Honorable Jim Kolbe</b> has served in the United States Congress since 1985, representing the 5th District of Arizona, which includes Tucson and parts of four Southeastern Arizona counties.  He currently serves on the House Appropriations Committee
, where he chairs the Subcommittee on Treasury, Postal Service and General Government.  He co-chairs the Public Pension Reform Caucus, which he co-founded in August 1995 with Representative Stenholm of Texas.  It had a bipartisan membership of 40 members 
in the 104th Congress.  Representative Kolbe also co-chairs the Congressional Economic Leadership Institute and a CSIS Congressional Study Group on Mexico and two other foreign policy working groups.<p>
	Congressman Kolbe previously served for six years in the Arizona State Senate where he was Judiciary Committee Chairman and Majority Whip.  He also was in the Navy on active duty in Vietnam from 1968 to 1969, for which he received the Navy's commendation
 "V" for valor.  He continued in the Naval Reserves until 1977.  His Congressional service has seen him awarded commendations from the National Federation of Independent Businesses, Citizens for a Sound Economy, the Jewish National Fund, Free Congress Fou
ndation and The Retired Officers Association.<p>
	He received a B.A. in political science from Northwestern University and an M.B.A. with a concentration in economics from Stanford University.
<p>

<b>The Honorable Charles Stenholm</b> has served in the U.S. House of Representatives since January of 1979.  He represents the 17th District of Texas, a 32-county area in West Central Texas.  He co-chairs the Public Pension Reform Caucus, which he co-fou
nded in August 1995 with Representative Kolbe.  He has served on the Agriculture Committee since coming to Congress and is now the second ranking Democrat on the House Budget Committee, where he is known as the "spiritual godfather of fiscal responsibilit
y." It was his balanced budget amendment to the U.S. Constitution which the House adopted in January 1995.  Representative Stenholm has served as a Democratic Deputy Whip since 1989 and was appointed to the House Democratic Leadership Advisory Group in 19
95.  Furthermore, he is a founding member of the House Rural Health Care coalition.<p>
	A third generation West Texan, Stenholm graduated from Tarleton State Junior College and received his B.A. and M.A. from Texas Tech University.  He is married and has two sons and a daughter.	<p>

	<i><b>Private Sector Co-Chairs:</b></i><p>

<b>Donald B. Marron</b> is the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Paine Webber Group Inc., a leading financial services firm.  Mr. Marron began his career in 1951 with the New York Trust Company and continued in investment counseling until starting h
is own investment banking firm, D.B. Marron and Co., Inc.  He also co-founded Data Resources, Inc. which became the largest source of non-governmental economic data in the world, before it was sold to McGraw-Hill in 1979.  Mr. Marron became president of P
aine Webber Group Inc. in 1977.  He became CEO in 1980 and was elected chairman a year later.<p>
	Mr. Marron has served in a number of leadership positions in both the industry and the  community.  He was a director of the New York Stock Exchange for several years and governor of the Securities Industry Association for three years, serving as vice ch
airman in 1985.  He was a member of the executive committee of the President's Private Sector Survey, "the Grace Commission" during the Reagan Administration and has been on the President's Committee on The Arts and The Humanities.  He also served a five-
year term as president of the Board of Trustees of The Museum of Modern Art, where he still serves as vice-chairman.     
 <p>

<b>Dr. Charles A. Sanders</b> is the retired Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Glaxo, Inc. as well as a former member of the board of Glaxo plc.  Prior to joining Glaxo, Inc., Dr. Sanders spent eight years with Squibb Corp. where he held a number of
 posts including the position of vice chairman.  He previously served as general director of Massachusetts General Hospital and a professor of medicine at Harvard Medical School.  A native of Dallas, he is a graduate of Southwestern Medical College of the
 University of Texas.<p>
	Among his professional associations, Dr. Sanders is a member of the Institute of Medicine of the National Academy of Sciences, a trustee of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Chairman of Project HOPE, and chairman of the Commonwealth Fund. 
 He also currently serves as a member of the President's Committee of Advisors on Science and Technology.  He lives in Durham, N.C.<p>


	<i><b>Commission Members:</b></i><p>

<b>Warren Batts</b> is the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Tupperware Corporation, a $1.4 billion consumer products company.  In May 1996, Tupperware was spun off from Premark International, Inc. where Mr. Batts still serves as Chairman of the Boa
rd.  He also is the Chairman of the National Association of Manufacturers.<p>
	Formerly the President and Co-Chief Executive Officer of Triangle Corporation, a manufacturing firm he co-founded in 1967.  Mr. Batts joined Mead Corporation as Vice President in 1971.  He became President and Chief Operating Officer in 1973 and was elec
ted Chief Executive Officer in 1978.  Mr. Batts was named President and Chief Operating Officer of Dart Industries shortly before the company merged with Kraft in 1980 and was elected President and COO of Dart & Kraft the following year.  When Kraft spun 
off most of its non-food operations in 1986, he took charge of the new company, which subsequently became Premark International, Inc.  Mr. Batts also serves as chairman of the Board of Children's Memorial Hospital in Chicago and as director on the boards 
of the Allstate Corporation, Sears, Roebuck and Co., Sprint Corporation, and the Art Institute of Chicago.  He is also a trustee of Northwestern University.<p>
	Mr. Batts earned a B.S. degree in electrical engineering from Georgia Institute of Technology and an M.B.A. degree from the Harvard Business School.
<p>

<b>Ronald E. Compton</b> is the Chairman, President, and Chief Executive Officer of Aetna Inc.  He first joined Aetna after graduating from Northwestern University in 1954 with a bachelor's degree in philosophy.  After a series of promotions, he was named
 Assistant Vice President of the Commercial Casualty Division in 1972 and General Manager of Aetna's Pittsburgh and Philadelphia offices in 1975 and 1979, respectively.<p>
	In 1980, Mr. Compton was named Senior Vice President of American Re-Insurance Company.  He was promoted to Executive Vice President in 1981, and made President of the subsidiary in 1983.  Mr. Compton returned to Aetna as Senior Vice President and Executi
ve Assistant to the Office of the Chairman in 1987.  He later became Executive Vice President and by 1988 was appointed President and a Director of Aetna.  In 1991, he was elected Chairman, President, and CEO, the positions he holds today.<p>
	Mr. Compton is a member of the Geneva Association.  He is a director of the Connecticut Business and Industry Association and the Connecticut Opera.  He also serves as a Trustee for the University of Hartford and Aperture Foundation and is President of T
he Bushnell theatre.  He and his wife live in Connecticut and have three grown children.
<p>

<b>Fred Goldberg</b> is a partner in the Washington law firm of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher and Flom which he joined in 1986.  He served as Commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service from 1989 to 1992 and as Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for Tax
 Policy in 1992.  He rejoined the law firm in 1992, where he specializes in tax legislation and financial products. <p> 
	Mr. Goldberg is involved with a number of community and civic organizations, including serving as a trustee of the Josephson Institute of Ethics, the executive director of the Bipartisan Commission on Entitlement and Tax Reform, and at present, a member 
of the National Commission on Restructuring the IRS.  He is married and has five children.<p>

<b>Lanny Hall</b> is President of Hardin-Simmons University and professor of political science.  Dr. Hall has an extensive background in politics, government and academia.  He came to serve as President of Hardin-Simmons in Abilene Texas in 1991.  Prior t
o that, Dr. Hall served as president of Wayland Baptist University, executive vice president and chief academic officer at Howard Payne University and professor of government and education at Texas Wesleyan College.  He also served in the Texas House of R
epresentatives for three terms from 1979-1984 and as a Congressional aide in the U.S. House of Representatives. <p>
	Dr. Hall also has tremendous experience with pension and retirement issues.  He was President of Educational Services, Inc., a firm which developed seminars on employee benefit plans.  He held two professional positions with the Teacher Retirement System
 of Texas.  Furthermore, his doctoral dissertation at the University of Texas at Austin was an analysis of state-funded retirement programs.  Dr. Hall is married with two children.<p>

<b>Beth Kobliner</b> has been writing about personal finance for a decade.  She is the author of <i>Get a Financial Life: Personal Finance in Your Twenties and Thirties</i>.  The book, published by Simon and Schuster in May 1996, is a national bestseller,
 appearing on the business lists of <i>The New York Times</i>, <i>Business Week</i>, and <i>USA Today</i>.  A graduate of Brown University, Kobliner started her career in financial writing as research associate for Sylvia Porter, the pioneer of personal f
inance journalism and syndicated columnist for over 150 newspapers nationwide.  Kobliner joined <i>Money</i> magazine as a staff writer in 1988, writing extensively on investing, pensions and taxes.  She is now a contributing writer for the publication.  
<p>
	In 1994 and 1995, Kobliner was selected by the TJFR Business News Reporter, the leading trade publication for financial journalism, as one of the country's most promising financial journalists under the age of 30.  She is interviewed regularly on nationa
l television and radio programs.  She lives in New York City with her husband and daughter.<p>   

<b>Estelle James</b> is Lead Economist for the Policy Research Department at the World Bank.  She is also principle author of  Averting the Old Age Crisis: Policies to Protect the Old and Promote Growth, a World Bank study that provides the first global a
nalysis of economic problems associated with population aging.  Dr. James has an impressive background in academia.  She was Professor and Chair of the Economics Department and Dean of the Social and Behavioral Sciences at the State University of New York
, Stony Brook.  She has also taught and researched at Yale, Tel Aviv, and Stanford universities as well as the University of California at Berkeley and the London School of Economics.<p>
	Dr. James is the author of several books and numerous articles on various aspects of public finance, human resources and the economics of old age security.  Her research has earned support from the National Science Foundation, the Social Science Research
 Council, and the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars.  She earned her Ph.D. from Massachusetts Institute of Technology.<p>

<b>Rudolph G. Penner</b> is a Managing Director of the Barents Group of KPMG Peat Marwick in Washington.  He is former Director of the Congressional Budget Office and was a senior fellow at the Urban Institute.  He also served as Director of Fiscal Policy
 Studies and Resident Scholar at the American Enterprise Institute for Public Policy Research.  Other government posts in which Mr. Penner served were Assistant Director for Economic Policy at the Office of Management and Budget, Deputy Assistant Secretar
y for Economic Affairs at the Department of Housing and Urban Development, and Senior Staff economist at the Council on Economic Advisors.<p>
	Mr. Penner's writings include Broken Purse Strings, co-authored with Alan Abramson, a study of the Congressional budget process, editing The Great Fiscal Experiment, the proceedings of a conference on the macroeconomic effects of the budget deficits of t
he 1980's, and a number of columns in various newspapers.<p>

<b>Robert C. Pozen</b> is one of ten Managing Directors of Fidelity Investments as well as Senior Vice President and General Counsel of FMR Corp., Fidelity's parent company.  Fidelity manages over $450 billion in assets and provides a broad array of other
 financial services.  Before coming to Fidelity, Mr. Pozen taught at Harvard, Georgetown, and New York University and published three books and numerous articles.  He also served as Associate General Counsel of the Securities and Exchange Commission and a
s managing partner of the banking-securities department at the Washington law firm of Caplin & Drysdale.<p>
	Mr. Pozen is a member of many government and industry boards.  He is a member of the Commerce Department's Advisory Committee on Trade in Services, as well as the Treasury Department's Advisory Committee on the Future of Financial Services.  He is a memb
er of the Executive Committee of the Investment Company Institute and of the Wharton Center for Financial Institutions.  He lives with his wife and two children in Newton, Massachusetts. <p> 

<b>Stanford G. Ross</b> is a Senior Partner in the Washington law firm of  Arnold & Porter.  He is also a former Commissioner of Social Security.   He also served as a Public Trustee of the Social Security and Medicare Trust Funds, at the U.S. Department 
of Treasury and on the domestic policy staff of the White House.  Mr. Ross' academic background includes teaching law at Georgetown, Harvard, New York University, and Virginia law schools as well as having been a visiting fellow at the Hoover Institution 
at Stanford University.  He has also served as Chairman of the American Bar Association Tax Section Committee on Social Security and Payroll Tax Programs.<p>
	Mr. Ross has provided technical assistance on Social Security and tax issues under the auspices of the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development, and the U.S. Treasury Department.  He is also fo
unding member and Director of the National Academy of Social Insurance.  He received his B.A. from Washington University (St. Louis) and J.D. from Harvard Law School.<p>

<b>Dallas L. Salisbury</b> is President and CEO of the Employee Benefit Research Institute (EBRI).  He joined  EBRI in 1978, when it was founded as a clearinghouse providing information regarding employee benefit system and related economic security issue
s.  He also serves as chairman and CEO of the American Savings Education Council, a partnership of public- and private-sector institutions that undertake initiatives to raise public awareness about what is needed to ensure long-term personal financial ind
ependence. <p>
	Salisbury is a member of the Board of Directors of the National Academy of Social Insurance, The Health Project, and the advisory board of the National Academy on Aging.  He served on the Secretary of Labor's ERISA Advisory Council, the Presidentially ap
pointed Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation (PBGC) Advisory Committee and has consulted for many government agencies and private organizations on economic security topics.  Prior to joining EBRI, Salisbury worked for the Washington State Legislature, the
 U.S. Department of Justice, the PBGC and the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration of the U.S Department of Labor.<p>

<b>Robert J. Shapiro</b> is a founder and the Vice President of the Progressive Policy Institute, a public policy research institution affiliated with the Democratic Leadership Council.  His expertise at the institute includes domestic and foreign economi
c policy, the federal budget, and tax policy.  Additionally, he serves as the Director of Economic Studies of the Progressive Foundation and is a contributing editor for The New Republic, The International Economy, and Intellectual Captiol.com.<p>
	Dr. Shapiro has served in a number of political, government, and academic positions.  He was principal economic advisor to Governor Bill Clinton in the 1992 presidential campaign and continues to serve as an informal advisor to senior officials in the Cl
inton Administration.  He was the deputy national issues director and economic advisor to the Dukakis-Bentsen presidential campaign.  He was also the legislative director and economic counsel to U.S. Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan.  Prior to that positio
n, he served as the Senator's counsel on tax policy and chief aide on budgetary policy. <p>
	 Dr. Shapiro has been a fellow at both Harvard University and the National Bureau of Economic Research.  He holds a doctorate from Harvard University, in addition to degrees from  the University of Chicago and the London School of Economics and Political
 Science.<p>

<b>Eugene Steurele</b> is a Senior Fellow at The Urban Institute where he conducts extensive research on budget and tax policy, Social Security, health care, and welfare reform.  He also authors a weekly column, "Economic Perspective," for Tax Notes magaz
ine.  Dr. Steurele has served in various positions in the U.S. Treasury Department under four Presidents including Deputy Assistant Secretary for Tax Analysis.  Between 1984 and 1986 he served as Economic Coordinator and original organizer of the Treasury
's tax reform effort.<p>
	His publications include six books and more than 100 reports and articles, 350 columns and 35 Congressional testimonies or reports.  One recent book (co-authored with Jon Bakija), Retooling Social Security for the Twenty-First Century, was cited by the f
ormer executive director of the National Commission on Social Security Reform as "undoubtedly the most comprehensive analysis of the very long-range financing problems confronting the Social Security program."  His most recent book, <i>The New World Fisca
l Order</i> (co-edited with Masahiro Kawai), lays out implications of common fiscal problems, including an aging population, in industrial countries across the globe.<p>
	Dr. Steurele serves or has served as an advisor, consultant, or board member to a Technical Panel to the Social Security Advisory Council, the National Academy on Aging, the Joint Committee on Taxation, the International Monetary Fund, the IRS and numero
us other private and public boards and agencies. <p> 

<b>Josephine "Josie" Tsao</b> is the Vice President of Global Compensation and Benefits for IBM Corporation.  She joined IBM at its corporate headquarters in Armonk, New York in September 1996.  Her present responsibilities include global oversight, strat
egy and principles of both executive and non-executive compensation and benefits programs.  Prior to joining IBM, Ms. Tsao held the position of Vice President, Executive/International Compensation and Benefits at J.P. Morgan and Co., Inc.  Ms. Tsao also p
racticed law in the areas of executive compensation and employee benefits at the law firms of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom and Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver & Jacobson.  She has extensive experience in both friendly and hostile mergers and acquisi
tions, as well as ERISA, tax, and securities law.<p>
	Ms. Tsao is a member of the American Bar Association, the Conference Board Council on Executive Compensation, and the Cato Institute Project on Social Security Privatization Business Council.<p>
	Ms. Tsao holds a B.A. in economics from the University of Michigan and a J.D. from the University of Michigan Law School.<p>

<b>David M. Walker</b> is a Partner and Global Managing Director of Arthur Andersen & Co.'s Human Capital Services Practice based in Atlanta.  His responsibilities include strategic and leadership duties relating to the practice, as well as audit, tax and
 consulting services and coordination of firm activities with the legislative and executive branches of government. <p> 
	Mr. Walker has held a variety of executive and policy making positions in the Federal government, including serving as the head of two of the three U.S. Government agencies that administer the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA).  He 
served as Assistant Secretary of Labor for Pension and Welfare Benefit Programs at the U.S. Department of Labor and as Acting Executive Director of the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation.  His most recent government position was serving as one of two pu
blic Trustees for the Social Security and Medicare Trust Funds from 1990 until 1995.<p>
	Mr. Walker is a certified public accountant with a B.S. in Accounting from Jacksonville University and an S.M.G. Certificate in Public Policy from the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard.<p>

<b>Murray Weidenbaum</b> is the Chairman of the Center for the Study of American Business at Washington University in St. Louis where he holds the Mallinckrodt Distinguished University Professorship.  He served in 1981 and 1982 as President Reagan's first
 chairman of the Council of Economic Advisors, where he helped formulate the Administration's economic policy and served as a key spokesman on economic and financial issues.  From 1983-89, he was a member of the President's Economic Policy Advisory Board.
  Earlier White House service included being Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for Economic Policy in the Nixon Administration.<p>
	Dr. Weidenbaum is widely known for his research on economic policy, taxes, and government spending.  He is the author of eight books; his latest is The Bamboo Network: How Expatriate Chinese Entrepreneurs Are Creating a New Economic Superpower in Asia.  
His Small Wars, Big Defense was judged by the Association of American Publishers to be the outstanding economics book of 1992.  He serves on a number of boards of directors and advisory boards, including the Congressional Joint Tax Committee, the American
 Council for Capital Formation, the Committee for Economic Development, and CSIS. <p>

<hr width=150><p>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4belt.html"><b>Bradley D. Belt</b></a>, Executive Director, is the director of capital markets and domestic policy issues at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, where he oversees the Center's domestic poli
cy and international financial markets initiatives.  He is also president of The Washington Capital Group, a financial institutions consulting firm, and managing director and general counsel of  The Commonwealth Group, a merchant banking and corporate con
sulting firm, both headquartered in Washington.<p>
	Previously, Mr. Belt served as counsel to the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs, and as chief Republican counsel to the Securities Subcommittee.  Mr. Belt also served as general counsel and legislative director to Senator John McCain
 (R-AZ).  He also held senior staff positions at the Securities and Exchange Commission.<p>
	Mr. Belt frequently has written and lectured on international finance, federal tax, and domestic policy issues.  He is on the Board of Directors of the Securities Traders Association and on various committees of the American Bar Association, including th
e Federal Regulations of Securities and International Law and Practice Committees.  He  is a graduate of the Georgetown University Law Center and is a member of the United States Supreme Court, New York state and District of Columbia bars.<p>

<b>Mark A. Weinberger</b>, Senior Advisor and Counsel, is a member of the Washington-based law firm, Washington Counsel, P.C., where he specializes in taxation, budget, and legislative issues.  He served as Chief of Staff to the President's 1994 Bipartisa
n Commission on Entitlement and Tax Reform (Kerrey-Danforth Commission).  The Commission, with members of the House and Senate and ten non-elected individuals appointed by the President, examined the major budgetary and fiscal issues facing the country du
ring the next decade.  Prior to his appointment with the Commission, Mr. Weinberger served as chief tax and budget counsel to Senator John C. Danforth, formerly ranking Member of the Commerce Committee and senior member of the Finance Committee.  He also 
worked as Tax Manager in a national accounting firm.<p>
	Mr. Weinberger has written several articles on tax issues and given numerous presentations on tax policy and budget issues.  He is an Adjunct Fellow on Tax Policy at the Center for Strategic and International Studies and serves on the Board of Directors 
of the Tax Section of the Federal Bar Association.    He received his B.A. from Emory University, his M.B.A. and J.D. from Case Western Reserve University, and his masters in Tax Law from Georgetown.  Mr. Weinberger is admitted to the District of Columbia
 and Ohio Bars and is admitted to practice before the United States Tax Court.</td></tr> </table>
