<HTML><TITLE>Enterprise for the Environment Initiative</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org//images/3resear.gif"></p>

<H2>Enterprise for the
Environment Initiative</H2><p>

<h3>Project Updates</h3>

<a href="#4">October 25, 1996</a><br>

<a href="#3">July 10, 1996</a><br>

<a href="#2">June 10, 1996</a><br>

<a href="#1">May 15, 1996</a><p>

<hr>


<b><a name="4">DATE:	October 25, 1996</a><br>
TO:	Interested Parties -- FYI<br>
FROM:	William Ruckelshaus, Chairman<br>
RE:	Enterprise for the Environment Update </b><p>

	I am pleased to report that we had a very productive and lively third Steering Committee meeting and second Plenary Session on October 2-3.  There has been considerable progress made in each of the four Action Groups,  in the NAPA case study selection process, and in the International Perspectives Project.  Before I summarize this progress, I'd like to address the importance of outreach in this project. <p> 
 
	A strong outreach and communications effort is essential to the success of the Enterprise for the Environment.  Project updates such as this one are one important element of our effort.  If you encounter additional persons who would like to receive them, please encourage them to pass on their rolodex information (including e-mail addresses) to Mike Farrar or James O'Brien at the Center for Strategic & International Studies (202/775-3267 phone; 202/467-0357 fax; Internet: <a href="mailto: mcf@csis.org">mcf@csis.org</a>).<p> 

<b>ACTION GROUP PROGRESS</b><br>   

	Action  Group 1 has adopted a three part agenda.  The group is looking at:<p>
<ul><li>1) designing and implementing  a goal-based decision-making process within EPA; 
<li>2) improving resource allocation consistent with these goals; and
<li>3) using environmental indicators as mechanisms for measuring the performance of the environmental management system.</ul>

At this stage, the stakeholders are focusing on the effectiveness of the current goal-setting process and developing options for improvements to the current system.<p>

	Action Group 2  is addressing standard-setting by developing a "Framework for Environmental Decision-Making."  This framework articulates four types of objectives for managing environmental problems, including:  Baseline Protections, Aspirational Goals,  Milestones to Reach Aspirational Goals, and Maintenance of Quality Environments.  The Action Group is deliberating on the criteria to be used for defining and achieving these objectives, including the role of cost, risk, equity and enforceability and the process for establishing and periodically reviewing these objectives.<p>

	Action Group 3 is exploring internal corporate decision-making in order to identify the  internal and external incentives/disincentives for companies to enhance environmental performance.  One  tool that the Action Group is considering is auditing, specifically, how to encourage small and medium businesses to audit, how to design sector-specific audits for such businesses and how to incorporate beyond compliance elements into audits.  The group will also build on recent work by the Aspen Institute and others in exploring "alternative compliance"/alternative pathways to boost environmental performance while increasing flexibility.  Finally, the Action Group is identifying the ways in which regulations may create barriers to enhanced performance and how to structure a regulatory system to encourage enhanced environmental  performance. <p>

	Action Group 4 is looking at incentives for environmental performance which are generally outside of EPA's purview, including: economic incentives, trade policies and the effect of information  on capital markets.  The group will also explore broader information issues concerning  how environmental information is gathered, analyzed, and released.<p> 

<b>NAPA CASE STUDIES AND INTERNATIONAL PERSPECTIVE PROJECT</b><br> 

	The expert panel convened by the National Academy of Public Administration has made three initial selections of case studies of innovation in environmental protection.  These case studies are a key part of NAPA's analytic support to the Enterprise for the Environment.  The case studies are: 
1)  EPA's Performance Partnership Agreement with New Jersey; 2) community-based environmental management in the Clarks Fork River watershed; and 3) early results of Project XL as reflected in the Intel's Arizona Plant proposal.  The NAPA panel will select three additional case studies later in November.  These case studies will provide valuable input to the work of the Action Groups.   Additional input is being provided in a series of roundtable discussions at CSIS conducted by the International Perspectives Project.  These discussions have brought together experts in policy innovations occurring in other countries.<p>

<b>NEXT STEPS </b><br>
	Much work lies ahead for the Steering Committee and the Action Groups.  November and December will be very busy months.  The next Plenary Session is scheduled for late January.  We are aiming to meet our timeline calling for completion of the project in April 1997.  I'm happy to note that the Mott Foundation and the Surdna Foundation recently awarded grants to the Enterprise for the Environment, recognizing the importance of the work we have undertaken. Thank you for your interest in this effort. <p>
<hr>


<b><a name="3">DATE:	July 10, 1996</a><br>
TO:	Stakeholders in the Enterprise for the Environment<br>
FROM:	William Ruckelshaus, Chairman<br>
RE:	Project Update and Next Steps III</b><p>


	This is the third in a series of updates on the Enterprise for the Environment that I will send regularly to all stakeholders describing the status of the project and next steps.<p>

	The second Steering Committee meeting of the Enterprise for the Environment took place on June 20.  It was a successful and productive meeting.  Attached are the minutes of the meeting which include a short summary for your convenience.<p>

	The meeting produced guidance on draft workplans for the Action Groups that had been prepared by the Group co-chairs and the project staff.  The next step is to convene the Action Groups and begin their work.<p>

	The Keystone Center, working with CSIS and the Action Group co-chairs, has completed the assignment of various stakeholders to Action Groups.  We were not able to assign all stakeholders to the Action Groups for which they expressed their highest preferences; however, we made every effort to satisfy as many preferences as possible.  Keystone facilitators are in the process of contacting you and your staff to notify you of the first Action Group meetings later this month.  Keystone is also recruiting a few select additional stakeholders to ensure that each Action Group has appropriate balance.<p>

	I look forward to seeing you at our next Plenary Session on October 2-3, and I am confident that the Action Groups will make substantial progress in the weeks ahead.	To ensure that all stakeholders have the correct dates on their calendars, I have attached the current schedule of future Plenary Sessions.<p>

	Thank you again for your support of the Enterprise for the Environment, and for the commitment of your personal time and attention.  With many of our organizational and membership issues resolved, we can turn to the challenging substantive work before us.<p>
<hr>

<b><a name="2">DATE:  June 10, 1996</a><br>
TO:	Stakeholders in the Enterprise for the Environment<br>
FROM:	William Ruckelshaus, Chairman<br>
RE:	Project Update and Next Steps II</b><p>


	This is the second in a series of updates on the Enterprise for the Environment that I will send regularly to all stakeholders describing the status of the project and next steps.<p>

	First, I would like to share with you some additional thoughts about certain fundamentals related to the project.  These thoughts are spurred in part from the discussions at the first Plenary Session and in part from subsequent conversations I have had with various members and project staff.  <p>

	Critical to the success of the Enterprise for the Environment is creating balance in its principles, goals, membership, and leadership.  The underlying principle of the project has a dual character.  "Cleaner, cheaper" is not a slogan -- it is truly a guiding principle.  Our environmental management systems (both public and private) must evolve in ways that produce higher levels of environmental protection and that promote more flexible, performance-based, cost-effective approaches to reaching these levels.  This is the vision set forth in the recent report of the President's Council on Sustainable Development, and it is the vision that guides the Enterprise for the Environment.  The most recent Project Summary captures this principle well, as it relates to the goal of developing recommendations in three areas: 1) transformation of EPA's environmental management system, with particular emphasis on its statutory base; 2) mechanisms that promote higher levels of responsibility, accountability, commitment, and stewardship in businesses regulated by EPA; and 3) changes to key economic policies to promote a cleaner environment as an integral component of our economy.  I am intent on ensuring that the "cleaner, cheaper" principle guides the work of the Action Groups as well.<p>

	Balance in membership requires the project to add additional stakeholders from the environmental community, including environmental justice groups.  I'm happy to report that, subsequent to my last update to you (May 15), two additional environmental groups have joined the project: the Natural Resources Defense Council and Friends of the Earth.  Project staff continue to hold discussions with several other potential stakeholders, and I am confident that we will secure additional participation.  I am also committed to creating balance in the membership of the Steering Committee and in the ranks of the Action Group co-chairs.<p>

			   Critical to the success of the Enterprise for the Environment is a well-		    	    designed, balanced, and well-managed process of consensus-building.  The Keystone Center excels in this task, which is why I asked Keystone to join CSIS and NAPA in this undertaking.  Keystone will design, lead, and manage the stakeholder process, and will facilitate all meetings.<p> 

	Another factor vital to a good process is the full engagement of the members.  We have assembled a talented and experienced group of stakeholders.  We need to ensure that the members themselves are actively participating, and are the driving force behind the project.  Members' staff can assist the process, but they cannot substitute for the members, even when discussions delve into "the details" (where the devil often lies).  I expect that it will be appropriate for various interested parties to attend some meetings and be allowed to comment on the proceedings.  Such comment can be helpful but will never substitute for the hard work required by project members.  The Keystone Center has prepared a draft set of groundrules for participation in the project.  I have attached this draft and your comments and suggestions would be helpful as we finalize it. <p> 

	One last process issue worth emphasizing is the role of the Steering Committee.  The role of the Steering Committee is to synthesize and integrate the work of the various Action Groups.  The Committee is also the starting point for consensus-building.  Consensus reached in the Steering Committee will be taken to the larger stakeholder group in a effort to gain the broadest support possible. <p> 

	Finally, success is dependent on a high-quality, fact-based work product.  The work of the Action Groups and the Steering Committee must be grounded in solid research and analysis, and on careful problem definitions -- "solutions" cannot wander in search of problems.  Solutions must address real problems.  Given that some policy recommendations may involve proposals for statutory change, it is particularly important that any such  recommendations be based on careful legal analysis of what policy changes require legislative versus administrative actions. <p>   

<b>NEXT STEPS</b><br>
	Nearly all of you have returned your Action Group Preference Forms as requested in my May 15 memo.  Keystone, working with CSIS, is close to finalizing Action Group membership, in consultation with the Action Group co-chairs.  We are not able to assign all stakeholders to the Action Groups for which they expressed their highest preferences; however, we made every effort to satisfy as many preferences as possible.  Upon finalizing these memberships, Keystone facilitators will contact members and, working with the co-chairs, set up the first meetings.<p>

	Later this month, the Steering Committee will meet to review the overall direction of the project and the draft workplans for the Action Groups that project staff have been developing in consultation with the co-chairs.  After receiving Steering Committee input, Action Group co-chairs will take the workplans to their initial Action Group meetings for further input and final shaping.<p> 
          
	Let me close by thanking each of you for your support of the Enterprise for the Environment, and for the commitment of your personal time and attention.  With many of our organizational and membership issues nearing resolution, I look forward to working with you as we move forward on the challenging substantive work before us.<p><hr>

<b><a name="1">DATE:	May 15, 1996</a><br>
TO:	Stakeholders in the Enterprise for the Environment<br>
FROM:	William D. Ruckelshaus <br>
RE:	Project Update and Next Steps</b><p>




	This is to update you on the progress of the Enterprise for the Environment since the April 1-2 Plenary Session, and to describe the next steps in the project.<p> 

	A high priority for the project staff and me in the wake of the April Plenary has been to recruit additional environmental groups as members of the Enterprise for the Environment.  Over the past month, we renewed existing contacts and established new contacts with a half dozen national organizations, and we engaged in extensive discussions with several of these groups.  Over the course of those discussions, we jointly developed a broadened agenda for the project, incorporating many of their ideas and those from the Plenary.  This broadened agenda is described in the enclosed Summary.  Despite this progress, I regret to say that we have yet to reach agreement on participation by additional national environmental groups.<p>
     
	It is my belief that, having agreed in the discussions with several of these groups to broaden the project's agenda, it is appropriate for us to continue on this path.  Their contributions to this agenda have improved it.  We will continue to seek the participation of additional environmental groups as we move forward.  In addition, we will make every effort to incorporate the views of these national environmental groups and keep them fully informed of our deliberations.  But whether or not such organizations participate, it should remain our intention to see this project to a productive and timely conclusion.  Both the need for genuine reform, and the likelihood of a "window of rationality" opening early in the next Congress, are great.  High quality recommendations from a broad-based, responsible process will appeal to reasonable people from both parties, and could form the basis for a comprehensive reform effort.<p>

<b>NEXT STEPS</b><br>
	We are in the process of convening the Action Groups to begin their work.  I have enclosed a revised description of each Group's scope of work that lists some of the questions that the various groups might explore.  The Action Groups are similar in structure to those proposed back in April.  Some of you have already expressed your interest in particular Groups, but you should quickly review this document once more and confirm your preferences for serving on those Action Groups. <p>

		 	   The plan for moving forward is as follows.  By this memo, each Stakeholder is being asked to complete the attached form indicating your preferences for serving on specific Action Groups.   Please FAX the form back to the project office at CSIS no later than Wednesday, May 22.    We will use the completed forms to organize the Action Groups.  In deploying the available experts and interests effectively, it may well turn out that not all members can be given their first choice.  Accordingly, please be sure to indicate your alternative preferences.  Some Steering Committee members may wish to participate only at the Steering Committee level; others may wish to participate in Action Groups as well.  The form permits Steering Committee members to indicate their preference in this regard.  Finally, the form allows members to request more information on the International Perspectives Project, which will analyze environmental management systems in other countries, and will develop insights for the Action Groups.<p>

	Project  staff will notify you no later than Wednesday, May 29, of your Action Group assignment.  Following this, Action Group co-chairs, working with project staff and in consultation with members, will develop work plans and meeting schedules.  The Steering Committee, at its June 20th meeting, will review work plans from the Action Group co-chairs and approve an overall work plan for the project.  A draft set of milestones is enclosed to give you a rough idea of the timelines necessary in delivering our product.  Again, thank you for participating in this worthwhile and necessary project. <p> 

