</DOCHDR>
<HTML><TITLE>Enterprise for the Environment Initiative</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org//images/3resear.gif"></p>

<H2>Enterprise for the
Environment Initiative</H2><p>

<h3>Project Summary</h3>
<p><hr><p>


<table cellpadding=15>
<td width=150 valign=top>
<font size="2">For additional information contact:<p>

<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hausker.html">Karl Hausker</a><br>
CSIS<br>
(202) 775-3267<p>

John Ehrmann,<br>
The Keystone Center<br>
(970) 468-5822<p>

DeWitt John,<br>
NAPA<br>
(202) 347-3190
</font></td>


<td valign=top>
<b>Introduction</b><p>

	Three trends have developed as America has pursued environmental cleanup programs over the past 25 years.  First, strong national environmental laws and expanded state and local programs have produced major progress in abating many of the more visible forms of pollution.  Second, the rigidity of many of these laws and regulations has produced growing frustration within the regulated community and beyond.  Third, the environmental community and others have objected to the faltering pace of efforts to address new environmental goals and to implement incomplete existing programs.  While America has made an impressive journey in the last 25 years, the road ahead is strewn with obstacles that will prevent continued success unless they are removed.<p>

	The problems of regulatory rigidity and the faltering pace of achieving environmental objectives are widely acknowledged but the nation has made little progress in addressing either problem. In large part, this has occurred because various interests have pursued solutions to one of these problems but not both, perceiving progress on one problem as detrimental to progress on the other. To move forward, diverse stakeholders must work together to seek integrated changes in the regulatory process and in key economic policies which, in combination, can enhance environmental performance and decrease regulatory rigidity. <p>

	Several broadly endorsed principles should guide the evolution of the environmental protection system:<br>
<ul>
<li>The environmental protection system needs to become more effective, efficient and equitable without undermining the strengths that have ensured the progress made over the last 25 years.  To accomplish this it should become more goal-based, performance-based, and flexible, with accountability mechanisms to ensure full performance.

<li>Change is needed to ensure that the policies and practices of businesses, non-profits, government agencies, and individuals will promote a healthy environment and continued economic progress. Members of the regulated community need to achieve higher levels of responsibility, accountability, commitment, and stewardship as the environmental protection system evolves.

<li>Changes to the existing environmental protection system should not be considered in isolation.  It is important to identify and change other key economic policies, including taxation, subsidies, trade, energy, transportation, agriculture, and research and development which have an indirect but powerful effect on the behavior of the regulated community and society as a whole.  As changes to the existing system are considered, changes to these other policies and practices should be integrated into a new environmental protection system to assure that economic and environmental goals are pursued in harmony.</ul><p>

<b>The Enterprise for the Environment</b><p>

	William  D. Ruckelshaus, former Administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, is chairing a policy forum, entitled "Enterprise for the Environment", that focuses on improving the regulatory process and environmental performance drivers that influence behavior in the areas EPA was created to address.   The project will aim to build a broad, durable, bipartisan consensus for comprehensive reform and improvement of the environmental protection system and the economic policies that drive public and private decisions affecting the environment.  Parallel to the three principles above, Enterprise for the Environment will develop sound, concrete policy recommendations in three areas: 1) transformation of EPA's environmental protection system, with particular emphasis on its statutory base; 2) mechanisms that promote higher levels of responsibility, accountability, commitment, and stewardship in businesses regulated by EPA; and 3) changes to key economic policies to promote a cleaner environment as an integral component of our economy.  These three areas are discussed in more detail in the sections below, as are the links among them.<p>

<b>Transforming EPA's Environmental Protection System</b><p>

	The environmental laws Congress enacted and amended in the 1970's and 1980's responded to public pressure for environmental improvement and frustration with the nation's slow progress in meeting environmental goals.  Because of the strong goals and authorities in these laws, major reductions in air and water pollution and improved management of hazardous waste have occurred.  Through these laws, however, Congress has created high expectations that have been difficult for EPA to fulfill for a variety of reasons.  Collectively, the laws place enormous responsibilities on EPA, yet the Agency rarely has had the resources to match its workload.  Splintered congressional committee jurisdiction over EPA hinders coordination, integration, and rational oversight.  Some provisions of these laws have been criticized as highly prescriptive, containing directives and statutory deadlines that critics argue inappropriately restrict the agency's ability to exercise judgment, set more effective priorities, or coordinate programs.  The result is that regulatory approaches often are perceived as rigid and inefficient, insensitive to the needs of local communities, failing to take advantage of new pollution prevention techniques, and not delivering the desired improvement in the environment.<p>

	Building on the strengths of existing laws, Enterprise for the Environment will develop recommendations that seek to integrate EPA's authorities, and that give EPA a coherent, well-defined statutory mission and the tools to carry it out.  The recommendations will aim to transform EPA's environmental protection system into one that is goal-based, performance-based, flexible, and accountable.  A transformed system will empower EPA to deliver higher levels of environmental protection at lower cost.  The Enterprise will pay particular attention to the Agency's statutory framework, given its powerful role in shaping the broader environmental protection system.  However, all recommendations will be based on careful analysis of what changes require legislative versus administrative actions.<p> 
 
<b>Strengthening Responsibility, Accountability, Commitment, and Stewardship</b><p>

	The Enterprise for the Environment will develop recommendations to transform the complex set of incentives and disincentives which influence corporate decision-making on environmental management issues.  The project will examine efforts in the areas of industrial ecology and pollution prevention (e.g., the Pollution Prevention Pilot Project -- a collaborative effort of the Natural Resources Defense Council, the New Jersey Dept. of Environmental Protection, and four major corporations). The project may examine other initiatives such as the Valdez Principles and the Responsible Care program of the Chemical Manufacturers Association as methods to spur higher levels of environmental protection.  <p>

	These examinations will produce an understanding of the internal and external barriers to investments in pollution prevention that improve protections while reducing costs.  This understanding, in turn, will inform the project's efforts to  transform EPA's environmental protection system.  It will also inform recommendations on mechanisms that promote higher levels of responsibility, accountability, commitment, and stewardship in businesses regulated by EPA -- a necessary corollary to change within EPA.<p>

<b>Reshaping Economic Drivers to Support Environmental Excellence</b><p>

	The decisions that businesses make with an eye toward short-term profitability may conflict with decisions that reflect a long-term societal perspective and  promote sustained environmental health and economic prosperity.  To reduce this conflict, Enterprise for the Environment will develop recommendations for changes in key economic policies that exert powerful influences on actions with environmental consequences.<p>

	It is well-understood that government policies in the arenas of taxation, subsidies, trade, energy, transportation, agriculture, and research and development all shape private sector investment decisions and business practices (as well as community development decisions).  However, there has been little concerted effort to date to identify changes in these policy areas that could reward environmentally superior decisions and discourage unsustainable practices.  Without change to these powerful economic influences, modification of the regulatory system alone would not provide a secure path to the high quality, sustainable environmental future Americans demand and expect for this generation and those that follow. <p>

	Enterprise for the Environment will proceed from the recognition that environmental protection strategies must include changes in key economic policies, but will go beyond previous efforts by formulating specific recommendations for changes in these policies that will support a more flexible, performance-based public environmental protection system.  The project will focus on economic policies that influence behavior in areas EPA was created to address.<p>

<b>Project Design</b><p> 

	Taken together, recommendations in these three areas can provide a path to a system of environmental protection that promotes mutually sustaining goals: a cleaner environment; more effective, less expensive, more flexible, and more equitable tools for meeting environmental standards; greater consensus-building and partnership in setting and achieving environmental goals; economic policies that reinforce and promote environmental protection; and greater public confidence in government and the regulated community.<p>

	Three institutions are collaborating in Enterprise for the Environment: the Center for Strategic & International Studies (CSIS), The Keystone Center, and the National Academy of Public Administration (NAPA). CSIS will convene an inclusive stakeholder process designed and facilitated by the Keystone Center.  The stakeholder process will aim to develop the specific policy recommendations. CSIS and NAPA will provide analytic support to the stakeholder process, including an independent NAPA panel report on efforts by EPA and others to promote more effective and efficient environmental management. Using a stakeholder process supported by solid, independent analysis, Enterprise for the Environment aims to create a broad, durable, bipartisan consensus on comprehensive reform and improvement of the nation's environmental protection system.<p>

	The Chairman of the project, Mr. Ruckelshaus, and the institutions involved, are securing the participation of members of Congress, and leaders from EPA, state and local government, business, the environmental community, and other essential constituencies.  If  these diverse interests can find agreement, the project will deliver a package of timely recommendations to Congress and the Administration during the 105th Congress.<p>
</td>
</table>

<p>

<HR>

