<HTML><TITLE>Enterprise for the Environment Initiative</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org//images/3resear.gif"></p>

<H2>Enterprise for the
Environment Initiative</H2><p>

<h3>Action Groups</h3>
<i>Topics and Leadership</i>
<hr><p>

<b>Action  Group #1 -- Setting a Course:  Goals, Priorities and Resource Allocation</b><p>

		This group's three-part agenda involves looking at (1) designing and implementing  a goal-based decision-making process within EPA; (2) improving resource allocation consistent with these goals; and (3) using environmental indicators as mechanisms for m
easuring the performance of the environmental management system.<p>

  		The leadership of this Action Group consists of three co-chairs:<br>

<ul>
<li>Curt Spalding, Executive Director of Save the [Narragansett] Bay
			
<li>Jim Strock, Secretary of the California Environmental Protection Agency and former Assistant Administrator for Enforcement of U.S. EPA

<li>Bob Sussman, partner in the law firm of Latham & Watkins
and former Deputy Administrator of U.S. EPA</ul><p>		


<b>Action Group #2 -- Setting Standards:  Meeting Goals with Efficiency and Fairness</b><p>

	This group is addressing standard-setting by developing a "Framework for Environmental Decision-Making."  This framework articulates four types of objectives for managing environmental problems, including:  Baseline Protections, Aspirational Goals,  Mile
stones to Reach Aspirational Goals, and Maintenance of Quality Environments.  The Action Group is deliberating on the criteria to be used for defining and achieving these objectives, including the role of cost, risk, equity and enforceability and the proc
ess for establishing and periodically reviewing these objectives.<p>

It is led by two co-chairs:<br>

<ul>
<li>Lee Thomas, Senior Vice President, Georgia-Pacific Corporation and former Administrator, U.S. EPA

<li>Christine Gregoire, Attorney General, State of Washington</ul>
<p>


<b>Action Group #3 -- Enhancing Environmental Performance and Flexibility</b><p>

	This group is exploring internal corporate decision-making in order to identify the  internal and external incentives/disincentives for companies to enhance environmental performance.  One  tool that the Action Group is considering is auditing, specifica
lly, how to encourage small and medium businesses to audit, how to design sector-specific audits for such businesses and how to incorporate "beyond compliance" elements into audits.  The group will also build on recent work by the Aspen Institute and othe
rs in exploring "alternative compliance"/alternative pathways to boost environmental performance while increasing flexibility.  Finally, the Action Group is identifying the ways in which regulations may create barriers to enhanced performance and how to s
tructure a regulatory system to encourage enhanced environmental  performance. <p>

Its two co-chairs are:<br>

<ul>
<li>Linda Fisher, Vice President, Federal Government Affairs, Monsanto Co. and former Assistant Administrator of U.S. EPA

<li>Linda Greer, Senior Scientist, Natural Resources Defense Council</ul><p>



<b>Action Group #4 -- Reshaping Environmental Drivers to Support Environmental Excellence</b><p>

	This group is looking at incentives for environmental performance which are generally outside of EPA's purview, including: economic incentives, trade policies and the effect of information  on capital markets.  The group will also explore broader informa
tion issues concerning  how environmental information is gathered, analyzed, and released. <p>

Its two co-chairs are:<br>

<ul>
<li>Bob Burt, Chairman, President and CEO, FMC Corporation

<li>Jonathan Lash, President, World Resources Institute
and Co-Chair of the President's Council on Sustainable Development</ul>


<p>
