<html>
<title>International Communcations Studies Program</title>
<body text="#000000" body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3resear.gif"></center>
<p>
<img align=left src="http://www.csis.org/images/icslogo.gif"><center><BR><h2>International Communications<br>
Studies Program</h2>
<p>
<a href="#Overview">Overview of the ICS Program</a><br>
<a href="#Priorities">Program Priorities</a><br>
<a href="#Contact Info">Contact Information</a><br>
<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/icsteam.html">ICS Team</a></center>
<p>
<hr>
<a name="Overview"><h3>Overview of the ICS Program</h3></a>

The CSIS International Communications Studies Program has a long track record of assisting senior-level policymakers in both developing and industrialized countries in addressing the impact of changing technological, political, and market dynamics. The ICS Program gives priority to bringing together government officials and industry leaders on an equal footing. ICS reports, forums, and seminars provide analysis and first-hand insights into the issues affecting the rapidly evolving telecom, broadcast, and
information service industries in a global context. ICS work is designed to promote effective strategic planning and workable policy initiatives for both government and industry.
<p>
ICS operates as a catalyst for action as well as analysis. Each year, it targets cutting-edge issues and technologies in the context of policy reforms and market applications. Where feasible, ICS also responds to invitations from governments and industry sectors to spearhead joint forums and analysis. In addition to activities focused on industrialized countries in Europe, Asia, and Latin America, ICS is expanding its work with "nations in transition" such as China, South Africa, and India.
<p>
As outgrowths of its forums, roundtables, and seminars, ICS has published over 25 major reports covering a diversity of issues, including <i>Microchips, Markets, and Madonna: The New Multimedia Mix</i>; <i>The New European Satellite Smorgasbord: Dishing Up Policies & Technologies of the 90's</i>; <i>The New Spectrum Mudwrestle</i>; <i>Telecommunications Policy: Issues for a New Administration</i>; and <i>Wireless World Wonders: Untethering the Marketplace</i>. ICS work involving "nations in transition" is
 internationally recognized for its groundbreaking precedents and far-reaching recommendations. <i>Eastern Europe: Please Stand By</i>, the report of the U.S. Task Force on Telecom and Broadcast in Eastern Europe chaired by <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4dougan.html>Ambassador Diana Lady Dougan</a> (ICS Chair), continues to be widely used as a blueprint for development and policy reform in both the telecom and broadcast sectors. A parallel landmark initiative under ICS leadership was the convening of
the first government-industry colloquium with the ministers of communications of all the former Soviet republics following the disbandment of the USSR.
<p>
Recent international initiatives launched by Ambassador Dougan under ICS auspices include the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/2giic.html">Global Information Infrastructure Commission</a> (GIIC) and the Center for Information Infrastructure & Economic Development (CIIED). The GII Commission is an independent, nongovernmental body composed of industry leaders from developing and industrialized countries dedicated to promoting policies and practices that foster the effective development and application of global information infrastructure. CIIED, a permanent center based in Beijing, was established in 1995 at the invitation of the prestigious Chinese Academy of Social Sciences. CIIED's Board includes senior policy officials from all the relevant ministries and actively involves diverse international industry experts.
<hr>
<a name="Priorities"><h3>1996-1997 Program Priorities</h3>
The 1996-97 ICS Program builds on the momentum of its ongoing activities and initiatives. High priority will be given to supporting the mandates and goals of the GIIC and CIIED. Activities are grouped in three major areas:
<p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li><a href="#Cyberspace">Restructuring for Cyberspace: Moving Countries from Theory to Reality</a></li><br>
<li><a href="#Electronic Commerce">Globalization of Electronic Commerce</a></li><br>
<li><a href="#Iiq">Information Intelligence Quotient - The IIQ&copy;</a></li><br>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>
<a name="Cyberspace"><h4>1. Restructuring for Cyberspace: Moving Countries from Theory to Reality</h4></a>
<b>Background</b>: Over 50 countries are currently developing or implementing massive reform of their telecom laws and regulations to attract investment, infrastructure development, and service offerings. Companies and countries are also restructuring to respond to, or to co-opt, the new dynamics of multimedia market potential, on the one hand, and the still-remaining basic telephone network requirements on the other.
<p>
<b>Importance</b>:  Restructuring the incumbent public network and enabling alternative technologies and networks are economically complex and politically sensitive issues in virtually all countries. Although there are no perfect models, a number of countries are moving from theory to practice with varying degrees of success. In addition to aiding government policymakers appraise their options, lessons derived from
these countries' experiences can be vital strategic planning tools for customers and providers of communications technologies and services.
<p>
<b>Purpose</b>:  To facilitate direct dialogue and cooperative analysis among private and public sector decision makers; to promote responsive policy options and "models that work"; to assess "real world" impacts of telecom and broadcast restructuring in targeted countries; and to enhance strategic planning capabilities of both government and industry.
<p>
<b>Areas of Focus and Activity</b>: In addition to periodic in-depth forums and analysis papers, ICS will continue its practice of convening informal sessions with senior government officials and industry experts to provide timely attention to fast-breaking legislation and events.
<p>
<blockquote><i>Europe</i>: The commitment of the European Union to liberalize basic telecommunications services by 1998 has generated a fast-paced timetable. At the request of the French and German governments, ICS will convene Washington-based briefings and government/industry roundtables on those countries' new telecommunications legislation. Other European restructuring initiatives will also be featured.<br>
<p>
<i>Asia</i>: The top ICS priority continues to be China. Work carried out through the ICS China Bridge  Project and CIIED will focus on areas of regulatory policy and market restructuring. In follow-up to Ambassador Dougan's in-depth meetings with Vice Premier Zou Jiahua, PTT Minister Wu Jichuan, and other senior Chinese officials, ICS has accepted the invitation to provide assistance in China's examination and analysis of diverse country models and policy options in drafting new laws. CIIED and ICS are developing a series of seminars and workshops examining selected country models and case studies. Scheduled to commence in the fall of 1996, this series will include special lectures and sessions with industry experts and regulators from diverse countries. In addition to forums held at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences in Beijing, under whose auspices CIIED operates, study missions and pilot projects in specific provinces will be considered. Advance papers, reports, and case studies generated for China will also be tailored to other countries that have requested assistance.
</blockquote>
<a name="Electronic Commerce"><h4>2. Globalization of Electronic Commerce</h4></a></center>
<b>Background</b>: "Electronic commerce" is becoming the biggest driver, not just a passenger, on the information highway. This past year, the combination of expanding Internet access and customer-friendly software has turned electronic commerce into a major force in the global marketplace. The ad-hoc, non-hierarchical structure of the Internet has enabled new forms and extensions of commercial activity to evolve largely outside the traditional rules of trade, commerce, and sovereignty. As each industry sector attempts to rationalize its own "rules of the road," governments are ill-equipped to assess the emerging policy and regulatory implications in the broader context. Privacy, ownership, rights, tariffing, and access are just a few of the issues that take on new ramifications in electronically generated or facilitated commerce.
<p>
<b>Importance</b>:  Because electronic commerce is rapidly changing the dynamics and overturning traditional modes of global trade, new ground rules are required to balance effectively new technological and market realities with accepted trade and economic practices.
<p>
<b>Purpose</b>:  To build on the principles adopted in the Beijing Declaration and Call for Action Statement on "Advancing Globalized Electronic Commerce."  Developed under the joint auspices of the GIIC, CIIED, the People's Bank of China, and the Ministry of Electronics Industry in the spring of 1996, the Beijing Declaration provides a pragmatic framework for action. This ICS project will build on the Statement's four principles:
<ul>
<li>increased private-sector leadership in cooperation with governments;</li>
<li>expanded access to the tools of electronic commerce to developing countries; </li>
<li>broad commitment to appropriate legal and regulatory frameworks; and,</li>
<li>rapid transformation of banking and currency management systems.</li>
</ul>
<b>Areas of Focus and Activities</b>:  During 1996-97, the ICS Electronic Commerce Project proposes to
<ul>
<li>facilitate development of common definitions and identify policy options that enhance cross-border electronic commerce. To initiate this work, a forum will be convened in early fall in conjunction with the American Electronics Association to review recent industry studies and recommendations.</li>
<li>analyze what should or can be most effectively done on a voluntary basis by industry rather than by governments. This work will include consideration of electronic commerce ramifications of the World Trade Organization negotiations on liberalizing basic telecommunications services (GBT). ICS will also propose priorities for issues that should appropriately be addressed by multilateral (WTO, ITU, WIPO), bilateral, or voluntary industry agreements.</li>
<li>coordinate one or more follow-up forums and issue papers on specific application aspects of electronic commerce. Already under consideration are</ul>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>a special session with Finance and Central Bank Ministers to be held in conjunction with the October IMF/World Bank meeting. This forum and companion analysis papers will address currency and monetary policies needed to facilitate transborder electronic commerce. </li>
<li>a spring 1997 forum in Shanghai-Pudong in cooperation with CIIED and the People's Bank of China on electronic banking in newly industrialized regions.</li></blockquote>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>publish a critique of perceived cultural and political barriers to cross-border access to Internet and "intranet"-based services. Specific countries will be featured as case studies.</li>
</ul>
<a name="Iiq"><h4>3. Information Intelligence Quotient - The IIQ&copy;</h4></a>
<b>Background</b>:  Electronic communications now reaches far beyond traditional networks, customers, and content providers. Current definitions and measurements of infrastructure, access, and use are inadequate and increasingly misleading in this rapidly changing environment. For example, despite the rapid
introduction of other versatile and increasingly competitive technologies such as cellular, V-sat, and cable, basic telephone density remains the centerpiece of infrastructure measurement. At the Harvard Internet and Society Conference in May 1996, Ambassador Dougan called for the development of an "IIQ" -- Information Intelligence Quotient -- to replace outdated definitions and measurements of communication infrastructure development and use and to support more effective planning and policy development.
<p>
<b>Importance</b>:  By using a common set of benchmarks, both government and industry can better measure and understand the impact of specific policies, practices, and technologies from one country or sector to another. Such benchmarking is especially important when the traditionally regulated telecom, cable, and broadcast industries are being restructured.
<p>
<b>Purpose</b>: To develop a framework for a flexible, comparative measurement that will support analysis,
planning, cooperation, and decision-making. The IIQ will be designed as a strategic tool for both governments and industry to measure and benchmark policies and technology options in three areas: 1) infrastructure; 2) access; and 3) use. The IIQ could also be utilized in the work of the GIIC as part of its legacy.
<p>
<b>Areas of Focus and Activities</b>: The IIQ project will be undertaken in cooperation with several of the GIIC's affiliate organizations to ensure a broadly gauged and useful framework. These include: NECTEC (Thailand), CIIED (China), Harvard University (U.S.), CSIR (South Africa), and other appropriate research organizations. The methodology is to be developed during fall 1996 with project work to commence in spring 1997 and to extend over a two-year period. Work products will include research, reports, presentations, and conferences.
<hr>
<a name="Contact Info"><h3>Contact Information</h3>
<p>
<A HREF="mailto:ics@csis.org">
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="http://www.csis.org/images/mail1.gif"></A>
Questions? Comments?  The International Communications Studies Program may be reached at: <b><A HREF="mailto:ics@csis.org">ics@csis.org</A></b>.
<p>
<blockquote><STRONG>International Communications Studies Program<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.csis.org">Center for Strategic and International Studies</A><BR>
1800 K Street,  Washington, D.C.  20006<BR>
Phone: (202) 775-3263 Fax: (202) 775-0898<BR></STRONG>
</blockquote>
<p>
