</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>December ICIB</title>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3pubs.gif"></center>
<p>
<h2><i>International Communications In Brief</i></h2>
December, 1996
<hr>
<h3>CIIED Seminar Explores Issues of Interconnection and Access Charges<i> -- Dec. 2, 1996</i></h3>
<p>
China is making unique strides for national communication and information modernization. The Ministry of Post and Telecommunications is rapidly building fibre optic, microwave, and satellite communication networks for nationwide voice, data, and advanced services, while more than 30 government organizations or state companies are operating and upgrading their own  dedicated networks. The multi-network environment indicates that China faces a critical challenge of network interconnection.
<p>
To examine network interconnection issues, a special forum was held on December 2, 1996 in Beijing by the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/2ciied.html">Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development (CIIED)</a>, which is co-established by CSIS and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences. The plenary session featured speakers from the Chinese State Council Development Center, the MPT, US West, Cable & Wireless, Mitsubishi, and Matsushita. At the subsequent breakout discussions, senior officials from the MPT, China Unicom, the Ministry of Railways, the Ministry of Electronic Power, and various international companies addressed issues of regulatory frameworks for interconnection and access charges, and the impact of relevant policies on service provision. The forum involved more than 110 participants representing 30 Chinese government organizations and business entities, as well as numerous foreign companies.
<p>
<hr>
<h3>Mobile Satellite Conference<i> -- Dec. 3, 1996</i></h3>
<p>
Two expert panels addressed regulatory and implementation issues that have arisen concerning the "Big LEO" satellite systems.  The first group presented a report on the World Telecommunications Policy Forum held at the ITU in October, bringing together representatives of government and industry to explore options for resolving those issues, particularly the licensing of these systems. Forum participants endorsed 10 voluntary principles for licensing to guide national regulators and adopted a Memorandum of Understanding regarding user terminals required by the systems. In an important departure from traditional ITU procedure, the MOU can be signed by private sector parties, not just governments. The panelists noted that the private sector played a more active role in this deliberation than in most ITU proceedings and that the forum contributed to a generally receptive attitude on the part of many developing countries toward the  LEO systems. These countries were able to raise and to discuss issues of concern rather than being required to adopt rules or binding positions.
<p>
The second panel of representatives of all five proposed Big LEO systems underscored wide variation in system design - for example, from 12 satellites in two systems to 840 in another. Reflecting the generally positive assessment given by the first panel, the industry representatives were optimistic concerning the reception of their proposed services by countries with developing economies. Once issues related to the systems' impact on matters such as bypass, sovereignty and national security are better understood, the panelists expressed belief that policy makers in those countries will resolve issues related to licensing and type approval relatively easily as the systems represent a flexible, low-cost alternative to expensive wireline infrastructure.
<p>
<hr>
<h3>Minister Fillon: "France Ready for the Globalization of Telecom Exchanges"<i> -- Dec. 4, 1996</i></h3>
<p>
In a major address hosted by the ICS program at CSIS, French MPT Minister FranÁois Fillon touted the new French telecommunications legislation as second only to the UK in creating an open and deregulated market. According to the minister, the two main components of the reform are a new regulatory framework to establish open competition in the sector and a modification of the status of France Telecom to transform it into a public limited company. Fillon stated that the passage in July of the telecommunications act allowed France to be "totally open to free market and competition in the telecommunications sector."  One of the main points of the new law allows for an open and transparent licensing system that will permit all those with capability to enter the market, without any limit on the number of licences.
<p>
Minister Fillon also praised the creation of a new regulatory authority due to enter into effect on January 1, 1997.  This body will have three essential powers in guiding the regulation of the industry. First, it will lead the preliminary process for license applications and will allocate the frequency and number resources required by operators to carry out their business. Second, it will settle disputes related to interconnection between operators and will set the level of interconnection tariffs.  Third, the authority will have the power to impose financial penalties on operators who fail to observe their obligations under the regulations. In short, according to Minister Fillon, "the regulatory authority will have the capability, from the time of its creation, to ensure the development of competition that is effective, innovative, fair, and beneficial to users."
<p>
For more information, please contact Mr. Christopher P. Foss of the ICS Program on 202.775.3177.
<p>
