<HTML><TITLE>Enterprise for the Environment Initiative</TITLE>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><p align="center"><img
src="http://www.csis.org//images/3resear.gif"></p>

<H2>Enterprise for the
Environment Initiative</H2><p>

<h3>Press Release</h3>
<i>
Contacts:</i><br>
								<a href="http://www.csis.org/html/4hausker.html">Karl Hausker</a> (CSIS)	202\775-3267<br>
								Philip Angell (BFI)	202\223-8151<br>
								Rich Innes (BFI)	202\223-8151<p><br><p>

<h3><p align="center">Project to Transform the Environmental Management System</p></h3>

<b>Washington, D.C. (April 17, 1996)</b>: <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/e4e/ruckbio.html">William D. Ruckelshaus</a>, Chairman of Browning-Ferris Industries, Inc. (BFI) and former Administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) announced today that the "The Enterprise for the Environment," a broad-based effort assembled to develop a comprehensive set of recommendations to transform the environmental management system, held its first meetings April 1st and 2nd.<p>

Ruckelshaus described the project in testimony before the U.S. House Appropriations Subcommittee on VA, HUD and Independent Agencies.  The Subcommittee is chaired by Congressman Jerry Lewis (R-CA).<p>

"The purpose of this effort," said Ruckelshaus, "is to transform the environmental management system by developing a well defined statutory mission for EPA and evaluating incentives for exemplary corporate environmental performance; the result will be a cleaner environment at a reasonable cost.  What we have now is a regulatory system that is perceived as rigid and inefficient, insensitive to the needs of local communities, and that fails to take advantage of new tools which maximize environmental benefits while reducing costs."<p>

The Enterprise for the Environment will be coordinated by the Center for Strategic & International Studies (CSIS) and the National Academy of  Public Administration (NAPA), whose recent report to Congress on EPA will serve as the starting point for the project.  The Keystone Center of Colorado will facilitate certain aspects of the project's work.<p>

"The process for achieving this," said Ruckelshaus, "must acknowledge that the vast majority of Americans place a high value on a clean environment, and that they expect their government to assist in delivering this at a reasonable cost ... Any successful consensus-building process, if designed properly, will include a truly representative group of stakeholders and will be conducted in an open and honest forum.  The project will rely heavily on its greatest asset: the talent and experience of its diverse members."<p>

The Enterprise for the Environment will consist of a steering committee, a number of stakeholder working groups, and a NAPA-convened expert panel.  Membership will be drawn from a wide range of interests, including Members of Congress, governors, mayors, state regulators, and leaders from environmental groups, business, labor, as well as participants from such diverse interests as agriculture, transportation, energy, economics, social justice and the law.<p>

"We think this effort will succeed where other efforts in the past decade have failed," Ruckelshaus stated.  "We have a waiting audience for our work.  Those who have the power to act on our recommendations want our recommendations," he continued.  "The leadership in Congress has given us their encouragement and cooperation.  The EPA, as well, is supportive of our effort."<p>

The group expects to deliver its recommendations to the Congress and the Administration in early 1997.


<p>
