<html>
<title>WTO Forum ICIB</title>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3pubs.gif"></center>
<p>
<h2><i>International Communications In Brief</i></h2>
December 17, 1996
<hr>
<h3>Experts Assess Prospects for WTO Telecom Agreements</h3>
<p>
Government and industry experts expressed guarded optimism this week about the current World Trade Organization (WTO) negotiations on liberalizing global telecommunications services. They spoke at a December 17 conference at CSIS, "Global Telecommunications Liberalization: Who Will Benefit?" cosponsored by the CSIS International Communications Studies Program, the Coalition of Service Industries, and the <a href="http://www.gii.org">Global Information Infrastructure Commission (GIIC)</a>. The conference followed the close of the WTO Ministerial Meeting in Singapore.
<p>
FCC Chairman Reed Hundt, said that a successful conclusion will not be easy: "If these talks degenerate into limited commitments to allow competitive provision of yesterday's services - but not tomorrow's - then we will have missed a great opportunity to bring advanced telecom services to every corner of the globe. And, if too few countries guarantee investment rights, then the opportunity to build the global information highway may be lost."
<p>
Don Abelson, chief U.S. negotiator, pointed out that there is now momentum towards a successful conclusion by the Feb. 15 deadline. 16 countries announced new offers at the Ministerial, representing a "major improvement." Summarizing the U.S. position, he said: "We are seeking the kind of offers of a caliber that the U.S. has put on the table, including provision of market access for all services on a technologically neutral basis, together with full opportunity for foreign investment."
<p>
<a href="http://www.gii.org/egi00162.html">Bowman Cutter</a>, chair of the GIIC steering committee and managing director of E.M. Warburg, Pincus & Co., observed that financial markets will provide strong incentives for compliance with a trade agreement because non-participating or non-complying nations will face severe difficulty in financing telecom-munications expansion.
<p>
Program participants agreed that significant developments taking place outside the negotiations could affect their outcome. Among them are:
<p>
<i>The FCC's new proposals on international accounting rates.</i> The proposals, announced by the FCC the next day, would lower the benchmark settlement rates that U.S. international carriers negotiate with each country for the origination and termination of international traffic. Peter Cowhey, senior counsel at the FCC International Bureau, pointed out that, while lower benchmarks are not a total solution to distortions in international telecom rates, they can help by reducing "the financial fuel" that sustains wide pricing asymmetry between competitive and non-competitive markets. Erik Olbeter of the Economic Strategy Institute said that a new ESI study indicates that 70 percent of settlement rates are above actual cost. Abelson observed that the FCC proposals will assist in reaching a trade agreement as they will compel pro-competitive pricing reform and will not be compromised through the trade negotiations.
<p>
<i>Information Technology Agreement.</i> Gary Hufbauer of the International Institute of Economics pointed out that the likely agreement on information technologies can strengthen the telecom talks by demonstrating how to square most-favored-nation principles with market reality in the information industries.
<p>
<i>What if the current negotiations fail?</i> Al Lewis, director of federal affairs for AT&T, believed that pressures from telecom users around the world will eventually force resumption of the negotiations. Bob Kramer of the Bank of America suggested that a partial agreement incorporating a base-line minimum could still be valuable because achieving a telecom agreement should provide renewed impetus for concluding a financial services agreement.
<p>
Brian Moir, senior counsel to the International Communications Association, stated that to be successful, an agreement must result in pro-competitive regulatory policies, cost-balanced rates, increased choice and quality of services, and elimination of barriers to technology, functions, and new entry. U.S. firms will need to monitor foreign implementation measures very closely, in the face of obvious temptations to delay or avoid a pro-competition mandate in the agreement. Alexander Sierck of Cameron and Hornbostel stated that U.S. firms need to prepare specific evidence and legal strategies for protecting their opportunities under the regulatory schemes of other countries. This will strengthen a given company's chances if it decides to take its case to the USTR for submission to the WTO disputes settlements process.
<p>
For more information, please contact Mr. Christopher P. Foss of the ICS Program on 202.775.3294.
<p>
Return to the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/">ICS Home Page</a>
