<html>
<title>Liu Cai ICIB</title>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><img src="http://www.csis.org/images/3pubs.gif"></center>
<p>
<h2><i>International Communications In Brief</i></h2>
December 11, 1996
<hr>
<h3>China's MPT Director General Outlines Issues for New Telecom Law</h3>
<p>
"We're laying the foundation for an information society in China." This was the theme of an in-depth briefing and question and answer session featuring Liu Cai, director general of Policy and Regulation of China's Ministry of Post and Telecommunications (MPT), held at CSIS on December 11.
<p>
Director General Liu and other senior-level delegates from the State Council, National People's Congress, and MPT met with CSIS as part of their assessment mission on U.S. legal and regulatory reforms in telecommunications. Liu, who has lead drafting responsibility for new telecommunication law, said it will take 8-9 months to draft law, but expects to send it to State Council and National Peoples Congress for consideration by end of 1997.
<p>
Legislation is needed, Mr. Liu said, to strengthen the structural framework for China's current telecom expansion. Telecom growth in China has averaged 50 percent annually in the last five years with more than a $60 billion investment in telecom facilities by the turn of the century. 94 percent of transmission lines and 99 percent of the switches including rural are digitalized according to Liu.
<p>
Despite this progress, Chinese telecom development is hampered by outmoded legal and regulatory constraints. "We need to work hard to meet different levels of demand for information transfer." The proposed telecom law will be part of this effort, Mr. Liu said. He cautioned, however, that installation fees would cover 30-40% of investment needed and remain a centerpiece of basic MPT system financing.  He did not dismiss private investment in the embryonic competing UNICOM system.  According to Liu, the legislation will address the following objectives:
<ul>
<li>maintaining the current pace of expan-sion, focusing on telecom's role as a multiplier of economic growth;</li>
<li>decentralizing the present structure of telecom enterprises;</li>
<li>assuring availability of advanced tech-nology, both from foreign sources and expanded domestic R&D facilities;</li>
<li>strengthening competition among foreign and domestic suppliers of network equip-ment, including the possible introduction of open bidding; and</li>
<li>encouraging improvements in financing telecom expansion, including changes in user-pricing patterns.</li>
</ul>
<p>
Regulatory reform at the central government level will tackle difficult problems of what Mr. Liu called "the three separations." They are (a) separating the MPT's postal and telecommunications units; (b) separating MPT's regulatory and operational functions, and (c) separating telecom manufacturing functions from service obligations. He noted likely transformation of the Ministry of Electronics Industries into an "association." He also predicted more network development decisions being devolved to provincial and municipal administrations.
<p>
Director General Liu also serves on the Advisory Board and Governing Council of the Center for Information Infrastructure and Economic Development (CIIED) which operates under the auspices of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and CSIS based in Beijing. CIIED's Board is co-chaired by Diana Lady Dougan of CSIS and Dr. Liu Guoguang of CASS.
<p>
For more information, please contact Mr. Christopher P. Foss of the ICS Program on 202.775.3294.
<p>
Return to the <a href="http://www.csis.org/html/ics/">ICS Home Page</a>
