<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> urgent/women.htm </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>Urgent Action:</I>
<P>
Sexual Harassment in the Name of the Law</B></FONT>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2.5><B>Violence and Degradation by Israeli Police
During Searches of Palestinian Homes in Hebron</CENTER></B></FONT>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2></FONT>
<I> Please write letters to the authorities listed below and/or distribute this information
as widely as possible. </I>
<P>
B'Tselem has released a report documenting house searches in ten Palestinian
apartments in Hebron, which included discriminatory and degrading strip
searches. The security forces forced fifteen Palestinian women, ranging in
age from 20 to 69, to undress from head to toe in the presence of women
soldiers and/or policewomen. In two instances, women were required to
undress in full vision of a male police officer.  Thirteen children, aged
one month to 14 years old, were also undressed.  In some cases, women were
compelled to undress in front of their relatives, their children and other
children.  The fact that most of the families involved are traditional and
religious, and that female honor is an important concept in Palestinian
society, makes what would be a degrading experience for any woman even more so.
<P>
Violence, threats and insults accompanied the order to undress in several
cases.  Women who initially refused to completely undress (including a
seven-month pregnant woman) were beaten.  Although men were  present in most
of the apartments, only one man was also required to undress.
<P>
The fact that only women and children were ordered to undress, while in
every case but one the men were not required to undergo this degradation,
indicates that this measure was taken to humiliate the women and their
families.  This together with the contemptuous and violent treatment of the
residents and their property, and the fact that almost none of the residents
were detained reinforce the suspicion that the violence and degradation were
intentional and totally unrelated to security needs.
<P>
B'Tselem urges the Israeli government to end this conduct:
<P>
1. The government must unequivocally instruct its security forces not to
order women to undress, and not to offend their honor in any other way; the
government must instruct its security forces that during house searches,
they must safeguard personal property and refrain from causing damage;
<P>
2.  If directives exist allowing such conduct, the authorities must
immediately revoke them and take measures against those who instituted them;
<P>
3. The authorities must thoroughly investigate the events described in this
report and prosecute any soldier or police officer who engaged in wrongoing.
<P>
Although B'Tselem has written to the authorities responsible and distributed
its report to the press, the problem continues.  The day B'Tselem issued
this report, Israeli police searched another house in Hebron and strip
searched four women.  None of the men in the house were required to undress.  
<P>
<B>Letters of concern should be sent to:</B>
<P>
Minister of Internal Security, Avigdor Kahalani, Fax: 972-2-5811832 
<P>
with copies to:
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Fax: 972-3-697-6218
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Fax: 972-2-566-4838 
<P>
See B'Tselem's complete report, which includes testimonies of ten women.

<HR>
