<DOCNO>WT10-B39-196</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA046-000817-B018-510</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/press/961119_1.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119021811 text/html 7431
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 02:17:06 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7260
Last-modified: Sat, 30 Nov 1996 21:32:35 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - November 19, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
                                       
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - November 19, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Military Court in Jaffa: <BR>
Value of a Palestinian's Life - Four Agorot (US$ 0.01) </B></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
 
                              
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Y</B></FONT>esterday the Jaffa military court gave its verdict in the case of the four
undercover soldiers who had been accused of negligently causing the death of
Iyad Mahmud 'Awal Amali. The court rejected the plea bargain, proposed by
the prosecution and defense, which provided that the defendants would be
sentenced to a conditional sentence of 30 days for a period of one year, and
imposed on each of the defendant's a fine of one agora.
<P>
B'Tselem contends that the judgment, the judges' statements, and the
position taken by the prosecution indicate an intolerable forgiveness,
inconsistent with the rule of law, of the judicial system in cases where
Palestinians are killed.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
The Case
</B></FONT>
<P>
Iyad Amali was killed on 13 November 1993 while traveling in an automobile
near Salfit village, Nablus District. Testimonies given to B'Tselem by two
persons who were with Amali at the time indicate that the checkpoint was not
properly marked, and that the driver of the car did not realize it was a
military checkpoint and that he was supposed to stop. Bilal Yehiye 'Abd
Al-Fatah 'Amal, the driver, stated in his testimony:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
... After we had gone about 1 1/2 kilometers from Salfit... I started to
ascend, and at the top I saw lots of lights and spotlights, which
prohibited me from traveling any further. I stopped because I couldn't
see. Suddenly, a fellow got out of a car with a searchlight and
directed it at me, and then the shooting started, lots of shooting. I
bent over and saw blood on Iyad's face, and I realized he had been wounded.
I heard the front windshield shatter. I started to yell: "Who are
you? You wounded my friend." Someone answered in Hebrew: We are soldiers."
They approached with searchlights in their hands, and for that reason I
couldn't see who they were.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Open-Fire Regulations
</B></FONT>
<P>
The IDF's regulations for opening fire at a motor vehicle that were in
effect in the Occupied Territories at the time of Amali's death explicitly
stipulate that: 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"It is prohibited to fire at the suspect's vehicle unless the checkpoint is
positioned conspicuously and illuminated at night - so that the driver is
able to distinguish that the site is a checkpoint of the IDF, or of the
security forces, from a  distance that enables the driver to slow down and
stop in front of the checkpoint."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
The regulations also explicitly stipulate that:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"when a vehicle reaches the location of an IDF checkpoint and the vehicle
backs up and flees (and does not break the   barricade), firing is
prohibited unless there is a concrete suspicion based on the circumstances
or on reliable   information, that one of the passengers is suspected of
committing a dangerous crime."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
In the Amali case, the soldiers did not have a concrete suspicion that any
of the passengers in the vehicle were involved in a dangerous crime, and the
shots were fired from a checkpoint that had not been properly set up.
Although the driver did not realize that a checkpoint was in front of him,
he had stopped his car; nevertheless, the soldiers opened fire and killed
Amali. It is patently clear that the shots were fired in violation of the
regulations. 
<P>
In their verdict, the court's majority held that "in the situation in the
field, we would act as the undercover unit acted." This statement indicates
an utter disregard for
human life, and it is doubtful if someone who justifies the killing of an
innocent person should be a judge. Killing an innocent person in total
violation of the written regulations should be strongly censured, and
certainly should not serve as a model for future conduct.
<P>
The willingness of the military prosecutor to enter into a plea bargain that
would have resulted in a conditional sentence of 30 days imprisonment for
the crime of illegal use of weapons raises doubts about the seriousness in
which the military handles violations of the open-fire regulations. The
prosecution's intention to appeal the lightness of the sentence is not
particularly encouraging, because even if its appeal is accepted, it is
unlikely that the subsequent sentence would be heavier than that of the plea
bargain.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Statistics
</B></FONT>
<P>
From 9 December 1987 to the end of August, 1996, Israeli security forces
killed 1251 Palestinians, among them 262 children under the age of 16.
Pursuant to the open-fire regulations, the only case in which firing to kill
is permitted is where the shooter is in a life-threatening situation.
B'Tselem knows of 55 members of the Israeli security forces who have been
prosecuted in cases in which Palestinians have been killed. From these 55 cases:
<UL>
<LI>    in 3 cases, those involved were convicted of manslaughter;
<LI>    in 16 cases, those involved were convicted of causing death by negligence;
<LI>    in 2 cases, those involved were convicted of maltreatment and causing
	bodily injury;
<LI>    in 12 cases, those involved were convicted of illegal use of weapons;
<LI>    in one case, those involved were convicted of disgraceful conduct;
<LI>    in one case, those involved were convicted of negligence in performing
	their duty;
<LI>    in 10 cases, those involved were found not guilty;
<LI>    in 5 cases, an indictment was filed, but the trial has not yet ended;
<LI>    in one case, the indictment was withdrawn.
</UL>
These statistics indicate that in over one thousand cases of deaths of
Palestinians, not even one person was indicted for causing the death. Since
it is unlikely that in each of these cases the soldiers were in concrete and
immediate life-threatening situations, which is the only instance in which
the regulations permit firing to kill, the number of cases in which the
open-fire regulations were violated is substantially higher than the number
of indictments filed.
<P>
Almost total disregard of violation of the open-fire regulations transmits a
message to soldiers that breach of the regulations, which lead to numerous
deaths, is permitted and would be accepted with understanding. Yesterday's
military court's judgment, which imposed symbolic punishment on soldiers who
had been found guilty of having killed a human being only reinforces this
conclusion and raises the question of the importance the military gives to
human life.


<P>
<HR>
