<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - November 4, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
                                       
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Speak Up for Academic Freedom </B><BR>
 A Public Campaign for Gaza Students' Right to Education </FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
 
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT>s university students throughout the world begin a new academic year, many
Palestinians from the Gaza Strip are being denied their basic right to
education. Out of a total of 1,200 students from the Gaza Strip who are
enrolled in West Bank universities, not one has been granted the permits
necessary to attend their universities.
<P>
The blanket restriction imposed by Israel on hundreds of Gazan students,
without a shred of evidence that they threaten the security of Israel,
consitutes collective punishment and violates their basic rights to
education and freedom of movement.  This policy increases the cost of
education, thereby hindering the advancement of Gazan society.  Furthermore,
these restrictions contradict the letter and spirit of the Oslo agreements
signed by Israel and the Palestinians and hinder the development of peace
and stability in the region.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Background
</B></FONT>
<P>
Over 900,000 Palestinians live in the Gaza Strip.  The two Gaza universities
have a combined enrollment of 8,000 students.  These institutions offer only
limited fields of study and cannot accommodate all qualified Gazans who want
to pursue higher education.   As a result, 1,200  Gaza residents study at
the six West Bank universities.  Gaza students comprise 7% of the student
body of West Bank universities.
<P>
Israeli-imposed travel restrictions are not new.  In 1991, Israel first
imposed an extended closure on the Occupied Territories, sealing off the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.  Since that time, even when a total closure is not
in place, Palestinians are only allowed to enter Israel or East Jerusalem by
obtaining a special permit.  These permits are usually issued for a single
day, but can be issued for up to a maximum of three months. Without a
permit, Palestinians are also unable to travel between the West Bank and
Gaza as Israel lies in between.
<P>
Although the closure and its accompanying permit system has been in place
since 1991, Israel has never established clear and transparant regulations
to govern the process.  On the contrary, the permit process is highly
arbitrary and overly bureaucratic.  Palestinians who want to travel from
Gaza to the West Bank must first undergo a rigorous security check to
receive the magnetic identity card necessary to leave the Gaza Strip.
Second, they must obtain a permit to travel through Israel.  Palestinians
who wish to stay overnight in the West Bank must obtain a third permit.
Applicants who are denied any of these permits are not informed of the
reason for denial, nor given an opportunity to appeal.  All travel permits
are cancelled each time Israel imposes a total closure on the Occupied
Territories.  
<P>
Since the imposition of a total closure in March 1996, following a series of
suicide-bombings inside Israel, Gaza students have not even enjoyed the
problematic permit system described above.  Even after this closure was
relaxed, all Gazans requesting permits to travel to the West Bank to study
have been rejected; Israel has not allowed a single Gaza student to attend a
West Bank university for the 1996/7 school year.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Gazan Students in The West Bank: A Security Threat to Israel?
</B></FONT>
<P>
Israeli officials use security considerations to justify travel restrictions
on Gaza students. In response to a recent inquiry, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai responded that, "for security reasons, we cannot allow Gaza
residents to study at West Bank educational institutions." In fact, however,
there is no legitimate security basis for denying Gaza students the right to
study in the West Bank.  
<P>
While Israel has a right to decide who enters its borders, Gaza students are
not interested in entering Israel.  Gaza students are only requesting to
cross through Israel to reach West Bank universities and to remain in the
West Bank for the period of their studies. If certain students are thought
to pose a security risk, this risk could be eliminated by providing them
with a security escort from Gaza to the West Bank at the beginning of each
semester.
<P>
The Israeli authorities do not restrict the movement of individual Gaza
students whom they suspect pose a security threat to Israel. All students
are restricted, even those who have passed all necessary security checks.
This suggests that limitations on Gaza students are not based solely on
security concerns, but are also intended as a punitive measure against Gaza
students as a group.  Such a measure constitutes collective punishment,
which inevitably increases the despair and hopelessness among Palestinian
youth.  This can only have negative implications for Israel's security.
<P>
As an Israeli organization, B'Tselem fully appreciates the need and
obligation of the Israeli government to adopt protective measures to ensure
the security of its citizens.  However, these measures must comply with
international law, including human rights principles and agreements which
Israel has signed.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
The Cost of an Education
</B><FONT>
<P>
As a result of delays in the issuance of permits at the beginning of 1995/6
academic year and the cancellation during the closure, Gaza university
students were allowed to attend their West Bank universities for a total of
three months out of the previous academic year and for none of the current
year. 
<P>
The myriad of obstacles preventing Gaza students from obtaining an education
cause tremendous hardships.  Even when a total closure is not in force,
permits may be cancelled or not renewed in the middle of a semester, causing
students to miss course work or final exams.  Many students, determined to
continue their studies, remain in the West Bank without the necessary
permits, risking detention if apprehended by Israeli security forces.
Students who return to the Gaza Strip for family visits may not be able to
get back to the West Bank.  
<P>
All of these hardships increase the time and money needed for a Gaza student
to complete a degree, raising the cost of higher education for the
individual and for Palestinian society as a whole.
<BLOCKQUOTE>

        The last time I went home to Gaza was 11 months ago, for 2 days. I 
        haven't gotten a permit since 1992. It's a very unpleasant feeling 
.... I'm here without a permit, always worried and feeling under attack ...
It really
        affects our studies.... At any minute, we could be caught at a
checkpoint, 
        and then we're finished, our whole future is ruined.<BR>
        <NOBR>        --- Nasser Hamed, 26 years old, in his final semester of<WBR>
studies for  a B.A. in Business at Bir Zeit University</NOBR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
A Breach of International Law and the Oslo Agreements
</B></FONT>
<P>
Preventing Gazan students from exercising their basic right to study in West
Bank universities blatantly violates internationally recognized rights to
education and freedom of movement.  This policy denies students these right
without due process of law and violates the internationally accepted
principle that an individual cannot be punished for the actions of another. 
<P>
In addition, this policy contravenes obligations undertaken by Israel in the
Israeli-Palestinian Accords. The agreements stipulate that the Gaza Strip
and West Bank comprise a single territorial entity. Israel undertook in
these agreements to provide "safe passage connecting the West Bank with the
Gaza Strip for movement of persons, vehicles and goods." Israel has not
provided this safe passage.
<P>
A peace process based on human rights violations is fragile and vulnerable
at its core. It is imperative, therefore, that the international community
acts to ensure that human rights are made an integral part of the peace
process. 
<P>
Now is the time for Israel to realize that security can and must be
protected without violating basic human rights. It is time to realize that
an equitable coexistence between Israelis and Palestinians based on mutual
respect of fundamental human rights is the only basis for a just, secure,
and lasting peace.
<P>
<HR>
