<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Newspaper Advertisement - October 29, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
                                       
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Newspaper Advertisement - October 29, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Human Rights Under Curfew </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><NOBR>
The following is the <B>second</B> in a series of paid advertisements 
<WBR> published by B'Tselem in the Hebrew dailies, <I>Ha'aretz</I> and <I>Yediot Aharonot </I></NOBR></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
 

Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, in his speech to the United States Congress: 

<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT COLOR=red>
"The time has come for countries in the Middle East to place human rights
and democracy on their agendas."</FONT> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B>                         
The Facts:
</B></FONT>
<P>

During nearly 30 years of occupation, Israel has created almost total
Palestinian dependence
on Israel by limiting development of economic, employment, and medical
infrastructure in
the Occupied Territories.
<P>
Since 1991, Israel has severely restricted the freedom of movement of
Palestinians in the Occupied
Territories, preventing most of them from entering Israel and East Jerusalem
and from travelling
between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank. At times, Israel has imposed a
total closure which
does not allow any Palestinian to leave the West Bank or the Gaza Strip. 
<P>
The closure harms all aspects of daily life for the Palestinian population,
and causes, inter
alia, the elimination of sources of income, harm to sick persons, disruption
of family relations,
and economic losses.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
The Question:
</B></FONT>
<P>
Does not every nation have the right to restrict entry of foreigners? Yes, but:
<UL>
<LI>    In the Oslo Accords, Israel did not relinquish supreme authority in
	the Occupied Territories. 
      	It therefore must ensure the welfare, the means to make a living, and
	the health of the residents there.
<P>
<LI>    Israel does not have the right to restrict the Palestinians' freedom
	of movement within and between the Occupied Territories:
	<UL>
	<P>
      	<LI>    The closure does not allow for movement between the Gaza Strip
		and the West Bank. In the framework of the Oslo Accords, Israel recognized
		the West Bank and the Gaza Strip as one unit, and undertook to ensure safe
		passage between them; Israel has not fulfilled this undertaking.
	<P>
      	<LI>	The closure prevents entry of Palestinians from the West Bank
		and the Gaza Strip into East Jerusalem because Israel considers East
		Jerusalem as an integral
	        part of Israel. East Jerusalem is the medical, economic,
		religious and educational
            	center for Palestinians. According to international law and the
		entire international
            	community, the status of East Jerusalem is identical to that of
		the rest of the
            	West Bank, and Israel unilaterally ignores this fact.  
	</UL>
</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
The Conclusions:
</B></FONT>
<UL>
<LI>    Israel must enable free movement between the Gaza Strip and the West
	Bank, as required by the Oslo agreements.
<P>
<LI>    Israel must remove the restrictions on Palestinians entering East
	Jerusalem.
<P>
<LI>    Israel must ensure movement of sick persons from the Occupied
	Territories to medical facilities in East Jerusalem and in Israel.
<P>
<LI>    Israel must immediately act to ensure alternative sources of income
	for Palestinians who lost their jobs as a result of the closure. It
	must also provide unemployment benefits
	to Palestinian workers who made payments to the Israeli National
	Insurance Institute
      	over the years.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=red><B>
HUMAN RIGHTS MUST BE RESPECTED!
</B></FONT> 

<P>
<HR>
