<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - Auguts 26, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - August 26, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
B'Tselem  Calls on the Prime Minister: <BR> Cease  the  Abuses
Against Human Rights Activist Bashar Tarabieh
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n  a  letter  sent today, B'Tselem called on  the  Prime
Minister,   Mr.   Benjamin  Netanyahu,   concerning   the
detention  of Bashar Tarabieh, a Golan Heights  resident.
Mr. Tarabieh, works and lives in the United States and is
married  to  a  U.S. citizen.  He has worked  on  various
projects for the international organization, Human Rights
Watch.
<P>
Mr. Tarabieh was detained on 19 August while visiting his
family  on  the Golan Heights.  Since then  he  has  been
detained  at  the  Kishon Detention Center,  near  Haifa.
According to information provided by Human Rights  Watch,
Mr. Tarabieh has been interrogated by the Israeli General
Security Service about his work for the organization. The
interrogators have tied his hands and legs  to  a  chair,
forced  him  to stay in painful positions for hours,  and
covered  his  head with a filthy sack. The interrogators,
have  also threatened to confiscate Mr. Tarabieh's travel
documents, preventing him from leaving Israel.  They have
also  called the work of organizations like Human  Rights
Watch and B'Tselem 'lies.'
<P>
The reports add that the GSS is holding Mr. Tarabieh in a
tiny  cell,  does  not  allow him  to  shower  or  change
clothes, and does not feed him regularly.
<P>
B'Tselem strongly opposes the detention of a human rights
activist,  and particularly the interrogation  about  the
activist's   work   on   behalf   of   a   human   rights
organization. Such interrogation constitutes
a  violation  of  the right to organize of  human  rights
organizations.  The detention and interrogation are clear
attempts  to  deter  such organizations  from  monitoring
human rights abuses by Israeli authorities.
<P>
Human  Rights  Watch is a widely respected  international
organization  which reports impartially on  human  rights
violations throughout the world.
<P>
In  its letter, B'Tselem calls on the Prime Minister, who
is responsible for the operations of the General Security
Service,  to  direct  the GSS to stop  interrogating  Mr.
Tarabieh  concerning his work as a human rights activist.
B'Tselem  further urges the Prime Minister to direct  the
GSS  not to use methods of interrogation like those  used
on  Mr.  Tarabieh, which are degrading and inhumane,  and
consequently prohibited by international law.
<P>
B'Tselem  further calls on the Prime Minister  to  direct
the  immediate release of Mr. Tarabieh in the event  that
no   evidence  has  been  found  linking  him  with   the
commission of a crime.
<P>

                                                         



<P>
