</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - Auguts 18, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - August 18, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
                 B'Tselem Calls on Netanyahu: <BR>
          New Hebron Plan Must Consider Human Rights

</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n  a  letter  sent  to  Prime  Minister  Binyamin  Netanyahu,
<B>B'Tselem</B>  urged  the Israeli government to consider  seriously
the  human rights implications of any alternative redeployment
plan for Hebron.
<P>
As the Netanyahu administration debates changes to the Oslo-II
agreement  regarding Hebron, <B>B'Tselem</B> reiterates the  findings
of  its September 1995 report, "Impossible Coexistence:  Human
Rights  in  Hebron  Since the Massacre  at  the  Cave  of  the
Patriarchs."
<P>
<B>B'Tselem</B> found that the presence of the IDF in Hebron  led  to
flagrant violations of the human rights of Palestinians in the
city,  including shootings, beatings, housing demolitions  and
restrictions  on  the freedom of movement  and  religion.   In
addition,  the  Israeli  authorities  failed  in  their  legal
responsibility to protect the lives, integrity and property of
Hebron's Palestinian residents from repeated attacks by Jewish
settlers.
<P>
The  letter to the Prime Minister reminds that, "Hebron,  like
all  Jewish settlements in the Occupied Territories,  violates
international law.  Furthermore, the massive military presence
necessary to protect a tiny minority of Jewish settlers living
amongst a Palestinian population of 160,000 caused severe  and
frequent violations of Palestinians' human rights."
<P>
<B>B'Tselem</B>  stands by its conclusion of eleven months  ago  that
the  only acceptable way to protect human rights in Hebron  is
"to  dismantle  the  Jewish settlement in  Hebron  and  remove
Israeli security forces from the city."  <B>B'Tselem</B> said at  the
time: "This solution does not constitute a political position;
its goal is to put an end to violations of Palestinians' human
rights  in Hebron, many of which result from the existence  of
Jewish settlement in the city.  Any settlement in the city and
Israeli control over the city, wholly or partially, will  lead
inevitably to additional violations of the human rights of the
city's  Palestinian  residents."  This conclusion  holds  true
today.
<P>
Any  plan  which increases the portion of the city  under  IDF
control would not only fail to improve human rights in Hebron,
but  in  the city's explosive climate could drastically worsen
the  situation.   <B>B'Tselem</B> urged the  Prime  Minister  not  to
accept any plan which would compromise the human rights of any
resident of Hebron.
<P>
For  additional information, please call Eitan Felner:  972-2-
5617-271/4.



<P>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
