<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - Auguts 14, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - August 14, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
B'Tselem calls upon the Palestinian Authority to Release Muhammad Dahman,  Gaza Director of the Addameer Association and to Respect the Freedom of Speech and Association of Human Rights Organizations
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>
n a letter to Khaled al-Qidra, General Prosecutor of the Palestinian Authority, B'Tselem urges the release of Muhammad Dahman, Gaza Director of the Addameer Prisoners Support Association.  Addameer is an organization which provides legal assistance to Palestinian political prisoners and detainees held by both Israeli and Palestinian authorities.
<P>
Muhammad Dahman was arrested from his home in Gaza on the night of 12 August by the <I>Mukhabarat</I> (Palestinian intelligence).  He is being detained for 48 hours at the Soria prison in Gaza on suspicion of publishing wrong information concerning the death of Nahed Dahalan.  Dahman was detained following the publication of a statement by Addameer which states that Nahed Dahalan was found dead near his house on 7 August, 1996 after being summoned for nightly interrogation sessions over the course of several days.  Addameer called on the Palestinian Authority to investigate the circumstances of Dahalan's death.
<P>
Dahman's attorney, Raji Sourani, has been informed that Dahman will be tried by the State Security Court.  The proceedings of this court do not meet the minimum standards for a fair trial.
<P>
Mr. Dahman is the fourth Palestinian human rights activist to be detained by the Palestinian Authority following the voicing of criticism of the PA's human rights practices.  Raji Sourani, then director of the Gaza Center for Rights and Law, and Bassem 'Eid, then fieldworker for B'Tselem, were both detained for 24 hours and subsequently released uncharged.  Dr. Iyad Sarraj, Commissioner General of the Palestinian Independent Commission for Citizens Rights, has been detained three times in the past year.  Most recently, Dr. Sarraj was held for 12 days, forcefully interrogated and charged with drug possession and assaulting a police officer.  These detentions indicate a pattern in which the Palestinian Authority intimidates and silences its critics rather than addressing the substance of their allegations.
<P>
In its letter to al-Qidra, B'Tselem emphasizes the vital role which Palestinian human rights activists have to play in building a Palestinian society governed by human dignity and the rule of law.  However, their ability to fulfil this role is severely impaired if they are not free to monitor, document and criticize without fear of personal reprisal.
<P>
B'Tselem regards the detention of human rights activists with the utmost concern.  The detention of Dahman represents a violation of free speech and freedom of association.  B'Tselem calls on the Palestinian Authority to cease its attacks on human rights organizations and activists. 
<P>
For more information, please contact Jessica Montell, 02-5617271.

<P>

<P>
<HR>
