<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - August 7, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - August 7, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
B'Tselem Urges International Community to Bring Ehud Yatom to Justice
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>B'</FONT>Tselem</B> today called upon human rights 
organizations around the world to demand that any state in which Ehud Yatom 
is present arrest and institute criminal proceedings against him. The request 
follows the admission of Yatom, former senior officer of the Israeli General 
Security Service (GSS), that he killed Subhi and Majdi Abu Jamea, two of the 
Palestinians who hijacked an Israeli bus in 1984 in the "Bus 300 Incident." 
<P>
This is the first time that <B>B'Tselem</B> has requested foreign countries to 
detain an Israeli official.  It decided to take this unprecedented action 
because Yatom cannot be held accountable inside Israel due to the sweeping 
pardon granted to him and other GSS agents by then-Israeli President 
Mr. Haim Herzog for "crimes relating to the so-called 300 bus incident," 
and the upholding of the pardon by the High Court of Justice.
<P>
The entire handling of the "Bus 300 incident" remains a mark of shame upon 
the State of Israel.  The excessive tolerance that all governmental 
authorities - GSS heads, the Israeli government, the President, and the 
High Court of Justice - demonstrated towards the crimes committed by Yatom 
and his GSS associates perpetuates the view that Israel's security justifies 
the taking of human life and the disregard of the rule of law. This 
forgiveness is illustrated not only by the pardon granted to Yatom and 
others exempting them from criminal prosecution for murder, whitewashing 
of facts, and fabrication of evidence, but also in the promotion of Yatom 
within the GSS to the equivalent of the military rank of general.
<P>
As an Israeli human rights organization, <B>B'Tselem</B> believes it unacceptable 
that a person proudly claiming to have committed premeditated murder walks 
freely within Israeli society. Yatom's contention that he performed this act 
"with permission and authority" recalls the most loathsome regimes that 
justified committing heinous crime on the grounds of following orders.
<P>
Yatom's statements, as reported by <I>Yediot Aharonot</I> on 26 July 1996, also raise the fear that the murder he committed, upon the orders of the then-head of the GSS, was not exceptional, but rather among the accepted norms of conduct of the GSS. This fear is reinforced by the arguments of then-Attorney General Joseph Harish during the hearing before the High Court of Justice.  In explaining the government's interest in maintaining the confidentiality of the entire affair, Harish argued that GSS agents were threatening to reveal other such incidents, saying "we won't have any choice, and then we shall defend ourselves and tell everything from day one."   
<P>
Against the background of these statements, the lack of a public and unequivocal condemnation by the current Prime Minister and the head of the GSS of the murder carried out by Yatom and an assertion that Israel opposes such actions is liable to give the impression to Israeli society as a whole and security personnel in particular that murder "with permission and authority" is allowed.
<P>
Yatom's acts, which by his own admission include crushing the heads of Subhi and Majdi Abu Jamea with a large stone, fall within the definition of torture according to the United Nation's Convention against Torture.  According to <B>B'Tselem</B>, Yatom can be arrested and tried abroad on the basis of this Convention, which obligates states-parties to take into custody any person alleged to have committed torture and to ensure that criminal or extradition proceedings are instigated against him.  As of 1 May 1996, 96 countries are a party to this convention, including Israel, the United States, and all states of Western Europe.  Yatom's actions also constitute a blatant example of state sanctioned extrajudicial execution, which is a violation of customary international law.
<P>
In addition to its appeal to the international community,  <B>B'Tselem</B> urges the 
Israeli government to take the following measures in order to uproot the 
phenomenon of murder, torture, and other human rights violations by security 
forces:
<UL>
<LI> Ensure that Ehud Yatom does not serve in any public position;
<LI> Indicate publicly and unequivocally that the government of 
     Israel will severely punish anyone who, in the name of ensuring 
     State security, commits patently illegal and immoral acts;
<LI> Initiate legislation stipulating that persons who commit extra-judicial 
     execution, "disappearances," torture, and other gross violations of 
     human rights may not benefit from legal or administrative measures 
     that absolve them from criminal responsibility.
</UL>
Granting preventive immunity or subsequent pardon to members of the security forces is a primary cause of the continuation of human rights violations.  So long as persons who commit gross violations of human rights are allowed to kill and torture with impunity and with no threat of being held accountable for their actions, such crimes are liable to continue.
<P>
For more information, please contact Eitan Felner, 02-561-7271.

<P>
<HR>
