<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - August 6, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - August 6, 1996 </I></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>In a letter to the Minister of Internal Security, B'Tselem argues that 
closing the investigation file against Border Police undercover agents 
who killed Daud Shweiki is liable to encourage use of unjustified deadly 
gunfire.
<P>
In 13 files monitored by B'Tselem of killings by Border Police undercover 
units, 12 were closed with no indictments being issued.
</FONT></B>
<HR>
<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT></B>n his letter to <B>B'Tselem</B> of 4 August 1996, Mr. Eran Shender, head of the 
Ministry of Justice's Department for the Investigation of Police Officers, 
indicated that the investigation file against Border Police officers who shot 
and killed Daud Shweiki in Ras-al-Amud, East Jerusalem, on 6 June 1996, was 
"closed due to absence of fault."
<P>
According to Shender, the investigation's findings indicate that "an 
unfortunate and tragic combination of circumstances occurred in which those 
injured thought a car was being stolen, while the police officers believed 
that the men were terrorists." In conclusion, Shender wrote: "after 
considering the circumstances of the incident in all its aspects, I reached 
the conclusion that the officer who fired the shot did not commit any 
criminal act."
<P>
Following receipt of Shender's letter, <B>B'Tselem</B> requested that the Department 
for the Investigation of Police Officers allow it to review the investigation 
file.
<P>
On 6 June 1996, about 2:00 a.m., Border Police Undercover Unit officers shot 
Daud Shweiki, 28, director of maintenance services at Jerusalem's Laromme 
Hotel.  Shweiki died as a result of the shooting, which occurred near his 
home in East Jerusalem. His brother, Muhammad Shweiki, 18, was injured by 
the gunfire. 
<P>
<B>B'Tselem</B>'s investigation shows that the Shweiki family noticed a transit 
van with civilian license plates approaching their home. The driver parked 
the vehicle nearby and turned out the lights. Since someone had broken into 
their car the previous night, the Shweikis thought that the persons in the 
vehicle intended to break into their car. 
<P>
The Shweiki brothers, Daud, Wahaba, and Muhammad, and their father, Ya'qub 
Shweiki,  approached the parked transit van.  In their testimony to <B>B'Tselem</B>, 
Wahaba and Muhammad Shweiki stated that as they moved unarmed towards the 
vehicle, shots were fired at them from inside the vehicle, striking Daud and 
Muhammad.  Daud died from bullet wounds to his head and chest, and Muhammad 
was wounded in the hand and chest.
<P>
In his testimony to <B>B'Tselem</B>, the father noted that neither Muhammad nor 
Daud were armed or had any object in their hands which might have been 
mistaken for a weapon. He gave similar testimony to the police.
<P>
According to statistics compiled by <B>B'Tselem</B>, since the beginning of the 
Intifada, Border Police and IDF undercover units have killed 159 Palestinians 
by gunfire; 29 of these deaths occurred since the signing of the Oslo Accords. 
Of the 13 investigations into deaths by gunfire of Border Police undercover 
units, 12 were closed. <B>B'Tselem</B> has not received a response to its inquiry 
about the remaining file.
<P>
<B>B'Tselem</B> believes that the methods used by undercover units create a 
substantial likelihood that innocent persons will be injured. When 
security forces disguise their identity and carry deadly weapons into 
populated areas, the danger exists that an "unfortunate and tragic 
combination of circumstances" will occur, just as it did in Ras-al-Amud. 
By using these methods, undercover unit personnel knowingly endanger their 
lives, requiring them at times to use their weapons. Under such circumstances, 
the argument that the use of deadly gunfire was an act of self-defense is 
not persuasive.
<P>
<B>B'Tselem</B> believes that the decision to close this file sends a message to 
security forces that while the hasty and irresponsible use of gunfire against 
Palestinians may not be intended, it also is not unacceptable behavior for 
which punishment can be expected. This message is both immoral and illegal. 
The police and judicial authorities must repeatedly clarify to police 
officers their obligations in circumstances like those that the Border 
Police faced in this case.
<P>
For additional information contact Yizhar Be'er, 050-317-531.

<P>
<HR>
