<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - July 31, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I> Press Release - July 31, 1996 </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>
Fear of Torture to Death by Palestinian Authority
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>


<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Y</B></FONT>esterday, 30 July 1996, Mahmud Jamal Jumaiel, 
aged 26, hospitalized on 26 July at the government hospital in Ramallah 
after being held in detention by the Palestinian Coastal Police, was 
pronounced clinically brain dead. 
<P>
Jumaiel had been arrested in December, 1995 by the Palestinian Police and
interrogated about his activities on behalf of the "Fatah Hawks".  Since 
then he was detained in Jericho without legal actions being taken against 
him. Several times during his detention, Jumaiel went on hunger strikes to 
demand his release.
<P>
On the night of 26 July, Palestinian authorities informed Jumaiel's family 
that he had been transferred to the Palestinian Authority's Coastal Police 
Section at the Juneid Prison, in Nablus.  A few hours later he was admitted 
to Rafidiyye Hospital, in Ramallah, under a pseudonym, and was then 
transferred to the government hospital where physicians yesterday pronounced 
him clinically brain dead.
<P>
B'Tselem fieldworker, Bassem 'Eid, who visited Jumaiel yesterday at 
the hospital, saw marks of severe beating over Jumaiel's entire body, 
as well as burn marks on his chest.  'Eid spoke with Jumaiel's relatives, 
who stated that they had visited him on 26 July in Jericho, before he was 
brought to Juneid Prison, and that he was in good health at the time.
<P>
B'Tselem urges the Palestinian Authority to investigate the matter quickly 
and thoroughly to determine the circumstances of the injuries suffered by 
Mahmud Jumaiel, and to indict those responsible.
<P>
Additionally, B'Tselem urges the Palestinian Authority to issue directives 
preventing the use of torture and ill treatment during interrogation of 
suspects, and to open detention facilities to periodic visits by human 
rights organizations. 

<P>
<HR>
