<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - June 12, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - June 12, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
Reported Mistreatment of Dr. Eyad Sarraj: <BR>
B'Tselem Appeals to the European Union and
Requests to Meet With Dr. Sarraj in Detention</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>


<FONT SIZE=+2><B>R</B></FONT>ecent information obtained by B'Tselem suggests that Dr. Eyad 
Sarraj, Commissioner General of the Palestinian Independent Commission for Citizens' Rights, 
has been subjected to physical violence in his detention by the Palestinian Authority and may 
be in danger.  Dr. Sarraj reportedly managed to smuggle a message out of detention last night 
which stated that he had been beaten and fears for his safety.  The note also stated that his 
interrogators were attempting to elicit a confession from him for drug offenses.
<P>
B'Tselem sent an urgent letter to Mr. Enrico Nardi, Consul General of Italy, which holds the 
European Union Presidency, urging him to take immediate steps to secure Dr. Sarraj's safe 
release.
<P>
B'Tselem, together with six other Israeli human rights organizations, also sent a letter to 
Palestinian Attorney General Khaled Al-Kidra, requesting to meet with Dr. Sarraj in detention. 
The organizations are HaMoked: Center for the Defense of the Individual, Physicians for Human 
Rights, the Public Committee Against Torture in Israel, Defense of Children International, 
Rabbis for Human Rights and the Workers Hotline.
<P>
Dr. Sarraj is a well-known and longstanding human rights activist who has been vocal in his 
criticisms of the Palestinian Authority.  This is his third detention by the Palestinian 
Authority in the past six months.  B'Tselem is concerned that the Palestinian Authority may 
attempt to convict him on trumped up charges in order to silence his outspoken human rights 
advocacy.
<P>
B'Tselem took steps in response to the danger to Dr. Sarraj's safety and the lack of response 
from the Palestinian Authority to its prior appeals on Dr. Sarraj's behalf. In addition to 
its concerns about Dr. Sarraj as an individual, the freedom of human rights activists to 
operate in safety is a necessary condition for the creation of a just and democratic society. 
Palestinians cannot hope to enjoy basic rights if human rights advocates cannot speak out 
freely without fear of personal reprisals.

<P>
<HR>
