<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - April 17, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - April 17, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
                       B'Tselem Calls on Israel:<BR>
     Stop Bombing Civilian Settlements and Infrastructure in Lebanon <BR>
                Allow Residents to Return to their Homes
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>


<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n a letter sent to Prime Minister and Defense Minister Shimon Peres, B'Tselem urged the
Israeli government to cease immediately the shelling and bombing of settlements and civilian
infrastructure in Lebanon, and to enable the residents to return to their homes, from which
the IDF evacuated them.  B'Tselem said that it is aware of Israel's obligation to protect its
citizens as a result of recent events in northern Israel, and condemns the Hizballah shelling
of the Galilee.  However, the letter stated, a state must not take measures that severely harm
hundreds of thousands of persons who are not involved in any violent activity.
<P>
B'Tselem is an information center that documents human rights in the Occupied Territories,
and does not generally deal with Israel's activities in other areas. However, it said, it cannot
remain silent while basic rights of Lebanese citizens are being violated as a result of IDF activity.
<P>
The shelling and bombing of populated areas in Lebanon for some seven days has already
left dozens of local residents dead and hundreds wounded. The recent forced evacuation of
southern Lebanese towns and villages has turned thousands of persons into refugees, with all
the suffering that refugee status entails.  As Shimon Peres wrote in The New Middle East:
"No reasonable human being can remain indifferent to the plight of refugees ... men, women
and children fleeing in fear of their lives, with terror in their eyes and despair in their faces..."
(page 181). 
<P>
A fundamental principle of international law is that all parties to an armed conflict must distinguish
between military and civilian targets, and must not harm civilians.  In case of uncertainty
regarding a specific object, international law requires that the site be considered civilian.  During
the widescale evacuation of entire areas in southern Lebanon, the IDF proclaimed that Lebanese
residents who remain "do so on their own personal responsibility, and at the risk of their lives."
In spite of this declaration, Israel cannot shirk its obligation to refrain from acts that may injure
civilians.
<P>
Notwithstanding official statements, it appears that Israel is not refraining from attacking civilian
targets, particularly property and public infrastructure.  A notable example is the shelling of
the electric power station in Beirut a few days ago.  According to Peres, "the Hizballah damaged
the supply of electricity in Kiryat Shmonah, and we damaged the supply of electricity in Beirut."
Reprisals against civilians are explicitly prohibited by international law, and B'Tselem urged
Mr. Peres to order their immediate cessation.
<P>
<HR>
