<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - March 19, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - March 19, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
Letter to Prime Minister: House Demolition
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B>
Prime Minister and Defense Minister<BR>
Shimon Peres<BR>
Office of the Prime Minister<BR>
Jerusalem
</B>
<P>
Re: House Demolition
<P>
The High Court of Justice rejected the appeals of the families
of those who plan and conducted bombing attacks inside Israel. 
The Court ruled that the families' houses can be demolished.  This
decision removes the final legal barrier to the demolitions which
may begin tomorrow.
<P>
In spite of the legal sanction provided by the High Court, we
urgently appeal to you to reconsider execution of the demolitions.
<P>
B'Tselem recognizes Israel's right, indeed its obligation, to ensure
the security of its citizens.  However, demolishing the houses
of innocent Palestinians, including children, solely for their
relationship to those who conducted attacks is a blatant violation
of their human rights and in contradiction of international law.
<P>
Since the beginning of the intifada, 400 houses of Palestinians
have been demolished in the territories as a punitive measure.
However, this collective punishment did not cause a cessation of
the attacks.
<P>
Punishment of the innocent, as proven in the past, does not increase
Israel's security and violates the central moral principle that
"a child shall not be held responsible for the offenses of the
parent, nor the parent for the child."
<P>
<UL><UL>
                                   Sincerely,
<P>
                                   Yizhar Be'er<BR>
                                   Executive Director
</UL></UL>
<P>
<HR>
