<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - March 12, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - March 12, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
An Open letter to Participants in the Sharm-a-Sheikh Summit <BR>
<I> The War Against Terrorism: Not At the Expense of Human Rights </I>
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>B'</B></FONT>Tselem calls on all governments participating in the international summit at Sharm-a-Sheikh,
and in particular on Israel, to express their commitment to human rights and the rule of law,
alongside their strong denunciations of terrorism.  In the framework of the international struggle
against terrorism, all conference participants should unequivocally reject all measures which
constitute violations of basic human rights.
<P>
B'Tselem recognizes Israel's need to take defensive measures to ensure the security of its citizens,
as well as measures intended to prevent additional bomb attacks. However, B'Tselem strongly
condemns Israel's use of measures following the latest bombings which constitute blatant violations
of the human rights of Palestinians in the occupied territories.  These measures include detentions
of family members of suicide bombers and demolition of their homes, curfews and closures
of cities and villages, shutting down educational institutions and administrative detentions. 
<P>
The prolonged closure imposed on the territories, as well as the internal closure declared on
all population centers in the West Bank, cause extreme hardship for the entire Palestinian
population of the territories.  The closure prevents medical personnel from reaching hospitals,
as well as preventing the critically ill from receiving treatment - and has already resulted in
the death of two people.  It also causes an increasing shortage of food and medical supplies,
especially in the Gaza Strip.  Many Palestinians have lost their source of employment and
suffer from economic hardship.  The stringent restrictions on movement separate husbands
and wives, and parents and children.
<P>
B'Tselem calls on the Israeli government to immediately cease those measures which constitute
collective punishment or extrajudicial punishment.  The principle that every person is responsible
for his or her actions and no one should be punished for the actions of another constitutes
a basic tenet of both Israeli and international law.  The use of punitive measures against innocent
Palestinians solely for their relationship to those who conduct attacks or their residence in
the same village is inherently amoral and contradicts the most fundamental legal principles. 
B'Tselem also calls on the Israeli government not to apply pressure on the Palestinian Authority
to take measures which result in human rights violations.
<P>
Moreover, the use of measures against Palestinians such as deportation and house demolition
constitutes discrimination on the basis of nationality; after Israelis conducted acts of terror,
the Israeli authorities did not consider taking measures against members of their family - and
rightly so - such as deportation or demolition of their houses.
<P>
According to the authorities, measures such as deportation and house demolition are necessary
in order to deter potential terrorists.  However, the use of security considerations to justify
serious violations of human rights opens the door for unlimited abuses of these rights. 
International law has formulated the legitimate boundaries of government action in all situations,
including states of emergency.
<P>
In addition, in spite of repeated declarations, the connection between the extended use of collective
punishments in the territories over the years and a decrease in violence has never been established. 
The Chief Military Prosecutor at the height of the intifada, Amnon Strashnov, claimed that
the effectiveness of house demolitions as a deterrent "has not been decisively proven in any
kind of empirical study.  Acts of terror continued, it is known, in spite of the house demolitions."
<P>
The lack of proof of their effectiveness creates the impression that the authorities engage in
such highly visible measures as house demolition in order to pacify the Israeli public and
demonstrate that it deals severely with acts of terror.  These are illegitimate motivations for
the use of punitive measures.
<P>
Israel's commitment to respect human rights is proven precisely in times of crisis.  B'Tselem
calls on the government of Israel to respect the basic values of law and morality also at this
time.
<P>
<HR>
