<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - March 5, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - March 5, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
     Israeli Human Rights Organizations Condemn the Brutal Attacks. <BR>
          Collective Punishments, However, Are Not the Answer.
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>W</B></FONT>e, the undersigned Israeli human rights organizations, are outraged at the brutal
attacks inside Israel against innocent people.  We strongly condemn these acts, which
blatantly contradict the basic principles of human rights.  They cannot be justified
by any circumstances of occupation, deprivation or suffering.
<P>
It is the right and the responsibility of the Government of Israel to protect its
citizens and to prevent additional attacks, by taking all possible measures which
conform with Israel's obligations to respect human rights and uphold international law
and the conventions to which it is a signatory.
<P>
In the past few days, the Israeli government has declared its intention to implement a
series of measures in the wake of the attacks, some of which constitute collective
punishment and will result in serious violation of the human rights of Palestinians in
the territories.  These measures, some of which have already been implemented, include
sealing and demolition of houses, imposition of curfew and closure on communities and
administrative detentions.
<P>
The principle that every person is responsible for his or her actions and no one
should be punished for the actions of another constitutes a basic principle of both
Israeli and international law.  Those who plan and conduct attacks must be brought to
justice;  there is no justification, however, for implementing punitive measures
against innocent Palestinians - including Palestinians who are shocked and disgusted
by the acts of terror.
<P>
Collective punishments such as the prolonged closure imposed on the territories, and
the curfew that has been declared in many communities, cause severe distress for the
entire Palestinian population in the territories.  The closure prevents patients in
critical condition from receiving treatment, and prevents doctors from reaching
hospitals.  It is also causing an increasingly serious shortage of food and essential
medical supplies in the Gaza Strip.  The stringent restrictions on travel separates
spouses, and parents and children, and prevents establishment of normal family life.
<P>
We call upon the government of Israel not to ignore its obligation to ensure
employment opportunities for Palestinian workers who are prevented from entering
Israel due to the closure, as well as to allow free movement to specific groups of
Palestinians, such as medical personnel and the sick.
<P>
We call upon the Israeli Government to act with reason even in these times of profound
pain and anger, and to uphold the basic values of law and morality.  Experience
demonstrates that illegal and immoral sweeping punitive measures do not reduce acts of
terror and are even liable to increase the support these acts receive.
<P>
Human rights organizations:
<UL>
<LI> B'Tselem - The Israeli Information Center for Human Rights in the Occupied Territories
<LI> HaMoked: Center for the Defense of the Individual
<LI> The Association of Physicians for Human Rights - Israel
<LI> The Public Committee Against Torture in Israel (PCATI)
<LI> Worker's Hotline
</UL>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
