<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - January 28, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - January 28, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<I>Human rights organizations - B'Tselem, HaMoked: Center
for the Defense of the Individual, the Association of
Physicians for Human Rights and the Public Committee
Against Torture in Israel - condemn today's decision
of the High Court of Justice, which permits the use of
torture against Palestinian detainee, Abed el-Halim
Balbisi.</I>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>oday, for the first time in its history, the High Court of Justice
permitted the General Security Service (GSS) to use physical
pressure, including forceful shaking, against a Palestinian detainee.
<P>
This permission was granted when the High Court cancelled the interim
injunction it had granted in the case of the detainee, Abed el-Halim
Balbisi.  This injunction prohibited the use of any physical force
against the detainee during his interrogation.  For all intents
and purposes, today's decision by the High Court gives the GSS
permission to employ measures against the detainee which constitute
torture.
<P>
In fact, the case of Balbisi refutes the claim of the authorities
that effective interrogation requires the use of physical force. 
The detainee provided important information, according to the GSS,
without being subjected to torture.
<P>
Balbisi was detained on 6 December 1995 and held by the GSS.  For
a period of 18 days he was subjected to an interrogation in which
physical force, including violent shaking, were used against him. 
<P>
Following a High Court appeal filed on Balbisi's behalf by attorney
Andre Rosenthal, the High Court issued an interim injunction which
prohibited the GSS from using physical force against Balbisi during
his interrogation.  After a few days, in which he was not subjected
to torture, the detainee provided information (according to the
GSS) which led to the discovery of an explosive device buried in
January 1995 in order to carry out the attack at the Beit Lid
junction during that month.
<P>
Forceful shaking of the head and body by GSS interrogators has
already caused the death of a Palestinian detainee - Abed a-Samed
Harizat in April 1995.  Following Harizat's death, the expert
forensic pathologist, Dr. Robert Kirschner, determined that
interrogation by forceful shaking carries a high risk of serious
and irreversible brain damage, as well as death.
<P>
The decision of the High Court supports the attempt of the
authorities to bestow institutional legitimacy on the use of torture
during interrogations of Palestinians.  
<P>
This decision contradicts the International Convention Against
Torture, which the Israeli Government has declared its intention
to incorporate into law.
<P>
Human rights organizations condemn this decision, which contradicts
international law, the Israeli Penal Code and the Basic Law: Human
Dignity and Freedom, and violates basic human rights concerning
dignity and bodily integrity.
<P>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=middle WIDTH=50% BGCOLOR="Lime"><A HREF="../news/96spring/torture.htm"> Back to The "Shaken to Death" </A></TD>
