<DOCNO>WT10-B39-217</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA046-000817-B021-24</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/press/960125.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119022507 text/html 4694
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 02:23:53 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4523
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 09:52:58 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - January 25, 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - January 25, 1996 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<B>B'Tselem's response to the proposed GSS Law: 
   Torture Under Law - Only in Israel
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he proposed General Security Service Law, as reported by the media, incorporates into law
the use of torture and perpetuates the existing condition, in which torture of Palestinians during
interrogations is systematic. 
<P>
B'Tselem welcomes the initiative to codify GSS powers, but it is wrong to exploit this initiative
to provide a cloak of legality on the use of torture. Allowing GSS interrogators to use violent
means during interrogations removes the taboo on causing harm to a person or his dignity,
and legitimizes such injuries, leaving the suspect defenseless.
<P>
If the proposed law is enacted, Israel would be the only country in the world in which
the use of torture during interrogations is allowed by law.
<P>
The  proposed law ostensibly prohibits torture, and only allows "the use of pressure" on suspects.
A similar distinction appears explicitly in the recommendations of the Landau Commission,
which allowed the use of "moderate" physical pressure only. However, prolonged experience
indicates that the use of pressure on suspects constitutes torture for all intents and purposes,
and any attempt to distinguish between permitted pressure and prohibited pressure failed utterly.
The attempt to distinguish between cases in which pressure is permitted and those in which
it was prohibited failed, and in most cases the suspects were tortured, though they were not
tortured under the criteria that had been set.
<P>
Numerous testimonies given to B'Tselem during its seven years of activity indicate that GSS
interrogators, when interrogating suspects, use violence constituting torture even when the
evidence against them is minimal; according to the late Prime Minister and Defense Minister,
Yitzhak Rabin, 8,000 Palestinians were "shaken" in GSS interrogations. Furthermore, most
of the tortured suspects were ultimately released without any legal measures being taken against
them. In almost every instance, the purpose of the use of torture during interrogations has
been to obtain confessions concerning past crimes, and not to obtain information about planned
attacks.
<P>
In effect, the proposed law is designed to incorporate into law the recommendation of the Landau
Commission to allow the use of "a moderate degree of physical pressure" on suspects. These
permitted measures have been implemented although they clearly violate the Penal Law, which
prohibits a public official from using force or violence against a person for the purpose of
extorting from him, or from anyone in whom he is interested, a confession of an offense or
information relating to an offense. The proposed law is the next stage of legitimizing torture
in Israel.
<P>
According to the proposed law, the measures GSS interrogators may use during interrogations
will be set forth in secret rules that will be made by the Prime Minister, upon approval of
the Cabinet Committee and the Knesset Committee for GSS Matters. B'Tselem rejects the
principle of secrecy of the permitted means of pressure. Secrecy will prevent meaningful public
and judicial criticism of the legality of the means. Undisclosed legislation that stipulates what
the interrogator is allowed and prohibited from doing is inherently unacceptable and emasculates
the important initiative of  incorporating GSS activities into law.
<P>
Together with other human rights groups, B'Tselem is undertaking a public campaign to prevent
the enactment of a law that critically harms the rule of law in Israel. B'Tselem urges the Israeli
government to amend the proposed law, delete any measure that permits the use of pressure
on suspects under interrogation, and end, in accord with its international obligations, the current
widespread use of torture and cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment. In addition, B'Tselem
urges the government to pass legislation that requires publication of the permitted measures.
<P>
<HR>
