<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Press Release - December 28, 1995 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Press Release - December 28, 1995 </I></B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>
Tortured to Death at Ketziot
</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>estimonies given to B'Tselem show that during August-October of
1995, a group of prisoners severely tortured dozens of prisoners.
The group members accused the interrogees of collaborating with
Israeli authorities, and coerced them into confessing to patently
false allegations.
<P>
During this period, two prisoners at Ketziot died, apparently as
a result of torture - Abd al-Karim Abd Al-Ghani Kanaze', 26 years
old, who died on 15 September 1995, and Muhammad Musa Abd a-Razeq
Abu-Shakra, 23 years old, who died on 7 October 1995. 
<P>
Among the methods of torture mentioned in the testimonies are the
following: 
Extinguishing cigarettes on the bodies of interrogees, laying
them on a board with nails while interrogators sat on them,
cutting the interrogees with knives and pouring salt on the
wounds, dripping molten plastic on their bodies, and inserting
electric wire and other objects into their penises.
<P>
"A.B."<SUP>*</SUP>, in his testimony to a B'Tselem fieldworker, stated:
<UL>
     On the first day of interrogation they undressed me
     completely, lay me on a board full of nails, sometimes with
     my chest on the nails, and at other times with my back lying
     on the nails and then they would sit on me... They would
     heat the plastic trays we used when eating until they
     melted, and they dripped the molten plastic on my penis. The
     pain was terrible.
</UL>
"D.H."<SUP>*</SUP> testified:
<UL>
     They inserted wire into my penis... They beat me all the
     time.. They used to douse the wounds of interrogees with
     salt and pepper after they cut them with a razor blade. 
</UL>
According to the testimonies, the prison authorities did not
intervene. This fact raises grave concern in the light of the
large number of prisoners tortured as well as the large number of
persons involved (the interrogators who perpetrated the torture
and the passive eye-witnesses) and the prolonged period over
which these incidents occurred. Indeed, the testimonies indicate
that the authorities knew, at least partially, about the torture.
They obviously were aware of the acts being perpetrated in the
prison facility after the two prisoners died as a result of the
violence inflicted on them. 
<P>
According to the testimonies, the entire group of those who
conducted the interrogations and torture was released in the
framework of the prisoner release under the Oslo II Agreement.
Munjad Kazaz, who was the head of the group, told the interrogees
that he was a member of the Palestinian Preventive Security
Service, headed by Gibril Rajoub. After his release he was
appointed to a senior position in the Preventive Security
Service. 
<P>
B'Tselem has sent urgent letters to the Minister of Defense, Mr.
Shimon Peres, and to the Chairman of the Palestinian Authority,
Mr. Yasser Arafat, demanding that the matter be investigated and
that those responsible for the torture and for the failure to
ensure the safety of the prisoners be punished. Copies of the
letters are enclosed.
<P>
* The names of the witnesses are on file at B'Tselem.
<P>
<HR>
