<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Sexual Harassment in the Name of the Law </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Sexual Harassment in the Name of the Law: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Violence and Degradation During Searches of Palestinian Homes in Hebron </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> December 1996 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>B'</B></FONT>Tselem has released a report documenting violent and degrading searches
which took place in ten Palestinian apartments in Hebron.  Testimonies given
to B'Tselem by persons residing in the apartments raise two disturbing
phenomena:
<OL>
<LI>  Strip Searches of Women: The security forces forced fifteen Palestinian
women, ranging in age from 20 to 69, to undress from head to toe in the
presence of women soldiers and/or policewomen. In two instances, women were
required to undress in full vision of a male police officer.  Thirteen
children, aged one month to 14 years old, were also undressed.  In some
cases, women were compelled to undress in front of their relatives, their
children and other children.  Screams, curses, and beatings accompanied the
order to undress in several cases.  Although men were also present in most
of the apartments, only one man was also required to undress.
<P>
<LI> Threats, Violence and Property Damage: During the house searches, the
security forces broke furniture and utensils, dumped food on the floor, and
tore mattresses, clothes and pictures.  In some of the instances, the
security forces threatened family members. One soldier threatened to kill a
woman's two-year-old daughter if the mother did not move away from the
window, and in another case, a woman soldier threatened to kill a woman if
she did not reveal information about her husband.
</OL>
The fact that only women and children were ordered to undress, while in
every case but one the men were not required to undergo this degradation,
indicates that this measure was taken to humiliate the women and their
families.  This together with the contemptuous and violent treatment of the
residents and their property, and the fact that almost none of the residents
were detained reinforce the suspicion that the violence and degradation were
intentional and totally unrelated to security needs.
<P>
This report is written a short time after exposure of the Border Police's
abuse of Palestinians at the A-Ram checkpoint. Following this incident,
security force officials stated the need to eradicate the phenomenon of ill
treatment. While these declarations were being made, soldiers and police
were abusing women and children in Hebron. These acts raise doubts about the
intention of those officials to act seriously in this matter.  B'Tselem
urges the Israeli government to end this conduct:
<OL>
<LI> The government must unequivocally instruct its security forces not to
order women to undress, and not to offend their honor in any other way; the
government must instruct its security forces that during house searches,
they must safeguard personal property and refrain from causing damage;
<P>
<LI>  If directives exist allowing such conduct, the authorities must
immediately revoke them and take measures against those who instituted them;
<P>
<LI> The authorities must thoroughly investigate the events described in this
report and prosecute any soldier or police officer who engaged in wrongoing.
</OL>
<B><I>Postscript:</I></B> The day B'Tselem issued this report, Police searched another
house in Hebron and strip searched four women.  None of the men in the house
were required to undress.
<P>
<B><A HREF="96dec.exe">Download full report</A></B><BR>
Run the file you have downloaded to extract the Word 6.0 file.

<P>
