<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Neither Law Nor Justice </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Neither Law Nor Justice: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Extrajudicial Punishment, Abduction, UnlawfulArrest, and Torture of 
Palestinian Residents of the West Bank by the Palestinian Preventive Security Service </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> August 1995 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>his report examines the policing activity in the West Bank of
the Preventive Security Service of the Palestinian Authority. 
<P>

Testimonies collected by B'Tselem's fieldworker, on which this
report is based, draw a disturbing picture of human rights violations
of West Bank Palestinians. These abuses include extra-judicial
punishment, abduction of residents from their homes, arrest without
warrants, holding detainees for lengthy periods without any judicial
scrutiny, refusal to allow legal representation, refusal to allow
regular family visits, and use of harsh torture techniques such
as beatings, painful tying-up, threats, humiliation, sleep
deprivation, and withholding of medical treatment. PSS (Preventive
Security Service) agents conduct policing actions without any lawful
authority, and their activities are subject to no judicial review.
The refusal of most of those who gave testimony to B'Tselem, and
many others who have been interviewed by the media on the subjects
raised in this report, to have their names published indicates
that many West Bank residents refrain from publicly criticizing
the PSS out of fear of a harsh and violent reaction by the PSS.
<P>

PSS agents have no legal authority to police the West Bank.  The
"Gaza-Jericho Agreement", signed in Cairo by Israel and the PLO
on 4 May 1994 limits the powers of the Palestinian Authority in
the area of internal security to the territory within its
jurisdiction.
<P>

So long as policing powers on the West Bank have not been transferred
to the PA openly and subject to a system of regulations complying
with international law, Israel continues to be responsible for
the Palestinian population. However, Israel has almost totally
refrained from taking any measures to prevent human rights violations
committed by the PSS and bringing those responsible to justice,
even though in most cases the identity of the perpetrator is known. 
<P>

Israel's shirking of its duty to protect the human rights of
Palestinian residents in the West Bank suggests its disregard for
the residents' well-being and freedom. 
<P>

This neglect of its responsibility is particularly blatant in light
of the determined efforts by the Israeli authorities to prevent
the activities of the PSS in East Jerusalem. Thus, Israel enforces
the law on PSS agents only because their actions challenge Israel's
sovereignty over Jerusalem, and not because they harm the well-being
and security of Palestinian residents. 
<P>

Senior PA officials repeatedly state that the Authority seeks to
respect human rights and preserve the rule of law. In keeping with
these declarations, and to show that they were not merely lip
service, the PA must act immediately to eradicate the practices
described in this report.
<P>

The peace process, the PA's efforts to combat crime among the
Palestinian population, and its desire to establish symbols of
sovereignty in the West Bank cannot justify the trampling on human
rights or excuse acts committed without authority and in flagrant
violation of the law.

<P>
<HR>
