<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Death and Injury Resulting From Exploding Munitions' Remnants </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Incidents of Death and Injury Resulting From
		     Exploding Munitions' Remnants </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>S</B></FONT>ince December 1987, 23 Palestinians have been killed and 60 injured
from the accidental explosion of munitions' remnants in the West
Bank.  A majority of the casualties were children, some as young
as five years old, who stumbled across the munitions either while
herding livestock or playing in or near military training areas.
<P>
In July, B'Tselem released a report which examines the phenomenon
of death and injury of Palestinians in the West Bank resulting
from the explosion of munitions' remnants of the Israel Defense
Forces (IDF).  
<P>
International law, Israeli law and IDF procedures all require Israel
to take measures to protect civilians from munitions' remnants. 
These measures include the provision of information to nearby
residents (through warning signs, maps, etc) regarding the location
of fire zones; construction of fences to prevent accidental entrance
into dangerous areas; and extensive combing of fire zones after
training exercises to remove unexploded munitions.  Israel has
been delinquent in enforcing its obligations.
<P>
In its report, B'Tselem recommended that the IDF ensure ongoing
enforcement of the safety regulations concerning training areas;
provide clear instructions regarding training areas and dangerous
materials to all echelons within the military; and conduct an
extensive investigation into all incidents of injury as a result
of munitions remnants.  In addition Israel should prosecute those
liable for these incidents, initiate payment of compensation and
act to prevent recurrence of similar accidents.

<P>
<HR>
