<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Closure of Schools and Other Setbacks to the 
Education System in the Occupied Territories </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>

<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Closure of Schools and Other Setbacks to the Education 
System in the Occupied Territories </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> September - October 1990 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>his report describes the state of the education system during
the Intifada, focusing on the elementary and high school levels. 
The situation in higher education is noted only as background. 
The report is based on information collected by the Education Unit
from official Israeli sources, Palestinian sources, and via field
trips and interviews.  The field trips included visits to schools
and meetings with Palestinian educators and with Civil Administration
officials responsible for education in the territories.  Also
included are statements by Israeli educators, psychologists and
jurists on various aspects of the setbacks sustained by the education
system in the territories during the Intifada.
<P>
The fourth school year since the start of the Intifada had
opened in September 1990, and already all the Palestinian
pupils had lost precious days.  The Israeli authorities were still
not upholding their international and moral obligation to enable
Palestinian children and youths to enjoy regular studies.  This,
after three years for part of which the education system in the
West Bank was closed more days than it was open, and in which Gaza
Strip pupils also went through long weeks without studies.
<P>
It is difficult to measure the damage that is caused to
children who are prevented from attending school for such lengthy
periods.   It is very doubtful whether these closures generated
respect for the authorities that brought them about.  Closure orders
were issued without stipulating a date for reopening, or were issued
orally by junior officers;  soldiers entered schools without making
any effort to coordinate this with principals or to minimize the
impact on studies.  Such behavior only intensifies the anger of the
population in general and of educators in particular.
<P>
The destruction of the education system becomes more apparent
when viewed against the background of its ongoing neglect since
the start of the occupation.  For more than 20 years, the system
had been maintained in a state of stagnation, deprived of
essential processes of development and change.  We did not ignore
the fact that the education system had undergone tremendous growth
in terms of its scope of activity, human resources, number of
classrooms, and so forth.  However, this growth was a response
to the considerable increase in the number of pupils.  There were
no significant changes in organizational structures, development
of pedagogical conceptions, work modes or teaching methods.  Today,
education systems everywhere are undergoing far-reaching changes,
and in Israel, too, there is increased awareness of the need to
develop the system and adapt it to the modern world.  In light
of this, the ever-widening gap between the school-age populations
in the territories and in Israel could have ruinous consequences. 
The curriculum in the territories consisted of basic subjects only; 
there were no formal or informal enrichment programs that broaden
horizons, scientific and technological studies were at a low level,
there was no acknowledgement of differential teaching methods for
different population groups, and nothing was done to tap the
children's human and social potential to the full.
<P>
Studies in these abominable conditions constituted an abridgement
of the pupils' basic rights.  The right to education to positive
values is nonexistent in a crowded and violent learning atmosphere,
and the children's right to be prepared for life in a modern and
constantly developing world is also infringed.

<P>
<HR>
