<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - "Collaborators" in the Occupied Territories </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> "Collaborators" in the Occupied Territories: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Human Rights Abuses and Violations </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> January 1994 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT>ccording to various sources, at least 771 Palestinians 
suspected of collaboration with Israeli authorities have been
killed between the start of the Intifada and December 1, 1993. Many
others were tortured or subject to ill-treatment during
interrogations.
<P>
      This report condems the killings and torture of collaborators
as gross abuses of the fundamental principles of international
human rights law.  It deals with the responsibility of Palestinian
political organizations and their activists for this phenomenon and
also addresses human rights violations by the Israeli authorities
in recruiting and operating collaborators in the territories.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Background</B></FONT>
<P>
       Since 1967, the Israeli authorities have operated an
extensive network of Palestinian collaborators in the occupied
territories for various purposes. Some are related to security -
such as obtaining intelligence and thwarting violent acts - while
others are political, such as seizing land to establish or expand
settlements.
<P>
      The creation of a broad network of thousands of collaborators
was made possible by the special conditions which exist in the
occupied territories.  Aided by military law, and using "carrot and
stick" policies, the military government has tied the Palestinian
population to a state of total dependence on the Israeli
authorities. Israeli officials commonly condition the granting of
permits or essential services to the collaboration of the
recipients. Other inducements have included granting certain
benefits, erasing criminal or security charges, and reducing
punishments.
<P>
        The collaborators received preferential treatment from the
authorities, and many of them took full advantage of their status.
Collaborators, especially those who were armed by the security
forces, frequently used violence against other Palestinians,
whether as part of their duties or for personal motives. 
<P>          
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Mechanisms of Law and Order</B></FONT>
<P>
     The vacuum created by the collapse of the mechanisms of
law-and-order in the territories, such as police and courts, was
filled during the Intifada by squads or cells identified with the
various Palestinian organizations, both Islamic and PLO-affiliated.
Taking upon themselves the imposition of order in their locales,
among other activities, they set about punishing individuals
suspected of being collaborators. 
<P>
        Many suspected collaborators were killed without any prior
interrogation or quasi-judicial proceeding to clarify the
accusations and without giving them an opportunity to defend
themselves. In other cases, persons were killed during or at the
conclusion of their interrogation - which often included severe
torture. Dozens of Palestinians suspected of being collaborators
were killed in detention facilities.
<P>
        Various sources -- Israeli and Palestinian -- estimate that
more than half of the Palestinians killed as being collaborators
were in fact not used by the authorities in this capacity. One
reason for this disparity is the expansive definition of the term
"collaborator" adopted by the Palestinian organizations. The
designation often included individuals who had close relations with
the military government but were not used as collaborators, as well
as "morals offenders" or others whose behavior was deemed socially
unacceptable. 
<P>
        Over time, the violent interrogations, injuries, and
killings generated growing reservations among the local Palestinian
population, leadership, journalists, and intellectuals from the
secular nationalist streams. This opposition became public
beginning in mid-1991, but protest meetings and public
condemnations were unable to curb the phenomenon.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Responsibility of Palestinian Political Organizations</B></FONT>
<P>
        The responsibility of the PLO and Hamas for killing and
otherwise harming suspected collaborators is clear. Hamas supported
such actions overtly, while the PLO, and Fatah in particular, did
not take the necessary steps which it could have taken in order to
put an end to the killings, despite some public calls expressing
reservations about the phenomenon.  
<P>
        The absence of an organized legal system and adequate law-
enforcement mechanisms in the territories notwithstanding, the PLO
did not impose, nor did it even threaten to impose, sanctions on
the faction activists who continued with the killings despite the
organization's public policy. Such measures, for example, could
have included expulsion of these individuals from the PLO or
breaking off payments to members of the squads who continued these
activities. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Responsibility of Israeli Authorities</B></FONT>
<P>
      While Israel bears no direct responsibility for the torture
and killing of collaborators, its commissions and omissions in a
number of related areas conflict with its obligations under
international law.
<P>
       The security authorities frequently make use of illegal
methods to recruit collaborators, including: pressure, threats,
extortion, and granting services and permits only if the recipient
agrees to assist the authorities.
<P>
       Israeli authorities are also responsible for operating
collaborators in the interrogation of Palestinians detained by the
Israeli authorities. B'Tselem has documented numerous cases in
which these collaborators used force and torture in extracting
"confessions" on behalf of the Israeli authorities.
<P>
        During the Intifada, at least 23 Palestinians have been
killed by armed collaborators. Moreover, many collaborators have
been involved in criminal acts, such as violence, forgery, and
fraud. In B'Tselem's view, the authorities do not attach the proper
importance to these complaints, and in some instances disregard
criminal acts imputed to collaborators.
<P>
        As part of their duty to ensure the safety and well-being
of all residents of the territories, Israeli authorities have the
responsibility to provide adequate protection to all Palestinians
suspected of being collaborators, whether they actually worked for
the security forces or are at risk for other reasons. The number of
fatalities in this connection during the Intifada points to gross
dereliction in this regard.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Recommendations</B></FONT>
<P>
      The fact that the Palestinians in the territories are subject
to a military occupation and lack law enforcement mechanisms does
not justify extra-judicial killing and torture. The prohibition in
international law against these measures is absolute and
irrevocable, regardless of circumstances.
<P>
        B'Tselem calls on the Palestinian political organizations
to put an immediate stop to the torture and killing of suspected
collaborators, and to sever all financial and organizational ties
with groups that continue to commit such acts.
<P>
       B'Tselem further calls on the Israeli authorities to put an
immediate stop to the recruitment of collaborators by illegal
methods, to stop using collaborators in illegal actions such as
violent interrogations, and to enforce the law equally against
collaborators who use violence or commit other criminal acts. 

<P>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=middle WIDTH=50% BGCOLOR="Lime"><A HREF="../../subjindx.htm"> Back to Pub. List by Subject </TD>
