<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT10-B39-235</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA046-000817-B023-176</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/reports/1994/march_2.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119023343 text/html 6057
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 02:31:53 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5886
Last-modified: Fri, 06 Sep 1996 17:45:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Hebron: Lethal Gunfire and Collective Punishment </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Lethal Gunfire and Collective Punishment in the Wake of the
   Massacre at the Tomb of the Patriarchs </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> March 1994 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>O</B></FONT>n the morning of February 25, 1994, immediately after receiving
first reports about the massacre in the Tomb of the Patriarchs in
Hebron, B'Tselem called on the Defense Minister to "refrain, to
the greatest extent possible, from the large-scale introduction 
of security forces into areas of Palestinian population
concentrations."  In its appeal, B'Tselem stressed that
"experience from similar situations in the past proves that the
massing of army forces causes unnecessary friction and the taking
of additional victims."
<P>
The IDF chose to enact policies which have failed in the past and
have exacted a high toll in terms of human life. These policies
include: streaming large numbers of troops into heavily populated
Palestinian areas, use of live fire, and the utilization of
various forms of collective punishment on the population. As a
result, in less than a week, 21 Palestinians and one Israeli were
killed.
<P>
The report presents findings of detailed investigations regarding
the circumstances of death of 12 of the Palestinians killed by
the security forces and analysis of the cases. The investigations
reveal the following facts:
<OL TYPE=A START=1>
<LI> In none of the cases investigated by B'Tselem were soldiers or
police in life-threatening circumstances.  In most of the cases,
soldiers engaged in confrontations with the demonstrators, using
live fire, even though they could have readily avoided the
confrontation.
<P>
<LI> None of the fatalities was caused by the use of relatively
"moderate" measures available for crowd dispersal, such as tear
gas, concussion grenades, or plastic bullets.
<P>
<LI> In all of the cases, the victim was hit in the upper portion
of the body (4 in the stomach or chest, 3 in the neck, and 5 in
the head). 
</OL>
The report also describes methods of collective punishment
imposed by the authorities on the Palestinian population, and its
consequences, primarily curfew and closure.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Curfew</B></FONT>
<P>
On February 2, 1994, following the massacre at the Tomb of the
Patriarchs, the IDF placed the city of Hebron under curfew.  The
next day, a curfew was placed on all cities in the West Bank and
on large areas of the Gaza Strip. A population of close to 1.5
million Palestinians was under curfew between 4 to 5 days.  
<P>
As in the past, the curfew was applied only to Palestinian
residents. Jewish settlers continued to move about freely in the
occupied territories. Residents of Kiryat Arba were required to
travel from the community by motorcade only; however, this
limitation was not strictly enforced. 
<P>
The curfew in the Gaza Strip was lifted on March 3, 1994. The
curfew in the West Bank was lifted for only a number of hours to
enable residents to purchase necessary provisions.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Closure </B></FONT>
<P>
The total closure of the territories, lightened slightly prior to
the massacre, was reinstated in full, denying tens of thousands
of Palestinian workers  and their families were access to their
source of livelihood.
<P>
The curfew and closure represent a serious form of collective
punishment enacted against a population in deep distress,
compounded by the fast of Ramadan.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Palestinian fatalities:</B></FONT>
<OL>
<LI> 'Atiyah Muhammad 'Atiyah a-Salaimah, age 30, killed 25.2.94,
Hebron
<LI> Isma'il Fayiz Isma'il Qafisheh, age 28, killed 25.2.94, Hebron
<LI> 'Arafat Mahmud al-Baid, age 27, killed 25.2.94, Hebron
<LI> Nader Salem Muhammad Zahadah, age 18, killed 25.2.94, Hebron
<LI> Aiman Ayub al-Qawasmah, age 22, killed 25.2.94, Hebron
<LI> Amjad Kamel Ahmad Shahin, age 17, killed 25.2.94, Temple Mount
<LI> Rami Nashat 'Azmi Jamus, age 16, killed 25.2.94, Rafidiyah,
Nablus
<LI> Fadel Muhammad Mahmud al-Qirnawi, age 21, killed 25.2.94, al-
Bureij refugee camp, Gaza Strip
<LI> Isma'il 'Adnan 'Izam, age 19, killed 25.2.94, Tulkarm refugee
camp
<LI> Muhammad Hasan a-Danaf, age 28, killed 25.2.94, Gaza.
<LI> Jihad 'Abd a-Rahman Ahmad Abu 'Abdu, age 25, killed 25.2.94,
al-Bureij refugee camp, Gaza Strip
<LI> Amjad Isma'il al-'Adawi, age 19, sustained shooting injury
25.2.94, Jilazun refugee camp, Ramallah District, died of his
wounds the following day.
<LI> Na'man 'Awni Subhi Abu Hajwah, age 17, killed  26.2.94, Gaza.
<LI> Fadi Tareq Ahmad al-'Issawi, age 17, killed 26.2.94,
'Issawiyah village, East Jerusalem
<LI> Aiman Ghazi Haniyah, age 17, killed 27.2.94, Gaza.
<LI> Najeh 'Awad 'Abd al-Fattah Ziadah, age 21, killed 27.2.94,
Madama village, Nablus District
<LI> Maryam Ahmad Mahmud al-'Omar, age 38, killed 27.2.94, Siniria
Village, Tulkarm District
<LI> Talal Wajiah 'Ali a-Salah Duweikat, age 23, killed 28.2.94,
'Askar neighborhood, Nablus
<LI> 'Abd a-Rahim Salam al-'Ajluni, age 65, killed 28.2.94, Hebron
<LI> 'Othman 'Ali Barhamah, age 17, killed 2.3.94, Jericho
<LI> Usama Mustafa Ghazal, killed 2.3.94, Hebron.
</OL>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Israeli fatality</B></FONT>
<OL>
<LI> David Baruch, age 28, killed 1.3.94, near Bidya village,
Tulkarm District by IDF gunfire
</OL>
     
<P>
