<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Collective Punishment in The West Bank and The Gaza Strip </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Collective Punishment in The West Bank and The Gaza Strip </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> November 1990 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B>The report includes the following sections:</B>
<OL>
<LI> Introduction;
<LI> Collective punishment in international law;
<LI> Data - the test of reality: curfews and closure, night curfew,
     closure of educational institutions, restrictions on travel abroad,
     disconnection of telephone lines, disconnection of electricity and 
     water supply, restrictions on marketing of agricultural produce, 
     demolition and sealing of houses, and uprooting of trees; 
<LI> Judicial review;
<LI> Conclusion;
<LI> Appendix, which includes accounts of field trips made by a B'Tselem
     team in the summer of 1990 to several places in the territories, as
     well as testimonies and affidavits of residents regarding the practical effect of restrictive collective
measures on their personal lives. 
</OL>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>his report addresses the various administrative measures which
were employed by the military government in the West Bank and
the Gaza Strip which raise a question of collective punishment,
a practice forbidden by the norms of public international law.
It addresses those measures that restricted the human rights
of entire population groups - curfew and closure, closure
of educational institutions, disconnection of telephone
lines, restrictions on travel abroad, disconnection of
electricity and water supply, and restrictions on marketing
agricultural produce - as well as measures employed as a
sanction consequent to the commission of a security offense
against persons who are not personally responsible for its
commission - demolition and sealing of houses, and uprooting of
trees.
<P>
The report shows that only rarely were these measures employed with
an express declaration that the purpose was punitive. Usually
the official justification relates to security needs, prevention
or deterrence.  However, the general impression is that the
discretion as to employment of these measures did not properly
balance security considerations with considerations of basic human
rights, and did not attach weight or importance to the governmental
duty to guarantee as far as possible individual liberty, which
falls within the general governmental duty to maintain normal
everyday life under the laws of belligerent occupancy.
<P>
The report also addresses the question of the judicial
review exercised by the High Court of Justice in relation to
the employment of collective punishment measures.  It appears that
in extreme cases, submission of a petition to the court was
sufficient to induce governmental authorities to lift
the restrictions.  But where matters reached the stage of
actual hearing before the court, it repeatedly dismissed the argument
that the restrictive measure was unlawful because it amounted to
collective punishment prohibited under international law.  As regards
house demolition, the court did order the authorities to observe
a due process of law before employing the punitive measure, but
the argument addressing directly the issue of collective punishment
was not explored in depth, which is regrettable.

<P>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=middle WIDTH=50% BGCOLOR="Lime"><A HREF="../../subjindx.htm"> Back to Pub. List by Subject </TD>
