<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Demolition and Sealing of Houses as a Punitive Measure </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Demolition and Sealing of Houses as a Punitive Measure in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip During the Intifada </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> September 1989 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he report includes the following major sections:
<OL>
<LI> The law; 
<LI> The method; 
<LI> The data; 
<LI> Data analysis; 
<LI> The extent of the use of demolition and sealing as a punitive measure; 
<LI> Incidental damage; 
<LI> Policy; 
<LI> The deterrent argument; 
<LI> Illegal construction; 
<LI> Conclusions; 
<LI> Appendices.
</OL>
The appendices include the IDF 1945 Seizure and Demolition Order,
the transcript of an affidavit given by the victim of a house
demolition, and testimonies of people whose houses were demolished.
<P>
The primary goal of this report is to present the public with
reliable information on the scope of demolition and sealing
of houses as a punitive measure in the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip during the Intifada.
<P>
We analyzed data and tried to discern the grounds for execution
of this measure, to examine policies, to locate the differences
in the method of execution between the West Bank and the Gaza Strip,
and to appraise the criteria that stand behind the decision to
demolish or seal a house.
<P>
When we tried to establish the exact numbers of houses demolished
and sealed in the occupied territories  as a punitive measure by
the security forces, we encountered various obstacles which prevented
us from reaching definitive and exact figures.
<P>
Our information stems from seven different sources:  two of them
are Palestinian human rights organizations, PHRIC (Palestinian
Human Rights Information Center) and al-Haq (Law in the Service
of Man).  Other sources include field investigations we conducted
ourselves, the Israeli press, the Association for Civil Rights
in Israel, the Israel Defence Forces Spokesperson, and the Ministry
of Defence.
<P>
The defense authorities disregarded the gravity of the issue and
the right of the public to receive accurate and credible information. 
They did not adhere to the principle of the public's right to know
and of the right of freedom of information.
<P>
In the Gaza Strip, the suspicion of a serious offense, such as
murder,  manslaughter, attempted murder, or other life-threatening
acts, was required as the pretext for demolition or sealing.  In
the West Bank, homes of suspected stone throwers, people suspected
of incitement, and people who forcefully resisted arrest, were
also demolished or sealed.
<P>
There were no definite and clear criteria upon which to base the
decision to carry out a demolition or a sealing.  The decision
was apparently quite arbitrary and is left, for the most part,
to the discretion of field commanders.     

<P>
<HR>
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
