<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Deportation of Women and Children from the Occupied Territories </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Renewal of Deportation of Women and Children from the Occupied
Terrirories on Account of "Illegal Residency" </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> September-October 1991 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n the recent weeks before the writing of this report, B'Tselem
gathered information about the deportation from the occupied
territories of Palestinian women and children who did not possess 
visitors' permits.  An examination of this information revealed
a clear pattern: the security authorities had resumed the systematic
deportation of people - mostly women and children - who had stayed
in the territories without  visitors' permits, thus separating
them from other members of their families.
<P>
The majority of cases concern Palestinian women who are not
residents of the territories (and their children), but who are
married to residents of the territories.  Many of these women had
their requests for family reunion rejected, leaving them with no
choice but to enter the territories with the status of "visitor,"
on a permit valid for a limited period.  When the permit expires,
their presence becomes "illegal."
<P>
Approximately two years prior to the writing of this report,
the authorities began deporting women with this status.  The policy
caused a public outcry both in Israel and abroad, and was eventually
stopped for what was termed "humanitarian reasons."  Some time
later, the State Attorney's Office, responding to a petition filed
with the High Court of Justice on this subject, announced an
arrangement that would enable the women and children who had been
deported to return to their homes, as well as a policy of
not deporting them again.
<P>
B'Tselem was in possession of information regarding several
dozen women who in the recent weeks prior to the writing of this
report were directed to leave the territories with their children. 
At least three had left.
<P>
Following intervention by B'Tselem and the Association for
Civil Rights in Israel, the permits of most of the women were
extended, and the Judea and Samaria Legal Advisor announced that
an order had been given in all the districts to freeze the
deportations.  However, additional deportation notices had been
issued in the meantime.  According to letters from the State
Attorney's Office and the Office of the Judea and Samaria Legal
Advisor, the state claimed that the arrangement announced at the
High Court hearing applied only to those women who married and
entered the territories before June 1990, the date of the
announcement. In other words, the administration felt at liberty
to deport those who married and entered the area subsequent to
this arbitrary date.
<P>
The security authorities were acting to prevent the residency
of two main groups: 
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI>  wives of residents who had transferred the main focus of
their lives to another place, namely, those who had resided outside
of the territories for many years 
<LI>  women who married subsequent to the High Court of Justice hearing
</OL>
One year following the High Court of Justice hearing, it
appeared that the new policy did not succeed in practice, and the
status of the families remained as unclear as before:  a large
number of women and children in the territories were denied legal
status - they did not have identity cards, their children were
not registered on their parents' identity cards, and they possessed
no rights or guarantees.  
<P>
Thousands of families in the territories, and not only women
who had been deported and permitted to return, lived in this
situation of uncertainty and "illegality."  There thus existed
an almost unknown additional "grey area" in the military rule in
the territories, which was fertile ground, both in theory and in
practice, for severe violations of one of the fundamental rights
of humanity:  to found a family and live together.

<P>
<HR>
