</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem -  Limitations on the Rights to Demonstrate and Protest in the Territories </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Limitations on the Right to Demonstrate and Protest in the Territories </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> January 1992 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>P</B></FONT>olitical rights of Palestinians in the territories in general,
and the right to demonstrate in particular, were severely limited
in comparison to the accepted norms in Israel, and among the Jewish
settlers in the territories.  Since the end of the 1970s, open
political activity of Palestinians in the territories had been
forbidden, with the exception of the activities of the Village
League, which was permitted to conduct public political gatherings
and events with the backing of the military government.  Political
gatherings in the territories were totally forbidden to Palestinians,
while they were generally permitted for Jewish residents of the
territories and Israelis who did not live in the territories, but
who were identified with the settlers' position.  Other Israelis
seeking to demonstrate and protest against government policy and
the settlements faced limitations which required them, in many
cases, to turn to the High Court of Justice, and only as a result
of the Court's intervention were they able to hold non-violent
protests.
<P>
Only occasionally, and inconsistently, did the IDF allow
Palestinians from the territories to conduct assemblies and even
more rarely, processions, but these cases did not reflect a set
policy.  For certain periods, the IDF did not prevent conferences
of mayors, trade unions, and academics in the territories, while
in other periods, it prevented similar conferences by orders which
closed an entire area, or even closed universities or other
institutions.  Palestinians, until November 1991, were prevented
entirely from requesting permits to hold assemblies and processions.
<P>
According to international law, the military government may
indeed deny freedom of expression in an occupied area, including
banning demonstrations, but according to the Israeli Supreme Court,
it also has an obligation to ensure order and public life, and
to assure "the existence of a government which protects civil rights
and sees to the general welfare of the population."
<P>
In addition, the Supreme Court recognized that freedom
of expression is a defensible principle also in occupied
territory, ruling that the authority seeking to limit this right
must demonstrate that extraordinary reasons exist which justify
a deviation from this principle.  The Supreme Court also accepted
the principle that there must be an appropriate balance between
two important public interests:  freedom of expression on the one
hand, and proper execution of the government's tasks on the other.
<P>
Israel's control in the territories for almost 25 years, and
the large-scale building for the Israeli civilian
population, illustrate that Israel was acting from the viewpoint
of a long-term occupation.  Based on this approach, which takes
expression in other spheres as well, the authorities must maintain
a better balance between the security needs and freedom of
expression, and demonstrate greater openness in approving non-violent
demonstrations in the territories.  It appeared to us that the
authorities tended to shy away from this responsibility to keep
a balance, with their tendency to limit demonstrations
systematically, particularly in the Palestinian sector, but also
in the case of Israelis who wished to demonstrate against
government policy and the settlements.  Thus, the military government
did not rest at implementing Order 101 Prohibiting Activities
of Incitement and Hostile Propaganda, requiring a license for
holding "gatherings" and "processions."  Rather, it also prevented
activities that did not require permission, such as "protest vigils,"
"ceremonies," and "outings," by declaring a closed military area. 

<P>
<HR>
