<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Limitations on Building of Residences on the West Bank </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Limitations on Building of Residences on the West Bank </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> August 1990 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT>ccording to estimates by Palestinian 
engineers, there were
approximately 13,000 homes in the West Bank which had been built
without permission at the writing of this report.  Approximately
80,000 people lived with the apprehension that a demolition order,
or bulldozers, would arrive at  their doorstep, and that they would
find themselves without a roof over their heads.  This fear was
based on the fact that each year, hundreds of homes were indeed
demolished.  Notwithstanding this risk, many Palestinians continued
to build homes without permission.
<P>
This report focuses on rural areas in the West Bank where
the problem was especially grave.  Within city limits in the West
Bank,  there were local municipal planning authorities, whereas
in the Gaza strip, demolitions were rare.
<P>
In most countries, building planning and authorizations are
an administrative matter and of no interest to human rights
organizations.  B'Tselem had nevertheless chosen to examine this
issue in the West Bank  for three reasons:
<UL>
<LI>  Data showed that the number of building licenses issued in the
West Bank was extremely small, and fell far below the minimum housing
needs.  At the same time, the authorities continued to demolish
premises built without permission.  Thus, rural West Bank
Palestinians had no proper way of exercising their natural
right to build a home.  The situation worsened considerably since
the beginning of the Intifada.
<LI>  Investigations, testimonies and discussions conducted by B'Tselem,
painted a picture of  secrecy, arbitrariness, disorganization and
endless delays in dealing with requests for licenses.  In an
interview with B'Tselem on June 10, 1990, Coordinator of Activities
in the West Bank Shumel Goren defined this situation in the  West
Bank as "improper."   Israel was obliged by international conventions
to maintain proper administration in the territories.
<LI>  The planning and building system in the Israeli settlements
in the West Bank was efficient, sympathetic and lenient
regarding unlicensed construction, creating a clear case of
discrimination.
</UL>
The West Bank village resident who requested a license to build 
on his land faced an extremely difficult, and in many  
cases impossible task:
<UL>
<LI> to prove ownership, although the land registration system is
obsolete and defective.                                     
<LI> to  present  proof  of having no debts or  problems with the
authorities,  a requirement which is entirely irrelevant and 
does not exist in Israel.                                    
<LI> to appear before an information board which will not approve
any  plan  which:
<OL Type=a>
<LI> is not within village  boundaries (the boundaries are not shown to
 applicants, and usually not even to their lawyers); 
<LI> which is  near an existing or proposed 
highway  (plans of  which  are not  given  to   applicants), 
<LI> which is located on government or army lands.             
</OL>
<LI> When permission is refused, the applicant may invest a large
sum  of  money and submit a parcellation plan for the  plot. 
The planning bodies tended not to approve such plans.        
<LI> Another option is to build without a license.                
</UL>

<P>
<HR>
