<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Law Enforcement Vis-a-Vis Israeli Civilians </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Law Enforcement Vis-a-Vis Israeli Civilians in the Occupied Territories </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> March 1994 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n 1982, an Israeli government inquiry was established to
examine the enforcement of law in the occupied territories. The
commission, headed by Deputy Attorney General Yehudit Karp, found
"substantial deficiencies" in the way the police handled offenses
imputed to Jewish residents in the territories. The commission
report warned that these omissions were "symptomatic of a deeper
problem, which contains within it the seeds of a dangerous process
whose end cannot be known". 
<P>
      This report reveals that more than a decade after the Karp
Report, not only is the work of the police still characterized by
the same omissions, but the conduct of the army, the State
Attorney's Office, and the courts also reflect an ongoing policy of
biased and partial law enforcement with regards to settlers in the
occupied territories. The Hebron massacre, twelve years later, is
but the most extreme consequence of a persisting environment in
which illegal acts by Israeli civilians in the occupied territories
have been handled with marked neglect by Israeli authorities. 
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>Amongst the main findings:</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI> <B>IDF</B> - As the sovereign authority in the area, the IDF has not
fulfilled its duty to protect the Palestinian population. Concrete
steps have not been taken to prevent violent or illegal acts by
settlers against Palestinians or intervene once they began. For
example, on numerous instances over recent months, leaders of
settler organizations publicly announced plans to block access to
Palestinian vehicles on public roads; yet, the army did not
intervene in these unlawful activities. On numerous other
occasions, army troops did not intervene when settlers shot towards
Palestinian residents or caused damage to their property. IDF
officers have testified at the commission of inquiry into the
Hebron massacre that army orders forbid soldiers from firing at
settlers, even in cases when the settlers were unlawfully shooting
at Palestinian residents. 
<P> 
<LI> <B>Police</B> - There are serious deficiencies in the way the police treat
offenses allegedly committed by Israeli settlers against
Palestinians in the territories. In many cases -- including those
involving fatalities -- even the most rudimentary of investigations
have not been conducted. 
<P>
     As a rule, incidents in which no complaint is filed are not
investigated, even if the police receive information from external
sources. Police often refuse to accept complaints from
Palestinians, or hinder their efforts to do so. In other cases the
police deny ever receiving a complaint, even when representatives
of local human rights organizations had accompanied the complainant
and been present when the complaint was made. If an investigation
is begun, the closing of the file on the grounds of "offender
unknown" is commonplace -- even when there are prima facie details
identifying the offender. 
<P>
     Commonly, the police investigation drag on for two years and
more, or files are held up for long periods in the police
Prosecutions Department. This foot-dragging has serious
consequences: a protracted investigation makes it more difficult to
locate witnesses and reduces their ability to remember details of
the incident. If, or when, the investigation is completed, the
delay influences the decision of the State Attorney's Office on
whether to submit an indictment.
<P>
<LI><B>The Courts</B> - The Israeli government has installed two systems of
justice -- based on national identity -- toward perpetrators of
crimes in the territories. Palestinians suspected of committing
violence against Israelis are tried before a military court;
Israeli citizens suspected of committing violent actions against
Palestinians are tried before a civilian court inside Israel.
<P>
     The charges brought against Jewish settlers have been
disproportionately light relative to the severity of the crimes
they alledgedly committed. In most cases, including those involving
fatalities, the penalties are incommensurate with the gravity of
the offense.  
<P> 
     Israeli settlers convicted in courts inside Israel for crimes
perpetrated against Palestinians generally received lighter
sentences than Palestinians convicted of the same crimes against
Jews. The grounds cited by judges for the punishment frequently
reflect a nationalist bias.
</UL> 
     The repeated failures of the various authorities to enforce
the law vis-a-vis the settlers suggest the existence of a policy
bordering on tacit consent to the violence perpetrated by these
individuals. B'Tselem calls on the Israeli government to take steps
to ensure that the rule of law is applied promptly, thoroughly, and
impartially.

<P>
<HR>
