<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - The Military Judicial System in the West Bank </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Followup Report: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> The Military Judicial System in the West Bank </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> May 1990 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>I</B></FONT>n November 1989 B'Tselem published a 
report on the military judicial
system in the West Bank.  With the help of seven Israeli attorneys,
we followed the judicial process over a period of eight months,
from the moment of the West Bank residents' detention right through
to the ruling in the military courts.  Since publication of the
report, B'Tselem continued monitoring the judicial system and
visited courts in Ramallah, Nablus and Hebron.  In this
Information Sheet the primary conclusions of the November 1989
report are reviewed, as well as the changes observed in the course
of our visits to the courts.  The Information Sheet also contains
the IDF Spokesperson's response to B'Tselem's report as received
by our office in March 1990. 
<P>
B'Tselem closely monitored the changes and improvements which
took place in the military courts on the West Bank, and
observed trials in Ramallah, Hebron, and Nablus.  The conclusions
of our follow-up deal chiefly with improvements and changes that
took place concerning the attendance of witnesses and defendants in
court.  According to the IDF Spokesperson's statistics, 88.15% of
defendants and 55.75% of witnesses appeared at regular trials in
January 1990.  This is indeed a significant increase in the
percentage of attendance at court since the publication of B'Tselem's
report in November 1989.
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1> Conclusions of the Followup: </FONT></B><BR>
The rights granted residents of the territories by 
Israeli military law were minimal at best and fell short of the
rights of suspects and defendants within Israel.  It is thus
essential to protect these basic rights.
<P>
The IDF response made it clear that the army was aware of
the delays and injustices inflicted upon thousands of
Palestinian suspects and defendants.  The IDF Spokesperson ascribed
this, to a great extent, to the workload which burdened the system.
<P>
The external appearance of the courthouses, the filth, the disorder,
the lack of punctuality, the fact that no one knew which cases
would be heard or which postponed, the degrading treatment of lawyers
who spent long hours in courtyards, without room, public phone,
or a drinking tap on hot days were all symptomatic of the judicial
process within the courtroom itself.
<P>
The lack of photocopying machines at the disposal of lawyers, made
it impossible to photocopy court records or to prepare a proper
defence.  The courts set dates for bail hearings, which meant that
detainees were held until their trial, a period which was weeks
long.
<P>
Improvements in the system, such as establishment of a new court
in Jenin and the new "expedited trials," led to the "closing of
cases" at a quicker pace than in the past.  The impression was
left that the military court, as a result of the pressure it was
under, began measuring its effectiveness in terms of productivity. 
Although a court must close cases, it must also determine guilt
based on legitimate evidence and witnesses, use predetermined
legal procedures, maintain an atmosphere of respect, preserve the
rights of defendants and their attorneys, and take into account
the feelings of defendants' families.

<P>
<HR>
