<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - The System of Taxation in the West Bank and Gaza Strip </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> The System of Taxation in the West Bank and Gaza Strip 
as an Instrument for the Enforcement of Authority During the Uprising </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> Fevruary 1990 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B> The report includes the following main sections: </B>
<OL>
<LI> Introduction;
<LI> Legal perspective;
<LI> Budget of the Territories - sources and revenues;
<LI> Taxation during the Uprising;
<LI> Conclusions;
<LI> Notes;
<LI> Appendices.
</OL>
This report deals with the system of taxation in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip during the Intifada period.  Its purpose is to
examine changes made to the system from 1989-1990, a period
which saw a significant drop in the income of the
residents, growing alienation between them and the government,
and the launch of a widespread overt and covert tax rebellion.
<P>
In democratic countries, taxes are imposed by an elected government,
giving the voters at least some feeling  of control over the amount
of tax they are expected to pay. In the case of a region under
foreign military occupation, the residents cannot have any say
in decisions concerning taxation. In such circumstances, the issue
of taxation takes on special political significance, becoming a
focus for friction between the occupier and the occupied.  The
former regards taxation as a legitimate means of financing the
needs of the population, while the latter perceives it as oppressive
and coercive.  The occupying government should, therefore, exercise
extreme caution and discretion with respect to fiscal measures. 
<P>
This report attempts to answer the following questions:
<OL>
<LI> Were actions being taken which contravened legal regulations
and orders?
<LI> Did the tax laws applied in the territories comply with
the spirit of the law?
<LI> What were the measures employed to enforce the tax laws?
<LI> What were the results of such enforcement?
</OL>
The report briefly surveys the legal aspects of tax collection
in the territories, with reference to the pertinent provisions
of international law and to the changes implemented in the local
law of the West Bank and Gaza Strip under Israeli rule.
<P>
The report goes on to present background data on the budget of
the occupied territories, tax revenues, and the ratio of taxes to
GNP. 
<P>
The report primarily addresses the situation vis-a-vis taxation
which arose in the wake of the uprising.  It describes the
system of tax collection in use since the start of the uprising
until February 1990 and the measures employed to maintain it. 
Some typical cases were selected from documented complaints to
illustrate the way the system works.  Finally, the norms of
enforcement and appeal which were in force in the territories are
compared with those which were in use in Israel.
<P>
The report does not purport to deal with the entire range of fiscal
matters in the territories.  Rather, it aims to examine the use
made of taxation in the territories, and to indicate  the policy,
objectives, and use of taxation in a situation of popular insurgency.

<P>
<HR>
