<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Information Sheet: Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Update </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> August 1989 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B>Special Report: Prison Facilities </B>
<UL>
<LI> General information
<LI> Army Spokesperson's Data
<LI> Types of prison facilities
<LI> IDF prisons
<LI> Differences among the various facilities
<LI> Typical problems in prisons
<LI> Prison killings
<LI> Women prisoners
<LI> Notification to relatives upon arrest.
</UL>

Estimates put the total number of Palestinian prisoners from
the beginning of the Intifada until the end of July 1989 at around
50,000 persons. 
<P>
The types of prisons where Palestinians were detained are
Prison Service facilities, Israel Police facilities, and facilities
under IDF authority, which include, in the territories: Tulkarm,
Fara'a, Anatot, Opher, Dvir (Dahariya), Gaza Coast Compound (Ansar
2), and Khan Yunis; in Israel, Megiddo and Ketsiot (Ansar 3). 
This category, prisons run by the IDF both in Israel and in the
territories, is the subject of this inquiry.
<P>
The network of military prisons was made up of facilities
designed for short-term imprisonment, in which prisoners were
supposed to be kept until the end of the legal proceedings against
them. There was also a small number of facilities designed for
long-term confinement which were supposed to hold convicted prisoners
and administrative detainees. The heavy pressure on the military
courts which delayed and drew out the court proceedings against
residents of the territories, and the overcrowding in the long-term
prison facilities were the reasons that, in many cases, prisoners
were held for long periods in short-term facilities which did not
provide the necessary conditions for long-term confinement. In
addition to the network of official prison facilities, the IDF
made use of the facilities of the Military Government of Judea,
Samaria and the Gaza Strip, as lock-up facilities for temporary
detainees as well as for persons who had been charged and were
in the process of a hastened judicial procedure. In these facilities
the prisoners were kept in conditions that did not meet the minimal
acceptable requirements for persons held in custody.  The number
of prisoners held in them was not reported and, because these were
not official facilities, there were no official criteria applied
in their administration.
<P>
To the best of our knowledge, lawyers were not permitted to
enter these facilities. According to evidence given to us, the
treatment of prisoners in these facilities appeared to be
particularly bad.
<P>
Typical problems in prisons included overcrowding, inadequate
sleeping arrangements, indecent arrangements for eating (i.e. no
chairs or tables provided), washing arrangements which were not
consistent throughout the prison system (i.e., in Dahariya, prisoners
are allowed to shower twice a week, while in Ofer the prisoners
have the use of a shower at all times), unvaried food lacking in
fresh fruit and vegetables, spices and coffee, a frequent water
shortage in the Gaza Coast Compound and in Block 1 of Ketsiot,
and unsatisfactory conditions for meeting lawyers.  Other problems
were a delay in distribution of newspapers and mail, and the
censoring of books and newspapers. 
<P>
The Army Spokesperson's Office reported that from the beginning
of the Intifada to the end of June 1989, 6 prisoners who were
residents of the territories were killed at Ketsiot prison by fellow
prisoners who suspected them of collaborating with the authorities
or of "immoral activity" (Palestinian term). The Army Spokesperson
did not give us data on prisoners killed by fellow prisoners in
other prison facilities.  There are at least another 9 cases of
prison deaths where there is a suspicion that the prison authorities
or GSS personnel were involved, directly or indirectly.
<P>
Until the writing of this report, in most of the arrests,
the prisoners were not allowed to inform their families of their
arrest, nor was the family notified within 48 hours through the
Civil Administration. In a number of cases, the family was notified
through the Red Cross, but in most cases many days elapsed before
the notification reaches the family. Over and above the natural
anxiety and uncertainty regarding the whereabouts of the prisoner,
there is the need for the family to know of his arrest in order
to secure the services of a lawyer to represent him.  

<P>
<HR>
