<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Information Sheet </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> July 1989 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B>SETTLERS</B> - The month of June 1989 saw an escalation in actions
initiated by Jewish settlers in the territories, against the
Palestinian population. For the first time settlers living in the
territories took action within the Green Line (within the borders
of the State of Israel), against Palestinians. A number of incidents
in which settlers attacked journalists and IDF soldiers were
recorded. Only in a few cases were arrests reported. A list of
the incidents is included in the information sheet. 
<P>
<B>INQUIRY</B> - On June 18 Salah el Bah'sh, age 17, was killed by IDF
soldiers, by shooting, in the Nablus Casbah, between 8 and 9 am.
The Army Spokesperson told journalists that the youngster was fired
on after he had pretended to draw his identity card from his pocket,
and then suddenly struck one of the soldiers and fled. According
to the IDF Spokesperson, El Bah'sh did not stop when the soldiers
called out "Halt!", and he was then fired upon ('Hadashot' June
19). The results of an inquiry conducted by B'Tselem and ACRI
(Association for Civil Rights in Israel) present a different picture,
in which Salah eventually halted and was shot while raising his
hands. He was killed by a rubber bullet. 
<P>
<B>DEPORTATIONS</B> - On June 13 1989, the Chief of Staff told the Knesset
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee that the IDF and the Ministry
of Justice were examining the possibility of shortening the process
of deportations from the territories, by speeding up the hearings
of appeals to the High Court. According to the Chief of Staff,
they were also examining the possibility of deportations being
carried out before the hearings are completed: if the High Court
ruled against deportation then the plaintiff would be permitted
to return. On June 29 1989, 8 residents of the territories were
deported to Lebanon. From 1967 to July 1989, the number of persons
deported by Israel from the territories totals 1253, 53 of them
since the beginning of the Intifada until the writing of this report,
among them students, journalists, university lecturers, lawyers
and teachers. The deportees, generally speaking, formed part of
the political leadership, on the local or national level. The reasons
generally given for deportations were incitement, political
subversion, active membership in banned organizations and so on.
The security establishment did not employ deportation as a punishment
for terrorist activities.
<P>
The legal perspective on the deporations is discussed. 

<P>
<HR>
