<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Information Sheet: Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Update </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> June 1989 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B>Contents:</B>
<UL>
<LI> Intifada Fatalities
<LI> Plastic Bullets
<LI> House Demolitions
<LI> Curfews
<LI> Settlers
<LI> Health Care
</UL>
In May 1989, 35 Palestinian residents were killed, and one
Israeli soldier.  In May, 2 children under 12 years of age , and
6 youths aged 13-16 were killed. Of note is the high number of
deaths among persons aged 40 or more, 4 in all, one of them a woman
aged 50 years. The rise in the number of fatalities, which began
in March 1989, continued. Half of those killed in May were from
the Gaza Strip, whereas in the past the proportion was generally
about one third of the total. The trend of Palestinians killing
Palestinians thought to be collaborators continued. 
<P>
61 of the Palestinians killed from August 1988 - March 1989
died as a result of the use of plastic bullets.  The Deputy Chief
of Staff, General Ehud Barak, justified the IDF's use of plastic
bullets in dealing with rioters. In his deposition, the Deputy
Chief of Staff declared: "Because of the characteristics of the
plastic bullet, which are quite different from those of live
ammunition, the correct use of this bullet, at certain distances
is not supposed to be fatal." The testimonies of officers in the
reserves, included in the information sheet, reveal that the training
in the use of plastic bullets was perfunctory, and that it was
difficult to follow the guidelines for shooting. 
<P>
There was a resumption of house demolitions in May 1989.  The
information sheet includes B'Tselem's investigation in El-Arub
refugee camp.
<P>
During 1989, the imposing of curfew was also used as a sweeping
collective punitive measure. Imposing a curfew is clearly
a collective punishment, thus contravening the international law
which prevailed in the territories.
<P>
The month of May 1989 was marked by an escalation of action
taken by settlers against Palestinians, in reaction to attacks
on vehicles travelling in Judea and Samaria. Although these actions
were planned in advance and well organized, neither the police
nor the IDF took sufficient action to prevent such occurrences.
In most of the  cases where there was a confrontation between
settlers and IDF soldiers, punitive and deterrent action was not
taken against the settlers.
<P>
At the beginning of May 1989 we received information concerning
an outbreak of Brucellosis in a small village, Ras Atiya, not far
from Kalkilya. Brucellosis, known also as 'Malta Fever', is a severe
illness that afflicts sheep and goats, and is passed to humans
through the affected milk. Complications of the disease can cause
paralysis of the limbs. The villagers complained that the Civil
Administration had given instructions to the Government Hospital
at Tul-Karem not to hospitalize the sick, unless they paid the
hospitalization fee of twenty shekels per day. The order was given
because most of the villagers do not have medical insurance through
the Civil Administration. B'tselem's findings were published in
the press, and the main points were relayed verbally to
senior officials of the Civil Administration. Within a week members
of the Civil Administration came to Ras Atiya, arranged for medical
care for the villagers, and began work on eradicating the disease
among the flocks.

<P>
<HR>
