<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem - Information Sheet: Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> Information Sheet: </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B> Update </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B> May 1989 </B></FONT>
</I>
<HR>
<P>
- Summary -
</CENTER>
<P>

<B>422</B> Palestinians, inhabitants of the territories, were killed in
the period from the beginning of the Intifada in December 1987
until the end of April 1989, by soldiers of the Israel Defence
Forces and by Israeli civilians. 391 were killed by live ammunition,
including plastic bullets, 15 of them children less than 12 years
old, 59 aged 13-16. 31 were killed as a result of beatings, burns
and other injuries not caused by live ammunition, 3 of them children
less than 12 years, 2 aged 13-16 years. A further 70 deaths occurred
a short time after exposure to tear gas, 27 of whom were infants.
From a medical point of view it is difficult to determine that
exposure to tear gas is the direct and sole cause of death. 
<P>
In this period 4 IDF soldiers and 9 Israeli civilians were killed,
3 of them infants. In April 1989, two thirds of the deaths occured
in the West Bank, one third in the Gaza Strip.  27 of the April
killings, the majority, occured in the 17 days between 13-28 April,
8 of them in the Bethlehem district, an area which had been till
then relatively quiet.  Despite the 'official ending' of the policy
of beatings, almost every month at least one death due to beating
was recorded. A total of 17 residents of the territories were killed
by Israeli civilians.  (The number of deaths reported is based
on information from both Israeli and Palestinian sources, together
with information collected by workers of the center. It is
difficult to establish precisely the number of Palestinians killed.
The data published by the center is the best assessment possible.)
<P>
From the partial data in our possession we know of nearly
700 houses that had been demolished since the beginning of
the Intifada until the writing of this report. 50 additional houses
had been sealed, as punishment for security offenses. 
<P>
From December 1987 to May 1, 1989, 45 Palestinian residents had
been deported.
<P>
Deportation orders were pending for 13 residents (details of name,
age, occupation, and family status are given in the informaiton
sheet.)
<P>
According to military sources, approximately 1020 men and women
were being held in administrative detention at the writing of this
sheet. (Approximately 5000 others were imprisoned, some
following trial and conviction, some held prior to being brought
to trial, and some held till the conclusions of proceedings against
them.)  According to the military sources, since the beginning
of the Intifada a total of 4500 residents of the territories had
been held in administrative detention.
<P>
The information sheet includes the investigation of two killing
incidents by the IDF in the Dehaishe Refugee Camp, based on
testimonies of residents of Dehaishe.  The first incident involved
Nasser Ibrahim Elkassas, 16.  The second involved Rafaida Abu Laban,
14.  These incidents raise some questions:
<OL TYPE=a>
<LI> In the two cases the youths were shot from behind, when the soldiers were
not endangered by them;
<LI> In at least one of the incidents the youth was not ordered to halt, and no warning shots were fired
before the fatal shots were fired.
</OL>
<BR>
Every resident of the West Bank and Gaza, over the age of
16, is obliged by order to carry his identity card with him.
A resident without his identity card commits a criminal offense
and can be arrested. A frequently occurring phenomenon around the
time of the writing of this report was the confiscation of identity
cards from inhabitants of the territories, in order to force them
to pay income tax or to report the military government and sometimes
apparently simply for the sake of harassment. The Association for
Civil Rights in Israel submitted a petition to the High Court of
Justice on behalf of seven residents of the territories whose
identity cards were confiscated and not returned. Responding to
the petition to the High Court, a representative for the Attorney
General, said there was no legal basis for the confiscating of
identity cards. (The affidavits of 3 of the 7 residents are included
in the information sheet.)

<P>
