<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Shaken to Death: Torture in Interrogation </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Shaken to Death: Torture in Interrogation </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT>bed a-Samed Harizat, a resident of Hebron, was detained on 22
April 1995 and taken to Jerusalem for interrogation.  During his
interrogation he lost consciousness and was taken to the hospital. 
He died on April 26.  His autopsy revealed that Harizat died as
a result of brain damage caused by violent shaking during
interrogation.  This was the first time that the Government publicly
attributed the death of a Palestinian in custody to interrogation
methods.
<P>
Violent shaking or whiplashing - in which an interrogator grabs
the detainee by the clothes or shoulders - has become the most
common form of violence experienced by GSS detainees.  It can cause
severe neck pain, loss of consciousness, as well as permanent brain
injury.  Dr. Robert Kirschner, a forensic pathologist and a
specialist in shaking injuries in children, submitted an affidavit
to the Israeli High Court of Justice which explained that shaking
produces a differential motion between the skull and the brain,
such that the brain continues in motion after the head has stopped
moving.
<P>
The State Attorney, Dorit Beinish, in consultation with the Attorney
General, Michael Ben-Yair, decided not to file criminal charges
against those responsible for Harizat's death; instead she decided
to subject one interrogator to internal disciplinary proceedings.
<P>
In response to this decision, B'Tselem published a notice in the
Israeli press calling for the criminal prosecution of all those
responsible for Harizat's death.  B'Tselem was joined by three
other organizations in publishing this notice: HaMoked: Center
for the Defence of the Individual, the Public Committee Against
Torture in Israel, and the Association of Israeli-Palestinian
Physicians for Human Rights.
<P>
B'Tselem also retained the services of civil rights attorney Andre
Rosenthal to file an appeal to the Israeli High Court to request
the results of the investigation into Harizat's death.  In addition,
B'Tselem, together with the Association for Civil Rights in Israel,
sent a letter to the Ministerial Committee which oversees the GSS
including testimonies of Palestinian detainees who were violently
shaken in interrogation and subsequently released without being
charged with any offense.
<P>
The death of Harizat generated a great deal of discussion and 
controversy, both within the media and the public as well as within
the Ministry of Justice, the Knesset and the Inter-Ministerial
Committee which oversees the GSS.  Immediately following Harizat's
death a GSS source claimed that 2,200 Islamist activists had been
detained and interrogated according to the Landau Commission
guidelines, which authorizes the use of "moderate physical pressure"
in interrogations.  Rabin went further in a radio interview and
defended shaking as an effective interrogation method by saying
that "it has been used against 8,000 detainees and there hasn't
been any problem" (Yoman Hashavua - Kol Yisrael, quoted in Ha'aretz
30.7.95).
<P>
The issue of the 1987 Landau Commission and its authorization of
"a moderate amount of physical pressure" came under renewed public
scrutiny.  Both the Justice Minister, Prof. David Libai, and Ben-Yair
expressed support for greater restrictions on interrogation methods. 
In response, Prime Minister Rabin and GSS officers accused Ben-Yair
and others of tying the hands of the GSS in their fight against
terrorism.  Ben-Yair reacted to the criticism by giving an interview
to a legal journal in which he criticized the GSS with unprecedented
candor, stating among other things that the form of shaking used
in interrogations was not what was authorized by the inter-
ministerial committee and that the GSS cannot consider themselves
above the law (see separate box). 
<P>
Despite all of this controversy, the use of torture and other forms
of ill-treatment in interrogations has continued.  Following an
attack which killed several soldiers at a bus stop in January 1995,
the Israeli Government authorized temporary "special permissions"
to enable the GSS to use extraordinary methods in the interrogation
of suspected Islamist extremists.  These special permissions have
been extended several times, most recently in October 1995 for
an additional three months.  The specific methods allowed have
not been made public.  However, the Attorney General stated that
violent shaking is still allowed as a method of interrogation. 
<P>
For the first time, the High Court of Justice recently permitted
the GSS to use physical force, including forceful shaking, against
a Palestinian detainee (see attached press release).  Such a legal
precedent represents an additional set back in the struggle to
outlaw all forms of torture and ill-treatment.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>More on this Issue:</B></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><B><A HREF="musa.htm"> Forcefully Shaken After the Death of Harizat </A></B><BR>
       Testimony of Musa Farid Musa Masharka, 26 years old, resident of
       Jafna, Ramallah District.  He was detained on March 7, 1995 and
       <B>interrogated for 64 days</B>.  On May 16, he was released with no charges
       filed against him.
<LI><B><A HREF="attrn.htm"> Attorney General, Michael Ben-Yair criticizes the GSS and shaking </A></B><BR>
        from an interview given to HaLishka, quoted in Ha'aretz 19.10.95
<LI><B><A HREF="../../press/960128.htm"> Press Release - January, 1996 </A></B><BR>
	Human rights organizations - B'Tselem, HaMoked: Center
	for the Defense of the Individual, the Association of
	Physicians for Human Rights and the Public Committee
	Against Torture in Israel - condemn today's decision
	of the High Court of Justice, which permits the use of
	torture against Palestinian detainee, Abed el-Halim
	Balbisi.
</UL>
<P>
