<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/news/96spring/tortupd.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119030101 text/html 5851
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 02:59:45 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5680
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 09:50:24 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Israel Proposes to Leagalize Torture </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Israel Proposes to Legalize Torture </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he Israeli government has drafted 
a bill to regulate the activities
and authority of the General Security Services (GSS), which up
to now has been regulated by an unwritten system of agreements
between it and other authorities.  Ostensibly such legislation
represents a positive development in terms of Israel's commitment
to human rights and the rule of law.  However, the GSS bill will
in fact legalize the methods of torture and ill-treatment routinely
used by the GSS in interrogations of Palestinians.  
<P>
A section of the GSS Law entitled "Special Interrogation Powers
to Prevent Terrorism" grants GSS interrogators the authority to
apply "pressure" to a detainee if there is a reasonable basis to
believe he has information which could prevent a clear danger to
the state or to human life.  The precise methods of pressure allowed
will be determined by rules which will remain confidential.
<P>
This framework of public guidelines whose details are secret was
established by the Landau Commission, a 1987 Commission of Inquiry
which authorized the GSS to use a "moderate amount of physical
pressure" in interrogations.  A secret annex to the Landau Commission
report details the specific measures allowed.  
<P>
Experience demonstrates that, rather than restricting physical
force to the most extreme situations, such guidelines result in
the routine application of methods constituting torture and ill-
treatment.  In the case of one interrogation method, violent shaking,
the late Prime Minister and Defense Minister, Yitzhak Rabin, stated
that this method had been used against 8,000 Palestinians.  Most
of these detainees were subsequently released with no charges brought
against them.  This suggests that physical force is a standard
rather than an exceptional part of GSS interrogations.
<P>
That the GSS bill would perpetuate the status quo regarding
interrogations of Palestinians is supported by the statement of
a GSS agent given in an interview with the Israeli daily <I>Ha'aretz</I>:
<UL>
     It's all a question of semantics.  The law can prohibit torture
     and humiliation of terrorists suspected of planning and
     conducting attacks and allow increased physical pressure. 
     Ultimately it's almost the same thing.
</UL>
At the same time, by incorporating these methods into law, it would
prevent legal experts and human rights organizations from contesting
their legality under Israeli law.  Currently, many High Court appeals
are based on the assertion that the Landau Commission has no
authority to sanction methods of interrogation which violate the
Israeli penal code; section 277 of the Israeli Penal Code prohibits
the use of force or violence by a public official.  
<P>
Together with the GSS Law, the government proposed an amendment
to the Penal Code to explicitly prohibit torture.  The "Prohibition
of Torture" bill mandates 10-20 years imprisonment for a public
official who uses torture.  However the bill initially defined
torture as "severe pain or suffering, whether physical or mental,
<I>with the exception of pain or suffering inherent in interrogation
procedures or punishment according to law</I>" (our emphasis).  This
clause ensured that the vast majority of incidents of torture -
those conducted as part of interrogations - would not be punishable. 
 It appears that as a result of preliminary advocacy by B'Tselem
and other groups, the Attorney General may recommend that this
definition be modified to conform to the International Convention
Against Torture.
<P>
The Prohibition of Torture Law may be used to deflect criticism
away from the GSS Law, and allow the government to claim that it
does not condone torture.  However, the gravity of the GSS Law
cannot be overestimated.  If passed, this law will provide legal
sanction to the methods of torture and ill-treatment routinely
used by the GSS.  Moreover, Israel will become the first country
in the twentieth century to legalize the intentional infliction
of pain and suffering during interrogation.  This would set a
dangerous precedent which could be copied by other countries.  
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>The Need for Action</B></FONT><P>

B'Tselem considers a concerted effort by the Israeli, Palestinian
and international human rights community to be essential to counter
the problematic aspects of both proposed laws.  The approach toward
these bills is as follows: 
<UL>
<LI> To welcome an explicit prohibition against torture in the Israeli
penal code and the regulation of the powers of the GSS by law.
<LI> To strongly oppose any piece of legislation that authorizes
government agents to resort to torture or ill-treatment under any
circumstance. 
</UL>
B'Tselem has organized a coalition of Israeli human rights groups
to coordinate a domestic and international campaign against the
legalization of torture in Israel. 
<UL>
Letters of concern can be sent to:
<LI> Justice Minister, Prof. David Libai, fax: 972-2-285-438
<LI> Minister Joseph Beilin, Prime Minister's Office, fax: 972-2-653-6101
</UL>

<HR>
