<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, B'Tselem Monitors Palestinian Elections
 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> B'Tselem Monitors Palestinian Elections </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>O</B></FONT>n January 20 1996, Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza elected
a Council and a Ra'is (president) of the Executive Authority. 
B'Tselem was granted observer status to these elections. Despite
the numerous problems in the election process caused by the
Palestinian Authority, as an Israeli organization B'Tselem monitored
only Israel's involvement in the elections.
<P>
From the standpoint of Israel's obligations, the main problems
centered around East Jerusalem.  As part of its continuing assertion
of unilateral sovereignty over Jerusalem, Israel imposed a great
many restrictions on election campaigning, the freedom of Palestinian
observers and the number of voters inside the city.
<P>
Approximately 50,000 Palestinians were registered to vote in the
Jerusalem district.  However, Israel only allowed some 4,500 persons
to vote inside the Jerusalem municipality.  Consequently, the
overwhelming majority of Palestinians registered to vote in the
district had to leave the city limits to cast their ballot.
<P>
Furthermore, those Palestinians registered to vote inside the city
had to confront a massive police and military presence to reach
their polling site.  Thousands of armed police officers and border
police created an atmosphere of tension at the East Jerusalem post
offices which served as polling stations.  B'Tselem monitors also
observed police officers photographing voters in at least two polling
sites.  This raised the fear among East Jerusalem voters that their
status as permanent residents of Israel would be jeopardized if
they voted. 
<P>
On the day of the elections, police prevented Palestinian observers
from approaching the polling sites in East Jerusalem and detained
at least 5 observers.  This despite the assurance which the Legal
Advisor to the Foreign Ministry, Joel Zinger, provided to B'Tselem
that local observers were entitled to enter the post offices to
monitor the election process.
<P>
All of these problems are likely to have contributed to reduced
voter turnout in the Jerusalem district.  While turnout throughout
the West Bank and Gaza was between 70-85% of eligible voters, in
the Jerusalem district less than 35% of registered voters cast
their ballots.

<P>
<HR>
