<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Human Rights in the Palestinian Authority </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Human Rights in the Palestinian Authority </I></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>The Palestinian Preventive Security Service </B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT> number of Palestinian security forces have been formed to operate
in the Palestinian autonomous areas.  Yet one of these forces -
the Preventive Security Service (PSS) - also operates outside of
the autonomous areas and is responsible for systematic human rights
violations.  In August, B'Tselem released a report on human rights
violations committed by the PSS in areas still under Israeli
jurisdiction.  
<P>
<B>Neither Law Nor Justice</B> documents many instances of extrajudicial
punishment, abduction, torture and prolonged, arbitrary detention
of Palestinians from the West Bank by the PSS.  The victims are
generally accused of "morals crimes" such as prostitution or
extramarital sex; drug use; theft; or collaboration with the Israeli
authorities.  In none of the cases investigated was the victim
presented with an arrest warrant, formally charged with a crime
or given the opportunity to defend him/herself.
<P>
While the PSS and the Palestinian Authority (PA) as a whole are
directly responsible for these incidents, Israel also bears
responsibility under international law for the safety and well-being
of the population under its rule.  In spite of this obligation,
the Israeli security forces have not taken any action to prevent
the continuation of these violations throughout the West Bank. 
In contrast, Israel vigorously enforces the prohibition on the
functioning of Palestinian security officials in East Jerusalem. 
This suggests that Israel is concerned exclusively with encroachment
upon its sovereignty, rather than with the well-being of the
population under its control.  Several sources point to a secret
agreement between Israel and the PA in which Israel gives the PSS
freedom of action throughout the West Bank in all criminal matters
in exchange for their cooperation against Islamic groups.  
<P>
This report is B'Tselem's first on issues related to the human
rights record of the Palestinian Authority.  As our mandate is
to monitor human rights violations by Israel, this report focused
on violations committed by the PSS in territory still under Israeli
control.  Since the report was issued, Israeli forces have withdrawn
from West Bank cities (except Hebron) and these areas have been
incorporated into the Palestinian Authority.  Most of the West
Bank still remains under Israeli control however (in what is defined
as Area C under the Oslo B Accords).  In addition, many Palestinian
villages in the West Bank are part of Area B, and as such are under
joint Israeli-Palestinian control.  The complicated division of
the West Bank into areas of Palestinian, Israeli and joint authority,
suggest that the issues raised in this report of overlapping
responsibilities for human rights remain relevant.
<P>
Since the report was issued, a Palestinian from Ramallah, 'Azzam
Muhammad Abd al-Rahim Mosleh died in Palestinian custody (September
28).  He is the fifth Palestinian to die in the custody of the
PA, apparently as a result of torture in interrogation.  Because
Mosleh was also a U.S. citizen, his death received extensive
international attention, as well as pressure by the U.S. government
to conduct a full investigation.  This pressure caused the PA to
allow the body to be exhumed for autopsy.  It is unfortunate that
only because Mosleh was a U.S. citizen did his death receive the
attention it deserved. 
<P>
<HR ALIGN=center WIDTH=60%>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>B'Tselem Fieldworker Detained by the Palestinian Authority</B></FONT>
<P>
Since B'Tselem issued its report on the Preventive Security Service
(PSS), its fieldworker Bassem 'Eid has been subjected to increasingly
serious harassment and intimidation by agents of the Palestinian
Authority. Other Palestinian human rights activists have faced similar forms of intimidation
<P>
Immediately following the release of the report in August 1995,
Colonel Jibril Rajoub, Head of the PSS in the West Bank, accused
Mr. 'Eid - one of the report's authors - of being "an agent of
the Israeli police."  In light of the hundreds of cases of
Palestinians killed by their compatriots during the intifada for
suspected collaboration with Israel, such a statement posed a direct
threat to Mr. 'Eid's safety.
<P>
Rajoub's statement was met with an international outcry: Palestinian,
Israeli and international human rights organizations protested
Rajoub's personal defamation of Mr. 'Eid as an attempt to evade
responsibility for the substantive allegations raised by the report. 
These organizations called for Chairman Arafat to personally
intervene to rescind the allegations against 'Eid.
<P>
In response to these appeals, Arafat's spokesperson responded that
the well-being and safety of Mr. 'Eid is not in jeopardy.  He did
not, however, retract the initial allegation.
<P>
On January 2 1996 at 11:00 p.m., Mr. 'Eid was approached by a
Palestinian police officer near his home in the Shuafat Refugee
Camp in East Jerusalem.  The officer asked Mr. 'Eid to accompany
him to Ramallah for questioning.  Mr. 'Eid was subsequently held
for 24 hours at the headquarters of Force 17 in Ramallah.  He was
not interrogated nor was he told the reason for his detention. 
Throughout this period, officials of the Authority denied the fact
that he was being detained and claimed that he was not being held
by any of the Palestinian security forces.
<P>
Clearly the prompt and unequivocal condemnation by local and
international human rights organizations, as well as the diplomatic
community, was instrumental in securing his safe release.
<P>
Mr. 'Eid's detention is a blatant example of an increasingly
prevalent pattern in which the Palestinian Authority attempts to
intimidate and silence its critics rather than addressing the
substance of their criticism.
On February 16 1995, longtime human rights activist and then-director of the Gaza Center
for Rights and Law, Raji Sourani, was detained for a day by Palestinian police in Gaza and
subsequently released eithout charge.
On December 7, Eyad Sarraj, the Commissioner General of the Palestinian independent Commission
for Citizens' Rights, was also detained for a day and released uncharged. PICCR is an 
independent civil rights ombudsmen office. Mr. Sarraj was detained after he criticized
the Palestinian Attorney General, Khaled al-Kidra, for not responding to his inquiries 
regarding specific cases of abuse.
<P> This pattern of detentions bodes poorly for freedom of human rights advocacy under 
Palestinian Authority.
<P>
<HR>
