<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/news/96spring/hebron.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119030337 text/html 5401
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 03:02:35 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5230
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 09:49:03 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Hebron Since the Massacre at the Cave </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Hebron Since the Massacre at the Cave </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

For more than twenty years, the Israeli government has failed to
protect the lives, integrity, and property of the Palestinian
residents of Hebron from repeated attacks by settlers in the city.
<P>
The Jewish settlement inside Hebron, located in the densely populated
center of a large Palestinian city, differs from other settlements
in the Occupied Territories.  B'Tselem, as well as other human
rights organizations, have repeatedly called attention to the serious
deficiencies regarding law enforcement vis-a-vis settlers,
particularly the settlers in Hebron.  These deficiencies continue
despite repeated acknowledgments by the Israeli authorities of
their obligations to act forcefully against violence.   
<P>
The most recent acknowledgment of this obligation occurred following
the massacre of Palestinian worshippers at the Cave of the Patriarchs
in February 1994.  The governmental commission of inquiry (the
Shamgar Commission), established to investigate the circumstances
surrounding the incident, forcefully and broadly criticized the
authorities' failure to enforce the law against settlers and Israeli
citizens, and noted serious defects in law enforcement.  The Israeli
government adopted the findings of the Shamgar Commission, increased
the police presence in Hebron and opened another police station
in the city.
<P>
These measures, however, did not improve the human rights situation
in Hebron.  In September, B'Tselem released a report which
demonstrated that in spite of the Shamgar Commission's unequivocal
recommendations, security forces continue to act half-heartedly
with regard to repeated acts of violence by settlers in Hebron
against Palestinians.  In numerous cases, the police conducted
no investigation following incidents of violence and only in isolated
instances were those responsible brought to trial. 
<P>
In fact, rather than protecting the Palestinian population, the
increased presence of security forces in Hebron only increased
human rights violations and the bureaucratic harassment of the
Palestinian population.  In the 18 months following the massacre
in the Cave of the Patriarchs, 26 Palestinians were killed in Hebron
by the security forces, and many more were injured.  This compares
to eleven Palestinian fatalities in the rest of the West Bank as
a whole during the same period.
<P>
Less dramatic than the casualty figures, yet perhaps more insidious,
is the massive disruption of daily life in Hebron as a result of
settlers and soldiers.  Palestinians wishing to travel from one
end of the city to the other are confronted by a logistical
nightmare.  The main roads surrounding the city center - where
the settlers live - are guarded by thirty-two roadblocks and 10
manned checkpoints.  Curfews and closures, imposed more often in
Hebron than in any other West Bank city, impose additional hardships.
<P>
These violations of the right to life and to freedom of movement
are the direct result of the presence of Israeli settlers.  The
massive military presence is there to protect the settlers, as
are the road closures, the curfews, the roadblocks, and the
checkpoints.  This creates an absurd moral and political reality
in which a minority of 450 Jewish settlers dictates the lives of
more than 120,000 Palestinians in the city.  
<P>
From a human rights perspective, the conclusion required by the
unique situation of Hebron's Jewish settlement - located within
a large Palestinian city and creating constant friction between
Palestinians and settlers - was unavoidable: the continued presence
of Jewish settlers will inevitably result in continued violations
of the human rights of Palestinian residents.  B'Tselem therefore
called for the dismantlement of the settlement inside the city
of Hebron. 
<P>
B'Tselem issued <B>Impossible Co-existence: Human Rights in Hebron Since 
the Massacre at the Cave of the Patriarchs</B> report during the negotiations for the Oslo
2 agreement in order to call attention to the problematic nature
of any solution which leaves the Jewish settlement intact.  Media
reports during the negotiations suggested that the agreement would
leave Israeli soldiers in control of the entire city.  The agreement
eventually reached, however, stipulates a partial redeployment,
with the IDF remaining in control of the portion of the city which
contains the settlement buildings.  While this is preferable to
the initial arrangement, it offers no solution for the Palestinians
who live in the neighborhoods around the settlement buildings -
precisely the population which suffers most from the problems
described in the report.

<P>
<HR>
