<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/news/96spring/stan.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119030359 text/html 6869
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 03:02:47 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6698
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 09:50:08 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, After the Report: Communicating Human Rights Information </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> After the Report: Communicating Human Rights Information </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<B>by Stan Cohen</B>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>B</B></FONT>'Tselem, like all national and international human rights
organizations, "trades" in one main resource: information.  By
collecting reliable information about human rights violations and
disseminating these facts in reports, we hope to have a public
and political impact.  If people (governments, media, the ordinary
public) "only knew" - about torture, political killings, house
demolition - then they would wake up, react, do something.
<P>
Behind this strategy is a touching faith in the power of knowledge. 
The human rights movement not only upholds the ideal of universal
values and standards, but also assumes that information about their
violations will produce universal moral and emotional responses.
<P>
This is just the faith that is contradicted by the daily practise
of human rights work.  The massive amount of information we generate
is not matched by public responses appropriate to the scale of
the atrocities.  Nor are the resources we devote to collecting
this information matched by sustained thinking about how it should
be disseminated or what effect it might have on its intended
audiences.  Reports are "released" - without evaluating or even
monitoring their impact.  A sophisticated international system
of moral bookkeeping carefully collects, checks, processes and
circulates information about human rights violations all over the
world.  But we have little idea what this information does to people. 
Sitting in New York, London or Paris, what does it mean to hear
about more horrors in Rwanda, Syria or Bosnia?  What do Israelis
actually think when they read in about yet another B'Tselem
report on torture?
<P>
Many human rights organizations are not interested in such questions
because they are not explicitly trying to reach the general public. 
Their information circulates in a closed circuit made up of other
like-minded organizations, governments, United Nations-type agencies,
lawyers and academics.  Within this circuit, the information is
indeed self-evident, the facts do speak for themselves.  For
converted audiences, this confirms what they already knew.  For
target governments and their protectors this is just more information
to be ignored, denied, explained away or justified.
<P>
Much human rights information remains in this loop, endlessly
circulating in reports, self-referential official documents, fact-
finding missions, enquiries, UN committees, conferences and legal
texts.  It simply does not reach a wider public.  And when it does,
it drops into some kind of cognitive black hole.  The information
itself is not denied.  But you accommodate to knowledge of atrocities
("that's the sort of thing that happens in places like that") or
just feel helpless ("what can I do about things like that?"). 
This happens even to the dramatic stories that pass the media
threshold - Bosnia, Somalia, Rwanda, Burundi, Haiti.  The initial
attention, compassion and outrage seem to burn themselves out. 
So the information is "lost" - preserved and recycled in yet another
"Follow-up Report" which records that indeed the same old things
are still happening.
<P>
For last two years, I have been studying how human rights
organizations disseminate their information to the wider public
and how to evaluate the effect of this information.  This project
grew out of my experience in human rights work in Israel and the
Occupied Territories.
<P>
This is a rather special case for human rights reporters.  The
violations against the Palestinians during Israel's twenty-eight
year military occupation could be expected from any such regime. 
But these abuses happened (and, in the shadow of the "Peace Process,"
still happen on a more restricted scale) while Israeli society
itself remained formally democratic.  Freedom of expression, the
rule of law and academic freedom have all remained intact.
<P>
Unlike most societies where gross human rights violations are
routine, this relative openness means that knowledge of what is
happening is available and accessible.  Investigative journalism
regularly informs the public about what is happening.  And - as
the Israeli government correctly replies to its critics - human
rights organizations, Israeli, international and even Palestinian,
benefit from an access and freedom to report quite unthinkable
in repressive societies elsewhere in the Middle East.  On one subject
alone - allegations of torture and mistreatment of Palestinian
detainees - five major reports have been produced which were widely
circulated over four years.  These were all composed of detailed,
vivid and irrefutable evidence.
<P>
Israelis then cannot say in good faith that "we didn't know" nor
claim that there were restrictions on their freedom and opportunity
to protest.  Yet the level of reaction has always seemed less than
this cumulative information "should" produce.
<P>
This gap between knowledge and action - what you know and what
you do - is not, of course, unique to Israel.  Human rights
information everywhere is always selectively filtered - whether
it is easily available or whether it has to penetrate the densest
official censorship, intimidation, lies and propaganda.
<P>
My report deals mainly with the international rather than the Israeli
context.  Based on fieldwork with organizations such as Amnesty
International, I set out some issues to consider in getting our
reports "off the shelves."  As well as moving quickly onto the
next campaign, we need to pause to think about what happened to
the last one.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center>
<P>
<I>Stan Cohen is Professor of Criminology at the Hebrew University,
Jerusalem.  He was a board member of B'Tselem and is a member of
the Public Committee Against Torture in Israel.
<P>
His report (201), <B>Denial and Acknowledgement: The Impact of
Information About Human Rights Violations</B>, is available from the
Center for Human Rights, Faculty of Law, Hebrew University, Jerusalem
91905 ($10 including postage).</I>

<P>
<HR>
