<DOCOLDNO>IA046-000818-B031-445</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.btselem.org:80/news/96spring/yizhar.htm 205.214.171.147 19970119030419 text/html 7478
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 03:03:10 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7307
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 09:50:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, After Rabin: Incitement and Violence </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Memo From the Director</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> After Rabin: Incitement and Violence </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he shock and outrage over the assassination of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin crossed national borders and was felt by Palestinians
as well as by Israelis.  Expressions of happiness by Palestinians over
Rabin's death, which would have been expected at the height of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, were almost non-existent.  As Defense
Minister at the beginning of the intifada, Yitzhak Rabin showed little
concern for the human rights of Palestinians and advocated crushing
the uprising by force - his most infamous instruction was to "break
their bones."  While human rights violations continued under his tenure
as Prime Minister, which began in 1992, Rabin also began to champion
a political solution based on negotiation and compromise.  The fact
that he was assassinated by a Jewish extremist after he signed peace
agreements with the PLO (even though many Palestinians are dissatisfied
with those agreements) turned him in the eyes of many into a hero who
sacrificed his life for the sake of peace.
<P>
     The assassination caused much soul searching within the Israeli
public.  For many the idea that a Jew would engage in an act of terrorism
seemed surprising.  Analysis of the security failures which allowed
the assassination demonstrated that the security services presumed
that only Arabs pose security risks.
<P>
     Such a discriminatory approach to law enforcement was documented
in B'Tselem's 1994 report <B>Law Enforcement Vis a Vis Israeli Civilians
in the Occupied Territories</B>.  This report focused specifically on acts
of violence committed by settlers against Palestinians, and the lack
of an appropriate response by the authorities.  In the wake of Rabin's
assassination, the Israeli public debated the causes of the murder. 
It seems clear that one cause is the sense of impunity with which the
radical right has acted over the years.
<P>
     The government took steps to compensate for its prior leniency
toward rightwing extremists.  In the weeks following the assassination,
dozens of investigations were completed and charges brought against
settlers suspected of committing acts of violence in the territories. 
<P>
     The government also investigated a possible connection between
anti-Rabin incitement and the assassination.   A policy adopted following
the assassination allows the application of pre-existing sedition and
incitement laws to prosecute not only those who commit seditious acts,
but also those who use inciting language.  In an unprecedented move,
the Attorney General, Michael Ben-Yair, sent a letter to newspaper
editors and television station managers requesting them to refrain
from publishing interviews with inciters or using quotes of incitement. 
Such publication, Ben-Yair warned, itself constitutes a crime and would
result in prosecution.  "Freedom of speech must take second place to
the threat to public order," Ben-Yair said.  
<P>
     The line between incitement and legitimate, if controversial,
speech can be difficult to draw.  Much judicial scrutiny following
the assassination focused on slogans used by the right, such as <I>Rabin
is a traitor</I> and <I>Rabin is a murderer</I>.  Whether these statements
constitute incitement to commit violence is debatable.  Certainly in
some instances the government overreacted and unnecessarily interfered
with freedom of speech and freedom of the press.   A few weeks after
the assassination, the Ministry of Justice acknowledged that rather
than prosecuting speech, law enforcement should concentrate on
prosecuting illegal acts.
<P>
     However, if the government has been overzealous in its crackdown
on anti-Rabin statements, it remains indifferent to incitement to commit
violence against Arabs.  At many of the same demonstrations which used
slogans such as <I>Rabin is a traitor</I>, the crowd also chanted <I>Death to
Arabs</I>.  This slogan - a clear example of incitement to commit violence
against individuals because of their nationality - was also chanted
following virtually every bus bombing or other attack by Palestinian
militants.  Neither before nor since the assassination have any
investigations been conducted into incidents of anti-Arab incitement,
nor has anyone been charged with incitement for using such slogans.
<P>
     The fact that prosecutions are brought for possible incitement
against Rabin but not for clear cases of incitement against Arabs is
yet another example of the government's discriminatory enforcement
of the law.  It also suggests a lack of concern for the safety of both
Arab citizens of the State and Arab residents of the Territories.
<P>
     The Israeli military demonstrates a similar lack of concern in
its operations in the territories.  This is clearly illustrated by
a juxtaposition of two recent events which took place on the same day
in the West Bank.  In the Jenin region, IDF forces conducted a raid
on a cafe to capture a Palestinian expelled to Jericho for attacking
collaborators.  The army's action occurred at the end of November 1995,
two days after responsibility for civil affairs and public order in
that region (defined as Area B under the Oslo Accords) had been
transferred to the Palestinian Authority.  
<P>
     On the same day in Nablus, which was still under complete Israeli
control, Fatah member Ahmad Tabuk shot and killed a local resident. 
Tabuk is known to have killed two other Nablus residents and has shot
several others in the legs as punishment for suspected collaboration
with Israel or so-called morals crimes.  Repeated demands by B'Tselem
to Israel's security authorities to stop Tabuk and his men from
committing these acts proved fruitless; the IDF gave Tabuk's gang a
free hand to operate in the city.  Only after the Palestinian Authority
took control of Nablus did Tabuk turn himself in.
<P>
     In the first incident, the IDF conducted a large scale military
operation in an area where it has ceded primary responsibility.  In
the second, the IDF took no action in an area still under its total
control.  The juxtaposition of these two events strengthens the claim
that the IDF is motivated solely by national, political considerations
and wantonly neglects its obligation to protect Palestinians under
its control.
<P>
     Both the issue of incitement to violence and IDF activities in
the territories demonstrate a failure to ensure and protect basic rights
to safety and well-being.  In both these cases, the inactions as well
as the actions of the government pose problems from a human rights
perspective and require the ongoing vigilance of B'Tselem.
<P>
<HR>
