<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Oslo II: A New Human Rights Map </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Oslo II: A New Human Rights Map </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he redeployment of Israeli forces in the West Bank according to the Oslo II agreement is well under
way.  All West Bank cities are now part of the Palestinian autonomous area with the exception of Hebron,
which will be handed over in March.
<P>
The implementation of autonomy will significantly reduce interaction between Palestinians and Israeli forces,
and thus lessen the potential for human rights violations.  However, the division of the West Bank into
three types of areas makes the situation more complex.  The majority of the Palestinian population live
in what is defined as Area A, which is Palestinian autonomous territory.  In Area B, populated by Palestinian
villages, the Palestinian Authority will have responsibility for civil affairs, while Israel will remain in
control of security issues.  The remaining 75% of West Bank territory is defined as Area C, in which
Israel remains in complete control.  In addition, Israel remains in control of overall security, borders,
East Jerusalem, and Jewish settlements.  
<P>
In light of this situation, the following issues relating to Israel's human rights policies and practices are
likely to require continued scrutiny:
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Freedom of movement: </B></FONT><P>
While the agreements all recognize that the West Bank and Gaza are one territorial
unit, Israel imposes a great many restrictions on travel between the two territories.  The populations most
injured by travel restrictions between the West Bank and Gaza are Gaza students enrolled in West Bank
universities; people needing to travel to receive medical care; and families where the spouses are not legal
residents of the same area.  Furthermore, Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza are denied access
to the many medical, educational and cultural institutions in East Jerusalem.  Israel also remains in control
of exit from the territories, and can therefore deny Palestinians the right to travel abroad.  
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Torture:</B></FONT><P>
 The General Security Service and other bodies which conduct interrogations of Palestinian suspects
are likely to continue to employ methods which constitute ill-treatment and torture (see articles in this
issue).
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Settler violence:</B></FONT><P>
  Palestinian police are forbidden under the Accords from arresting or prosecuting Israeli
citizens.  B'Tselem has documented both the violent acts of settlers and the lax law enforcement by Israeli
authorities.  It is unclear how the militant settlers will respond to Palestinian autonomy.  
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Human Rights in East Jerusalem:</B></FONT><P>
 The 160,000 Palestinian residents of East Jerusalem remain under
direct Israeli control.  Unlike Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza, East Jerusalem Palestinians are
considered residents of the State of Israel and are therefore subject to Israeli law, rather than the laws
and military orders which apply in the territories.  While this affords them greater protection for basic
rights, they are still subject to a variety of violations.  The most pressing of these are denial of family
reunification and discriminatory policies regarding land use and housing (see article in this issue).
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Land:</B></FONT><P>
 Throughout the occupation, Israel has confiscated privately-owned land for the construction of
settlements.  Since the signing of the Oslo II Accords, much additional land was confiscated for the construction
of by-pass roads to enable settlers to travel in the West Bank while avoiding Palestinian population centers. 
<P>
Just Compensation for past confiscations as well as the issue of future confiscations
will require scrutiny.
<P>
<HR>
