<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Forcefully Shaken After the Death of Harizat </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Forcefully Shaken After the Death of Harizat </I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<I>       Testimony of Musa Farid Musa Masharka, 26 years old, resident of
Jafna, Ramallah District.  He was detained on March 7, 1995 and
<B>interrogated for 64 days</B>.  On May 16, he was released with no charges
filed against him.</I>
<HR>
<P>
... On about the seventh day they also started to shake me - Mufaz
was first.  I would be sitting on the low chair, and he would grab
me by the shirt and shake me 15-20 times.  Twice, three times and
sometimes more during every interrogation session.
<P>
Adnan also started to shake me that same day.  Sometimes while
he stood and I sat and sometimes while we both stood.  My back
started to hurt.
<P>
Every 48 hours they let me sleep an hour or two.  Aside from that
only on the weekends.  On Fridays I could shower, but not change
clothes.
<P>
On the eighth day (March 15) Captain Dori came in and received
my file.  He is also very strong.  He lifts weights.  He made me
crouch on my toes.  Every day there were 6-8 hours of interrogation,
sometimes I ate in the interrogation room.  They let me go to the
bathroom about an hour after I started asking.  In shabeh (abusive
body positioning where the detainee is tied in an uncomfortable
position awaiting the next interrogation) they let me whenever
I needed to.  Until the eighth day, my jacket, my shirt and my
undershirt were completely torn.  When they made me kneel on my
toes, I would kneel two, three minutes and then collapse and say
that I couldn't get up, I didn't care if they killed me.  They
pulled me up by my clothes or by the handcuffs.  My hands were
torn from this.  They would hit and kick me when I got up.
<P>
... On the 34th day, April 10, 1995, "Emilio" came, who identified
himself as a Colonel, "Abu Amin," Ghali, and Dori and another from
Ramallah.  The five of them interrogated me ... They began to
interrogate me for 20 hours a day.  9 hours of interrogation, shabeh
for an hour, another 8 or 9 hours - and so on.
<P>
There were more beatings and shakings, they pressed forcefully
on my forehead from both sides.  A lot of violence.
<P>
I would throw up a lot.  The intensive interrogation continued
three days - Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.  When I threw up they
stopped for a bit and then started again.  They didn't call anyone. 
Only on the last night did they bring a medic to the interrogation
room.  A policeman.  He gave me aspirin and told me to drink -
that's what they always say.

<P>
<HR>
