<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> B'Tselem, Attorney General, Michael Ben-Yair criticizes the GSS and shaking </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I> Attorney General, Michael Ben-Yair criticizes the GSS and shaking </I></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>from an interview given to HaLishka, quoted in Ha'aretz 19.10.95</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B>"F</B></FONT>ollowing the death of Harizat in interrogation we saw how shaking
was done and we decided that this could not be a routine method
of interrogation.  This is not the "defense of necessity" (an
emergency situation which allows the use of violence outlawed by
the penal code).  ... We did not know what shaking consisted of. 
We thought that shaking is a light jostling intended to ensure
attention.  The damage liable to be caused by shaking is not just
death.  It is liable to cause brain damage as well.  I am not willing
for every young Palestinian with a black beard who is detained
to suffer brain damage.  But if he has information which is likely
to prevent a much greater evil and the interrogator uses this method
in order to discover this information, I will not charge him with
a criminal offense... 
<P>
We have to walk a very fine line.  I recognize the need to provide
the GSS with tools, but we live in a law-abiding, democratic country. 
In this country the law applies to all authorities of the state
including this interrogation authority, i.e. the GSS and those
in charge of it, i.e. the Prime Minister.  Interrogations can be
conducted only according to law, not outside of the law and not
above the law.  The way in which the legal system functioned in
the disagreement over GSS interrogations, and the way we articulated
things, provided the interrogator with the defense of the law when
he employed certain methods, including shaking, in order to prevent
a more serious injury, if there was no other way to prevent it.
... of course the Knesset could pass a law - although I don't know
how legal it would be - so that certain laws do not apply to the
security forces.  But so long as the Knesset does not do so, the
laws of Israel apply to all interrogation authorities.  ... 
<P>
It is impossible to provide [the GSS] with other methods that are
illegal.  There's no such thing.  We're not opening up torture
chambers instead of intelligence.  What do we need interrogators
for?  An interrogator works with intelligence and with sense..."

<P>
