<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> More About B'Tselem </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">

<CENTER>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B> More About B'Tselem </B></FONT>
</I>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
     <B> B'Tselem </B> was founded in 1989 by a group of Knesset
members, public figures, lawyers, academics, and journalists
with the following goals:
<UL>
<LI> To provide information to the Israeli public and the
international community about violations of human rights in
the Occupied Territories.
<P>
<LI> To recommend and encourage policy changes to ensure greater
protection of human rights.
</UL>
     Since its founding, <B>B'Tselem</B> has
earned international recognition as the leading Israeli
organization monitoring, documenting and advocating to improve
the human rights situation in the Occupied Territories.  It
has issued over 50 publications which have generated extensive
media coverage both in Israel and internationally.
<P>
     <B>B'Tselem</B> serves as a leading source of information about
human rights in the territories.  Quantitative and qualitative
data is compiled from <B>B'Tselem's</B> fieldwork, government sources
and the Israeli, Palestinian and international press.  Regular
data summaries are distributed to the media and other
interested parties.  In addition, <B>B'Tselem</B> responds to queries
from Knesset members, government committees, researchers,
students and the media.  It also provides human rights
briefings to visiting foreign delegations and members of the
diplomatic community.
<P>
     <B>B'Tselem</B> faces new challenges in advocating for human
rights in light of the Oslo process and the transfer of
partial self-governance to the Palestinian Authority.  In this
process, human rights issues and obligations have frequently
been dismissed, marginalized and ignored.  
<P>
     The Oslo process has resulted in human rights
improvements in several spheres, including fewer clashes
between Palestinians and security forces and therefore fewer
casualties.  Human rights violations by Israel continue,
however, particularly in the areas of torture and ill-
treatment in interrogations; freedom of movement;
administrative detentions; lax law enforcement regarding
settler violence; discriminatory policies in East Jerusalem;
and ongoing settlement activity and land expropriation.
<P>
     Repeated acts of violence by Islamist militants opposed
to the peace process have increased the pressure on the
government to use a strong hand to quell terrorism.  The
result is a resort to such forms of collective punishment as
extended closures, as well as greater tolerance for torture of
suspected extremists. While Israel has a
right, and even an obligation, to take measures to protect its
citizens from violence, it must do so in a manner consistent
with its obligations as a state bound by the rule of law.
<P>
     In addition to continuing abuses by Israeli authorities,
the partial transfer of authority makes Palestinians subject
to human rights violations by their own governing authority as
well.  As an Israeli organization, <B>B'Tselem</B> focuses primarily
on the Israeli authorities and their legal responsibilities to
protect and ensure human rights in the Occupied Territories. 
However, <B>B'Tselem</B> also monitors human rights violations by the
Palestinian Authority.
<P>
<HR ALIGN=center WIDTH=50%>
<P>
In 1996, <B>B'Tselem</B> received financial support from the
following organizations:
<UL>
<LI>EZE (Germany)
<LI>Ford Foundation (USA)
<LI>International Commission of Jurists (Sweden)
<LI>ICCO (Netherlands)
<LI>Novib (Netherlands)
<LI>New Israel Fund (Israel)
<LI>DanChurchAid (Denmark)
<LI>Christian Aid (Britain)
</UL>
