<h3>INTRODUCTION TO FORESTRY AND FOREST PRODUCTS RESEARCH INSTITUTE</h3>

<p>

<TABLE BORDER=5>

<TR>

<TD><img src="sym-mrk.gif"></TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>

<p>



<b>April 1996



<p>



<p>







<br>Forestry and Forest Products Research Institute (FFPRI)

<br>Forestry Agency

<br>Ministry of Agriculture

 Forestry and Fisheries

 Japan

<p>

<p>



</B>

</center>



<BLOCKQUOTE><b>

CONTENTS

<hr>

    <a href="#no.0">PREFACE</a>

<br><a href="#no.1">1. FOREST ENVIRONMENT IN JAPAN</a>

<br><a href="#no.2">2. FORESTRY AND FOREST PRODUCTS RESEARCH INSTITUTE(FFPRI)</a>

<br><a href="#no.3">3. STATUS OF RESEARCH ACTIVITIES AT FFPRI</a>

<br><a href="#no.4">4. FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PLAN OF FFPRI</a>

<br><a href="#no.5">5. RECENT PROJECT-TYPE DOMESTIC RESEARCHES</a>

<br><a href="#no.6">6. STATUS OF INTERNATIONAL RESEARCH COOPERATION</a>

<br><a href="#no.7">APPENDIX</a>

<hr>

</BLOCKQUOTE></b>

<dl>

<center><dd><A NAME="no.0"><h3>PREFACE</h3></center>



<dd>



	As people demand increasingly various services from forests

 forests are expected to



be the place for stroll

 recreational use

 learning of the nature

 and conservation of environment and bio-diversity for the future.



	The area of forests in Japan is about 25 million ha

 which is 68 % of the total land area.



About 40 percent of the forests

 about ten million ha

 consists of man-made forests

 and the



rest consists of natural forests. The man-made forests have been established mostly with



coniferous species after the World War II

 and 80 percent of them has become around 35



years old

 which need to be thinned. The proper management of these young forests including



thinning is one of the major tasks of present forestry in Japan.



<br>	The estimated wood stock of Japan is about 3.1 thousand million cubic meters

 and its



annual increment is about 7 hundred million cubic meters now. The demand for wood in



Japan is

 however

 around one hundred million cubic meters

 and does not increase recently



because of the substitute materials. Meanwhile

 70 % of the total wood consumption in



Japan comprizes imported wood

 and the portion of the processed wood products in the



imported wood is increasing. This trend is leading to a decline of wood industry. Also the



majority of the workers engaged in forest industry communities in Japan are aged

 and



Japanese forestry and forest industry have been declined. Under such circumstances





activating the forestry through solving these problems is an important task subjected to Forestry



Agency of Japan.



<br>	On the other hand

 changes of global environment as global warming

 forest decline by



acid deposition

 decrease of tropical forests

 desertification and so on have become a world-



wide issue recently

 which is connected directly or indirectly with the survival of mankind.



Thus

 the functions of forest and the roles of forestry in conserving global environment is



becoming international concern. Japan

 as the nation that has the duty to contribute to the



countries world-wide

 is expected to promote the international cooperation and foreign aid



toward the developing area of the world.



<br>	Two basic tasks are there in Japanese forestry

 sustainable forest management for



hamonizing functions of wood production and environmental conservation

 and activation



of forestry and forest industry to develop domestic wood utilization. And in research

 the



technical cooperation of global environment conservation may be added to the two. There



are seven major assignments of research and development for the Institute

 according to Agriculture

 Forestry and Fisheries Research Council.

<br>    The first viewpoint is to seek ways of reinforcing overall industrial structures of agriculture

 forestry and fisheries in the efforts of raising productivity

 improving products quality

 improving labor environment and establishing advanced technologies

 under the evolving situations in international communities in the years of post Urguay round agreement

 which is consistent with environmental conservation.

<br>    The second viewpoint is to seep ways of creating new industries

 which are beyond the frame of traditional agriculture

 forestry and fisheries by nature

 by means of promoting fundamental research in biotechnologies.

<br>    The third viewpoint is to seek ways of attaining efficient processing and distribution systems of products in agriculture

 forestry and fisheries by means of realizing a good supply of products which are free from damages of agricultural chemicals.

<br>    The fourth viewpoint is to seek ways of vitalizing rural communities

 improving living enviroment and enhancing multi-functions which are endowed in agricultural

 mountain and fishing villages under the evolving fear of extensive use of farmland

 extensive management of forest land and declining vital power of economic activities in rural communities.

<br>    The fifth viewpoint is to seek ways of promoting environmental conservation and  appropriate resource management which aims at achieving sustainable development of human society in harmony with global environment.

<br>    The sixth view point is to seek ways of contributing sustainable development of world agriculture

 forestry and fisheries.

<br>    The seventh viewpoint is to seek ways of promoting fundamental research which is the basis for attaining more efficient technological development in agriculture

 forestry and fisheries.





<br>

	To meet with the changing demands

 Forestry and Forest Products Research Institute was



reorganized in 1988. This booklet is introducing the state of our 



researches at Forestry and Forest Products Research Institute in brief.



<p><b>



March 1996



<p>



Itsuhito OHNUKI



<br>



Director General



<p>Forestry and Forest Products Research Institute



<br>Ministry of Agriculture

 Forestry and Fisheries</b>



