<blockquote>



<A NAME="no.1"><h3>1. FOREST ENVIRONMENT IN JAPAN</h3></A>



<p>



<h4>Climate</h4>



<p>	Since the zone fro



m 20 to 46 of north latitude

 wherein the main Japanese islands lie





has variable climatic conditions

 horizontal climates ranging from subtropical to boreal are



observable in Japan. Also

 since the islands lie from the northeast to the southwest along the



Asian continent's east coast

 northwest monsoon blows in from the continent in winter and



southeast monsoon blows in from the Pacific Ocean in summer. The winter monsoon is



blocked by high mountains and gives abundant snowfall in the regions facing the Sea of



Japan

 whereas dry and clear weather continues in the regions facing the Pacific Ocean.



Although fine weather dominates due to the Ogasawara high pressure in summer

 the Baiu



and Shurin fronts give much rainfall before and after summer season.



<br>	In addition

 many typhoons generated over the south Pacific strike Japan every year.



These climatic conditions bring much rain and snow to Japan making it one of the most rainy



and humid countries in the world.



<p>



<h4>Topography and Geology</h4>



<p>



	The Japanese islands

 lying adjacent to the Asian continent's east coast

 have been



receiving frequent crustal movements since the Paleozoic era and have had volcanic activity



since the Cenozoic era. Thus the topography is of a great variety. Mountainous

 volcanic





and hilly areas occupy about 75 % of the entire land area. Mountainous areas are dissected



finely by rivers of all sizes

 and mountain slopes generally are very steep. There are about



two-hundred volcanoes of large and small sizes

 with the most famous one being Mt. Fuji.



Several of them are still active. New and old ejecta from these volcanoes widely covers the



land. Although not large in scale

 some glacial sediments are observable at higher altitudes





and not a little residue from periglacial phenomenon exists. Terraces formed by transgression



and regression are scattered in low-altitude areas.



<br>	Because of the scarcity of plains suitable for farming

 Japan's forestry is concentrated



in mountainous regions with steep terrain.



<br>	The Japanese islands can be divided structurally into two parts

 northeast Japan and



southwest Japan

 by a fracture belt called the Fossa Magna that extends across the center of



Honshu Island from the north to the south. In northeastern Japan

 strata of the Cenozoic era



and volcanic rocks are distributed widely

 and only in a few areas are rocks of the Paleozoic



and Mesozoic eras found. On the other hand

 in southwestern Japan

 there are strata of the



Paleozoic and Mesozoic eras with very little of the Cenozoic era. Southwestern Japan is



divided further into two zones

 the inner (Japan Sea coast zone) and the outer (Pacific Ocean



side) by the Median Tectonic Line. In the outer Zone

 the Paleozoic and Mesozoic strata and



metamorphic rocks parallel the Median Tectonic Line. This is reflected in the mountain range.



Acidic rocks are distributed in the inner zone.



<p>



<h4>Forest Soils</h4>



<p>	Since the weather is variable

 and the geology and the topography is complicated

 a



variety of forest soils are found in Japan. The most widespread forest soil in Japan is Brown



forest soil covering about one half of the entire forest land. Other important forest soils of



Japan are Black soils

 Podozolic soils in the cooler areas

 and the Red and Yellow soil



occurring in central Honshu

 Kyushu

 and the southwestern islands. Gley soils

 Peaty soils





Dark red soils and Immature soils are also found in relatively small areas.



<br>	Brown forest soils are the most common soils which are distributed in the temperate



to warm-temperate zones of Japan

 but their properties vary widely depending upon region





altitude

 and parent material. Usually

 Brown forest soils have the horizon sequence of (Ao)-



A-B-C

  and no eluvi-illuviation. The Brown forest soils are characterized by brown colored



B horizons and slightly to moderately strong acidities. The Brown forest soils are divided



further into sub-types based on soil moisture condition in the Japanese Forest Soil Classification

 which was developed as a basis for the reforestation by "Right Site

 Right Species". Out



of the sub-types

 Moderately moist Brown forest soils being distributed most widely

 have



been demonstrated to be suitable for reforestation with Sugi (<i>Cryptomeria japonica</i>) and



hinoki (<i>Chamaecyparis obtusa</i>). 



<br>	Black soils

 which have been called "Kuroboku" traditionally

 have thick black colored



A horizons rich in humus. Most of the Black soils are derived from volcanic ash

 and



distributed widely on gentle slopes of volcano skirts in the Hokkaido

 Tohoku

 Kanto and



Kyushu districts

 but they are scarce in Kinki

 Chugoku

 and Shikoku.



<br>	Podozolic soils occur from upper temperate to alpine zones. The soils are divided into



the Dry and Wet types. Establishment of man-made forest in the Dry podozolic soil area is



comparatively difficult because of their strong acidity and poor nutrient status. In the Wet



Podozolic soil areas

 natural old-growth forests of Hinoki do exist

 and when the forests are



cut

 regeneration becomes extremely difficult.



<br>	Red and Yellow soils occur principally in the tropical and sub-tropical zones

 but some



of them are found in the warm-temperate zones of Japan. The Red and Yellow soils of



temperate Japan were not formed under the current climate

 but they are the so-called "relic



soils"

 which were originally formed under the warmer climate of the Pleistocene interglacial



epoch

 and remained in the area of relatively stable topography. However

 the Yellow soils



found commonly in the Ryukyu Islands were suggested to have been formed in a recent



epoch. These Red and Yellow soils are generally infertile irrespective of the genesis

 and



support Akamatsu (<i>Pinus densiflora</i>) forests in many cases in the mainland Japan.



<p>



<h4>General Fearture of Natural and Manmade Forests</h4>



<p>	Japanese archiperago lies between 20 and 46 of north latitude and shows a very wide range of climatic conditions

 especially in temperature and snow fall. Though annual precipitation ranges from about 800 mm to more than 3,000 mm

 it is high enough to sustain forests. The following four principal vegetation zones are recognized. 



<br>    Sub-alpine evergreen conifer (boreal) forest:Conifer forests consisting of <i>Abies veitchii</i>

 <i>Tsuga diversifolia</i>

 <i>Picea jezoensis var. hondoensis</i> are found at high elevations of middle to northern Honshu. <i>Abies sachalinensis</i> and <i>Picea jezoensis</i> are dominant in Hokkaido. A decidious conifers

 <i>Larix kaempferi</i> and <i>Abies sachalinensis</i> are the main species of the plantation forest.



<br>    Cool-temperate braod-leaved deciduous (summer-green) forest:</i>Fagus crenata</i> and <i>Querucus cripsula</i> from the main portion of the natural forests in the northeast Honshu. <i>Fagus crenata</i> is diminant especially in the snowy region of the Japan Sea side. Such conifers as <i>Tsuga sieboldii</i>

 <i>Abies firma</i> and <i>A. homolepis</i> are rather dominant in the Pacific side. <i>Cryptomeria japonica</i>

 that grows originally as an edaphic climax of this zone

 is widely planted.



<br>    Warm-Temperate and Sub-tropical broad-leaved evergreen (laurel) fbrorest:The laurel forests

 consisting <i>Presea thumbergii

 Castanopsis cuspidata

 Querucus acuta</i> and other evergreen broad-leaved trees

 are the principal vegetation of Kyushu

 Shikoku and southwestern Honshu. 



<br>    The plantaion forests of <i>Cryptomeria japonica</i> and <i>Chamaecyparis obtusa</i>

 and secondary forest of <i>Pinus densiflora</i> cover more than one half of forested area.



<p>



