<h3><A NAME="no.2">2. FORESTRY AND FOREST PRODUCTS RESEARCH INSTITUTE(FFPRI)</h3>



<p>



<h4>2.1. History </h4>



<p>

	FFPRI was established in 1905 as the Government Forest Experiment Station in the Ministry of Agriculture and Commerce.  In accordance with the unification of forestry organization in 1947

 the institute has developed both in scale and research scope as the only integrated forestry research institute in Japan. The headquarters unit was transferred from Meguro

 Tokyo

 to Tsukuba

 Ibaraki in 1978 and the building with facilities were entirely renewed. In 1988

 research systems have been reorganized for an improved response to nationwide demands for the use of forest resources. 



<p>



<h4>2.2. Organization</h4>



<p>

	The Institute is comprised of nine divisions in the headquaters

 five regional Research Centers

 and one Forest Science Garden as shown in the following figure. Research Coordination Div.

 General Affair Div.

 Forest Environment Div.

 Forest Biology Div.

 Bio-resources Technology Div.

 Forestry Technology Div.

 Wood Chemistry Div.

 Wood technology Div. and Forest Management Div.

 in the headquarters

 Research Centers in Hokkaido

 Tohoku

 Kansai

 Shikoku and Kyusyu

 and Tama Forest Science Garden in Tokyo. 

<P>

<img src="fig-10.GIF"><P>

<img src="fig-11.GIF">

<P>

<h4>2.3. Research Divisions</h4>



<p>



<h4>2.3.1. Forest Environment Division</h4>



<p>



	Forest has multiple functions for conserving natural environment as well as producing timber. In the Forest Environment Division

 environmental researches are conducted on the subjects to enhance the functions of forest ecosystems and to develop forest conservation technology. One of the main subjects is to elucidate the characteristics of site environments and forest communities in forest ecosystems and the interactions between them

 and to evaluate roles of forest ecosystems on environmental functions. Another subject is to evaluate the functions of soil and water conservation and of climate amelioration through elucidating the mechanism of mass movement and hydrology.

<P>

<img src="fig-12.GIF">

<P>

<h4>2.3.2. Forest Biology Division</h4>



<p>



	In a forest ecosystem

 many organisms such as mammals

 birds

 insects

 nematodes and microorganisms co-exist and exhibit their own biological functions. Research activities of the division cover a wide range of both basic and applied topics on these organisms.

<br>	Taxonomical,

 ecological and physiological studies are conducted comprehensively on these organisms to analyze their roles in the ecosystem and their natural relationships.

<br>	Pest management and wildlife management are studied to conserve forest resources and characteristics of certain organisms are also studied for the further use of forest resources.



<P>

<img src="fig-13.GIF">

<P>

<h4>2.3.3. Bio-resources Technology Division</h4>



<p>



	The characteristics of forest trees populations are studied from the viewpoint of genetics to conserve and use forest genetic resources. New ways of utilizing the forest resources are pursued through the latest techniques and knowledge of biology

 microbiology

 biochemistry

 etc. Studies of gene manipulation

 cell fusion

 cell or tissue culture of forest trees and mushrooms are performed. Biologically active substances

 and metabolites produced by forest animals

 plants and microorganisms are studied in terms of their properties.



<p>

<img src="fig-14.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.3.4 Forest Technology Division</h4>



<p>

	Increasing forest harvest and improving the living standards of rural forestry people is the unending task of forestry research. Silvicultural techniques are developed by studies of regeneration

 natural-forest treatment

 and establishment of multi-storied stand. Experiments are made to develop machines which enable work in steep topography more efficient in harvesting

 transportation and silvicultural operations. Technologies are investigated to construct forest road with minimum disturbance

 and to develop working system to make the labor productivity higher with regard to safety.

<p>

<img src="fig-15.GIF">

<p>



<h4>2.3.5 Wood Chemistry Division</h4>



<p>

	The Division

 covering from basic studies to applications

  has three main goals; 1) to develop technologies for conversion of wood components such as cellulose

 hemicellulose and extractives to useful materials; functional films

 biodegradable plastics

 adhesives

 fine chemicals etc.

 2) to develop technologies for improvement of disadvantageous properties such as biodegrability

 flammability

dimention-instability

 degradability by UV light

 and 3) to develop new wood-based composites with organic and inorganic materials.



<p>

<img src="fig-16.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.3.6. Wood Technology Division</h4>



<p>



	Research has been conducted to find the most effective use of timber and to make good use of various properties of timber particularly in the fields of wood anatomy

 wood quality and wood physics. The comprehensive research

 from basic studies to applications

 has also been conducted for developing improved and more sophisticated methods of sawmilling

 kiln drying

 machining

 and manufacturing glue laminated timber. Furthermore

 research has been carried out into the studies of the timber strength

 joint

 structural performance of timber construction

 and evaluation of wooden dwelling environment for human comfort.



<p>

<img src="fig-17.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.3.7. Forest Management Division</h4>



<p>



	To meet with the public needs for well coordinated use of both forest environment and timber

 integrated research is required in resources planning and managerial economics. Basic studies to develop multi-resource inventory

 planning and assessment system are performed with special regard to environmental consideration. Based on an economic analysis of Japanese forestry and forest products industries at both countrywide and regional levels

 measures to improve timber management and to increase timber supply are being investigated.



<p>

<img src="fig-18.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4. Regional Forest Research Centers</h4>



<p>



	Since Japanese archipelago stretches long from the north to the south

 and is different in climate

 vegetation

 topography

 soil

 land-use history and socio-economic status from region to region

 forestry issues also vary from place to place. Five Forest Research Centers have responsibilities of carrying out researches to tackle on the regional forestry issues

 respectively. The main research assignments to be performed by the respective research centers; sutsainable management of cool-temperate and boreal forests in Hokkaido

 management of snowy area forests and beech forests in Tohoku

 management of sub-alpine and urban forests in Kanto-Chubu

 landscape-ecological and architectural forest management and forests on poor soils in Kansai-Chugoku

 management of man-made forests on steep topography in Shikoku

 and management of warm-temperate forests in Kyushu. Furthermore

 the Centers contribute and often lead national-level research programs.



<p>

<img src="fig-19.GIF">



<h4>2.4.1. Hokkaido Research Center</h4>



<p>



	In Hokkaido

 there are three main of forest cool-temperate broadleaved

 boreal coniferous and mixed forests

 consisting of the same tree species of the former two types. These forest types and their species composition are different from those of the other areas of Japan. Toward sustainable management of these forests

 the Hokkaido Research Center is conducting various surveys and studies. They investigate the characteristics and functions of these forests

 improve quality and quantity of the foersts based on the results obtained from other studies

 improve forest protection and management systems for sustainable yield

 and meet the demand of global environmental problems.



<p>

<img src="fig-20.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4.2. Tohoku Research Center</h4>



<p>



	The Tohoku district is in the northern part of Honshu (Mainland) and consists of six prefectures. The total area is 6,689,000ha and the forest land is 4,704,000ha. The forest land belongs to the private(48 %)

 the local government(8 %) and the national government(44 %).  There are high mountains running from the north to the south in the central portion. These mountains separate the climatical condition into 2 types. One is the Japan Sea type with much snow and rainfall and the other is the Pacific Ocean type with less snow and rainfall.

<br>	Tohoku Research Center does research on silviculture

 forest management

 forest protection and forest influences under snowy and cold condition through 3 research divisions (10 laboratories)

 1 research coordination office and 1 general affairs sections.



<p>

<img src="fig-21.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4.3. Kansai Research Center</h4>



<p>



	As Kansai Area had been  most advanced in forest resource development in the nation

 the area is mostly covered by secondary vegetation and plantations. One of the main subjects is to elucidate the mechanism and establish conservation techniques of such forest functions as timber production

 soil and water conservation

 amenity in ralation to forest dynamics. Another subject is to develop various techniques of forestry and pest controls in order to establish sustainable timber management systems. The third subject is to develop a methodology to integrate these outcomes in order to establish a regional system to utilize multiple forest resources.



<p>

<img src="fig-22.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4.4. Shikoku Research Center</h4>



<p>



	The Forest on Shikoku island covers 74 % of the island.  Most of it is man-made forest.  People have attached greater importance to forestry as one of the basic industries.  Development of healthy forests is highly expected as an object of forest management. In climate setting

 Shikoku island shows a contrast in precipitation between the inland sea side (slight rain) and  the other Pacific Ocean side (heavy rain).  Fragile geological structure and recent water shortage heighten the interest and expectation to the conservational function of forests.  We are working cooperatively on the subject for developing advanced technology for better forest management.



<p>

<img src="fig-23.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4.5. Kyushu Research Center</h4>



<p>



	Kyushu is covered with warm temperate and subtropical forests including two major types: evergreen broad-leaved forests and coniferous plantations of Sugi

 (<i>Cryptomeria japonica</i>)

 and Hinoki

 (<i>Chamaecyparis obtusa</i>).

<br>	Research is aimed at developing sustainable forest management systems

 which are based on environmental

 ecological and socio-economical characteristics of the region. Longterm study sites have been established to monitor the dynamics of forest ecosystems. Studies on interactions among forest organisms are applied to both conservation of biological diversity and pest management. Molecular biological technologies are developed to analyze phylogenetic relationships and identify species. Various kinds of information are integrated using advanced computer technologies including GIS.







<p>

<img src="fig-24.GIF">

<p>

<h4>2.4.6. Tama Forest Science Garden</h4>



<p>



	Tama Forest Science Garden was established in 1921 as Forest Experiment Station of the Imperial Forestry Office. The Garden has two aims; one is to conduct researches on urban forest ecosystems

 the other is to function as an information center of FFPRI. The researches are carried out by two laboratories to develop technologies to conserve urban forests. As an information center

 the Garden provides the public with various information through its Forest Science Hall

 Arboretum and Cherry tree conservation forest.







<p>

<img src="fig-25.GIF">

<p>

<hr>



<p>



<A NAME="no.3"><h3>3. STATUS OF RESEARCH ACTIVITIES AT FFPRI</h3>



<p>



<h4>3.1. Research program</h4>



<p>



	Long term research subjects of FFPRI are listed in the "Fundamental Research Plan of FFPRI"

 where ten-year henceforth fundamental research plans are framed (page 31-44).  The followings are the priority research areas of the FFPRI

 which are mentioned in the "Fundamental Research Plan of FFPRI". The order of the six research areas does not connote the order of priority.



<p>



(1) Elucidation of properties of forest ecosystem and promotion of environmental function of forest.

<p>

(2) Increase of forest production and improvement of forest productivity.

<p>

(3) Improvement of timber utilization technology and development of new usage of wood resources.

<p>

(4) Innovation of technology by development and utilization of forest biological function.

<p>

(5) Development of regional forestry and diversified techniques of forest utilization.

<p>

(6) Promotion of international research and contribution to global environment



<p>



	Project research has a special budget for intensive research work in this framework

 and some research projects are now in progress through joint research with other organizations. 



<p>



<h4>3.2. Human and financial resources</h4>



<p>



	Major part of forestry research in Japan is conducted at FFPRI

 prefectural forestry



research institutes and universities. Research activities at private sector have been relatively



slow. As to the burden share of research

 universities (forestry-related faculty) is for



fundamental researches

 FFPRI for application and development researches

 and prefectural



forestry research institutes for researches for local needs in general. However

 there is no



clear-cut share of the burden among them. Also

 FFPRI accepts about 90 trainees annually



from other domestic organizations mainly of prefectural research institutions.



<br>	FFPRI has 712 staff which consists of 474 research officials and 238 administrative



staff  as of 1995 fiscal year. Three hundred and one research officials out of 474 and 132



administrative officials out of 238 are stationed in the headquarter unit and the rest in the



five Regional Forest Research Centers

 Tama Forest Science Garden and seven Experiment



Stations.



<br>	Annual budget of FFPRI is 8,391 million yen for 1995 fiscal year including the research



budget transferred from the Science and Technology Agency

 the Environment Agency and so



on. 



<p>



<h4>3.3. Facilities</h4>



<p> 



	Total land area of the FFPRI headquarter is 325,111.45 m<sup>2</sup>

 and 96 buildings are located



there. Total floor area is 61,582.38m<sup>2</sup>. The major facilities of the headquarters are as follows;



<p>



(1) Main Building (31,870 m<sup>2</sup>)



 Administration and research lab. complex



<p>



(2) Chemical Processing Building (1,835 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1) Building for plant-scale manufacture of engineered-wood products and chemically-



modified woods



<br>2)  Large-sized jar fermentor and extractor for wood extractives are also set up	



</blockquote>



<p>(3) Gluing Test Building (1,013 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1) Improving of manufacturing process of engineered woods such as laminated wood





parallel strand lumber (PSL)

 laminated veneer lumber (LVL) etc



<br>2) Peeling and drying of softwood veneer



</blockquote>



<p>(4) Drying and Preservation Building (1,202 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1) Conventional kiln drying of lumber



<br>2) Special drying (high temperature drying

 vacuum drying with high frequency electric



heating) of large dimensional construction lumber



<br>3) Preservative treatment by use of large sized preservative vacuum-pressure impregnation machine



</blockquote>



<p>(5) Wood Material Testing Building (951 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1) Examination of log quality



<br>2)  Physical properties (acoustic

 hygroscopic) of wood



<br>3)  Mechanical properties of wood using small clear test pieces



</blockquote>



<p>(6) Structural Member Testing Building (691 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1)  Non-destructive test of lumber strength



<br>2)  Engineering properties of full size lumber



<br>3)  Joint performance of wood structures



<br>4)  Seismic behavior of wood structures



</blockquote>



<p>(7) Machine Processing Building (1,624 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1)  Sawing performance of band saws



<br>2)  Knife cutting & finger jointing of lumber



<br>3)  Cutting performance of NC router machine



<br>4)  Properties of test pieces (woodworking shop)



</blockquote>



<p>(8) Sawmill Building (456 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1)  Sawing of test pieces supplied for various experiment



<br>2)  Improvement of sawing pattern of small and medium size logs



<br>3)  Saw doctoring



</blockquote>



(9) Autoclave Facility Building (109 m<sup>2</sup>)



<blockquote>



1) (Specially-designed) Explosion-proof construction building for dangerous experiment



using high pressure and temperature gases such as hydrogen

 oxygen

 steam

 etc.



</blockquote>



