<p>

<h4>3.4. Library</h4>

                     

<p>



	The library has 1,035 m<sup>2</sup> of floor area

 and a collection of more than 192 thousand



volumes of publications

 including about 63 thousand volumes written in foreign languages. 



Nearly 1,500 kinds of periodical publications on forestry and forest products



from all over the world are subscribed. 



<br>	The library is also exchanging Kpublications on forestry and forest products with many



other research organizations

 and functioning as a core information center of forest and



forestry science in Japan.



	Literature information services are available by the information system of FORIS.



<p>



<h4>3.5. Major research achievements for past five years</h4>



<h4><i>1994</h4></i>



1) Water storage and drainage properties of forest soil at the different positions on a slope                                                               <br>2) Japanese squirrel (<i>Scuirus lis</i>) as seed dispersers of walnuts (<i>Juglans mandshurica</i>).



<br>3) Soil disturbance on bared site caused by mechanized operation



<br>4) Monitoring of birch forest catastrophe in the northern boreal zone



<br>5) Development of the support system for regional resources management and timber



supply forecast using GIS



<br>6) Fire Endurance of Solid Wood (Lumber)



<br>7) Morphological changes of wood fibers during their elongation



<br>8) Economical and speedy drying of Sugi column by high-frequency heat and vacuum



<br>9) Comparison of stemflow chemistry among tree species and its effect on soil acidification



<br>10) Effect of thinning in Todo-fir plantations



<br>11) A study on planning of forested watershed management based on a landscape



concept



<br>12) Population dynamics of the beech caterpillar

 (<i>Quadricalcarifera punctatella</i>),          



      

 and environmental factors



<br>13) Breeding bird communities and effect of forest management in the beech forests of



Tohoku district



<br>14) Study of the status of black woodpecker in Tohoku district



<br>15) Growth of Hiba experimental stands in relation to selective cutting methods



<br>16) Blossom's morphological features in different cherry species



<br>17) Ecological management of insect pests of bamboo



<br>18) Invasion of forest stand by bamboo



<br>19) Ovulation mode of the Anderson's red-backed vole from the Kii Peninsula



<br>20) Relationship of pine wilt disease development to water relations in pine



<br>21) The actual condition of wood discoloration of Sugi (<i>Cryptomeria japonica</i>) caused by



Guignadia dieback (<i>Guignadia cryptomeriae</i>)



<br>22) Development of a system yield table for Sugi (<i>Cryptomeria japonica</i>) plantation in



Kyushu region



<br>23) A succession process of the degenerated (Kalimantan) forest



<br>24) Water conditions control the desert vegetation



