<p>



<h4>3.6. Interaction with users of research results</h4>



<p>



	The research subjects of FFPRI are composed of ordinary researches and project



researches. New research projects are set up in responding to the research needs proposed



by Agriculture

 Forestry and Fisheries Research Council

 Forestry Agency (Ministry of



Agriculture

 Forestry and Fisheries)

 local conferences organized mainly with prefecture and



private sector. 



<br>	The research results are notified by means of bulletins

 journals

 newsletter

 etc. Results



are also published at the conference or meeting to the organization above-mentioned. The



applicable technology developed through the reseaches are communicated to forest owners



through prefectural extension system. 



<p>



<hr>



<p>



<center><A NAME="no.4"><h3>4. THE FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH PLAN OF FFPRI</h3></center>



<p>



<h4>4.1. Properties of site environment and forest communities</h4> 



<p>



	Forest ecosystem has various functions and demands of people enhancing and



utilizing them have been increasing. To establish sustainable forest management

 in which



various functions of forest ecosystem are harmonized

 obtaining fundamental knowledge on



the forest ecosystem is essential. In the research subject on site environment

 studies are



undertaken on genesis and properties of forest soils

 water dynamics and thermo-flux in



forest soils

 and geomorphological and geological properties of subsoils on hill slopes

 etc. 



for evaluating soil and water resources. The human impacts such as acid deposition and



undesirable forest management on site environment is also analyzed

 and methods for



forecasting the change of site environment  is developed. In the studies on forest communities

 properties of species in the communities are analyzed in terms of the adaptation to the



environment

 breeding properties

 and life history. Then distribution properties of the



composed species

 the relationship between stand structure and natural disturbance





nutrient dynamics

 etc. are analyzed. Effects of climate change on growing processes of trees



is analyzed and it is forecasted how trees are adapted to the change.



<p>



<h4><i>4.1.1. Elucidating and evaluating forest site characteristics</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Genetic factors and properties of forest soils.



<br>(2) Biogeochemical transformation in forest soils.



<br>(3) Soil physical properties and water-thermo dynamics.



<br>(4) Subsurface geology and mineralogy  of the forest land.



<br>(5) Analysis of forest site information

 and technology development of soil resource



evaluation.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.1.2. Elucidating structure and function of forest communities</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Growing process of trees and their adaptability to environment.



<br>(2) Reproductive properties and life histories of trees.



<br>(3) Structures and successional mechanisms of forest communities.



<br>(4) Nutrient dynamics in forest communities.



<br>(5) Effects of environmental changes on forest communities.



</blockquote>



<h4>4.2. Technology development of forest treatment for soil and water conservation and disaster prevention</h4>



<p>



	As forest ecosystem has the functions to create preferable environment such as supply



of high quality water

 mitigation of meteorology

 and prevention of meteorological disasters





the expectation to the development of the technology for the forest management for



environmental conservation has been much more increasing.  On the other hand

 as hazardous areas for slope failure and avalanches are increasing as a result of inadequate forest



management and exploitation

 and large scale debris flows

 landslides

 and pyroclastic



flows are frequently occurring by earthquake

 eruption

 and severe rainfall

the development



of technology to reduce and prevent the damages have been much more required.Therefore





erosion control technology and watershed management method by which function of water



and soil conservation is enhanced is exploited by promoting the studies on the mechanisms



of water cycle and sediment production.  At the same time

 as basic studies

the function of



forests to effect on climate and the effect of meteorology on forests are promoted

 and



technology to prevent meteorological disasters and the technology to enhance the function of



forests to prevent disasters in accordance with the topography and climatical conditions of



the objective areas are exploited.



<p>



<h4><i>4.2.1. Elucidation of soil and water conservation functions of forests and improvement of erosion



control technology</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Hydrological process of forests and its analyses in headwater drainage areas.



<br>(2) Water conservation and management technology in mountainous areas.



<br>(3) Prediction of landslide

 erosion

 and debris flow

 and establishment of disaster



prevention technology.



<br>(4) Landslide hazard estimation and improvement of landslide prevention technology.



<br>(5) Development of soil and water conservation technology.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.2.2. Elucidation of environment conservation function of forest and improvement of forest disaster



prevention technology</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Forest influence on climate.



<br>(2) Improvement of forecast methods for meteorological damages on forests and



prevention technology for them.



<br>(3) Development of management technology for environment conservation function of



forests on heavy snowcover areas.



<br>(4) Elucidation of environment conservation forest function and development of



management technology for it.



<br>(5) Evaluation of forest function for prevention of sediment disaster.   



</blockquote>



<h4>4.3. Researches on biological characteristics and functions of organisms in



forest ecosystem and development of advanced management techniques</h4>



	



	It has been recognized that the forest ecosystems play an important role not only as



timber production but also as natural resources for gene bank

 culture

 and education. Thus





conservation of forest ecosystem is a contemporary theme. It is necessary

 therefore

 to



establish management plan based upon researches on the effects of environmental changes



and human impacts on forest animals

 and on the present status of endangered wildlife. 



Control techniques for pest animals

 on the other hand

 is needed based upon elucidating



factors responsible for damage. Establishing a system of management techniques is required



through researches on classification

 physiology

 and ecology of forest organisms.



<p>



<h4><i>4.3.1. Researches on biological characteristics and functions of forest microorganism and development



of their control techniques</i></h4>

<blockquote>



(1) Classification and identification of forest microorganisms and analysis of genetic



characters.



<br>(2) Researches on physiological and ecological characteristics of forest microorganisms.



<br>(3) Researches on physiological and ecological characteristics of forest nematodes.



<br>(4) Researches on mechanism of disease occurrence in forests and development of



control techniques for the disease.



<br>(5) Development of advanced techniques for utilization of forest microorganisms.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.3.2. Researches on biological characteristics and functions of animals in forest ecosystem</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Researches on ecology of insects and small animals and their classification.



<br>(2) Researches on physiological characteristics of insects and small animals.



<br>(3) Classification of microorganisms pathogenic to insects and researches on their



ecology and functions.



<br>(4) Researches on community structure of insects and small animals in forest ecosystem.



<br>(5) Researches on ecology and interactions of wildlife in forest ecosystem.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.3.3. Development of advanced management techniques for forest animals</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Development of advanced management techniques for forest insects.



<br>(2) Development of advanced management techniques for wildlife.



<br>(3) Development of control techniques for forest pest insects by using natural enemy.



<br>(4) Development of pest control techniques based on chemical ecology.



<br>(5) Development of evaluation methods for forest damage by pests.



</blockquote>



<h4>4.4. Development of silvicultural techniques

 and establishment of mechanized forest operation systems</h4>







	For proper forest management with enhancement of forest functions

 it is necessary to



develop and systematize sound silvicultural techniques combined with mechanized forest



operation systems.For this purpose

 ecological processes of forests should be elucidated on



various silvicultural systems

 such as long-rotation plantation

 multi-storied plantation and



natural forests. Silvicultural options for both plantation forestry and natural forest management are to be developed for increasing productivity and wood quality

 and for maintaining



biodiversity and other various functions of the forest.



<br>	In addition

 to establish a higher operational efficiency and low-cost operation systems



of various forest operations from afforestation to harvesting by mechanization

 the researches are conducted on the development and improvement of the forestry machines

 which has



higher performance and new functions. Also the researches are conducted on the improvement of the operational efficiency

 assuring labor safety

 the reduction of work intensity

 and



the development of reasonable operating systems and the environmentally sound mechanized forestry technology etc.  Moreover

 the methods for proper arrangement  and simple



construction of forest road network

 which is the foundation of forest management are



developed.



<p>



<h4><i>4.4.1. Improvement of regeneration and silvicultural techniques by elucidation of production



mechanism of forest</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1)Improvement of tending techniques by elucidating the plant production dynamics of



forest.



<br>(2)Improvement of vegetation control and regeneration techniques on the basis of



ecological process of forest regeneration.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.4.2. Development of mechanized forest operating system and enhancement of forest road planning



system and forest road construction techniques</i></h4>



 <blockquote>







(1)Improvement of forest operating techniques and development of operating system.



<br>(2)Improvement of operating techniques for reduction of work intensity and enhancing



labor safety.



<br>(3)Development of forest road planning system and enhancement of forest road



construction techniques.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.4.3. Development and improvement of forest machinery</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1)Development and improvement of silvicultural machinery.



<br>(2)Development and improvement of logging machinery.



<br>(3)Development of automatic control technologies for forest machinery.



</blockquote>



<h4>4.5. Development of integrated forest use planning and sustainable forest



management systems</h4>







	To meet with the diverse public needs for multiple-use of forest resources

 integrated



forest planning system is required. It is necessary to develop advanced information systems



as well as monitoring techniques to assess environmental changes using GIS and remote



sensing. Development of techniques to predict forest growth and to assess multiple functions



of the forest are also needed to establish integrated forest planning systems.



<br>	To vitalize domestic forestry and utilize forest resources efficiently

 it is required to



develop appropriate forest management systems based on river basin as a unit. Systems for



sustainable management should be established based on researches on demand-and-supply



and trade of wood

 development of advanced planning systems for forest management

 and



assessment of policies for organizing and promoting forest management practices by forest



owners.



<p>



<h4><i>4.5.1. Development of resources management techniques with special reference to multiple function of



forest</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1)Development of techniques for observation and monitoring of forest resources using



remote sensing technology.



<br>(2)Development of techniques for forest resources inventory

 modelling and planning.



<br>(3)Development of techniques for establishing multiple-use-forest planning.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.5.2. Development of management systems for sustainable forestry</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1)Development of advanced planning systems for forest management practices.



<br>(2)Development of forest management bodies to organize and promote forestry



productions.



<br>(3)Economic analysis on demand-and-supply and trade sturucture in forest products.



</blockquote>



<h4>4.6. Development of advanced technology for conversion of wood resources



into highly useful materials</h4>







	It is required to develop new uses of domestic softwoods

 supply of which is expected



to increase drastically in the near future

 and of other wood materials such as sawmill waste





thinning wood

 etc.

 which are underutilized at present. We conduct researches covering a



wide area from basic studies on reaction characteristics of wood components to applied



researches on development of new wood materials and the evaluation of their performance.



<p>



<h4><i>4.6.1. Development of technologies for utilization of wood components</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1)Separation and characterization of main wood components.



<br>(2)Utilization of lignin and other polyphenols from wood and bark.



<br>(3)Microorganism and enzyme applications for utilization of wood components.



<br>(4)Characterization and utilization of wood extractives.



</blockquote>



<h4><i>4.6.2. Development of technologies for Chemical processing of wood</i></h4>



<blockquote>



(1) Chemical modification technologies for high performance wood materials.



<br>(2) Functional materials from woods and their components.



<br>(3)Development and characterization of high performance wood adhesives.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.6.3. Development of  technologies for improvement in wood qualities</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Biodegradation and preservation technologies of woods.



<br>(2) Fire-retardant and fire-resistive technologies of wood-based materials.



<br>(3) Advanced technologies for weatherability of wood.



<br>(4) Production and evaluation of high performance wood-based composites.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.7. Development of wood technology</h4>







	Research is conducted to find the most effective use of timber and to make good use of



timber characteristics particularly in the fields of wood anatomy

 wood quality and wood



physics.  The comprehensive research

 from basic studies to application technology

 is also



promoted for developing improved and more sophisticated process in sawmilling

 kiln



drying

 machining and manufacturing glue laminated timber.  Further research is carried out



into the studies of engineering properties of timber and wood based materials

 joining



technology of construction members

 structural performance of timber construction

 and



evaluation of wooden dwelling environment for human comfort.



<p>







<h4><i>4.7.1. Elucidation of fundamental characteristics of wood</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Wood anatomy and identification.



<br>(2) Cellular composition and cell wall structure.



<br>(3) Effects of factors controlling wood properties.



<br>(4) Evaluation of wood quality as raw materials.



<br>(5) Thermal and hygroscopic properties of wood.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.7.2. Improvement and development of wood processing technology</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Establishment of high efficiency machining processes.



<br>(2) Development of production management and technology in sawmilling.



<br>(3) Development and evaluation of high efficiency drying methods.



<br>(4) Development of wood laminating technology.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.7.3. Evaluation of engineering properties and development of utilization technology of wood and



wood-based materials</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1)Evaluation of timber and wood-based materials as structural members.



<br>(2)Innovation of engineered timber joints.



<br>(3)Evaluation of structural performance of timber construction.



<br>(4)Evaluation of dwelling environment of wood buildings.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.8. Research and development of advanced utilization of biological functions and genetic resources on forest plants and microorganisms</h4>







	An advanced technology for innovative and efficient uses of biological potentials of



forest plants and microorganisms is developed through researches on their biological



functions and genetic characteristics. This technology should bring about development of a



new bio-industry and contribute to conservation of global environments and forest genetic



resources. Under the above aims

 the following research and development are carrying on;



evolution

 characterization and conservation of genetic resources of forest trees and



mushrooms

 molecular and cell biology and biotechnology of forest trees

 biochemistry of



woody cell wall

 utilization of ecochemicals produced by forest plants

 and advanced



utilization and biotechnology of mushrooms and wood decaying fungi.



<p>



<h4><i>4.8.1. Research and development of evaluation

 conservation and utilization on forest genetic



resources</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Mode of inheritance in various traits and linkage analysis of forest plants.



<br>(2) Genetic diversity and its maintenance mechanism in tree populations.



<br>(3) Genetic differentiation and selection regime of plant populations in forest ecosystem.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.8.2. Research and development of molecular and cell biology and biotechnology of forest trees</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Molecular mechanism of tree physiology.



<br>(2) Regulation of gene expression on tree growth and development.



<br>(3) Research and development of cell manipulation technology.



<br>(4) Research and development of tissue culture technology.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.8.3. Biochemical approaches for research and utilization of biological function of forest plants and



microbes</i></h4>



<blockquote>



 



(1) Biochemically active functions of ecochemicals produced by forest plants.



<br>(2) Mechanisms of elongation and differentiation of woody plant cell wall.



<br>(3) Mechanisms and its utilization of biodegradation of wood components.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.8.4. Research and efficient utilization of biological functions and genetic resources of mushroom</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Taxonomy

 ecology

 physiology

 and pathology of mushrooms and development of



their advanced utilization techniques.



<br>(2) Characterization of genetic resources and development of new breeding techniques



of mushrooms.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.9. Establishing techniques for managing cool-temperate and boreal forests



by the effective use of their own natural processes and patterns</h4>







	In Hokkaido

 there are three main forest types of cool-temperate broadleaved

 boreal



coniferous and mixed forests. The last type consists of the same tree species of the former



two types.  These forest types and species composition are different from those of the other



areas of Japan.



<br>	Selective cutting and natural regeneration are practiced principally in natural forests of



Hokkaido. On the other hand

 artificial forests have actively been established since the latter



half of 1950's.  At present

 the area of artificial forests is approximately 1.5 million hectares. 



Thinning is being practiced in their young-and middle-aged stands.  However

 there occur



various problems in the thinning practice.  In addition

 other problems are appearing in the



establishment processes of the even-aged pure stands.  Developments of techniques to



overcome these problems are insufficient because of our little experience in artificial forest



management. This situation renews understanding of the management based on the natural



processes and patterns

 and demands improvement and development of techniques



concerned.



<br>	To solve these problems and to contribute to sustainable management of cooltemperate and boreal forests

 the Hokkaido Research Center will carry out the following



studies.  The Center will clarify characteristics of the forests from various aspects such as



species characteristics

 biodiversity

 forest dynamics

 and so on

 and aim at improvement



and development of management techniques of natural forests based on the obtained results



from the former clarification.



<br>	The Center will also improve and develop new techniques of artificial forest management along natural processes and patterns.  Besides

 the Center will make efforts to improve



and to develop techniques for the avoidance of damages caused by various organisms both



in natural and artificial forests.  To improve life-quality of residents in the community and to



meet their diverse demands on forests

 the Center will clarify functions of forests for



environmental conservation

 and improve and develop techniques to keep and to increase



these functions.  By integrating the above-mentioned studies

 the Center will improve and



develop the methods of forest planning

 forest management and effective utilization of



forests in northern areas.



<p>



<h4><i>4.9.1. Analyses of biodiversity and dynamics

 and improvement of regeneration and tending



techniques of cool-temperate and boreal forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>



  



(1) Genetic diversity

 genetic variation and breeding system of tree species in cool-



temperate and boreal forests.



<br>(2) Physiological characteristics of cool temperate and boreal tree species with



emphasis on their responses to environmental stress.



<br>(3) Studies of growing process and dynamics of natural cool-temperate and boreal



forests.



<br>(4) Site characteristics of northern forest ecosystems.



<br>(5) Improvement of regeneration and tending techniques of cool-temperate and boreal



forests.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.9.2. Improvement of forest management and techniques on environment conservation for cooltemperate and boreal forest</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Improvement of methods for forest survey and management planning of cool temperate and boreal forests.



<br>(2) Improvement of management techniques in cool-temperate and boreal forests from



the environment conservation view point.



<br>(3) Improvement of forest activation management techniques in Hokkaido.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.9.3. Improvement of techniques for the forest protection from pests and for the management of



forest insects and wildlife in cool-temperate and boreal forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Improvement of wildlife management techniques.



<br>(2) Improvement of management techniques for forest insects.



<br>(3) Improvement of techniques for controlling forest diseases.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.10. Systematization of techniques for forest conservation and management in a snowy & cold region</h4>







	The woodland in the Tohoku district is composed of specific ecosystems with



abundant natural forest and various wildlife

 under severe climatic conditions; with heavy



snow in the region facing the Japan Sea and being cold in the region facing the Pacific Ocean.



<br>	Recently,

 there have been nationwide demands for protection of specific and precious



wildlife as well as for the development of specific techniques for forest resource management

 including timber production

 which are suitable to the severe socio-economic and



natural conditions in the region.



<br>	With this background

 researches is being performed to elucidate the characteristics



and functions of site factors and wildlife in forest ecosystems there.  Furthermore

 applied



studies are conducted to promote forestry and local economy in harmony with the conservation of ecosystems and biodiversity in the region.  The studies are designed to  devise and



improve techniques for maintaining and restoring the forest ecosystems

 conserving the



hydrological environment of the forest

 controlling natural disasters

 protecting and managing



wildlife

 producing high-quality timber through long-rotation operation

 and conducting



integrated control of forest damage

 forest resource management

 and regional forestry



programming.  



<p>



<h4><i>4.10.1. Elucidation of the characteristics and functions of site factors and forest ecosystems in a



snowy and cold region</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Elucidation of properties of site factors in forest ecosystems.



<br>(2) Elucidation of biological characteristics in forest ecosystems.



<br>(3) Elucidation of functions of the forest.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.10.2. Advancement of techniques for forest conservation and management in a snowy and cold



region</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Development of techniques for forest conservation in snowy region.



<br>(2) Research on the forest functions for soil and water conservation and disaster



prevention

 and the development of techniques to improve such functions.



<br>(3) Development of techniques for wildlife protection and management.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.10.3. Establishment of techniques for forest management and managerial economics in a snowy



and cold region</i></h4>

<blockquote>







(1) Development of techniques for forest resource management.



<br>(2) Improvement of production techniques of high-quality timbers through long-rotation



operation.



<br>(3) Development of techniques for preventing biological and meteorological damage to



forests.



<br>(4) Development of techniques for regional forestry programming.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.11. Development of forest management techniques in the metropolitan



area

  suburban and alpine zones</h4>







	Researches are undertaken to develop the techniques of multipurpose forest management for the protection of forest environment in the urban and suburban areas.  In the alpine



and wet-snow zones

 researches to increase the production of timber and to enhance the



comfortable environment are also undertaken.  To improve techniques and management



system

 the studies of regeneration

 natural-forest treatment

 snowslide

 economic analysis





and forest damages by organisms are carried out.



<p>



<h4><i>4.11.1. Development of forest management techniques in the metropolitan area and suburban forest</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Conservation of isolated suburban forest ecosystem and development of educational application techniques of these forests.



<br>(2) Development of silvicultural techniques corresponding on the goal of production.



<br>(3) Development of sustainable forest management systems in Kanto and Chubu



regions.



<br>(4) Development of forest planning techniques for forest multiple uses in Kanto and



Chubu regions.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.11.2. Development of forest management techniques in the alpine and snowy zones</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Improvement of forest management techniques in the alpine zone.



<br>(2) Establishment of management techniques for the protection of environment in the



wet-snow areas.



</blockquote>



<p>



<h4><i>4.11.3. Improvement of management techniques of pathogenic microorganisms

 insectpests

 and



wildlife</i></h4>

<blockquote>







(1) Development of management techniques of pathogenic microorganisms

 insectpests





and wildlife.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.12. Establishment of holistic management technology for multiple use of



forests based on their functions in developed region</h4>







	In Kansai region

 there are many extremely urbanized and industrialized districts. 



Consequently

 the various modes of forest functions such as environmental conservation and



cultural representation are in great demand. In the Kansai research center

 soil and site



properties

 soil and water conservation

 wildlife conservation

 mechanism and evaluation of



forest amenity and scenic beauty  will be elucidated with urban and suburban forests and



other regional forests. Stability and transition mechanism of the fragmented forests and



forest islands

 characterizing the forest type of the region having a very long history of



development

 will be elucidated

 and conservation technology based on these elucidations



will be developed. It is important to explicate the developments of the various silviculture



systems

 the forest pest management systems

 and the sustainable forest management



systems. Moreover

 it is necessary to realize a multiple-use of the forest resources timber



production

 and it is inevitable to establish a methodology for the planning of the most



efficient spatial use of each resource. The methodology for an innovative regional forest



resource management planning which is adapted to socio economic change and various needs



of the people will be developed. In addition

 it will be necessary to elucidate the relation of



the regional forests and the forestry with climatic changes

 for the reason that the global



environmental changes are not to be ignored.



<p>



<h4><i>4.12.1. Elucidation of functions of urban-forests and other regional forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Elucidation of functions of urban and suburban forest ecosystem.



<br>(2) Elucidation of soil and water conservation mechanism of urban and suburban



forests.



<br>(3) Elucidation of scenic beauty of forest landscape and environmental amenity and



development of their evaluation methods.



<br>(4) Elucidation of maintenance and transition mechanism of fragmented forest ecosystem and development of their conservation technology.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.12.2. Integration of various sustainable forest management and silvicultural systems</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Development of various silviculture systems.



<br>(2) Development of technique of forest pest management.



<br>(3) Development of sustainable forest management systems.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.12.3. Development of methodology for regional forest resource management and multiple-use of



forest resources</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Development of methodology for multiple-use of forest resources and regional



forest resource management planning.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.13. Enhancement of forest management technology in steep slope region



with heavy rainfall</h4>







	Shikoku island belongs to the warm-temperature zone with heavy rainfall. Since the



land is composed of steep slopes

 land slide is a serious problem in these areas. Also





improper forest treatments are liable to lead soil loss and soil degradations.  Forestry is one



of the major industries in Shikoku.  On the other hand

 forest enriches people's life by supplying



forest products

 and providing places for health care and recreation as well as education for



the people.



<br>	New techniques should be developed to maintain forests health and to promote



forestry. For enhancing forest management technology

 our research priority have been placed



on the following subjects.



<p>



<h4><i>4.13.1. Improvement of forest management technology with respect to environmental conservation</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Development of forest site conservation technology at steep slope mountain area.



<br>(2) Improvement of forest conservation techniques in relation to environmental



resources.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.13.2. Improvement of forest management technology in areas with a high plantation ratio</i></h4>

<blockquote>







(1)Improvement of forest management techniques in mountainous area.



<br>(2)Development of management techniques for forest animals and microorganisms in



mountainous area.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.14. Improvement of management systems in warm temperate and subtropical forests</h4>







	The Kyushu area is covered with warm temperate forests and subtropical forests



including two major forest types: evergreen broad-leaved forests and coniferous plantations



of Sugi and Hinoki.  The expansion of coniferous plantation has reduced the biomass of



broad-leaved evergreen forests and the forest function of environmental conservation.  The



public needs for the forest conservation and management systems are increasing.  To meet



with the public needs for well coordinated use of both forest environment and timber





Kyushu Research Center is carrying out three main subjects including many research fields:



silviculture

 forest soil

 water and land conservation

 insects

 disease

 animals

 mushrooms





resources planning and multiple farming.



<p>



<h4><i>4.14.1. Studies of ecosystems and improvement of conservation systems in warm temperate and



subtropical forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Regeneration mechanism of evergreen broad-leaved forests.



<br>(2) Effects of environmental changes on forest ecosystem and estimation of their 



influences.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.14.2. Improvement of management and utilization methods of forest biology in warm temperate



rain forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1)Infestation mechanism and control of forest diseases.



<br>(2)Ecological studies and control of forest pest insects and animals.



<br>(3)Production techniques of forest by-products such as mushrooms.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.14.3. Improvement of watershed conservation and forest management systems in warm temperate



rain forests</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1)Forest management and planning techniques.



<br>(2)Watershed management on soil and water conservation.



<br>(3)Regional forestry systems based on multiple farming.



</blockquote>







<h4>4.15. Studies on forest characteristics

 technologies for environment conservation and sustainable use of overseas forests</h4>







	Environmental impacts at a global scale such as warming

 desertification or acid



deposition which have been brought by human activities in a recent short period are closely



related to decrease or degradation of forests. In order to succeed forest resources as a



heritage to our offsprings

 active improvement of research and technology development for



conservation and sustainable use of forest resources in the world is needed under cooperation between developed and developing countries. Studies to be carried out are those on



characteristics of forest ecosystems

 functions of forests

 biodiversities

 monitoring and



forecasting technologies of forest resources

 and forest management for their conservation



and sustainable use.



<p>



<h4><i>4.15.1. Identification of forest ecosystem characteristics and development of technologies for



environmental conservation</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Interaction between forest ecosystem and environment. 



<br>(2) Conservation technologies of forest fauna and flora.



<br>(3) Forestation technologies to improve environment-conserving function of forests.



</blockquote>







<h4><i>4.15.2. Development of technologies for forecasting of forest dynamics and for sustainable use of



forest resources</i></h4>



<blockquote>







(1) Analyses of research information on forest resources movements and environmental



changes

 and their forecasting technologies.



<br>(2) Environmentally favorable usage of forest products.



<br>(3) Forest management for resource and environmental conservation.



</blockquote>



<p>



