<p>



<center><A NAME="no.6"><h3>6. STATUS OF INTERNATIONAL RESEARCH COOPERATION</h3></center> 







	Research cooperation with overseas research organizations is based on the bilateral



agreement

 such as with Australia

 Canada

 the U.S.A.

 People's Republic of China

 Republic



of Korea

 Thailand

 Malaysia etc. 



<br>



	Especially

 FFPRI and Forestry Agency of Japan have held Panel of Forestry with the



Forest Service and Department of the Interior of the United States of America periodically



since 1967 for exchanging research information within the framework of UJNR (U.S.-Japan



Cooperating Program in Natural Resources Development) which was established to facilitate



better development and conservation of natural resources for our next generation.



<br>	International assistance and cooperation by the Japanese government toward developing



countries in forestry is conducted mainly by the Japan International Cooperation Agency



(JICA). It functions in three ways

 (1) sending experts (2) providing machinery and materials





and (3) technical training. There are two types of technical cooperation projects in which



experts are dispatched as a team; one is a research type project

 and the other is an



implementation project.



<br>	The number of forestry research experts

 including the both types and survey team



members

 who have been sent from 1952 through 1995 totalled xxxx. The number of forestry



trainees who came to Japan from 1964 through 1995 totalled 3,700 from about 70 countries.



As of 1995

 technical cooperation is being conducted on 33 projects in 18 countries in the



fields of reforestation

 soil conservation

 watershed management

 silvicultural research





forest surveying

 timber utilization

 and wood processing. In addition

 some development



survey is being conducted as technical cooperation on the government basis.



<br>	Besides the JICA bilateral projects

 FFPRI participates in the international research



cooperation projects through the Science & Technology Agency and Environment Agency of 



Japan.



<br>	FFPRI is as well making contribution to CIFOR (Center for International Forestry



Research) established in 1993 under CGIAR (Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research)

 which intends to expand its responsibilities to enhance forestry research

 and



as well as to IUFRO (International Union of Forestry Research Organization)

 including its



SPDC (Special Program for Developing Countries) and APAFRI/FORSPA (Asia Pacific



Association of Forestry Research Institutions/Forestry Research Support Program for the



Asia Pacific Region) established respectively in 1990 and 1995.



<p>



