<B><h2>1 TOWARD THE EPOCH OF FOREST AND TREES</B></h2>
<P>
-Retrospect of 30 years of forest/forestry and wood industries, and prospects-
<P>
(Prologue) 
<P>
1 As this report marks the 30th anniversary since it was first submitted under the 
Forestry Basic Law, it features "Toward the Epoch of Forest and Trees" and intends 
to look back and forward on foresVforestry and wood industries in Japan. 
<P>
2 Stagnation of upstream villages and forestry that nurtured forest has continued in 
the process of high economic growih and enlarged scale of economy in Japan. This 
trend has not stopped under the current longest POSt-war recession since the 
ruptured "bubble economy". Furthermore, the recent disasters caused to forests by 
typhoons, the cold weather damage in 1993, and the rice crop failure caused by 
prolonged rain seriously affected the villages in upstream areas. It is being feared 
under the circumstances that it will become difficult to maintain the functions of forest 
to supply wood and protect beautiful land and provide for bountiful water. 
<P>
3 Even under those constraints, however, forest in Japan which was devastated 
during and after the war has been improved and maintained nearly at the level of 
70% of the land. Presently, 80% of the planted forest is still in the stage of tending 
and thinning but is maturing toward the 21st century as valuable renewable 
resources of resource-scarce Japan. 
<P>
4 Strengthening of forestry and wood industries is required as the impact of the 
international market further increases along with the implementation of the 
agreements of the Uruguay Round in GATT on the other hand, the world is aware 
that establishing a sustainable economic development symbiotic with the global 
environment and nature's regenerative capacity is becoming an urgent matter. The 
concept of "forest conse~ation and sustainable management" for all the world's 
forests that was agreed upon at the United Nations Conference on Environment and 
Development (Earth Summit) is a noteworthy strategy for mankind in the area of 
foresVf orestry. 
<P>
5 Japan is now at the crossroads as to whether it can resuscitate foresVforestry toward 
the 21st century. It is expected that the leading countries of the world in the 21st 
century will be the ones which conserve good environment and rich forest, develop 
economies while maintaining primary industries such as forestry, and establish an 
industrystructure and life style that harmonize with the global environment. It is for 
this reason that Japan should aim at the epoch of forest and trees. Under the 
circumstance in which there has been growing awareness and interest in "green 
and waterf', what is important in envisioning the future is to look back on the efforts in 
the past years for building up "green and water" and secure stronger supportfrom 
the general public for its maintenance and improvement. 
<P>
<h3><B>1 Changes in forest/forestry and wood industries over the past 30 years</h3></B> 

(Background of the enactment of Forestry Basic Law and its policy thrusts) 
By the mid 50's, the post-war reconstruction in Japan was completed and the 
conditions for high economic growih were laid down. From the need for the forestry 
sector to strategically respond to the progress of economic growth, Forestry Basic Law 
was enacted in 1 964. Following is the environment surrounding the foresVforestry and 
wood industries at that time. 
<P>
+ Wood demand in Japan increased sharply with a structural change involving 
growing demand for industrial timber and declining demand for fuel wood. 
<br>
+ Due to the excessive cutting during and after the War, the forests had been 
devastated. Wood supply could not meet the surging demand and led to eventual 
increase in wood imports. It was, therefore, necessary to augment the supply 
POWer of domestic forest resources over the long term. 
<br>
+ The work force was drained from upstream villages and shrinkage of forestry labor 
became conspicuous. 
<br>
+ Income differences between the forestry sector and the secondary/tertiary sectors 
widened. 
<P>
Forestry Basic Law that was enacted taking into consideration the above situations 
upheld as goals of forestry policy stable development of forestry and improvement of 
forestry workers' economic and social status corresponding to the national economic 
growth and improvement of life standard. The signposts of the goals were 
enlargement of total forestry production coupled with improvement of forestry 
productivity, and increase of forestry workers' income. 
<P>
<B><h3>(1)Achievements during the 30 years</B></h3> 

Imrovement and enrichment of forest resources 
<P>
+ Rich forest has been nurtured while ensuring high economic development under 
the constraint of high density and a large population. 
<br>
i) World forest area 
<br>
. Decrease by 0.1% during the 10 years after 1966. 
<br>
. Decrease by 3.4% (equivalent to about 5.6 times of Japan's forest) during the 
15 years atter 1975. 
<p>
<img src="fig-3.gif">
<p>
ii) Japan's forest area
<br> 
. Maintained 25 million ha (67% of total land) for the past 30 years. 
<br>
. Among the OECD member countries, only Japan, Sweden, and Finland have 
per capita GDP of US$10,000 or more, and percentage of forest 60% or more. 
<br>
. There are 6 countries including Japan with GDP of US$ 1 trillion. The 
countries other than Japan have percentage of forest about 30% or less. 
Japan is the only country with population density 300/km2 or more. 
<br>
+ The epoch of domestic wood can be envisioned toward the 21st century if the 
forest resources in Japan are given proper treatment. 
<br>
. The forest growing stock has enlarged by 1.7 times during the past 30 years. 
<br>
. The forest resources are in a maturing stage, especially for the 1O million ha of 
Planted forest, with annual average increment of 70 million m3. 
<br>
. The area of Sugi forest that already passed the standard cutting age is 
increasing. (11% in 1981-> 17% in 1990)
<br> 
. The percentage of Sugi in the domestic saw log production is on the rise. 
(33% in 1968 -> 49% in 1992)
<br> 
. The above achievements were attained mainly by the efforts of the people in 
upstream villages engaged ih forestry for vigorous silvicultural activities and 
sustainable forest management. 
<br>
. Proper implementation of the Forest Planning System, Protection Forest System, 
and land conservation projects. 
. Observance of allowable harvest in principle below annual increment since the 
50's. 
<br>
+ In response to the diverse demands on forest in recent years, new policies for 
forest improvement were adopted which include adequate nurturing of planted 
forests such as tending and thinning, prolonged cutting age, uneven-aged forest, 
tended natural forest work for establishing non-coniferous stand. 
<P>
Improvement of forest productivity
<P> 
+ Forestry mechanization progressed and labor productivity improved. 
<br>
. Log production: 1 .3m3/man'day in 1968 ->2.4m3 in 1985 (1.8 times increase) 
<br>
. Comparison of productivity for silvicultural works in FY 1964 and FY 1991 
<br>
showed improvements of 1.3 times for land preparation, 1.5 times for planting, 
and 1.9 times for weeding. ' 
<br>
+ Introduction of high performance forestry machinery using high-tech 
mechatronics is progressing lately. (23 machines in 1988 -> 495 in 1992) 
<P>
+ Diversification of management to cover wood processing, civil work, construction, 
etc. is strived for in order to stabilize forestry management, and maintain and 
enhance profitability. 
<br>
+ Promotion of cooperative operations by forest owners' associations contributed to 
the improvement of rationalization of forestry production and improvement of labor 
productivity. 
<br>
i) Share of forest owners' associations in private planted forests (1 991) 
<P>. area of new planting 82%<P>
. area of thinning 67%
<P> 
ii) Progress of establishment of Prefectural Afforestation Corporation (45 
corporations as of January 1994) . 
<br>
Im rovement of forestry labor safety 
<br>
+ Although the occurrence of forestry labor accidents is still at a higher level than 
the all-industries average, both the incidence (number of accidents per one 
million hours of labor) and the intensity (loss days per 1,000 days of labor) were 
reduced. 
<br>
. The incidence in 1992 was 58% of 1964. 
<br>
. The intensity in 1992 was 15% of 1964. 
<P>
<img src="fig-5.gif">
<P>
Development of wood industries 
<P>
+ Enlargement of sawmills progressed. 
<br>
. Output Power per sawmill: 31.6kw (1964)->80.8kw (1992) 
<br>
+ New use of wood progressed such as laminated timber and LVL 
<br>. Production of laminated timber in 1 992 was about 29 times that of 1 964. 
<br>. Production of large section structural laminated timber in 1 992 was about 1 1 5 
times that of 1983. 
<br>+ Handling size of log distribution points was enlarged in order for efficient supply 
of domestic logs. 
<br>. Handling volume of a log market: 13,000m3 (1968) ->18,000m3 (1991) 
<br>+ Rationalization of housing construction from the wood supply side was promoted 
with the increased use of pre-cut materials. 
<br>. Number of pre-cut mills in 1994: 654 
<br>+ New use of wood is progressing. 
<br>. Since 1986, the Technology Research Consortium has been developing fiber 
containing wood-extract substance, interior materials for vehicles, and wood 
carbon fiber and other new materials. 
<P>
<B><h3>(2) Problems during the 30 years</B></h3>
<P> 
Stagnant forestry production and declining self-sufficiency of wood 
<P>
+ Forestry production declined and log production decreased. 
<br>. Forestry production (real terms): \949.3 billion in 1970 ->\624.2 billion in 
1992 
<br>. Log production: 50.68 million m3 in 1964 -> 27.11 million m3 in 1992 
<br>+ Self-sufficiency in industrial wood declined as wood imports increased. 
<br>. Wood self-sufficiency: 72.9% in 1964 ->25.0% in 1 992 
<P>
Weakenin forestry profitability and widening gap in income between other industries 
<P>
+ Forestry profitability worsened due to the stagnant wood price as a result of 
increased wood imports and intensifying competition with non-wood materials, 
and to the rising management cost. 
<br>. Investment return for Sugi plantation: 6.3% in FY 1965-~ 0.9% in FY 1992 
<br>. Dependence on forestry income by agri/forestry household (5-20 ha ownership) 
9.5% in FY 1971 ->2.7% in FY 1991 
<br>+ In proportion to the wood imports increase, the wood price was gradually led by 
imported wood and stayed stagnant. 
<br>. Price of medium size Sugi log: \18,900/m3 in 1970->23,200 in 1992 
( a drop of 33% in real terms) 
<br>+ The gap between the forestry and all-industries average incomes widened. 
<br>. Rate of forestry income against all-industries average: 
20-50ha stratum 39.5% in FY 1972-> 6.5% in FY 1992 
50-100ha stratum 83.1% in FY 1972-> 20.0% in FY 1992 
1OO-500ha stratum 242.7% in FY 1972->74.7% in FY 1992 (below all-
industries average since FY 1980)
<P>
<img src="fig-7.gif"> 
<P>+ Depopulation of villages in upstream areas, and shrinkage and aging of forestry 
workforce continued. 
<br>. Number of forestry workers: 440,000 in 1960 ->110,000 in 1990 
<br>. Aging quotient (% of 50 years and older):23.7% in 1960->67.9% in 1990 
<br>+ Insufficient utilization of domestic wood sometimes led to inadequate caretaking 
of forest. 
<br>. The growing stock of Sugi stands above standard cutting age in 1 990 was 1 .7 
times as large as that in 1 981 but the log production was only 1.1 times. 
<br>. Only 53% of the timber from thinning was used in FY 1992. 
<br>. The percentage of non-resident forest ownership increased: 
15% in 1970 ->22% in 1990 
<br>+ International competitiveness of the wood industries is weak. 
<br>i) Domestic wood supply is small and sporadic. Rationalization of production and 
distribution is lagging behind. Stable supply ability both in quantity and quality 
is questionable. 
<br>. If taking the price of medium-size Sugi log in 1993 as 1OO, the price of sugi 
sawn square is 273, Hemlock log 1 1 8 and Hemlock sawn square 254. 
<br>ii) Delayed action in meeting the structural changes in wood supply e.g. recent 
upsurge of finished products imports 
. Percentage of finished products impors in total volume of wood import: 
19.5% in 1964->66.3% in 1 992 
<P>
<B><h3>(3) Backgrounds of the problems</B></h3> 
<P>
Basically, forestry is a primary industry with a characteristic of a very long period of 
production as it deals with forest and, therefore, has an intrinsic handicap against 
other sectors which developed rapidly in th'e process of Japan's economic growth. 
In addition, the environment for forest/forestry also changed during the 30 years. 
<P>
Internationalization 
<P>
+ Liberalization of wood trade which was implemented gradually in the late 50's 
and was completed in 1964 brought a significant impact on forestry and wood 
industries that were mainstays of local economies. 
<br>+ The Plaza Agreement (1985) and the ensuing precipitant high yen movement 
triggered increased import of finished wood products. Furthermore, in GAπ 
Uruguay Round, wood exporting countries, despite their domestic environment 
protection issues and resource constraints, demanded that Japan eliminate import 
tariffs on forest Products from the standpoint of maintaining and developing their 
respective economies. These movements will not only affect forest maintenance 
and management in Japan but also adversely affect global environment if 
sustainable forest management is not done in exporting countries. 
<P>
<img src="fig-9.gif">
<P>
Urbanization and industrialization 
<P>+ During the period of high economic growth, concentration of industries and 
Population to large cities mostly in the Pacific belt occurred and brought 
depopulation to villages in upstream areas. 
<br>+ Relocation of corporations overseas expanded along with internationalization 
and hollowing of the overall Japanese industries is being pointed out. 
<P>
<B><h3>2 Toward the epoch of forest and trees
<br>
(1)Changes that have potentials to realize the epoch of forest and trees 
</B></h3>
Uncertain wood im orts and augmenting Japan's forest resources 
<br>+ With the background of reinforced environmental regulations in wood producing 
countries, wood imports are becoming uncertain. As seen in the acute 
fluctuation of prices of imported wood, international wood demand/supply is also 
becoming unstable. 
<br>. The price of Lauan peeler log: 100(Aug. 1992), 179(June 1993), 144(Dec. 1993) 
<br>. The price of Hemlock log: 100(Feb. 1992), 120(June 1993),110(Dec. 1993) 
<br>+ Forest resources in Japan are being solidified in preparation for the epoch of 
domestic wood. 
<P>
Chane in sense of values toward forest 
<br>+ The sense of values of the general public toward forest is changi
 The sense of values of the general public toward forest is changing in the 
direction of seeking multiple public benefit functions in addition to wood 
production. 
<br>+ There has been growing interest in the roles of forestry to contribute to creation of 
better environment. 
<br>. Value estimation of public benefit functions of Japan's forest: \39 trillion 
<br>. National forest has been divided into four types: Land conservation forest, nature 
preservation forest, total utilization forest, timber production forest. 
<br>. Forest Biosphere Reserves in Yakushima and Shirakami Mountain Range have 
been registered on the World Heritage List under the Convention for the 
Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage. 
<P>
Wood is amenable to both global environment and human beings
<P>+ The value of wood is being re-appreciated along with the growing interest in 
forest conservation at a global level and the importance of sustainable 
management. 
<br>. Tropical forests are feared to disappear in 80-129 years if the current trend 
continues. (in 58 years for continental South East Asia) 
<br>. About 20% of CO2 emittance from Japan's energy consumption is absorbed 
and fixed by forest. 
<br>. The amount of CO2 stocked in the timber used for housing in Japan is equivalent 
to about 40% of that in the plantation forest. 
<br>. Construction of "traditional wooden houses" emit half of CO2 Per area compared 
with "reinforced prefab houses", and wood materials emit less than 10%. 
<br>. Curves and sways produced by annual growih rings give human beings a sense 
of nature and relaxation. 
<P>
<img src="fig-11.gif">
<P>Health and high-quality life 
<P>+ People are oriented toward building a high quality life supported by "rich green 
and water" and "culture of wood". 
<br>. The supply of drinking water in containes in 1 991 (244,000 kl) was about 1 3 
times as large as that of 1975. 
<br>. 10% concentration of hiba timber oil controls proliferation of ticks. 
<br>. Effect of curves and warps of annual growih rings on human beings to give a 
sense of nature and relaxation. 
<br>. Percentage of wooden houses: 41%(1988) -> 48%(1992) 
<br>. Wooden buildings in public school facilities increased in area by 1 20 times from 
1984 to 1993. 
<br>. Output of wooden toys in value in 1 991 was 2.7 times of 1 965. 
<br>. OutPut value of wooden desks, tables and chairs in 1991 was 6.3 times of 1967. 
<P>
Promotion of fores/forestry international cooperation 
<P>+ Japan is now possessed of the economic and technical capabilities for promoting 
international forest/forestry cooperation. 
<br>. Monetary cooperation in the forms of loans and grants started in 1 978 and 
extended to 30 cases in 13 countries by October 1993. 
<br>. Project type technical cooperation started in 1976 and by December 1 993 
implemented 20 projects in 13 countries. 
<br>. Total of about 830 long-term experts mainly from Forestry Agency were 
dispatched. About 80 People are constantly working overseas. 
<P>
<B><h3>(2) Tasks in order to attain an epoch of forest and trees </B></h3>
<P>
The prerequisite of attaining an epoch of forest and trees is maintenance and 
development of villages in upstream areas by promoting comprehensive measures 
with the cooperation of government offices concerned. 
<P>
Tasks 
<br>+ Maintain and develop forestry as industry from the region wide perspective. 
<br>. Establishment of viable forest management under the River Basin Forest 
Management System, improvement of forest resources to meet market needs, 
improvement of forestry production infr~structure such as forest roads, 
strengthening of management by introduction of high performance forestry 
machinery, securing successors, etc. 
<br>+ Facilitate contribution of foresVforestry to the creation of good environment. 
. Maintain healthy forest resources through the establishment of diverse forests 
Placing importance on ecosystems such as promotion of prolonged cutting age 
and uneven aged forest work, promotion of tending and thinning. PreseNation 
of natural forest and proper application of Forest Planning System and 
Protection Forest System.
<P>
<img src="fig-13.gif"> 
<P>
Source:Japan Wood Information Center,"Report on the Survey for the Promotion of Wood Use (volume on affective)",1992
<P>+ Promote total utilization of forest Paying due attention to forest conservation 
<br>. Improve the conditions for forest recreation, education and cultural activities 
while paying due attention to forest conservation, and promote exchange 
between upstream villages and cities. 
<P>+ Consolidate the system of wood production, processing and distribution with a 
view towards an epoch of domestic timber. 
<br>. Ensure a stable supply of logs, develop and extend new use of wood that meets 
consumers' needs reflecting the change in construction methods, restructuring 
of wood industries including shift into new business areas and conversion of raw 
materials, establishing an overall production/distribution system that organically 
combines wood production/processing/distribution and housing construction. 
<P>+ Promote wood trade that is compatible with sustainable forest management. 
<br>. Japan will maintain and strengthen sustainable forest management following 
"The Year 2000 objective" under the new International Tropical Timber 
Agreement (ITTA) and the consuming countries' joint statement for attaining 
sustainable forest management. Japan will continue its efforts for building 
international rules on wood trade with a perspective of conserving all the forests 
in the world be it tropical, temperate, frigid, wood exporting countries' or 
importing countries'. 
<br>. Japan will thus contribute to building an economy and society where 
sustainable development is possible by ensuring global environment 
conservation and nature's regeneration ability. 
<P>+ Actively promote international foresVforestry cooperation. 
<br>. Building upon the achievements of forest maintenance over the past half 
century, Japan will promote foresVforestry cooperation that contributes to forest 
conservation and sustainable management in developing countries at bilateral, 
multi-lateral, governmental, and non-governmental levels. 
<P>
Forest/forestry in Japan is facing adversity. In order for Japan to develop as truly a 
country of forest into the 21st century, wide support from the people in the nation is 
indispensable to tackle the issues of renaissance of villages in upstream areas and 
forestry. At the same time what are required are, a shifting of life style from the 
resources squandering seen in the process of high economic growth to appropriate 
use of renewable forest resources, promotion df wood recycling, continued energy 
saving efforts, which lead to a life style symbiotic with global environment. Realizing 
the importance of forest for conseNation of the global environment, it is necessary to 
promote appropriate use and protection of forest within the sustainable forest 
management especially for tropical forest, and to further proper forest management 
through increased utilization of domestic timber in Japan. 
Table-4 New endeavors for forest improvement and Vitalization of foresby and wood industrieS 
<P>
<img src="fig-15.gif">
<P>
