<B><h2>2 FORESTRY AND VILLAGES IN UPSTREAM AREAS</B></h2>
<P> 
<h3><B>1 Recent trends in forestry production</B></h3> 
<P>
Forest plantation 
<br>+ The area of forest Plantation has been decreasing due to diminishing size of land 
suitable for new plantations, shift of forest improvement Policy, and lowering 
profitability of forestry. 
<br>
Thinning
<br>+ Further utilization of thinning logs is important for effective use of forest resources. 
Development of technology and its practical application of using softwood 
thinning logs for shiitake mushroom is called for. 
<br>Forest road network 
<br>+ From the viewpoints of productivity enhancement and improvement of conditions 
for settlement in upstream village§, it is important to improve main forest roads 
and networks, and improve village sewage systems. 
<br>Log production 
<br>+ Log production is on the decrease due to an inadequate system of production/ 
processing/distribution, a declining workforce,and resource constraints. 
<br>+ Production of Sugi is increasing: 8.82 million m3 jn 1992 (+4% against Previous 
year), 33'/o of domestic timber production, 49% of domestic sawlog production. 
Consolidation of stable domestic timber supply is necessary to realize epoch 
domestic timber. 
<br>Non-wood forest roducts 
<br>+ The production of non-timber forest Products which is an important source of 
income in upstream villages was about the same level as the previous year 
(\38.8 billion) reflecting the consumers' preference for health, nature and 
authenticity. 
<br>Breeding 
<br>+ Since FY 1993, preservation of genes has started for large trees and old/famous 
trees (national monuments). 
Fores forest education 
<br>+ "Forest/Forestry Education Center" was established in FY 1993. Various 
information is disseminated from the Center e.g. Iist of leaders, activity case 
studies, and reference books for youth, etc. 
<h3><B>2 Recent trends in forestry management system</h3></B>
Establishment of river basin forest management system
<br>+It is necessary to establish a system of forest management and domestic timber supply 
system encompassing production ,processing and distribution from upstream through downstream 
for both private and national forests.
<br>.River Basin Forestry Vitalization Centers are scheduled to be established in about
70% of the 158 river basins across the nation by the end of FY 1993.
 both private and national forests.
<br>.As leaders of introducing and instituting river basin management system,13 basin were
selected.
<br>Forest possessors(forest owners,corporations,etc)
<br>+Improvement of forestry management by enlarging forest operation scale is necessary
:economic return of forestry...0.9%(FY 1992)
<P>
<img src="fig-17.gif">
<P>
Forestry enterprises
<br>+ It is imperative to obtain a stable workload, reduce costs, cooperate with other 
sectors, and improve employment conditions in order to maintain sound 
management and secure workforce. 
<br>+ Forest owners' associations are expected to play a core role in river basin forestry 
as a driving force of forestry work in the private sector, 
<br>Forest labor 
<br>+ It is necessary to promote mechanization, improve welfare facilities and 
employmenVcompensation systems in orderto secure forestry iabor. 
. Labor Standard Law was applied totally to forestlV since April, 1 994. 
. In supportof the establishment of endowment fund for securing labor for forest 
improvement, \50 billion assistance to local governments was made in n/ 1 993. 
<br>Forest loans 
<br>+ Use of a forestry loan system is encouraged in orderto promote cost reduction, 
introduction of high performance forestry machinery in response to the 
decreasing workforce, enlargement of forestry operation,,and improvement of 
forest road network. 
<P>
<h3><B>3 Damage to forest and countermeasures </h3></B>
Climatic damage 
<br>+ In 1993, typhoons hit Japan frequently as in the case of 1 991 , and caused serious 
<br>damage to about 10,000 ha of private forest mostly in Kagoshima and Kumamoto. 
. A task force was established to discuss promotion and expansion of use of wind-
blown trees. 
<br>Damage by animals and insects 
<br>+ Damage by deer is increasing. Countermeasures are being discussed at the 
"Inter-agency meeting on protection and control of wild life". , 
<br>Acid rain 
<br>+ It is feared in recent years that the forest ecosystem is being affected by acid rain. 
Establishment of forest work techniques that keep the health of forest is being 
attempted by identifyjng damage caused by acid rain and conducting research on 
the effect of acid rain on forest trees in mountain areas. 
<P>
<h3><B>4 Recent trends in villages in upstream villages</h3></B> 
+ In order to protect and maintain forest, it is necessary to build vital villages . 
<br>. Population of upstream villages (designated) is only 4% of the national total, but 
they occupy 47% of the national land and 61% of the total forest. 
<br>. Depopulation and aging.....20% of residents 65 years or older (12% nationally) 
<br>. Delayed infrastructure.....drinking water system 79%. (95% for non-designated 
villages), flush toilet 22% (68%), paved road 51% (68%), medical doctor per 
thousand people 0.9 (2.8) 
<br>."The Law concerning the Promotion of the Improvement of Basic Conditions of 
Agriculture, Forestry and other Businesses in Hilly and Mountainous Areas" was 
enacted in June, 1993. 
<br>. It is necessary to develop industries capitalizing on local resources. 
<br>+ it is important to promote exchange between cities and upstream villages. 
<br>. In 1991 , 81% of designated villages (965 municipalities) organized creative 
business and events, e.g. direct delivery service, sister cities, ownership sales. 
<br>. It is important to look for new approaches to enjoy beautiful green and nature. 
<P>
<img src="fig-17.gif">
<P>
<hr>
