<B><h2>4 WOOD DEMAND/SUPPLY AND WOOD INDUSTRIES</B></h2>
<P> 
<h3><B>1 Recent trends in wood demand and supply </h3></B>
Wood demand and housin construction 
<br>+ Total wood demand in 1992 declined for industrial timber, shiitake mushroom 
logs, and fuel wood.  
<br>+ As for the supply of industrial timber in 1992, domestic timber decreased by 3%. 
against the previous year and imported timber by 3.4%. 
<br>. Self-sufficiency in industrial timber was 25.0%,the same level as previous year. 
<br>. The supply of Sugi has been on the rise since 1985 and showed 4.5% increase. 
<br>+ The new housing starts in 1993 were 1,486,000, 5.9% up from previous year. 
<br>. Floor area per house showed steady increase: 108 m2 jn 1993. 
<br>. Percentage of wooden houses in 1993 was in the same level of previous year: 
46.9% in 1993. 
<br>+ The production of paper and paperboard in 1993 was 27.77 million ton, 1.9%. 
down against Previous year. 
<br>. The percentage of domestic wood chips is decreasing recently due to strong yen 
( 51% in 1988 -> 41% in 1992) 
<br>. It is important to solidity the system of a stable and efficient supply of raw 
material including the use of thinning logs, insect damages timber, cannibalized 
wood from deconstruction, and improved use of recycled paper. 
<P>
Recent trends in wood imports 
<br>+ Wood import is on the increase since 1987. Import of logs is decreasing but 
import in the form of finished products is increasing, 
<br>+ The Uruguay Round reached an substantial agreement at the Trade Negotiation 
Committee on December 15, 1993. Japan offered about a 50% reduction of 
import tariff from the base rate. 
<br>. Over the next 5 years, sawn and planed timber of SPF(Spruce, Pine, Fir) will be 
reduced from 8% to 4.8%, and plywood from 10-15% to 6-10%. 
<br>+ Japan needs to ensure stable import of timber commensurate with demand with a 
view to the epoch of domestic timber supported by maturing forest resources. 
<br>+ President Clinton announced in July 1993 "The Forest Plan For a Sustainable 
Economy and Sustainable Environment". 
<br>. Havesting volume from the federal forest west of the Cascade mountains will be 
reduced to the total of 12 billion BF (approximately 54.3 million m3) in 10 years. 
<br>+ Malaysia is tightening export control on unprocessed timber. 
<br>. Sarawak implemented reduction of harvesting volume since September 1992. 
<br>. Since January 1993, Sabah adopted a temporary ban of log export and raised 
substantially the export tariff on wood products.  
<br>+ Indonesia lifted the total ban on log export in May 1992 but it is virtually 
impossible to export logs because of the high export tax. 
<br>. In the middle of 1991 the export tax on sawn timber was raised again. Export of 
roughly sawn timber is virtually impossible. 
<br>. Indonesia's export of plywood expanded drastically. In 1992, the export was 
9.54 million m3, up 9.4% against the previous year (28% of which is for Japan). 
<br>+Import of Russian timber had been on the decline but its supply to Japan is 
recovering recently. 
<P>
<img src="fig-23.gif">
<P>
<h3><B>2 Recent trends in wood prices</h3></B> 
+ The prices of imported timber rose in a fluctuating manner recently due to 
reduction of harvesting volume and log export restrictions in exporting counties. 
In the beginning of 1993 there was an upward trend in the market. The domestic 
prices did not rise as high as those in exporting countries due to the high yen. 
The price of domestic Sugi was higher than that of the previous year. 
<br>. The price of Douglas Fir logs rose considerably from February 1992 until June 
1993, then softened (annual average was 13% up). 
<br>. The price of Western Hemlock logs rose considerably from December 1992 until 
June 1 993, then softened (annual average 12% up). 
<br>.The prices of Lauan both for sawlogs and peeler logs rose sharply from August 
1992 until June 1993, then softened (annual average 18% up and 51% up). 
<br>.The price of Sugi logs rose from August 1992 until March 1993, then leveled off. 
(annual average 3% up). 
<br>. The price of Hinoki logs showed a similar trend to that of Sugi. 
<P>
<h3><B>3 Recent trends in wood industries</h3></B> 
<P>
Management of wood industries 
<br>+ The number of bankruptcies in 1993 in the wood products manufacturing sector 
decreased by 12 against the previous year and in the sales sector increased by 
14. 
<br>+ National Federation of Wood Cooperatives put forward a wood industries' vision 
toward the 21st century in December 1993 which thrusts a shift from excessive 
dependency on imported wood to domestic wood. 
<br>Wood distribution and rocessin 
<br>+ It is important that the supply system of domestic timber be improved to ensure 
highly finished quality products in large quantity at low cost. As production of sugi 
timber of general quality is anticipated to increase in the future, enlargement and 
expansion of distribution lot is required to meet the needs of the demand side. 
<br>+ Reduction of the number of sawmills is occurring in the smaller size category. 
Output Power per mill is constantly increasing.  
<br>+ The number of plywood and veneer mills is decreasing (506 mills in 1992) but the 
demand for laminated lumber is increasing and so is the numberof its producers 
(there were 281 producers and the production in 1992 was 451,000 m3). 
Production of large cross-section structural laminated lumber showed upward 
trend recently. There are 19 LVL manufacturing plants and the production is 
expected to increase for structural use as well. 
<P>
<img src="fig-25.gif">
<P>
<HR>
