<B><h2>5 WORLD FOREST RESOURCES AND JAPAN'S INTERNATIONAL FOREST/FORESTRY COOPERATION </B></h2>
<P>
<h3><B>1 State of world forest resources, global environment issues, and wood trade</h3></B> 
State of world forest resources 
<br>+ The area of tropical forest dropped from 1,910 million ha in 1980 to 1,756 million 
ha in 1990 (annual average of 15.4 million ha decrease). 
<br>+ The area of forest and other wooded land in the developed temperate-zone 
countries was 2,060 million ha as of 1990 (39% of the total land area). 
<br>+ If damage to the forest in Europe can be gauged by the defoliation, 23.5%. 
of the trees were more than 25% defoliated in 1992. 
<P>International efforts for lobal environment issues 
<br>+ It was pointed out from the beginning that the importance of the "United Nations 
Conference on Environment and Development (Earth Summit)" would be the 
unilateral and international post conference actions. 
<br>. The outline of the "Commission on Sustainable Development " was decided as 
a follow-up to the Earth Summit. 
<br>+ In December 1993, Japan formulated "Agenda 21 " action plans incorporating 
NGOs' opinions. 
<br>+ A number of international conferences on forest and forestry such as "Global 
Forest Conference (in Indonesia)" were held following the Earth Summit. 
<br>+ Seven "Carbon Offsets" projects that utilize forest's"function as a carbon sink are 
implemented in six countries. 
<br>. An average of 250 tons of CO2 (in terms of carbon) is fixed by conserving 1 ha of 
tropical forest, and by establishing 1 ha of forest 10 tons of CO2 is fixed annually, 
<P>World wood supply demand and wood trade 
<br>+ The world's log consumption in 1991 was 3,430 million m3. 
<br>+ The world's industrial wood production was 1,600 million m3 (conifers 67%, 
hardwood 33%) 
<br>. The traded volume was less than 8% of the production. 
<br>+ Major exporting countries of industrial roundwood are USA, Malaysia, and former 
USSR and they occupy 50% of the total export in the world, whereas Japan, 
China, and Korea occupy 50% of the total import. 
<br>+ International Tropical Timber Organization (ITTO) established underthe ITTA is 
strengthening its policy making activities as shown in the adoption of the strategic 
goal of "achieving exports of tropical timber and timber products from 
sustainably managed sources by the year 2000". 
<br>+ After the revision negotiation of ITTA, the new agreement was adopted that clearly 
upholds "The Year 2000 Objective" and attempts to create a new fund for 
sustainable management of tropical forest. 
<br>+ OECD and GATT are also discussing how to achieve compatibility of wood trade 
and environment conservation. 
<P>
<img src="fig-27.gif">
<h3><B>2 japan's efforts for international forest/forestry cooperation </h3></B>
Bilateral forest/forestry cooperation 
<br>+ The project-type technical cooperation through Japan International Cooperation 
Agency (JICA) is expanding in number and diversitying in content. 
<br>. As of December 1993, there are 20 projects in 13 countries. 
<br>+ Japan also carries out development suNey, development cooperation, Ioan 
assistance and grant aid. 
<P>Cooperation throu h international organization 
<br>+ Japan participated in the formulation of Tropical Forests Action Programme 
(TFAP) which aims at maintaining/establishing tropical forest and ensuring 
appropriate use, and donated a trust fund to the Food and Agriculture 
Organization of the United Nations (FAO) for the purpose. 
<br>. As a multi-lateral trust fund: US$ 394,000 a year (FY 1988-FY 1990) 
<br>. As a trust fund for preparing urgent plantation plan: US$ 349,000 (FY 1991-FY 
1993) 
<br>+ Japan is the largest donor to ITTO. 
<br>. In 1993, assessed contribution was \85 million and voluntary contribution \1.56 
billion. 
<br>+ Financial contribution and dispatch of a director and experts are arranged for to 
support International Center for research in Agroforestry (ICRAF) and Center for 
International Forestry Research (CIFOR). 
<br>\183 million to CIFOR and \61 million to ICRAF (in FY 1993) 
<P>Other international fores forest cooperation 
<br>+ In order to contribute to the maintenance and enrichment of forest resources and 
enhancement of forestry productivity, the overseas forestry cooperation project is 
actively implemented e.g. survey and analysis of forest condition by remote 
sensing, and improvement of the information service system. 
<br>+ Japan International Forestry Promotion and Cooperation Center (JIFPRO) is 
promoting extensive activities such as recruitment/training of human resources, 
collection/compilation/dissemination of technical information, support of NGOs' 
cooperative activities, extension/education of international greening. 
<br>+ NGOs' efforts include improvement of local people's living environment and forest 
Plantation for prevention of global warming by CO2 sink/fixation. 
<br>. The Organization for Industrial, Spiritual and Cultural Advancement (OISCA) is 
carrying out "Children Forest Program" (an attempt to help children understand 
the importance of forest through the establishment of school's forest) at about 
300 schools in 11 countries. 
<P>
<img src="fig-29.gif">
<P>
<HR>
