<B><h2>Epilogue</B></h2> 
The world today, after the end of the cold war, is witnessing the progress of a market 
economy beyond the differences of social regimes and an intensifying 
interdependence in all aspects such as politics, economy and culture. The Uruguay 
Round, which was virtually agreed upon recently, was driven forward under these 
circumstances with the banner of free trade promotion. On the other hand, discussions 
on economy versus resources and global environment have been vehemently held, 
kicked off by the "limitation of growth" by the Rome Club in 1972 and proposals at the 
recent "Earth Summif' We should be prepared that, as mankind's economic activities 
become more and more extensive and reach a colossal scale on the finite earth, the 
issues of resources and environment may confront the future course of free trade and 
free economy. 
<P>Japan, while developing its economy, has become one of the world's highly forested 
countries where about 70% of the land is covered by 10 million ha of plantation 
forests. These forests, presently in a maturing stage, were revived from the dilapidated 
state during and after the War by the incessant efforts of the people residing in villages 
in upstream areas. Today, forestry that has long nurtured forest is in adversity and at 
the turning point whether it can rejubinate toward the 21st century. 
Japan is, at the same time, expected to have a long-term perspective and realize the 
epoch of forest and trees, based on its built up potential for the development of forest 
and forestry. 
<P>With the above basic understanding, in order for Japan to contribute to sustainable 
economic development symbiotic with global environment in the area of forest/forestry 
while developing its f,orestry and wood industries as a country continuing to be  
enriched with forest, the following tasks should be actively addressed.  
<br>The first is to vitalize upstream villages that support forest. 
<br>The second is to maintain and develop forestry as an industry.  
<br>The third is to promote forest/forestry's contribution to creation of the environment. 
<br>The fourth is to envisage the epoch of domestic timber and improve the system of  
wood production, processing, and distribution. 
<br>The fifth is to implement management reform of the National Forest Operation 
thereby ensuring national forest's important roles into the future. 
<br>The sixth is to actively promote international forest/forestry cooperation. 
<P>Needless to say, self-help efforts of the people engaged in forestry and wood 
industries are indispensable to achieve the above. However, considering the difficult 
situation villages in upstream areas and forestry are placed in, and also the fact that 
forest is not only an economic asset to human beings and the Japanese people but 
also a precious environmental asset, understanding and strong support of all the 
people in the nation is necessary. At the same time, for Japan to truly realize the 
epoch of forest and trees, a shift of life style is required from that of resource 
squandering seen along with high economic growth to one that is symbiotic with the 
global environment. 
<P>
<HR>
</DOC>
