<h2><B>PROLOGUE</B></h2> 
<p>
<b>1</b> This year is the 50th anniversary of the end of the Worid War II ,
 a significant node in the history of Japan, and we are at the 
threshold of a new era having only several years left before we 
enter the 21st century. After the War, Japan achieved reconstruction 
starting from rubble and, having gone through various stages, 
attained remarkable economic development. Today, it is one of the 
countries with largest economic scale. 
<p>
<b>2</b> However, Japan is facing unprecedented issues both within and 
outside the country such as limitation of mass production and 
consumption, a change of people's preference from materialistic 
richness to spiritual happiness, a rapidly aging population, 
borderless economy and information, and clear emergence of global 
environmental probiems. A new set of values with a perspective 
into 21st century is sought for. 
<p>
<b>3</b> It has long been known empirically that forests are not only 
source of wood that fills materialistic needs of people and 
industries but also have various functions such as land and water 
conservation. In addition, the roles of forests in recent years 
as sites for recreation for every people including elder generation, 
cultural activities, sports, and education of youth have become 
significant. Furthermore, expectations of forests are growing such 
as for maintenance and creation of a fine living condition and 
landscapes, and for new uses of wood to make residential circumstances 
more comfortable. They match the people's inclination to seek mental
 richness, and expectations of forests tend to be more diverse than 
ever. 
<p>
<b>4</b> These roles of forest, forestry and wood materials were often 
ignored during the period of high economic growth. However, as for 
the present situation of forests, it is noteworthy that Japan still 
maintains rich forests that occupy nearly 70% of the total land. 
This is partly due to the natural conditions and historical circumstances,
 but largely to the efforts of many harbingers who endeavored to 
reconcile both forest conservation and effective utilization. 
Owing greatly to them, people in the nation today can still enjoy 
tremendous benefits from forests without realizing their efforts. 
<p>
<b>5</b> Such wisdom for reconciling forest conservation and effective 
utilization, technologies and systems as its crystallized forms, 
and life patterns based on them, can be collectively called "forest 
culture". Since the economy and society are in a momentous transitional
 period, it is expected that reviewing the history of forest culture 
and discussing the possibility of its further development will 
provide valuable suggestions to new orders of economy and society 
in the 21st centuly. By doing so, Japan's role in the solution of 
global environmental issues will become clearer including the 
establishment of compatibility of sustainable management and forest 
conservation which is indispensable to mankind's prosperity into 
the future. 
<p>
<b>6</b> The substance of forest culture lies with "symbiosis" of forest 
and mankind, and "circulation" of materials intrinsic in forests. 
For its further development, on top of the self-help efforts 
of those who are engaged in forest and forestry, people's 
participation in all dimensions is imperative. 
<p>
<b>7</b> From the abovementioned viewpoints, this annual report 
places forestry and wood industries as the primary carriers 
of forest culture, and upstream villages as the site of its 
nurture and regeneration. Thus, the first chapter is entitled 
"For further development of forest culture". The second 
chapter "Forest, forestry, and upstream villages" 
describes the current situation of forests, recent trends 
in forestry production and forestry management, current 
situation and direction for vitalization of upstream villages 
where forestry and agriculture are the mainstay industries. 
The third chapter "Role of National Forest Operation and 
management reform" describes the current situation of the 
National Forest Operation and the progress made toward the
improvement of its management. The fourth chapter "Wood 
demand, supply, and wood industries" gives analyses of wood 
demand and supply, wood import, and movements of wood prices, 
and describes the management situation of wood industries 
and the recent trends in domestic timber distribution. The 
fifth chapter "World forest resources and Japan's international 
forest and forestry cooperation" touches upon the issue of
deforestation in tropical areas which has become one of the 
global environmental problems, the current efforts and future 
tasks of international forest and forestry cooperation, 
and the international attempts for the realization of 
sustainable forest management. 
<p>
<hr>
