<b>I. FOR FURTHER DEVELOPMENT OF FOREST CULTURE</b> 
<p>
<b>1 Forest and Culture</b> 
<p>(1) Forest Culture 
<p>Relationshi between forest and mankind 
<br>The life of human beings since olden times has been closely 
related to forest and wood in various ways. 
<br><ul>
<li>The relationship can be characterized as a "symbiosis" considering 
that a number of early civilizations were supported by gitts from 
forests and depended on their supply of wood and water. 
<br>
<li>"Circulation" of materials takes place in forest and, at the same 
time, forest functions as medium of circulation such as for water. 
Forest's multiple functions are made Possible by its fundamental 
function of organic material production. 
<ul>
<li>Sustainable production of wood and grass is possible if 
exploitation is kept within the limit of reproduction capacity. 
<li>Distribution of forests in the world varies greatly since in 
some regions or countries utilization and exploitation of forests 
have exceeded the reproduction capacity whereas forests have not 
been restored to date.
</ul></ul> 
Forest culture 
<ul>
<li>In Japan, influenced by its climatic and topographic conditions, 
it has been a widely accepted perception that deforestation and 
degradation of forests lead to natural disasters such as floods, 
and that a stable supply of water indispensable for the irrigation 
of rice paddy agriculture is ensured by the existence of forests. 
<br>
<li>As a result, the recognition has grown that forest is an 
indispensable resource for life and industries, and hence the 
wisdom has been developed to benefit in perpetuity by conserving 
and nurturing forest and thereby maximizing its various effioacies. 
In this report, <b>wisdom to effectively utilize forests while 
ensuring their conservation and as its crystallized form technologies,
 systems and the life style based on these</b>, shall be collectively
 expressed by the term <b>forest culture</b>.
</ul>
<p> 
(2) Foundation of Forest Culture in Japan 
<br><ul>
<li>Conservation of forests has been achieved through economic 
activities of forestry, and wisdom and technologies to effectively 
utilize forests and wood have been developed through activities of 
forestry and wood industries. It can be said, therefore, that the 
primary carriers of forest culture are forestry and wood industries, 
and that upstream villages are the field for the generation and 
reproduction of forest culture. 
<br>
<li>Various gifis from forests, realized through activities of forestry
and wood industries which hava developed along streams and river 
basins, pervaded the country. The concept of effectively utilizing 
forests while ensuring conservation was fostered and developed in 
such geographical extension. 
</ul>
<img src="f-1.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-2.gif">
<p>
(3) Closely feit forest culture
<br><ul>
<li>In 1994, there was a severe shortage of water in western Japan 
due to droughty weather from the spring. 
<ul>
<li>More than 15.8 million people were affected by a water cut-off.
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Efrective means to prevent water shortage are to stabilize water 
flow in rivers and to maintain usable water quantity. It is essential 
to capitalize on functions of forests which occupy 2/3 of Japan's 
land and have enormous water storage oapacity. 
<br></ul>
<ul>
<li>Forest is called "green dam" and serves for mitigation of drought 
and flood, and purfication of water. It also prevents soil wash-out 
and landslide, and reduce sedimentary deposits in dams. 
<ul>
<li> In Kanagawa prefecture, water supply control has never been 
necessary. Prefectural Corporate Agency (1959) and Yokohama City 
(1916) established watershed forest in the upstream Doshi River. 
</ul></ul>
<b>2 Relationship of Japanese with Forest and Wood</b> 
<p>
(1) Relationship with forest and wood 
<p>
Daily life
<ul>
<li>In the Jomon period, ways to select appropriate wood according 
its usage were already known.
<ul>
<li> Sugi for a dugout because of its water resistance and easy 
processing, Horse Chestnut for a bowl because of its fine grain, <i>
Daphniphyllum</i> for the grip of an ax still using for the shaft of 
agricultural tools because of its tenacity. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Nuts of Conkers and Acorns were part of the diet.
<ul>
<li> They had been used as reserve food until the Meiji era 
(from 1868 to 1911).
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Wood was indispensable for materials of daiiy use such as 
barrels, pails, chopsticks, and furniture. 
</ul>
Houses and buildings 
<ul>
<li>A Iarge quantity of wood was used in the end of the 6th century 
for the construction of large buildings i.e. temples and palaces.
<ul>
<li>Horyuji Temple has stood for more than thousand years, proving 
the fine quality of its wood.
<li>In the 7th century, forest exploitation proceeded and disasters 
such as soii wash-out occurred.
</ul></ul>
<ul> 
<li>In Edo era (from 1603 to 1867), demand for wood sharply increased 
following frequent large-scale fires in cities.
<ul>
<li>Measures to sustain forest resources: "<i>Tomeyama</i>"- prohibition 
of logging in designated forests, "<i>Tomegi</i>"- prohibition of 
felling certain species of trees e.g. "Five Major Tree Species of 
Kiso region"' 
<li>The wooden post and beam joint methods for housing construction 
were perfected in the Edo era and are still in use today.
</ul></ul>
Agriculture
<ul>
<li>Forests were indispensable for rice paddy agriculture to provide 
water resource, grass and fallen leaves for organic fertilizer.
<br>
<li>Forest degradation caused by excessive exploitation consequently 
led to the development of farmers' wisdom to reconcile both forest 
conservation and utilization. 
</ul>
<img src="f-3.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-4.gif">
<p>
Belief and arts
<ul>
<li>The faith in forest itself as god or belief that gods descend 
upon tall or big trees date back to olden times. Even today, there 
is a faith of 'Yamanokami" that many forest workers believe. There 
are still existing many festivals and habits based on faith in many 
places.
<br>
<li>In performances of literature, paintings, and other arts, rich 
forests that change their appearance from season to season have 
been described. 
</ul>
<p>
(2) The change of people's attitude toward forest and wood in recent 
years 
<br>Durin the period of high economic growth 
<ul>
<li>The relationship between people and forest tended to attenuate.
<ul> 
<li>Increase of wood import: 2.48 million <img src="m3.GIF"> (6% of total consumption)
in 1955 -> 20.16 million <img src="m3.GIF"> (29%) in 1965 -> 82.68 million <img src="m3.GIF"> (76%)
in 1993.
<li> Sharp drop of charcoal purchase (charcoal's share of light and 
fuel expenses): 57.4% in 1947 -> 7.3% in 1965-> 0.10% in 1985 
</ul></ul>
In recent years
<ul>
<li>Movement to seek active contacts with forests and greenery, and 
enhanced interest in forests have been seen. People's attitude has 
been changing from passive to active states.
<ul>
<li> Increase of the number of people who use forests as a field 
for refreshment, sports, and education. 
<li> Increase of peopie who are wishing to participate in nurturing 
forest: 53.6% in 1986 -> 66.2% in 1993 
</ul></ul>
<b>3 Development of Forest Culture in Modern Japan</b>
<p>
(1) "Sustained Harvest" and Forest Establishment
<br>
 Formulation of forest management plan for sustained halrvest 
<ul>
<li>Before the modern era, there existed the recognition that sustained 
harvest of forest products and maintenance of forest functions for 
public benefit can be attained by proper forest management, and that 
maximum harvest is possible by planting species suited to the site.
<ul>
<li> In the Edo era methods to ensure sustainable wood production 
were known (Banyama, Banguriyama, Jungiriyama, etc.). 
<li> In 1894, a "Forest Management Plan" was prepared for national 
forest, which is equivalent to the Forest Plan today including 
methods and quantity of logging, and how to restore forest. 
</ul></ul>
Development of forest management technology 
<ul>
<li>The technology of plantation forest has been developed for maximum 
and sustainable production of desired wood, and rapid and certain 
recovery of devastated forest.
<ul>
<li> The forests devastated during and afier the World War II were 
recovered by Plantation supported by the nation-wide greening movement
 (10 million ha of plantation forest has been established to the 
present).
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Multi-storied forest management and tended natural forest management
 have been actively introduced. 
</ul>
<img src="f-5.gif">
<br>
<img src="f-6.gif">
<p>
(2) Protection Forest System and Protected Forest System 
<br>Creation of the rotection forest system 
<br>Since the 7th century there had been various orders to prohibit 
or restrict logging and forest exploitation in many parts of the 
country, and in the Edo era certain forests played roles equivalent 
to protection forests today. 
<ul>
<li>Building on to the various endeavors up to the Edo era, the 
protection forest system was established under the Forest Law (1897) 
in the Meiji era. 
<ul>
<li> Classification of protection forest similar to today's: 
Tide Damage Prevention Forest, Fish Trap Forest, Navigation Target 
Forest, Scenic Site Preservation Forest, Public Health Forest, etc. 
<li> Today 1/3 of the total forest is designated (an aggregate of 
8.9 million ha as protection forests), and the system has been 
solidified constantly. 
</ul></ul>
Creation of the Protected Forest System.
<ul>
<li>In 1915, preceding the enactment of the National Park Law, the 
protected forest system in the National Forest was established for 
the protection forest for academic research, scenic beauty, etc. 
<ul>
<li> These protected forests became many of the scenically important 
sites of the early national parks. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>In 1989, restructuring and expansion of the protected forest 
system was done including the review of the existing protected forest 
and creation of Forest Biosphere Reserves (preservation of primeval-
like forest for both flora and fauna).
<ul>
<li> Shirakami Mountain Range and Yakushima Island which are registered 
on the World Natural Heritage List are also Forest Biosphere Reserves.
</ul></ul>
(3) Restoration of forests as a basis for safe and comfortable life 
<br>Restoration of forest by modern technology and nurturing of head 
water conservation forest 
<br>The concept of forest conservation started prevailing as 
exemplified in the promulgation of "Yamakawa-no-okite" (forest and 
riverside conservation rules) which ordered tree planting in upstream 
areas. 
<ul>
<li>Toward the end of the Edo era, many districts suffered from flood 
due to overexploited forests. Recovery of damaged forests continued 
to be an important issue into the Meiji era and, therefore, many 
experts such as J.Drijke were invited from Holland. 
<ul>
<li> As a Japanese, Kinbara Meizen in the early Meiji era is well 
known for the establishment of watershed forest in the Tenryu River 
basin. 
<li> In Tokyo, a city water conservation forest of 22,000 ha has 
been established in the upstream Tama River since 1903. 
</ul></ul>
Program-based implementation of land conservation work
<ul>
<li>In 1911,"The Phase I Forest Improvement and Watershed Management 
Project" was started.
<ul>
<li> The 8th Five Year Programme of Forest Conservation Projects 
is being implemented. 
</ul></ul>
<img src="f-7.gif">
<br>
<img src="f-8.gif">
<p>
Forest improvement for the conservation of livin circumstances and 
natural conditions
<ul>
<li>Since 1971,the "Forest Improvement Project for Living Circumstances 
Conservation" has been implemented to improve the forest in the 
vicinity of residential areas and in 1994 the "Forest Improvement 
Project for Nature Conservation" was launched. 
<ul>
<li> At Utsubuki-yama in Kurayoshi-shi of Tottori prefecture, 
the forest has been improved by "Forest Improvement Project for 
Living Circumstances Conservation" and civil activities for 
establishing squirrels' Iiving forest has been developed. 
</ul></ul>
Nurturing forest for a rich sea
<ul>
<li>It has been recognized that forests contribute to the conservation 
of marine life habitat in their downstream by providing nutritious 
water and preventing wash-out of soil and sand. Efforts to improve 
and nurture forests are being made in order to restore a life-rich sea.
<ul>
<li> At Erimo Point the haul of fish has increased due to the 
recovery of forests set up by land conservation work. 
</ul></ul>
(4) Effective utilization of wood for enrichment of people's lives 
<br>Improvement of wood rocessin techniques
<ul>
<li>Along with the extensive use of mechanical saw milling since the 
latter of Meiji era, sawing pattern techniques have been improved 
and efficient production of sawn timber has been ensured. Construction
 of large wooden buildings such as school buildings are increasing, 
being enabled by the use of large sectional laminated wood. 
</ul>
Expanded use of wood
<ul>
Efficient utilization of wood has been promoted by recycling 
and by using for various purposes.
<ul>
<li>Demand for wooden houses continues to be strong: the ratio of 
wooden houses has been 80% of single houses.
<li>Use of wood has been expanding e.g. for outdoor facilities such 
as bridges and benches, pavement materials, etc. 
</ul></ul>
<b>4 Status Quo of Forestry, Wood Industries, and Upstream Villages 
That Bear Forest Culture</b>
<ul>
<li>Japan has achieved remarkable economic development, while 67% of 
its land is occupied by forest. 
<ul>
<li>(Causes) 1. Difficulty of development in the steep and unexploitable 
mountain regions, 2. Moist temperate monsoon climate which is suitable 
for exuberance of forests, 3. Rice paddy agriculture extensively practiced 
which needs symbiosis with forests, and 4. Nurturing and developing superior 
forest culture. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Forestly and wood industries which carried forest culture are now 
facing difficulties and the vitality of upstream villages that 
nurtured and developed forest culture is diminishing. 
<li>As a result, it may become difficult to continue receiving the 
benefit and efficacy from forest. 
</ul>
<img src="tbl-1.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-9.gif">
<p>
Stagnation of forestry
<ul>
<li>The declining profitability of forestry in recent years has 
discouraged forest owners from undertaking forestly operaticns 
such as thinning.
<ul>
<li> Actual price index in 1993 against 1965: stumpage of Sugi 100->70,
 logging wage 100 -> 502, Planting cost 100 -> 929 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>It is difficult to secure a young work force due to the high 
occurrence rate of labor accidents and unstable working hours. 
<ul>
<li> The number of high schooi graduates who entered forestry was 211
 in 1994.
<li> 80,000 out of 110,000 forestry workers are 50 years old or older.
</ul></ul>
Wood industries that are facing severity
<ul>
<li>The costs of production, processing, and distribution of domestic 
wood are relatively higher, caused by small and scattered production 
and distribution. 
<br>
<li>In recent years, it has become difficult for small-sized 
entrepreneurs to secure a stable demand due to the competition 
with large housing corporations which systematized processing and 
distribution of wood materials for housing.
<br>
<li>it is feared that tariff reduction by the settlement of the Uruguay 
Round of GATT might lead to further severity to wood industries.
</ul>
Upstream villages where aging and depopulation roceed
<ul>
<li>In the process of high economic growth, depopulation and aging 
proceeded in upstream villages.
<br>
<li>In addition to various inconveniences in daily lives, it is 
difficult to secure employment opportunities, and the social 
infrastructure is insufficient compared with urban areas. 
<br>
<li>Entering the new phase i.e. natural attrition of population 
(the number of death exceeds that of birth), sustaining the local 
community is likely to become difficult in some villages. 
<ul>
<li> The number of municipalities with natural attrition among 
those designated under the Mountain Village Development Law: 
344 municipalities (29%) in 1981-> 772(65%) in 1991 
</ul></ul>
<b>5 Pursuing Further Development of Forest Culture</b>
<p>
(1)Necessity of Further Development of Forest Culture 
<br>
Forest culture as practical wisdom was generated through close 
contacts of mankind with forest and wood, developed through numerous 
experiences, and has been succeeded throughout the history, changing 
its form with time and circumstances. 
<ul>
Spatial
<br>
<li>Forest culture was transmitted from the narrow area of villages 
to wider areas, and lately, along with urbanization and enlargement 
of metropolis, to across the nation. Furthermore, the influence of 
one nation's industrial activities are likely to expand beyond 
borders and affect global environment. 
<br>
Qualitative 
<br>
<li>Forest culture affects and permeates not only the economic 
efficacy of stably supplying forest Products, but also public 
aspects such as watershed conservation, provision for health 
recreation, education, sports, etc. 
<ul>
<li>It is important to review the relationship between forest 
culture and cities from a new perspective (urban forests are 
part of the living circumstances and wooden houses and products 
serve as carbon dioxide sink). 
<li> The development of technology for new use of wood has a 
potential to improve better living conditions. 
</ul></ul>
<img src="f-10.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-11.gif">
<ul>
<li>In order to meet the expanding, diversifying, and upgrading 
needs for forest and wood, it is necessary not only to inherit 
the traditional forest culture but also to accurately recognize 
its significance and its role at present and to plan for 
further development with a perspective into the future.
<br>
<li>Sustainable management of forests has become an impcrtant 
task today. It behooves Japan to recognize the effectiveness
 of its fine forest culture nurtured within and transmit it 
outwardly to the world, which would solve global environmental
 issues in the course of time. 
</ul>
(2) The Direction of Further Development of Forest Culture
<ul>
<li>It is important to vitalize forestry, wood industries, and 
upstream villages through improvement of forest as a source 
of greenery and water, improvement of the system for production, 
processing, and distribution of local timber, by means of the
 establishment of river basin forest management system, and 
promotion of wood use.
<br>
<li>However, considering the adverse conditions surrounding 
forestry, wood industries, and upstream villages, it is 
doubtful whether they can be vitalized by the efforts only 
of the people on the part of forestry, wood industries, 
and upstream villages. 
<br>
<li>People's inclination to have contacts with forest and 
greenery and to participate in nurturing forests in some 
from or other has been growing, which is regarded as 
fixation and support of forest culture. 
<ul>
<li> Voluntary actions of nurturing forest by means of 
Middle-term Profit-sharing Silviculture, Junior Green 
Friends' Federation, participation for volunteer activities, 
corporation philanthropy, etc. 
<li> Creation of endowment funds for forest improvement 
by the coalition of municipalities in both downstream and 
upstream areas. Activities to improve and nurture forests 
in the upstream in order to restore a rich sea. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>It is henceforth important to expand the circle of 
people's participation in forest improvement as well 
as to strengthen the nation-wide support in the form 
of cost-sharing of forest improvement, which is a 
efficient foothold to vitalize forestry, wood 
industries, and upstream villages. 
</ul>
There has been an argument that the existence of forest 
will be one of the most critical requirements for the 
survival of human being in the 21st century. In order 
for Japan's forest, forestry and wood industries to 
contribute to enriching people's lives and prospering 
human being, it is essential to shed light from new 
angles to "symbiosis" and "circulation" which are the 
bases of forest culture. 
<p>
There steady efforts should make it establish sustainable 
management of Japanese and world forest, and formulate 
a new social and economic system to enable symbiosis 
with earth environment. 
<p>
<b>Table-2 Examples of new endeavors based on forest culture</b> 
<p>
<b>Based on a concept similar to forest culture, or using 
key words such as "forest culture" and "wood culture", new 
and original attempts were made to expand utilization of 
forests and wood. </b>
<p>
<b>Prefectures</b> 
<hr>
Shimane Hiroshima 
<blockquote> 
Formulation of "Chugoku Mountain Range Forest Culture Zone Concept":
 aiming at fostering the area so that human and nature can coexist, 
based on the review of the forest culture nurtured in the 
historically rich nature and social tradihons. 
</blockquote>
Kochi
<blockquote>
Highest ratio of forest land in Japan. In 1994, the "Concept 
of Wood Culture Prefecture" was proposed from the viewpoint 
of "Nurturing wood", "Be dose to wood", and "Let wood live". 
Aiming at establishing beautiful forest, cultural heritage 
of wood, and comfortable city lives. 
</blockquote>
Miyazaki 
<blockquote>
Anticipating the advent of "forest society" in the 21st century 
when forests would become indispensable for human existence 
for cultural basis, "Concept of Forestopia" to form ideal areas 
was proposed. 
</blockquote>
Kanagawa
<blockquote>
"Kanagawa Forest Plan" was formulated, which gives basic direction 
of forest nurturing, in order to pass on variety of attractive 
forests to the 21st century while ensuring the harmony of 
conservation and utilizahon of forests. 
</blockquote>
Yamagata
<blockquote>
"Head Water Forest" improvement plan was prepared to enable 
recreating, educating, playing, and training in the forests 
and villages of the Okitama district located in the upstream 
of Mogami River and Arakawa River. 
<hr>
</blockquote>
<b>Municipalities</b> 
<hr>
Tokyo-to Musashino city 
<blockquote>
A home-stay program for giving originality and sensibility 
is offered to elementary school children brought up in cities, 
in cooperahon with Tono city in Iwate prefecture and Kawakami 
village in Nagano prefecture, so that they can experience 
agricultural mountain village life, etc. 
</blockquote>
Hokkaido Nishiokoppe village
<blockquote>
Elementary school children in the village and Asahikawa city 
have interactions between cities and villages and learn together 
about the roles of and benefits from forests through annual 
outdoor actvities in forests. 
<hr>
</blockquote>
<b>National Forest Operation</b> 
<hr>
National Forest Operation 
<blockquote>
For the purpose of creating sites for human to be close with 
forests, "Human Green Plan" has been carried aut and comprehensive 
forest use facilities including educational, cultural, and 
recreative purposes were established (24 sites as of the end 
of FY 1993) 
<hr>
</blockquote>
</DOC>
