<b>II. FOREST, FORESTRY AND UPSTREAM VILLAGES</b>
<p>
<b>1 Forest in Japan</b> 
<ul>
Improvement of forests
<br>
<li>An important task is to establish the river basin forest 
management system for improvement of forests through forestry 
production activities. 
<br>
<li>Improvement of protection forests is important for the 
maintenance and enhancement of public functions of forest. 
<ul>
<li> Revision of the Fifth Plan for Improvement of Protection 
Forest 
</ul></ul>
Roles of forests as expected by the people in Japan 
<ul>
<li>People's expectations of forests have become more diverse. 
</ul>
Various means for forest im rovement
<ul>
<li>There have been cases of cost-sharing of forest improvement 
based on the better awareness of the beneficiaries.
<ul>
<li>More than 80% of the people in Japan recognize the 
importance of downstream and upstream interactions in the future. 
<li>Sharp increase of cost-sharing cases for the improvement 
of water conservation forests (about 100 cases across the nation)
</ul></ul>
Influences of the Great Hanshin-Awaji Earthquake 
<ul>
<li>The Forestry Agency dispatched survey teams to prepare 
a restoration plan, and conducted inspection for the prevention 
of secondary disasters, and carried temporary measures on the 
landslides sites. 
<li>The Forestry Agency ensured wood supply for restoration 
through the National Forest Operation, etc. 
</ul>
<p>
<b>2 Trends in Forestry Production</b>
<p>
Log production 
<ul>
<li>In the overall downward trends, production of Sugi is 
showing an upward trend in recent years supported by the 
increasing volume of halvestable resources (a sign of the 
epoch of domestic wood). 
</ul>
Non-timber forest roducts 
<ul>
<li>Reflecting the consumers' inclination for health and 
authenticity, production of non-timber forest products is 
on the increase in recent years. 
</ul>
Forest plantations
<ul>
<li>The area of annual forest Plantation had been declining 
due to the shift of forest improvement Policy(introduction of 
prolonged cutting age) and low profitability of forestry, 
but showed an increase in 1993. 
</ul>
Thinning
<ul>
<li>It is important to oarry out thinning efficiently by 
collective operation realized through improving road network 
and introducing high performance machinery. 
</ul>
Improvement of road network 
<ul>
<li>An integrated approach is needed to improve forest 
roads network and to improve living environment facilities e.g. 
village sewage systems in order to promote proper forest 
management and improvement of settlement conditions in 
upstream villages. 
</ul>
Introduction of high performance forest machine
<ul>
<li>In all parts of Japan, introduction of high performance 
machinely is rapidly expanding in recent years.
<ul>
<li>739 machines at the end of FY 1993 (49% up from previous year)
</ul></ul>
 Education about forests and forestry
<ul>
<li>Forests and forestry education classes have been actively 
held for school children. 
</ul>
<img src="f-12.gif">
<p>
<img src="tbl-3.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-13.gif">
<p>
<b>3 Recent Trends in Forestry Management</b>
<p>
Establishment of river basin forest management system
<ul>
<li>It is essential to promote upstream-downstream coalition.
<ul>
<li>By the end of FY 1995 in each of the 158 basins a river 
basin forestry vitalization center will be established as a 
forum for basic policy discussion. 
<li>Nine basins (13 in 1993) were selected as leading basins 
since they can be models of developing river basin forest 
management system. 
<li>In the Sendai river basin of Tottori prefecture, the third 
sector enterprise "Tottori Forestry Service" has been established 
as an integrated river basin forestry service center which 
coordinates the amount of forestry operations and jointly use 
of high performance forestry machinery.
<li>Forest owners' cooperatives are expected to be the driving force.
</ul></ul>
Third sector forest enterprises
<ul>
<li>Recently, incorporations of third sector forestry enterprises 
are increasing. Despite the difficulty of securing profitability, 
they are watched with keen interest. 
</ul>
Forest work force 
<ul>
<li>It is necessary to promote mechanization and to improve 
working and wage systems which should be on par with other sectors. 
</ul>
<p>
<b>4 Recent Trends in Upstream Villages</b> 
<p>
Current situation 
<ul>
<li>The so-called hilly mountainous areas are main field of 
forest Production, which plays important roles. These areas 
are prone to be adversely affected by the GATT Uruguay Round 
agreement. It is, therefore, important to piace vitalization 
of agriculture and forestry as a central task, and to make 
integrated efforts with close connections of relevant agencies. 
</ul>
Attractive upstream villages
<ul>
<li>It is necessaly to establish beautiful and vitalized village 
in order to keep up national land and forest.
<ul>
<li>Promotion of industries utilizing local resources and 
improvement of settlement conditions for the village people 
are the prerequisite. 
</ul></ul>
Exchanges between upstream villages and cities
<ul>
<li>It is necessary to promote in various ways exchanges 
between upstream villages and cities for the vitalization 
of villages and balanced the nation-wide development. 
<ul>
<li>Those who want to spend hoiidays in mountain villages: 
60.4% 
<br>Those who want to stay private lodging houses: 39.5%
<li>After participating in the "Forest Experience Green Scout" 
(the aim was to deepen understanding of forest and forestry) 
organized by Miyama-cho in Kyoto prefecture three urban youngsters 
here found employment in forestry. 
</ul></ul>
<img src="tbl-4.gif">
<p>
<img src="tbl-5.gif">
<p>
<img src="tbl-6.gif">
<p>
<hr>
