<b>III ROLE OF NATIONAL FOREST OPERATION AND MANAGEMENT REFORM</b>
<p> 
<b>1 Role of National Forest Operation and Progress of Its Undertakings</b>
<ul>
<li>The National Forest Operation is expected to play a core 
role in ensuring public functions of forest, Planning and 
sustainable supply of forest products, and vitalization 
of agriculture and forestry districts.
<ul>
<li>20% of the national land area, 30% of the total forest area.
<li>Implementation of forest management according to main functions: 
land conservation, nature maintenance, recreational use, and 
timber production (water conservation is expected of all types of 
forests).
<li>Active participation in the river basin forest management system.
</ul></ul>
Ensurin public functions of forests
<ul>
<li>Forest Biosphere Reserves which maintain primeval states have 
been established in protected forests in order to conserve natural 
environment. 
<ul>
<li>In FY 1993, 6 locations of 45,000 ha were newly established. 
</ul></ul>
Opportunities to be close with forests 
<ul>
<li>Green Owner System (middle-term profit-sharing silviculture) 
has been actively promoted as a joint effort of the state and people.
<ul>
<li>As of the end of FY 1993, the number of contractual agreements 
both with individuals and corporates was 73,000. 
</ul></ul>
Wood supply
<ul>
<li>Sales of "Dry Logs" (naturally dried stems without limbing) 
from national forests have been actively promoted. 
<ul>
<li>The supply of logs in 1993 was 6.17 million <img src="m3.GIF"> (1/4 of the 
total production of domestic timber). 
<li>Active efforts for management reform, for example that in 
cooperation with local agriculture cooperatives, a health drink 
made from the extract from Megusurinoki, which is believed to 
have efficacy on liver function recovery, has been put out to 
markets. 
</ul></ul>
<b>2 Implementation of Management Reform</b>
<p>
Financial situation 
<ul>
<li>Due to the difficulty of securing revenue as a result of 
declining harvest, and the increasing interest payment for the
 growing accumulated debt, the financial burden is as severe 
as ever.
</ul>
Management reform
<ul>
<li>Based on the Improvement Plan of National Forest Operation,
 to balance the revenue and expenses by the year 2000, vigorous
 efforts are being made i.e. simplification and rationalization 
of organization, reduction of employees, and improvement of work
 efficiencies.
<ul>
<li>Merging and reorganization of 38 district forest offices 
(newly establishing of Forest Technology Centers and Yakushima 
Forest Environment Conservation Center) in FY 1994. 
</ul></ul>
<p>
<img src="tbl-7.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-14.gif">
<p>
<img src="tbl-8.gif">
<p>
