<b>IV WOOD DEMAND, SUPPLY AND WOOD INDUSTRIES</b><p><b>1 Recent Trends in Wood Demand and Supply</b><p>Wood demand and housin construction<ul><li>The total demand of wood in 1993 was 110.21 million <img src="m3.GIF">about the same level as that of the previous year.<ul><li>5.8% decrease in domestic wood, 1.7% increase in imported wood.<li>The self sufficiency rate of industrial wood 23.6% (1.4 points down from the previous year) and that of sawn wood was 33.8%. <li>The supply of Sugi (Japanese Cedar) has been showing a steady increase since 1985 and increased 2.0% from the previous year.</ul></ul><uL><li>The new housing starts in 1994 was 1.57 million, an increase of 5.7% from the previous year. The number of wooden houses also increased to 721,000 (3.4% up). <ul><li>The percentage of wooden houses was 45.9% (1 point down).<li>Floor area per wooden houses is increasing (112 <img src="m2.GIF">in 1994).<li>A low cost supply system of housing materials is needed.</ul></ul><ul><li>The production of paper and paper board in 1994 increased by 2.7%. <ul><li>The ratio of domestic wood chips decreased due to the strong yen ( 51% in 1988 -> 36% in 1994). </ul></ul>Recent trends in wood import<ul><li>Log imports are decreasing whereas imports of manufactured products are increasing. The Uruguay Round was concluded its 7 1/2 year negotiation by the signing of the Final Act at Marrakech Ministerial meeting in April 1994.<ul><li>The World Trade Organization (WTO) was established in January 1995.<li>The Japanese import tariffs on wood products will be reduced by an average of 50% from the base rates over 5 years from Janualy 1995.</ul></ul><ul><li>The US President, in response to the concern about the diminishing timber harvest, formulated a plan to set the annual harvest as 1.1 billion BF and submitted it to the federal court in Seattle.<ul><li>Environmental organizations are deliberating on repeal of the plan and the future of harvest recovely is unpredictable.</ul></ul><ul><li>In Canada, legislation on forest management for compatible harvest and environment is being formulated and review of the annual allowable cut is being undertaken.<ul><li>Reduction of harvest in the future is anticipated.</ul></ul><ul><li>Export control of unprocessed wood has been tightened in Malaysia.<ul><li>Sarawak implemented reduction of harvest from September 1992.<li>Sabah implemented a temporaly ban on log export from January 1993, and a sharp raise of export tax on wood products.</ul></ul><ul><li>Indonesia lifted the total ban on log export in May 1992 but in reality log export is virtually impossible because of the very high export tax.<ul><li>In 1993, plywood exports to Japan were 3.65 million <img src="m3.GIF">, an increase of 37% against the previous year.</ul></ul><ul><li>Import of Russian timber was showing a downward trend but recently log import is recovering (3.65 million <img src="m3.GIF">in 1993, an increase of 19% against the previous year). </ul><img src="tbl-9.gif"><p><img src="f-15.gif"><p><img src="f-16.gif"><p>Promotion of wood use<ul><li>It is necessary to expand the areas for using woody materials and their production, and from the environmental point of view, enhance the utility rate of lesser used woody resources, to improve durability, and to promote recycled use of wood.<ul><li>The new material (WPC) that adds the attributes of plastic to wood.<li>Acetylated wood as non-toxic non-rotting wood. </ul></ul><b>2 Recent Trends in Wood Prices</b> <p>Prices of imported wood vs. domestic wood<ul><li>The wood prices in 1993 showed smaller fluctuations in Japan compared with those of the producing countries because of the trend of strong yen, and the trend continued in 1994.<ul><li>Medium-sized Sugi and Hinoki logs dropped by 4.2% and 1.9% respectively.<li>Douglas-fir, Hemlock, and Lauan (peeler) logs dropped by 4.6%, 1.4%, and 17.7% respectively.<li>The price of medium-sized Sigi logs has been lower than that of Hemlock logs since 1992, and the difference rate was -17.6% in 1994.<li>The price difference of Sugi and Hemlock sawn timber has been minimizing (difference rate: 21.5% in 1985 -> 6.7% in 1994) </ul></ul><b>3 Recent Trends in Wood Industries</b> <p>Management situation of wood industries<ul><li>The number of bankruptcies in the wood and wood products sector in 1994 was 179 for manufacturing (34 more than the previous year), 222 for sales (2 fewer) . The total value of insolvencies were  <img src="yen.GIF">42.8 billion and <img src="yen.GIF">49.7 billion respectively. </ul>Processin and distribution of wood<ul><li>It is essential to establish the stable wood supply system and to promote the distribution of Sugi medium quality wood.<ul><li>The capacities of sawmills continued to enlarge ( 71.7kw per mill in 1988 -> 82.0kw in 1993).<li>Production of plywood has been declining but import is increasing (production of ordinary plywood in 1993 was 790 million <img src="m2.GIF">, 10% less than the previous year, and import 580 million <img src="m2.GIF">, 32% more). <li>Production of laminated wood is increasing (497,000 <img src="m3.GIF">in 1993, 10% more than the previous year, of which structural large sectional laminated timber was 42,000 <img src="m3.GIF">, 23% more).<li>As substitutes for plywood, production of particle board (PB) and fiber board (FB) increased (PB production in 1993 was 80 million <img src="m2.GIF">, 8.7% more than the previous year, and FB 140 million <img src="m2.GIF">, 13.9% more). </ul></ul><img src="f-17.gif"><p><img src="f-18.gif"><p><img src="f-19.gif"><p><hr>
</DOC>
