<b>V WORLD FOREST RESOURCES AND JAPAN'S INTERNATIONAL FOREST 
AND FORESTRY COOPERATION</b> 
<p>
<b>1 Current Situation of World Forest Resources, Sustainable 
Forest Management, and Trends in Wood Trade</b> 
<p>
Current situation of world forest resources
<ul>
<li>The world total of forest area as of 1992 was 3.88 biilion ha,
 which is 29% of the total land area.
</ul>
<ul>
<li>There has been growing concern in the world about 
deforestation especially in tropic areas.
<ul>
<li>The area of tropical forest as of the end of 1990 was 1,756 
million ha and the average annual decrease between 1980 and 1990 
was 15.4 million ha (equivalent to 41% of Japan's land area).
<li>The total biomass of tropical forest as of 1990 was 296.2 
billion tons. 
</ul></ul>
<p>
Criteria and indicators for sustainable forest management
<ul>
<li>At the Commission on Sustainable Development (CSD) which 
was established as a follow-up to the UN Conference on 
Environment and Development (Earth Summit), various endeavors 
have been made. In addition, efforts to prepare criteria and 
indicators for sustainable management of forests other than 
tropioal forests are promoted under two initiatives (criteria 
and indioators for tropical forests have already been 
formulated by ITTO before the Earth Summit).
<ul>
<li>The Helsinki Process (for European forests): an agreement 
has been reached at the First Expert Level Follow-up Meeting 
of the Second Ministerial Conference on the Protection of 
Forests in Europe (June 1994).
<li>The Montreal Process (for forests other than European 
and tropical forests): an agreement has been reached at the 
6th meeting of the Working Group on Criteria and Indicators 
for the Conservation and Sustainable Management of Temperate 
and Boreal Forests (February 1995). 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>In Japan, a committee was established to cope positively 
with the movement of the Working Group, and proposals on 
criteria and indicators were submitted. 
</ul>
World wood demand, supply, and trade
<ul>
<li>Total round wood consumption in the world was 3.47 billion
m3 in 1992.
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Production of industrial round wood in the world was 1.6 
billion <img src="m3.GIF">    56| billion <img src="m3.GIF"> (conifers 67%, hardwood 33%).
 (conifers 67%, hardwood 33%).
<ul>
<li>The exported volume was 120 million <img src="m3.GIF">, 7% of the production. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Major exporting countries of industrial wood are USA, 
Malaysia, and Russia, which supply nearly 50% of the total 
export. Major importing countries are Japan, Korea, and China 
(60% of the total import).
</ul>
<ul>
<li>At ITTO substantial measures to achieve the "Year 2000 
Objective" in order to ensure that "by the year 2000 all 
tropical timber for export should be produced from sustainably 
managed forest" are being discussed.
</ul>
<ul>
<li>"Committee on Trade and Environment" was established at WTO.
</ul>
<img src="f-20.gif">
<p>
<img src="f-21.gif">
<p> 
<b>2 Japan's Efforts for International Forest and Forestry Cooperation</b> 
<p>
Bilateral cooperation 
<ul>
<li>The number of project-type technical cooperations through 
Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA) has been 
increasing and their nature is diversifying.
<ul>
<li>As of January 1995, 20 projects are on-going in 12 countries.
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Development survey, development cooperation, yen loan are 
also being implemented. 
</ul>
Cooperation through international organizations
<ul>
<li>Funding support and dispatch of experts have been 
provided to UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) for 
the formulation of Tropical Forest Action Plan (TFAP) which 
lays out actions for field projects for afforestation and 
extension, maintenance and establishment of tropioal forest, 
and appropriate utilization.
<ul>
<li>From 1991 to 1993, $349,000 was contributed as trust 
fund for strengthening the re-afforestation program .
<li>In 1994, $436,000 was contributed for the Support to 
the Reorientation of Forestry Policies and Institutions of 
Countries of Asia in Reform to Market Economy.
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Japan has been the single largest contributor to ITTO. 
<ul>
<li>In 1994, assessed contribution <img src="yen.GIF">93 million, voluntary 
contribution <img src="yen.GIF">1.652 billion. 
</ul></ul>
<ul>
<li>Funding and personnel support has been provided to 
Center for International Forestry Research (CIFOR) and 
International Center for Research in Agroforestry (ICRAF).
<ul>
<li>In 1994, <img src="yen.GIF">183 miilion to CIFOR, <img src="yen.GIF">124.6 million to ICRAF. 
</ul></ul>
Other international cooperation
<ul>
<li>In order to contribute to sustaining forest resources 
and improving forestry production, Overseas Forestry 
Cooperation Promotion Projects have been actively carried 
out e.g. preparation of a manual of regeneration techniques 
for useful indigenous species such as Dipterocarps.
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Japan International Forestry Promotion and Cooperation 
Center (JIFPRO) is making extensive efforts for training and 
securing of personnel, collection, compilation, and dissemination 
of technical information, support to NGO's activities, extension 
and education for international greening movements, etc. 
</ul>
<ul>
<li>NGO's efforts include improvement of living conditions 
for local people and forest Plantation to hold off 
desertification.
<ul>
<li>"The Action for Mangrove Reforestation" started mangrove 
reforestation model project in Vietnam. 
</ul></ul>
<img src="tbl-10.gif">
<p>
<hr>
