<b>EPILOGUE</b> 
<p>
Japanese people has established today's living by receiving 
various benefits from forest. The urban life, which appears
 to be kept irrespective of forest, owes a lot to the forest
 in the surroundings and upstream for a stable supply of 
clean drinking water and formulation of fine living circumstances. 
On the other hand, mankind has many bitter historical experiences 
of causing deforestation, in the process of population growth 
and social/economic development, by harvesting and exploiting 
the forests in excess of their reproduction capacity. 
<br>Continuation of deforestation and degradation of forests 
mostly in tropic areas is one of the major global environmental
 problems and is closely iinked with other global environmental 
issues. 
<p>
Japan has nurtured forest culture and is one of the most 
forest-rich countries in the world. Promotion of proper 
forest management, however, has been hindered by worsening 
management environment for forestry and wood industries, 
depopulation of upstream villages, and weakening and aging 
forestry work force. If the current trends continue, 
it is feared that not only the value of wood resources as 
economic assets would be lost but also important functions 
of forests to protect the national land, to create a fine 
living environment, and to foster a healthy high-quality life, 
would be impaired. 
<p>
Under these circumstances, it is imperative for Japan, as 
a country rich in forest, to develop forestry and wood 
industries, and at the same time, to make a contribution
 to create a system of sustainable economic development 
compatible with the global environment and nature's 
regeneration power. Hence the significance of featuring 
forest culture in this report. Based on such understandings, 
the following tasks should be vigorously pursued;
<blockquote>
- first, to nurture diverse forests and to develop 
forestry as an industry; 
<br>
- second, to improve the system of wood production, 
processing, and distribution;
<br>
- third, to vitalize upstream villages which protect 
and support forests;
<br>
- fourth, to ensure sound management of National Forest 
Operation so that it can play the expected important roles;
<br>
- fifth, to support wood trade compatible with sustainable 
forest management, and promote international forest and 
forestry cooperation. 
</blockquote>
In order to accomplish these tasks, it is helpful to 
revisit the signiflcance of forest culture, that has 
been nurtured to derive maximum sustainable benefit 
from forests, and to further develop it toward the 
21st century. Forestly that has been the carrier of 
forest culture is in predicament and its self-help 
effort alone is insufficient to substantiate forest 
culture, to nurture forests as its bases, and to 
vitalize upstream villages. What is urgently needed 
is a strong support of Japanese people who enjoy 
various benefits of the forests as both economic
 and environmental assets. 
</DOC>
